x4i.pyparsing

pyparsing module - Classes and methods to define and execute parsing grammars

The pyparsing module is an alternative approach to creating and executing simple grammars, vs. the traditional lex/yacc approach, or the use of regular expressions. With pyparsing, you don't need to learn a new syntax for defining grammars or matching expressions - the parsing module provides a library of classes that you use to construct the grammar directly in Python.

Here is a program to parse "Hello, World!" (or any greeting of the form "<salutation>, <addressee>!"), built up using Word, Literal, and And elements (the '+'<ParserElement.__add__> operators create And expressions, and the strings are auto-converted to Literal expressions)::

from pyparsing import Word, alphas

# define grammar of a greeting
greet = Word(alphas) + "," + Word(alphas) + "!"

hello = "Hello, World!"
print (hello, "->", greet.parseString(hello))

The program outputs the following::

Hello, World! -> ['Hello', ',', 'World', '!']

The Python representation of the grammar is quite readable, owing to the self-explanatory class names, and the use of '+', '|' and '^' operators.

The ParseResults object returned from ParserElement.parseString can be accessed as a nested list, a dictionary, or an object with named attributes.

The pyparsing module handles some of the problems that are typically vexing when writing text parsers:

  • extra or missing whitespace (the above program will also handle "Hello,World!", "Hello , World !", etc.)
  • quoted strings
  • embedded comments

Getting Started -

Visit the classes ParserElement and ParseResults to see the base classes that most other pyparsing classes inherit from. Use the docstrings for examples of how to:

  • construct literal match expressions from Literal and CaselessLiteral classes
  • construct character word-group expressions using the Word class
  • see how to create repetitive expressions using ZeroOrMore and OneOrMore classes
  • use '+'<And>, '|'<MatchFirst>, '^'<Or>, and '&'<Each> operators to combine simple expressions into more complex ones
  • associate names with your parsed results using ParserElement.setResultsName
  • find some helpful expression short-cuts like delimitedList and oneOf
  • find more useful common expressions in the pyparsing_common namespace class

  32__doc__ = \
  33"""
  34pyparsing module - Classes and methods to define and execute parsing grammars
  35=============================================================================
  36
  37The pyparsing module is an alternative approach to creating and
  38executing simple grammars, vs. the traditional lex/yacc approach, or the
  39use of regular expressions.  With pyparsing, you don't need to learn
  40a new syntax for defining grammars or matching expressions - the parsing
  41module provides a library of classes that you use to construct the
  42grammar directly in Python.
  43
  44Here is a program to parse "Hello, World!" (or any greeting of the form
  45``"<salutation>, <addressee>!"``), built up using :class:`Word`,
  46:class:`Literal`, and :class:`And` elements
  47(the :class:`'+'<ParserElement.__add__>` operators create :class:`And` expressions,
  48and the strings are auto-converted to :class:`Literal` expressions)::
  49
  50    from pyparsing import Word, alphas
  51
  52    # define grammar of a greeting
  53    greet = Word(alphas) + "," + Word(alphas) + "!"
  54
  55    hello = "Hello, World!"
  56    print (hello, "->", greet.parseString(hello))
  57
  58The program outputs the following::
  59
  60    Hello, World! -> ['Hello', ',', 'World', '!']
  61
  62The Python representation of the grammar is quite readable, owing to the
  63self-explanatory class names, and the use of '+', '|' and '^' operators.
  64
  65The :class:`ParseResults` object returned from
  66:class:`ParserElement.parseString` can be
  67accessed as a nested list, a dictionary, or an object with named
  68attributes.
  69
  70The pyparsing module handles some of the problems that are typically
  71vexing when writing text parsers:
  72
  73  - extra or missing whitespace (the above program will also handle
  74    "Hello,World!", "Hello  ,  World  !", etc.)
  75  - quoted strings
  76  - embedded comments
  77
  78
  79Getting Started -
  80-----------------
  81Visit the classes :class:`ParserElement` and :class:`ParseResults` to
  82see the base classes that most other pyparsing
  83classes inherit from. Use the docstrings for examples of how to:
  84
  85 - construct literal match expressions from :class:`Literal` and
  86   :class:`CaselessLiteral` classes
  87 - construct character word-group expressions using the :class:`Word`
  88   class
  89 - see how to create repetitive expressions using :class:`ZeroOrMore`
  90   and :class:`OneOrMore` classes
  91 - use :class:`'+'<And>`, :class:`'|'<MatchFirst>`, :class:`'^'<Or>`,
  92   and :class:`'&'<Each>` operators to combine simple expressions into
  93   more complex ones
  94 - associate names with your parsed results using
  95   :class:`ParserElement.setResultsName`
  96 - find some helpful expression short-cuts like :class:`delimitedList`
  97   and :class:`oneOf`
  98 - find more useful common expressions in the :class:`pyparsing_common`
  99   namespace class
 100"""

 185    # build list of single arg builtins, that can be used as parse actions

 192    def _ustr(obj):
 193        """Drop-in replacement for str(obj) that tries to be Unicode
 194        friendly. It first tries str(obj). If that fails with
 195        a UnicodeEncodeError, then it tries unicode(obj). It then
 196        < returns the unicode object | encodes it with the default
 197        encoding | ... >.
 198        """
 199        if isinstance(obj,unicode):
 200            return obj
 201
 202        try:
 203            # If this works, then _ustr(obj) has the same behaviour as str(obj), so
 204            # it won't break any existing code.
 205            return str(obj)
 206
 207        except UnicodeEncodeError:
 208            # Else encode it
 209            ret = unicode(obj).encode(sys.getdefaultencoding(), 'xmlcharrefreplace')
 210            xmlcharref = Regex(r'&#\d+;')
 211            xmlcharref.setParseAction(lambda t: '\\u' + hex(int(t[0][2:-1]))[2:])
 212            return xmlcharref.transformString(ret)
 213
 214    # build list of single arg builtins, tolerant of Python version, that can be used as parse actions
 215    singleArgBuiltins = []
 216    import __builtin__
 217    for fname in "sum len sorted reversed list tuple set any all min max".split():
 218        try:
 219            singleArgBuiltins.append(getattr(__builtin__,fname))
 220        except AttributeError:
 221            continue

 223_generatorType = type((y for y in range(1)))

 225def _xml_escape(data):
 226    """Escape &, <, >, ", ', etc. in a string of data."""
 227
 228    # ampersand must be replaced first
 229    from_symbols = '&><"\''
 230    to_symbols = ('&'+s+';' for s in "amp gt lt quot apos".split())
 231    for from_,to_ in zip(from_symbols, to_symbols):
 232        data = data.replace(from_, to_)
 233    return data

 235alphas     = string.ascii_uppercase + string.ascii_lowercase
 236nums       = "0123456789"
 237hexnums    = nums + "ABCDEFabcdef"
 238alphanums  = alphas + nums
 239_bslash    = chr(92)
 240printables = "".join(c for c in string.printable if c not in string.whitespace)

 242class ParseBaseException(Exception):
 243    """base exception class for all parsing runtime exceptions"""
 244    # Performance tuning: we construct a *lot* of these, so keep this
 245    # constructor as small and fast as possible
 246    def __init__( self, pstr, loc=0, msg=None, elem=None ):
 247        self.loc = loc
 248        if msg is None:
 249            self.msg = pstr
 250            self.pstr = ""
 251        else:
 252            self.msg = msg
 253            self.pstr = pstr
 254        self.parserElement = elem
 255        self.args = (pstr, loc, msg)
 256
 257    @classmethod
 258    def _from_exception(cls, pe):
 259        """
 260        internal factory method to simplify creating one type of ParseException
 261        from another - avoids having __init__ signature conflicts among subclasses
 262        """
 263        return cls(pe.pstr, pe.loc, pe.msg, pe.parserElement)
 264
 265    def __getattr__( self, aname ):
 266        """supported attributes by name are:
 267           - lineno - returns the line number of the exception text
 268           - col - returns the column number of the exception text
 269           - line - returns the line containing the exception text
 270        """
 271        if( aname == "lineno" ):
 272            return lineno( self.loc, self.pstr )
 273        elif( aname in ("col", "column") ):
 274            return col( self.loc, self.pstr )
 275        elif( aname == "line" ):
 276            return line( self.loc, self.pstr )
 277        else:
 278            raise AttributeError(aname)
 279
 280    def __str__( self ):
 281        return "%s (at char %d), (line:%d, col:%d)" % \
 282                ( self.msg, self.loc, self.lineno, self.column )
 283    def __repr__( self ):
 284        return _ustr(self)
 285    def markInputline( self, markerString = ">!<" ):
 286        """Extracts the exception line from the input string, and marks
 287           the location of the exception with a special symbol.
 288        """
 289        line_str = self.line
 290        line_column = self.column - 1
 291        if markerString:
 292            line_str = "".join((line_str[:line_column],
 293                                markerString, line_str[line_column:]))
 294        return line_str.strip()
 295    def __dir__(self):
 296        return "lineno col line".split() + dir(type(self))
 297
 298class ParseException(ParseBaseException):
 299    """
 300    Exception thrown when parse expressions don't match class;
 301    supported attributes by name are:
 302    - lineno - returns the line number of the exception text
 303    - col - returns the column number of the exception text
 304    - line - returns the line containing the exception text
 305
 306    Example::
 307
 308        try:
 309            Word(nums).setName("integer").parseString("ABC")
 310        except ParseException as pe:
 311            print(pe)
 312            print("column: {}".format(pe.col))
 313
 314    prints::
 315
 316       Expected integer (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
 317        column: 1
 318
 319    """
 320    pass
 321
 322class ParseFatalException(ParseBaseException):
 323    """user-throwable exception thrown when inconsistent parse content
 324       is found; stops all parsing immediately"""
 325    pass
 326
 327class ParseSyntaxException(ParseFatalException):
 328    """just like :class:`ParseFatalException`, but thrown internally
 329    when an :class:`ErrorStop<And._ErrorStop>` ('-' operator) indicates
 330    that parsing is to stop immediately because an unbacktrackable
 331    syntax error has been found.
 332    """
 333    pass
 334
 335#~ class ReparseException(ParseBaseException):
 336    #~ """Experimental class - parse actions can raise this exception to cause
 337       #~ pyparsing to reparse the input string:
 338        #~ - with a modified input string, and/or
 339        #~ - with a modified start location
 340       #~ Set the values of the ReparseException in the constructor, and raise the
 341       #~ exception in a parse action to cause pyparsing to use the new string/location.
 342       #~ Setting the values as None causes no change to be made.
 343       #~ """
 344    #~ def __init_( self, newstring, restartLoc ):
 345        #~ self.newParseText = newstring
 346        #~ self.reparseLoc = restartLoc
 347
 348class RecursiveGrammarException(Exception):
 349    """exception thrown by :class:`ParserElement.validate` if the
 350    grammar could be improperly recursive
 351    """
 352    def __init__( self, parseElementList ):
 353        self.parseElementTrace = parseElementList
 354
 355    def __str__( self ):
 356        return "RecursiveGrammarException: %s" % self.parseElementTrace
 357
 358class _ParseResultsWithOffset(object):
 359    def __init__(self,p1,p2):
 360        self.tup = (p1,p2)
 361    def __getitem__(self,i):
 362        return self.tup[i]
 363    def __repr__(self):
 364        return repr(self.tup[0])
 365    def setOffset(self,i):
 366        self.tup = (self.tup[0],i)
 367
 368class ParseResults(object):
 369    """Structured parse results, to provide multiple means of access to
 370    the parsed data:
 371
 372       - as a list (``len(results)``)
 373       - by list index (``results[0], results[1]``, etc.)
 374       - by attribute (``results.<resultsName>`` - see :class:`ParserElement.setResultsName`)
 375
 376    Example::
 377
 378        integer = Word(nums)
 379        date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
 380                        + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
 381                        + integer.setResultsName("day"))
 382        # equivalent form:
 383        # date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 384
 385        # parseString returns a ParseResults object
 386        result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")
 387
 388        def test(s, fn=repr):
 389            print("%s -> %s" % (s, fn(eval(s))))
 390        test("list(result)")
 391        test("result[0]")
 392        test("result['month']")
 393        test("result.day")
 394        test("'month' in result")
 395        test("'minutes' in result")
 396        test("result.dump()", str)
 397
 398    prints::
 399
 400        list(result) -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
 401        result[0] -> '1999'
 402        result['month'] -> '12'
 403        result.day -> '31'
 404        'month' in result -> True
 405        'minutes' in result -> False
 406        result.dump() -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
 407        - day: 31
 408        - month: 12
 409        - year: 1999
 410    """
 411    def __new__(cls, toklist=None, name=None, asList=True, modal=True ):
 412        if isinstance(toklist, cls):
 413            return toklist
 414        retobj = object.__new__(cls)
 415        retobj.__doinit = True
 416        return retobj
 417
 418    # Performance tuning: we construct a *lot* of these, so keep this
 419    # constructor as small and fast as possible
 420    def __init__( self, toklist=None, name=None, asList=True, modal=True, isinstance=isinstance ):
 421        if self.__doinit:
 422            self.__doinit = False
 423            self.__name = None
 424            self.__parent = None
 425            self.__accumNames = {}
 426            self.__asList = asList
 427            self.__modal = modal
 428            if toklist is None:
 429                toklist = []
 430            if isinstance(toklist, list):
 431                self.__toklist = toklist[:]
 432            elif isinstance(toklist, _generatorType):
 433                self.__toklist = list(toklist)
 434            else:
 435                self.__toklist = [toklist]
 436            self.__tokdict = dict()
 437
 438        if name is not None and name:
 439            if not modal:
 440                self.__accumNames[name] = 0
 441            if isinstance(name,int):
 442                name = _ustr(name) # will always return a str, but use _ustr for consistency
 443            self.__name = name
 444            if not (isinstance(toklist, (type(None), basestring, list)) and toklist in (None,'',[])):
 445                if isinstance(toklist,basestring):
 446                    toklist = [ toklist ]
 447                if asList:
 448                    if isinstance(toklist,ParseResults):
 449                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist.__toklist), 0)
 450                    else:
 451                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist[0]),0)
 452                    self[name].__name = name
 453                else:
 454                    try:
 455                        self[name] = toklist[0]
 456                    except (KeyError,TypeError,IndexError):
 457                        self[name] = toklist
 458
 459    def __getitem__( self, i ):
 460        if isinstance( i, (int,slice) ):
 461            return self.__toklist[i]
 462        else:
 463            if i not in self.__accumNames:
 464                return self.__tokdict[i][-1][0]
 465            else:
 466                return ParseResults([ v[0] for v in self.__tokdict[i] ])
 467
 468    def __setitem__( self, k, v, isinstance=isinstance ):
 469        if isinstance(v,_ParseResultsWithOffset):
 470            self.__tokdict[k] = self.__tokdict.get(k,list()) + [v]
 471            sub = v[0]
 472        elif isinstance(k,(int,slice)):
 473            self.__toklist[k] = v
 474            sub = v
 475        else:
 476            self.__tokdict[k] = self.__tokdict.get(k,list()) + [_ParseResultsWithOffset(v,0)]
 477            sub = v
 478        if isinstance(sub,ParseResults):
 479            sub.__parent = wkref(self)
 480
 481    def __delitem__( self, i ):
 482        if isinstance(i,(int,slice)):
 483            mylen = len( self.__toklist )
 484            del self.__toklist[i]
 485
 486            # convert int to slice
 487            if isinstance(i, int):
 488                if i < 0:
 489                    i += mylen
 490                i = slice(i, i+1)
 491            # get removed indices
 492            removed = list(range(*i.indices(mylen)))
 493            removed.reverse()
 494            # fixup indices in token dictionary
 495            for name,occurrences in self.__tokdict.items():
 496                for j in removed:
 497                    for k, (value, position) in enumerate(occurrences):
 498                        occurrences[k] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(value, position - (position > j))
 499        else:
 500            del self.__tokdict[i]
 501
 502    def __contains__( self, k ):
 503        return k in self.__tokdict
 504
 505    def __len__( self ): return len( self.__toklist )
 506    def __bool__(self): return ( not not self.__toklist )
 507    __nonzero__ = __bool__
 508    def __iter__( self ): return iter( self.__toklist )
 509    def __reversed__( self ): return iter( self.__toklist[::-1] )
 510    def _iterkeys( self ):
 511        if hasattr(self.__tokdict, "iterkeys"):
 512            return self.__tokdict.iterkeys()
 513        else:
 514            return iter(self.__tokdict)
 515
 516    def _itervalues( self ):
 517        return (self[k] for k in self._iterkeys())
 518
 519    def _iteritems( self ):
 520        return ((k, self[k]) for k in self._iterkeys())
 521
 522    if PY_3:
 523        keys = _iterkeys
 524        """Returns an iterator of all named result keys (Python 3.x only)."""
 525
 526        values = _itervalues
 527        """Returns an iterator of all named result values (Python 3.x only)."""
 528
 529        items = _iteritems
 530        """Returns an iterator of all named result key-value tuples (Python 3.x only)."""
 531
 532    else:
 533        iterkeys = _iterkeys
 534        """Returns an iterator of all named result keys (Python 2.x only)."""
 535
 536        itervalues = _itervalues
 537        """Returns an iterator of all named result values (Python 2.x only)."""
 538
 539        iteritems = _iteritems
 540        """Returns an iterator of all named result key-value tuples (Python 2.x only)."""
 541
 542        def keys( self ):
 543            """Returns all named result keys (as a list in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 544            return list(self.iterkeys())
 545
 546        def values( self ):
 547            """Returns all named result values (as a list in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 548            return list(self.itervalues())
 549
 550        def items( self ):
 551            """Returns all named result key-values (as a list of tuples in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 552            return list(self.iteritems())
 553
 554    def haskeys( self ):
 555        """Since keys() returns an iterator, this method is helpful in bypassing
 556           code that looks for the existence of any defined results names."""
 557        return bool(self.__tokdict)
 558
 559    def pop( self, *args, **kwargs):
 560        """
 561        Removes and returns item at specified index (default= ``last``).
 562        Supports both ``list`` and ``dict`` semantics for ``pop()``. If
 563        passed no argument or an integer argument, it will use ``list``
 564        semantics and pop tokens from the list of parsed tokens. If passed
 565        a non-integer argument (most likely a string), it will use ``dict``
 566        semantics and pop the corresponding value from any defined results
 567        names. A second default return value argument is supported, just as in
 568        ``dict.pop()``.
 569
 570        Example::
 571
 572            def remove_first(tokens):
 573                tokens.pop(0)
 574            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 575            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(remove_first).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['123', '321']
 576
 577            label = Word(alphas)
 578            patt = label("LABEL") + OneOrMore(Word(nums))
 579            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
 580
 581            # Use pop() in a parse action to remove named result (note that corresponding value is not
 582            # removed from list form of results)
 583            def remove_LABEL(tokens):
 584                tokens.pop("LABEL")
 585                return tokens
 586            patt.addParseAction(remove_LABEL)
 587            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
 588
 589        prints::
 590
 591            ['AAB', '123', '321']
 592            - LABEL: AAB
 593
 594            ['AAB', '123', '321']
 595        """
 596        if not args:
 597            args = [-1]
 598        for k,v in kwargs.items():
 599            if k == 'default':
 600                args = (args[0], v)
 601            else:
 602                raise TypeError("pop() got an unexpected keyword argument '%s'" % k)
 603        if (isinstance(args[0], int) or
 604                        len(args) == 1 or
 605                        args[0] in self):
 606            index = args[0]
 607            ret = self[index]
 608            del self[index]
 609            return ret
 610        else:
 611            defaultvalue = args[1]
 612            return defaultvalue
 613
 614    def get(self, key, defaultValue=None):
 615        """
 616        Returns named result matching the given key, or if there is no
 617        such name, then returns the given ``defaultValue`` or ``None`` if no
 618        ``defaultValue`` is specified.
 619
 620        Similar to ``dict.get()``.
 621
 622        Example::
 623
 624            integer = Word(nums)
 625            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 626
 627            result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")
 628            print(result.get("year")) # -> '1999'
 629            print(result.get("hour", "not specified")) # -> 'not specified'
 630            print(result.get("hour")) # -> None
 631        """
 632        if key in self:
 633            return self[key]
 634        else:
 635            return defaultValue
 636
 637    def insert( self, index, insStr ):
 638        """
 639        Inserts new element at location index in the list of parsed tokens.
 640
 641        Similar to ``list.insert()``.
 642
 643        Example::
 644
 645            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 646
 647            # use a parse action to insert the parse location in the front of the parsed results
 648            def insert_locn(locn, tokens):
 649                tokens.insert(0, locn)
 650            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(insert_locn).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> [0, '0', '123', '321']
 651        """
 652        self.__toklist.insert(index, insStr)
 653        # fixup indices in token dictionary
 654        for name,occurrences in self.__tokdict.items():
 655            for k, (value, position) in enumerate(occurrences):
 656                occurrences[k] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(value, position + (position > index))
 657
 658    def append( self, item ):
 659        """
 660        Add single element to end of ParseResults list of elements.
 661
 662        Example::
 663
 664            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 665
 666            # use a parse action to compute the sum of the parsed integers, and add it to the end
 667            def append_sum(tokens):
 668                tokens.append(sum(map(int, tokens)))
 669            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(append_sum).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321', 444]
 670        """
 671        self.__toklist.append(item)
 672
 673    def extend( self, itemseq ):
 674        """
 675        Add sequence of elements to end of ParseResults list of elements.
 676
 677        Example::
 678
 679            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
 680
 681            # use a parse action to append the reverse of the matched strings, to make a palindrome
 682            def make_palindrome(tokens):
 683                tokens.extend(reversed([t[::-1] for t in tokens]))
 684                return ''.join(tokens)
 685            print(patt.addParseAction(make_palindrome).parseString("lskdj sdlkjf lksd")) # -> 'lskdjsdlkjflksddsklfjkldsjdksl'
 686        """
 687        if isinstance(itemseq, ParseResults):
 688            self += itemseq
 689        else:
 690            self.__toklist.extend(itemseq)
 691
 692    def clear( self ):
 693        """
 694        Clear all elements and results names.
 695        """
 696        del self.__toklist[:]
 697        self.__tokdict.clear()
 698
 699    def __getattr__( self, name ):
 700        try:
 701            return self[name]
 702        except KeyError:
 703            return ""
 704
 705        if name in self.__tokdict:
 706            if name not in self.__accumNames:
 707                return self.__tokdict[name][-1][0]
 708            else:
 709                return ParseResults([ v[0] for v in self.__tokdict[name] ])
 710        else:
 711            return ""
 712
 713    def __add__( self, other ):
 714        ret = self.copy()
 715        ret += other
 716        return ret
 717
 718    def __iadd__( self, other ):
 719        if other.__tokdict:
 720            offset = len(self.__toklist)
 721            addoffset = lambda a: offset if a<0 else a+offset
 722            otheritems = other.__tokdict.items()
 723            otherdictitems = [(k, _ParseResultsWithOffset(v[0],addoffset(v[1])) )
 724                                for (k,vlist) in otheritems for v in vlist]
 725            for k,v in otherdictitems:
 726                self[k] = v
 727                if isinstance(v[0],ParseResults):
 728                    v[0].__parent = wkref(self)
 729
 730        self.__toklist += other.__toklist
 731        self.__accumNames.update( other.__accumNames )
 732        return self
 733
 734    def __radd__(self, other):
 735        if isinstance(other,int) and other == 0:
 736            # useful for merging many ParseResults using sum() builtin
 737            return self.copy()
 738        else:
 739            # this may raise a TypeError - so be it
 740            return other + self
 741
 742    def __repr__( self ):
 743        return "(%s, %s)" % ( repr( self.__toklist ), repr( self.__tokdict ) )
 744
 745    def __str__( self ):
 746        return '[' + ', '.join(_ustr(i) if isinstance(i, ParseResults) else repr(i) for i in self.__toklist) + ']'
 747
 748    def _asStringList( self, sep='' ):
 749        out = []
 750        for item in self.__toklist:
 751            if out and sep:
 752                out.append(sep)
 753            if isinstance( item, ParseResults ):
 754                out += item._asStringList()
 755            else:
 756                out.append( _ustr(item) )
 757        return out
 758
 759    def asList( self ):
 760        """
 761        Returns the parse results as a nested list of matching tokens, all converted to strings.
 762
 763        Example::
 764
 765            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
 766            result = patt.parseString("sldkj lsdkj sldkj")
 767            # even though the result prints in string-like form, it is actually a pyparsing ParseResults
 768            print(type(result), result) # -> <class 'pyparsing.ParseResults'> ['sldkj', 'lsdkj', 'sldkj']
 769
 770            # Use asList() to create an actual list
 771            result_list = result.asList()
 772            print(type(result_list), result_list) # -> <class 'list'> ['sldkj', 'lsdkj', 'sldkj']
 773        """
 774        return [res.asList() if isinstance(res,ParseResults) else res for res in self.__toklist]
 775
 776    def asDict( self ):
 777        """
 778        Returns the named parse results as a nested dictionary.
 779
 780        Example::
 781
 782            integer = Word(nums)
 783            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 784
 785            result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
 786            print(type(result), repr(result)) # -> <class 'pyparsing.ParseResults'> (['12', '/', '31', '/', '1999'], {'day': [('1999', 4)], 'year': [('12', 0)], 'month': [('31', 2)]})
 787
 788            result_dict = result.asDict()
 789            print(type(result_dict), repr(result_dict)) # -> <class 'dict'> {'day': '1999', 'year': '12', 'month': '31'}
 790
 791            # even though a ParseResults supports dict-like access, sometime you just need to have a dict
 792            import json
 793            print(json.dumps(result)) # -> Exception: TypeError: ... is not JSON serializable
 794            print(json.dumps(result.asDict())) # -> {"month": "31", "day": "1999", "year": "12"}
 795        """
 796        if PY_3:
 797            item_fn = self.items
 798        else:
 799            item_fn = self.iteritems
 800
 801        def toItem(obj):
 802            if isinstance(obj, ParseResults):
 803                if obj.haskeys():
 804                    return obj.asDict()
 805                else:
 806                    return [toItem(v) for v in obj]
 807            else:
 808                return obj
 809
 810        return dict((k,toItem(v)) for k,v in item_fn())
 811
 812    def copy( self ):
 813        """
 814        Returns a new copy of a :class:`ParseResults` object.
 815        """
 816        ret = ParseResults( self.__toklist )
 817        ret.__tokdict = dict(self.__tokdict.items())
 818        ret.__parent = self.__parent
 819        ret.__accumNames.update( self.__accumNames )
 820        ret.__name = self.__name
 821        return ret
 822
 823    def asXML( self, doctag=None, namedItemsOnly=False, indent="", formatted=True ):
 824        """
 825        (Deprecated) Returns the parse results as XML. Tags are created for tokens and lists that have defined results names.
 826        """
 827        nl = "\n"
 828        out = []
 829        namedItems = dict((v[1],k) for (k,vlist) in self.__tokdict.items()
 830                                                            for v in vlist)
 831        nextLevelIndent = indent + "  "
 832
 833        # collapse out indents if formatting is not desired
 834        if not formatted:
 835            indent = ""
 836            nextLevelIndent = ""
 837            nl = ""
 838
 839        selfTag = None
 840        if doctag is not None:
 841            selfTag = doctag
 842        else:
 843            if self.__name:
 844                selfTag = self.__name
 845
 846        if not selfTag:
 847            if namedItemsOnly:
 848                return ""
 849            else:
 850                selfTag = "ITEM"
 851
 852        out += [ nl, indent, "<", selfTag, ">" ]
 853
 854        for i,res in enumerate(self.__toklist):
 855            if isinstance(res,ParseResults):
 856                if i in namedItems:
 857                    out += [ res.asXML(namedItems[i],
 858                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
 859                                        nextLevelIndent,
 860                                        formatted)]
 861                else:
 862                    out += [ res.asXML(None,
 863                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
 864                                        nextLevelIndent,
 865                                        formatted)]
 866            else:
 867                # individual token, see if there is a name for it
 868                resTag = None
 869                if i in namedItems:
 870                    resTag = namedItems[i]
 871                if not resTag:
 872                    if namedItemsOnly:
 873                        continue
 874                    else:
 875                        resTag = "ITEM"
 876                xmlBodyText = _xml_escape(_ustr(res))
 877                out += [ nl, nextLevelIndent, "<", resTag, ">",
 878                                                xmlBodyText,
 879                                                "</", resTag, ">" ]
 880
 881        out += [ nl, indent, "</", selfTag, ">" ]
 882        return "".join(out)
 883
 884    def __lookup(self,sub):
 885        for k,vlist in self.__tokdict.items():
 886            for v,loc in vlist:
 887                if sub is v:
 888                    return k
 889        return None
 890
 891    def getName(self):
 892        r"""
 893        Returns the results name for this token expression. Useful when several
 894        different expressions might match at a particular location.
 895
 896        Example::
 897
 898            integer = Word(nums)
 899            ssn_expr = Regex(r"\d\d\d-\d\d-\d\d\d\d")
 900            house_number_expr = Suppress('#') + Word(nums, alphanums)
 901            user_data = (Group(house_number_expr)("house_number")
 902                        | Group(ssn_expr)("ssn")
 903                        | Group(integer)("age"))
 904            user_info = OneOrMore(user_data)
 905
 906            result = user_info.parseString("22 111-22-3333 #221B")
 907            for item in result:
 908                print(item.getName(), ':', item[0])
 909
 910        prints::
 911
 912            age : 22
 913            ssn : 111-22-3333
 914            house_number : 221B
 915        """
 916        if self.__name:
 917            return self.__name
 918        elif self.__parent:
 919            par = self.__parent()
 920            if par:
 921                return par.__lookup(self)
 922            else:
 923                return None
 924        elif (len(self) == 1 and
 925               len(self.__tokdict) == 1 and
 926               next(iter(self.__tokdict.values()))[0][1] in (0,-1)):
 927            return next(iter(self.__tokdict.keys()))
 928        else:
 929            return None
 930
 931    def dump(self, indent='', depth=0, full=True):
 932        """
 933        Diagnostic method for listing out the contents of
 934        a :class:`ParseResults`. Accepts an optional ``indent`` argument so
 935        that this string can be embedded in a nested display of other data.
 936
 937        Example::
 938
 939            integer = Word(nums)
 940            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 941
 942            result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
 943            print(result.dump())
 944
 945        prints::
 946
 947            ['12', '/', '31', '/', '1999']
 948            - day: 1999
 949            - month: 31
 950            - year: 12
 951        """
 952        out = []
 953        NL = '\n'
 954        out.append( indent+_ustr(self.asList()) )
 955        if full:
 956            if self.haskeys():
 957                items = sorted((str(k), v) for k,v in self.items())
 958                for k,v in items:
 959                    if out:
 960                        out.append(NL)
 961                    out.append( "%s%s- %s: " % (indent,('  '*depth), k) )
 962                    if isinstance(v,ParseResults):
 963                        if v:
 964                            out.append( v.dump(indent,depth+1) )
 965                        else:
 966                            out.append(_ustr(v))
 967                    else:
 968                        out.append(repr(v))
 969            elif any(isinstance(vv,ParseResults) for vv in self):
 970                v = self
 971                for i,vv in enumerate(v):
 972                    if isinstance(vv,ParseResults):
 973                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),vv.dump(indent,depth+1) ))
 974                    else:
 975                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),_ustr(vv)))
 976
 977        return "".join(out)
 978
 979    def pprint(self, *args, **kwargs):
 980        """
 981        Pretty-printer for parsed results as a list, using the
 982        `pprint <http://docs.python.org/3/library/pprint.html>`_ module.
 983        Accepts additional positional or keyword args as defined for
 984        `pprint.pprint <http://docs.python.org/3/library/pprint.html#pprint.pprint>`_ .
 985
 986        Example::
 987
 988            ident = Word(alphas, alphanums)
 989            num = Word(nums)
 990            func = Forward()
 991            term = ident | num | Group('(' + func + ')')
 992            func <<= ident + Group(Optional(delimitedList(term)))
 993            result = func.parseString("fna a,b,(fnb c,d,200),100")
 994            result.pprint(width=40)
 995
 996        prints::
 997
 998            ['fna',
 999             ['a',
1000              'b',
1001              ['(', 'fnb', ['c', 'd', '200'], ')'],
1002              '100']]
1003        """
1004        pprint.pprint(self.asList(), *args, **kwargs)
1005
1006    # add support for pickle protocol
1007    def __getstate__(self):
1008        return ( self.__toklist,
1009                 ( self.__tokdict.copy(),
1010                   self.__parent is not None and self.__parent() or None,
1011                   self.__accumNames,
1012                   self.__name ) )
1013
1014    def __setstate__(self,state):
1015        self.__toklist = state[0]
1016        (self.__tokdict,
1017         par,
1018         inAccumNames,
1019         self.__name) = state[1]
1020        self.__accumNames = {}
1021        self.__accumNames.update(inAccumNames)
1022        if par is not None:
1023            self.__parent = wkref(par)
1024        else:
1025            self.__parent = None
1026
1027    def __getnewargs__(self):
1028        return self.__toklist, self.__name, self.__asList, self.__modal
1029
1030    def __dir__(self):
1031        return (dir(type(self)) + list(self.keys()))
1032
1033MutableMapping.register(ParseResults)
1034
1035def col (loc,strg):
1036    """Returns current column within a string, counting newlines as line separators.
1037   The first column is number 1.
1038
1039   Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1040   before starting the parsing process.  See
1041   :class:`ParserElement.parseString` for more
1042   information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and suggested
1043   methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse
1044   location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1045   """
1046    s = strg
1047    return 1 if 0<loc<len(s) and s[loc-1] == '\n' else loc - s.rfind("\n", 0, loc)
1048
1049def lineno(loc,strg):
1050    """Returns current line number within a string, counting newlines as line separators.
1051    The first line is number 1.
1052
1053    Note - the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1054    before starting the parsing process.  See :class:`ParserElement.parseString`
1055    for more information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and
1056    suggested methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the
1057    parse location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1058    """
1059    return strg.count("\n",0,loc) + 1
1060
1061def line( loc, strg ):
1062    """Returns the line of text containing loc within a string, counting newlines as line separators.
1063       """
1064    lastCR = strg.rfind("\n", 0, loc)
1065    nextCR = strg.find("\n", loc)
1066    if nextCR >= 0:
1067        return strg[lastCR+1:nextCR]
1068    else:
1069        return strg[lastCR+1:]
1070
1071def _defaultStartDebugAction( instring, loc, expr ):
1072    print (("Match " + _ustr(expr) + " at loc " + _ustr(loc) + "(%d,%d)" % ( lineno(loc,instring), col(loc,instring) )))
1073
1074def _defaultSuccessDebugAction( instring, startloc, endloc, expr, toks ):
1075    print ("Matched " + _ustr(expr) + " -> " + str(toks.asList()))
1076
1077def _defaultExceptionDebugAction( instring, loc, expr, exc ):
1078    print ("Exception raised:" + _ustr(exc))
1079
1080def nullDebugAction(*args):
1081    """'Do-nothing' debug action, to suppress debugging output during parsing."""
1082    pass
1083
1084# Only works on Python 3.x - nonlocal is toxic to Python 2 installs
1085#~ 'decorator to trim function calls to match the arity of the target'
1086#~ def _trim_arity(func, maxargs=3):
1087    #~ if func in singleArgBuiltins:
1088        #~ return lambda s,l,t: func(t)
1089    #~ limit = 0
1090    #~ foundArity = False
1091    #~ def wrapper(*args):
1092        #~ nonlocal limit,foundArity
1093        #~ while 1:
1094            #~ try:
1095                #~ ret = func(*args[limit:])
1096                #~ foundArity = True
1097                #~ return ret
1098            #~ except TypeError:
1099                #~ if limit == maxargs or foundArity:
1100                    #~ raise
1101                #~ limit += 1
1102                #~ continue
1103    #~ return wrapper
1104
1105# this version is Python 2.x-3.x cross-compatible
1106'decorator to trim function calls to match the arity of the target'
1107def _trim_arity(func, maxargs=2):
1108    if func in singleArgBuiltins:
1109        return lambda s,l,t: func(t)
1110    limit = [0]
1111    foundArity = [False]
1112
1113    # traceback return data structure changed in Py3.5 - normalize back to plain tuples
1114    if system_version[:2] >= (3,5):
1115        def extract_stack(limit=0):
1116            # special handling for Python 3.5.0 - extra deep call stack by 1
1117            offset = -3 if system_version == (3,5,0) else -2
1118            frame_summary = traceback.extract_stack(limit=-offset+limit-1)[offset]
1119            return [frame_summary[:2]]
1120        def extract_tb(tb, limit=0):
1121            frames = traceback.extract_tb(tb, limit=limit)
1122            frame_summary = frames[-1]
1123            return [frame_summary[:2]]
1124    else:
1125        extract_stack = traceback.extract_stack
1126        extract_tb = traceback.extract_tb
1127
1128    # synthesize what would be returned by traceback.extract_stack at the call to
1129    # user's parse action 'func', so that we don't incur call penalty at parse time
1130
1131    LINE_DIFF = 6
1132    # IF ANY CODE CHANGES, EVEN JUST COMMENTS OR BLANK LINES, BETWEEN THE NEXT LINE AND
1133    # THE CALL TO FUNC INSIDE WRAPPER, LINE_DIFF MUST BE MODIFIED!!!!
1134    this_line = extract_stack(limit=2)[-1]
1135    pa_call_line_synth = (this_line[0], this_line[1]+LINE_DIFF)
1136
1137    def wrapper(*args):
1138        while 1:
1139            try:
1140                ret = func(*args[limit[0]:])
1141                foundArity[0] = True
1142                return ret
1143            except TypeError:
1144                # re-raise TypeErrors if they did not come from our arity testing
1145                if foundArity[0]:
1146                    raise
1147                else:
1148                    try:
1149                        tb = sys.exc_info()[-1]
1150                        if not extract_tb(tb, limit=2)[-1][:2] == pa_call_line_synth:
1151                            raise
1152                    finally:
1153                        del tb
1154
1155                if limit[0] <= maxargs:
1156                    limit[0] += 1
1157                    continue
1158                raise
1159
1160    # copy func name to wrapper for sensible debug output
1161    func_name = "<parse action>"
1162    try:
1163        func_name = getattr(func, '__name__',
1164                            getattr(func, '__class__').__name__)
1165    except Exception:
1166        func_name = str(func)
1167    wrapper.__name__ = func_name
1168
1169    return wrapper
1170
1171class ParserElement(object):
1172    """Abstract base level parser element class."""
1173    DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS = " \n\t\r"
1174    verbose_stacktrace = False
1175
1176    @staticmethod
1177    def setDefaultWhitespaceChars( chars ):
1178        r"""
1179        Overrides the default whitespace chars
1180
1181        Example::
1182
1183            # default whitespace chars are space, <TAB> and newline
1184            OneOrMore(Word(alphas)).parseString("abc def\nghi jkl")  # -> ['abc', 'def', 'ghi', 'jkl']
1185
1186            # change to just treat newline as significant
1187            ParserElement.setDefaultWhitespaceChars(" \t")
1188            OneOrMore(Word(alphas)).parseString("abc def\nghi jkl")  # -> ['abc', 'def']
1189        """
1190        ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS = chars
1191
1192    @staticmethod
1193    def inlineLiteralsUsing(cls):
1194        """
1195        Set class to be used for inclusion of string literals into a parser.
1196
1197        Example::
1198
1199            # default literal class used is Literal
1200            integer = Word(nums)
1201            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1202
1203            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
1204
1205
1206            # change to Suppress
1207            ParserElement.inlineLiteralsUsing(Suppress)
1208            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1209
1210            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '12', '31']
1211        """
1212        ParserElement._literalStringClass = cls
1213
1214    def __init__( self, savelist=False ):
1215        self.parseAction = list()
1216        self.failAction = None
1217        #~ self.name = "<unknown>"  # don't define self.name, let subclasses try/except upcall
1218        self.strRepr = None
1219        self.resultsName = None
1220        self.saveAsList = savelist
1221        self.skipWhitespace = True
1222        self.whiteChars = ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
1223        self.copyDefaultWhiteChars = True
1224        self.mayReturnEmpty = False # used when checking for left-recursion
1225        self.keepTabs = False
1226        self.ignoreExprs = list()
1227        self.debug = False
1228        self.streamlined = False
1229        self.mayIndexError = True # used to optimize exception handling for subclasses that don't advance parse index
1230        self.errmsg = ""
1231        self.modalResults = True # used to mark results names as modal (report only last) or cumulative (list all)
1232        self.debugActions = ( None, None, None ) #custom debug actions
1233        self.re = None
1234        self.callPreparse = True # used to avoid redundant calls to preParse
1235        self.callDuringTry = False
1236
1237    def copy( self ):
1238        """
1239        Make a copy of this :class:`ParserElement`.  Useful for defining
1240        different parse actions for the same parsing pattern, using copies of
1241        the original parse element.
1242
1243        Example::
1244
1245            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1246            integerK = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024) + Suppress("K")
1247            integerM = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")
1248
1249            print(OneOrMore(integerK | integerM | integer).parseString("5K 100 640K 256M"))
1250
1251        prints::
1252
1253            [5120, 100, 655360, 268435456]
1254
1255        Equivalent form of ``expr.copy()`` is just ``expr()``::
1256
1257            integerM = integer().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")
1258        """
1259        cpy = copy.copy( self )
1260        cpy.parseAction = self.parseAction[:]
1261        cpy.ignoreExprs = self.ignoreExprs[:]
1262        if self.copyDefaultWhiteChars:
1263            cpy.whiteChars = ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
1264        return cpy
1265
1266    def setName( self, name ):
1267        """
1268        Define name for this expression, makes debugging and exception messages clearer.
1269
1270        Example::
1271
1272            Word(nums).parseString("ABC")  # -> Exception: Expected W:(0123...) (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1273            Word(nums).setName("integer").parseString("ABC")  # -> Exception: Expected integer (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1274        """
1275        self.name = name
1276        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
1277        if hasattr(self,"exception"):
1278            self.exception.msg = self.errmsg
1279        return self
1280
1281    def setResultsName( self, name, listAllMatches=False ):
1282        """
1283        Define name for referencing matching tokens as a nested attribute
1284        of the returned parse results.
1285        NOTE: this returns a *copy* of the original :class:`ParserElement` object;
1286        this is so that the client can define a basic element, such as an
1287        integer, and reference it in multiple places with different names.
1288
1289        You can also set results names using the abbreviated syntax,
1290        ``expr("name")`` in place of ``expr.setResultsName("name")``
1291        - see :class:`__call__`.
1292
1293        Example::
1294
1295            date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
1296                        + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
1297                        + integer.setResultsName("day"))
1298
1299            # equivalent form:
1300            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1301        """
1302        newself = self.copy()
1303        if name.endswith("*"):
1304            name = name[:-1]
1305            listAllMatches=True
1306        newself.resultsName = name
1307        newself.modalResults = not listAllMatches
1308        return newself
1309
1310    def setBreak(self,breakFlag = True):
1311        """Method to invoke the Python pdb debugger when this element is
1312           about to be parsed. Set ``breakFlag`` to True to enable, False to
1313           disable.
1314        """
1315        if breakFlag:
1316            _parseMethod = self._parse
1317            def breaker(instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True):
1318                import pdb
1319                pdb.set_trace()
1320                return _parseMethod( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse )
1321            breaker._originalParseMethod = _parseMethod
1322            self._parse = breaker
1323        else:
1324            if hasattr(self._parse,"_originalParseMethod"):
1325                self._parse = self._parse._originalParseMethod
1326        return self
1327
1328    def setParseAction( self, *fns, **kwargs ):
1329        """
1330        Define one or more actions to perform when successfully matching parse element definition.
1331        Parse action fn is a callable method with 0-3 arguments, called as ``fn(s,loc,toks)`` ,
1332        ``fn(loc,toks)`` , ``fn(toks)`` , or just ``fn()`` , where:
1333
1334        - s   = the original string being parsed (see note below)
1335        - loc = the location of the matching substring
1336        - toks = a list of the matched tokens, packaged as a :class:`ParseResults` object
1337
1338        If the functions in fns modify the tokens, they can return them as the return
1339        value from fn, and the modified list of tokens will replace the original.
1340        Otherwise, fn does not need to return any value.
1341
1342        Optional keyword arguments:
1343        - callDuringTry = (default= ``False`` ) indicate if parse action should be run during lookaheads and alternate testing
1344
1345        Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1346        before starting the parsing process.  See :class:`parseString for more
1347        information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and suggested
1348        methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse
1349        location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1350
1351        Example::
1352
1353            integer = Word(nums)
1354            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1355
1356            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
1357
1358            # use parse action to convert to ints at parse time
1359            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1360            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1361
1362            # note that integer fields are now ints, not strings
1363            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> [1999, '/', 12, '/', 31]
1364        """
1365        self.parseAction = list(map(_trim_arity, list(fns)))
1366        self.callDuringTry = kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1367        return self
1368
1369    def addParseAction( self, *fns, **kwargs ):
1370        """
1371        Add one or more parse actions to expression's list of parse actions. See :class:`setParseAction`.
1372
1373        See examples in :class:`copy`.
1374        """
1375        self.parseAction += list(map(_trim_arity, list(fns)))
1376        self.callDuringTry = self.callDuringTry or kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1377        return self
1378
1379    def addCondition(self, *fns, **kwargs):
1380        """Add a boolean predicate function to expression's list of parse actions. See
1381        :class:`setParseAction` for function call signatures. Unlike ``setParseAction``,
1382        functions passed to ``addCondition`` need to return boolean success/fail of the condition.
1383
1384        Optional keyword arguments:
1385        - message = define a custom message to be used in the raised exception
1386        - fatal   = if True, will raise ParseFatalException to stop parsing immediately; otherwise will raise ParseException
1387
1388        Example::
1389
1390            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1391            year_int = integer.copy()
1392            year_int.addCondition(lambda toks: toks[0] >= 2000, message="Only support years 2000 and later")
1393            date_str = year_int + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1394
1395            result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> Exception: Only support years 2000 and later (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1396        """
1397        msg = kwargs.get("message", "failed user-defined condition")
1398        exc_type = ParseFatalException if kwargs.get("fatal", False) else ParseException
1399        for fn in fns:
1400            def pa(s,l,t):
1401                if not bool(_trim_arity(fn)(s,l,t)):
1402                    raise exc_type(s,l,msg)
1403            self.parseAction.append(pa)
1404        self.callDuringTry = self.callDuringTry or kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1405        return self
1406
1407    def setFailAction( self, fn ):
1408        """Define action to perform if parsing fails at this expression.
1409           Fail acton fn is a callable function that takes the arguments
1410           ``fn(s,loc,expr,err)`` where:
1411           - s = string being parsed
1412           - loc = location where expression match was attempted and failed
1413           - expr = the parse expression that failed
1414           - err = the exception thrown
1415           The function returns no value.  It may throw :class:`ParseFatalException`
1416           if it is desired to stop parsing immediately."""
1417        self.failAction = fn
1418        return self
1419
1420    def _skipIgnorables( self, instring, loc ):
1421        exprsFound = True
1422        while exprsFound:
1423            exprsFound = False
1424            for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1425                try:
1426                    while 1:
1427                        loc,dummy = e._parse( instring, loc )
1428                        exprsFound = True
1429                except ParseException:
1430                    pass
1431        return loc
1432
1433    def preParse( self, instring, loc ):
1434        if self.ignoreExprs:
1435            loc = self._skipIgnorables( instring, loc )
1436
1437        if self.skipWhitespace:
1438            wt = self.whiteChars
1439            instrlen = len(instring)
1440            while loc < instrlen and instring[loc] in wt:
1441                loc += 1
1442
1443        return loc
1444
1445    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
1446        return loc, []
1447
1448    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
1449        return tokenlist
1450
1451    #~ @profile
1452    def _parseNoCache( self, instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True ):
1453        debugging = ( self.debug ) #and doActions )
1454
1455        if debugging or self.failAction:
1456            #~ print ("Match",self,"at loc",loc,"(%d,%d)" % ( lineno(loc,instring), col(loc,instring) ))
1457            if (self.debugActions[0] ):
1458                self.debugActions[0]( instring, loc, self )
1459            if callPreParse and self.callPreparse:
1460                preloc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1461            else:
1462                preloc = loc
1463            tokensStart = preloc
1464            try:
1465                try:
1466                    loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1467                except IndexError:
1468                    raise ParseException( instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self )
1469            except ParseBaseException as err:
1470                #~ print ("Exception raised:", err)
1471                if self.debugActions[2]:
1472                    self.debugActions[2]( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1473                if self.failAction:
1474                    self.failAction( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1475                raise
1476        else:
1477            if callPreParse and self.callPreparse:
1478                preloc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1479            else:
1480                preloc = loc
1481            tokensStart = preloc
1482            if self.mayIndexError or preloc >= len(instring):
1483                try:
1484                    loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1485                except IndexError:
1486                    raise ParseException( instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self )
1487            else:
1488                loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1489
1490        tokens = self.postParse( instring, loc, tokens )
1491
1492        retTokens = ParseResults( tokens, self.resultsName, asList=self.saveAsList, modal=self.modalResults )
1493        if self.parseAction and (doActions or self.callDuringTry):
1494            if debugging:
1495                try:
1496                    for fn in self.parseAction:
1497                        try:
1498                            tokens = fn( instring, tokensStart, retTokens )
1499                        except IndexError as parse_action_exc:
1500                            exc = ParseException("exception raised in parse action")
1501                            exc.__cause__ = parse_action_exc
1502                            raise exc
1503
1504                        if tokens is not None and tokens is not retTokens:
1505                            retTokens = ParseResults( tokens,
1506                                                      self.resultsName,
1507                                                      asList=self.saveAsList and isinstance(tokens,(ParseResults,list)),
1508                                                      modal=self.modalResults )
1509                except ParseBaseException as err:
1510                    #~ print "Exception raised in user parse action:", err
1511                    if (self.debugActions[2] ):
1512                        self.debugActions[2]( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1513                    raise
1514            else:
1515                for fn in self.parseAction:
1516                    try:
1517                        tokens = fn( instring, tokensStart, retTokens )
1518                    except IndexError as parse_action_exc:
1519                        exc = ParseException("exception raised in parse action")
1520                        exc.__cause__ = parse_action_exc
1521                        raise exc
1522
1523                    if tokens is not None and tokens is not retTokens:
1524                        retTokens = ParseResults( tokens,
1525                                                  self.resultsName,
1526                                                  asList=self.saveAsList and isinstance(tokens,(ParseResults,list)),
1527                                                  modal=self.modalResults )
1528        if debugging:
1529            #~ print ("Matched",self,"->",retTokens.asList())
1530            if (self.debugActions[1] ):
1531                self.debugActions[1]( instring, tokensStart, loc, self, retTokens )
1532
1533        return loc, retTokens
1534
1535    def tryParse( self, instring, loc ):
1536        try:
1537            return self._parse( instring, loc, doActions=False )[0]
1538        except ParseFatalException:
1539            raise ParseException( instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
1540
1541    def canParseNext(self, instring, loc):
1542        try:
1543            self.tryParse(instring, loc)
1544        except (ParseException, IndexError):
1545            return False
1546        else:
1547            return True
