1549    class _UnboundedCache(object):
1550        def __init__(self):
1551            cache = {}
1552            self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1553
1554            def get(self, key):
1555                return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1556
1557            def set(self, key, value):
1558                cache[key] = value
1559
1560            def clear(self):
1561                cache.clear()
1562
1563            def cache_len(self):
1564                return len(cache)
1565
1566            self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1567            self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1568            self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1569            self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1570
1571    if _OrderedDict is not None:
1572        class _FifoCache(object):
1573            def __init__(self, size):
1574                self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1575
1576                cache = _OrderedDict()
1577
1578                def get(self, key):
1579                    return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1580
1581                def set(self, key, value):
1582                    cache[key] = value
1583                    while len(cache) > size:
1584                        try:
1585                            cache.popitem(False)
1586                        except KeyError:
1587                            pass
1588
1589                def clear(self):
1590                    cache.clear()
1591
1592                def cache_len(self):
1593                    return len(cache)
1594
1595                self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1596                self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1597                self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1598                self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1599
1600    else:
1601        class _FifoCache(object):
1602            def __init__(self, size):
1603                self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1604
1605                cache = {}
1606                key_fifo = collections.deque([], size)
1607
1608                def get(self, key):
1609                    return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1610
1611                def set(self, key, value):
1612                    cache[key] = value
1613                    while len(key_fifo) > size:
1614                        cache.pop(key_fifo.popleft(), None)
1615                    key_fifo.append(key)
1616
1617                def clear(self):
1618                    cache.clear()
1619                    key_fifo.clear()
1620
1621                def cache_len(self):
1622                    return len(cache)
1623
1624                self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1625                self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1626                self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1627                self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1628
1629    # argument cache for optimizing repeated calls when backtracking through recursive expressions
1630    packrat_cache = {} # this is set later by enabledPackrat(); this is here so that resetCache() doesn't fail
1631    packrat_cache_lock = RLock()
1632    packrat_cache_stats = [0, 0]
1633
1634    # this method gets repeatedly called during backtracking with the same arguments -
1635    # we can cache these arguments and save ourselves the trouble of re-parsing the contained expression
1636    def _parseCache( self, instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True ):
1637        HIT, MISS = 0, 1
1638        lookup = (self, instring, loc, callPreParse, doActions)
1639        with ParserElement.packrat_cache_lock:
1640            cache = ParserElement.packrat_cache
1641            value = cache.get(lookup)
1642            if value is cache.not_in_cache:
1643                ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[MISS] += 1
1644                try:
1645                    value = self._parseNoCache(instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse)
1646                except ParseBaseException as pe:
1647                    # cache a copy of the exception, without the traceback
1648                    cache.set(lookup, pe.__class__(*pe.args))
1649                    raise
1650                else:
1651                    cache.set(lookup, (value[0], value[1].copy()))
1652                    return value
1653            else:
1654                ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[HIT] += 1
1655                if isinstance(value, Exception):
1656                    raise value
1657                return (value[0], value[1].copy())
1658
1659    _parse = _parseNoCache
1660
1661    @staticmethod
1662    def resetCache():
1663        ParserElement.packrat_cache.clear()
1664        ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[:] = [0] * len(ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats)
1665
1666    _packratEnabled = False
1667    @staticmethod
1668    def enablePackrat(cache_size_limit=128):
1669        """Enables "packrat" parsing, which adds memoizing to the parsing logic.
1670           Repeated parse attempts at the same string location (which happens
1671           often in many complex grammars) can immediately return a cached value,
1672           instead of re-executing parsing/validating code.  Memoizing is done of
1673           both valid results and parsing exceptions.
1674
1675           Parameters:
1676
1677           - cache_size_limit - (default= ``128``) - if an integer value is provided
1678             will limit the size of the packrat cache; if None is passed, then
1679             the cache size will be unbounded; if 0 is passed, the cache will
1680             be effectively disabled.
1681
1682           This speedup may break existing programs that use parse actions that
1683           have side-effects.  For this reason, packrat parsing is disabled when
1684           you first import pyparsing.  To activate the packrat feature, your
1685           program must call the class method :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat`.  If
1686           your program uses ``psyco`` to "compile as you go", you must call
1687           ``enablePackrat`` before calling ``psyco.full()``.  If you do not do this,
1688           Python will crash.  For best results, call ``enablePackrat()`` immediately
1689           after importing pyparsing.
1690
1691           Example::
1692
1693               import pyparsing
1694               pyparsing.ParserElement.enablePackrat()
1695        """
1696        if not ParserElement._packratEnabled:
1697            ParserElement._packratEnabled = True
1698            if cache_size_limit is None:
1699                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._UnboundedCache()
1700            else:
1701                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._FifoCache(cache_size_limit)
1702            ParserElement._parse = ParserElement._parseCache
1703
1704    def parseString( self, instring, parseAll=False ):
1705        """
1706        Execute the parse expression with the given string.
1707        This is the main interface to the client code, once the complete
1708        expression has been built.
1709
1710        If you want the grammar to require that the entire input string be
1711        successfully parsed, then set ``parseAll`` to True (equivalent to ending
1712        the grammar with ``StringEnd()``).
1713
1714        Note: ``parseString`` implicitly calls ``expandtabs()`` on the input string,
1715        in order to report proper column numbers in parse actions.
1716        If the input string contains tabs and
1717        the grammar uses parse actions that use the ``loc`` argument to index into the
1718        string being parsed, you can ensure you have a consistent view of the input
1719        string by:
1720
1721        - calling ``parseWithTabs`` on your grammar before calling ``parseString``
1722          (see :class:`parseWithTabs`)
1723        - define your parse action using the full ``(s,loc,toks)`` signature, and
1724          reference the input string using the parse action's ``s`` argument
1725        - explictly expand the tabs in your input string before calling
1726          ``parseString``
1727
1728        Example::
1729
1730            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa')  # -> ['aaaaa']
1731            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa', parseAll=True)  # -> Exception: Expected end of text
1732        """
1733        ParserElement.resetCache()
1734        if not self.streamlined:
1735            self.streamline()
1736            #~ self.saveAsList = True
1737        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1738            e.streamline()
1739        if not self.keepTabs:
1740            instring = instring.expandtabs()
1741        try:
1742            loc, tokens = self._parse( instring, 0 )
1743            if parseAll:
1744                loc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1745                se = Empty() + StringEnd()
1746                se._parse( instring, loc )
1747        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1748            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1749                raise
1750            else:
1751                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1752                raise exc
1753        else:
1754            return tokens
1755
1756    def scanString( self, instring, maxMatches=_MAX_INT, overlap=False ):
1757        """
1758        Scan the input string for expression matches.  Each match will return the
1759        matching tokens, start location, and end location.  May be called with optional
1760        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip scanning after 'n' matches are found.  If
1761        ``overlap`` is specified, then overlapping matches will be reported.
1762
1763        Note that the start and end locations are reported relative to the string
1764        being parsed.  See :class:`parseString` for more information on parsing
1765        strings with embedded tabs.
1766
1767        Example::
1768
1769            source = "sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987"
1770            print(source)
1771            for tokens,start,end in Word(alphas).scanString(source):
1772                print(' '*start + '^'*(end-start))
1773                print(' '*start + tokens[0])
1774
1775        prints::
1776
1777            sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987
1778            ^^^^^
1779            sldjf
1780                    ^^^^^^^
1781                    lsdjjkf
1782                              ^^^^^^
1783                              sldkjf
1784                                       ^^^^^^
1785                                       lkjsfd
1786        """
1787        if not self.streamlined:
1788            self.streamline()
1789        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1790            e.streamline()
1791
1792        if not self.keepTabs:
1793            instring = _ustr(instring).expandtabs()
1794        instrlen = len(instring)
1795        loc = 0
1796        preparseFn = self.preParse
1797        parseFn = self._parse
1798        ParserElement.resetCache()
1799        matches = 0
1800        try:
1801            while loc <= instrlen and matches < maxMatches:
1802                try:
1803                    preloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1804                    nextLoc,tokens = parseFn( instring, preloc, callPreParse=False )
1805                except ParseException:
1806                    loc = preloc+1
1807                else:
1808                    if nextLoc > loc:
1809                        matches += 1
1810                        yield tokens, preloc, nextLoc
1811                        if overlap:
1812                            nextloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1813                            if nextloc > loc:
1814                                loc = nextLoc
1815                            else:
1816                                loc += 1
1817                        else:
1818                            loc = nextLoc
1819                    else:
1820                        loc = preloc+1
1821        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1822            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1823                raise
1824            else:
1825                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1826                raise exc
1827
1828    def transformString( self, instring ):
1829        """
1830        Extension to :class:`scanString`, to modify matching text with modified tokens that may
1831        be returned from a parse action.  To use ``transformString``, define a grammar and
1832        attach a parse action to it that modifies the returned token list.
1833        Invoking ``transformString()`` on a target string will then scan for matches,
1834        and replace the matched text patterns according to the logic in the parse
1835        action.  ``transformString()`` returns the resulting transformed string.
1836
1837        Example::
1838
1839            wd = Word(alphas)
1840            wd.setParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0].title())
1841
1842            print(wd.transformString("now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york."))
1843
1844        prints::
1845
1846            Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York.
1847        """
1848        out = []
1849        lastE = 0
1850        # force preservation of <TAB>s, to minimize unwanted transformation of string, and to
1851        # keep string locs straight between transformString and scanString
1852        self.keepTabs = True
1853        try:
1854            for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring ):
1855                out.append( instring[lastE:s] )
1856                if t:
1857                    if isinstance(t,ParseResults):
1858                        out += t.asList()
1859                    elif isinstance(t,list):
1860                        out += t
1861                    else:
1862                        out.append(t)
1863                lastE = e
1864            out.append(instring[lastE:])
1865            out = [o for o in out if o]
1866            return "".join(map(_ustr,_flatten(out)))
1867        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1868            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1869                raise
1870            else:
1871                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1872                raise exc
1873
1874    def searchString( self, instring, maxMatches=_MAX_INT ):
1875        """
1876        Another extension to :class:`scanString`, simplifying the access to the tokens found
1877        to match the given parse expression.  May be called with optional
1878        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip searching after 'n' matches are found.
1879
1880        Example::
1881
1882            # a capitalized word starts with an uppercase letter, followed by zero or more lowercase letters
1883            cap_word = Word(alphas.upper(), alphas.lower())
1884
1885            print(cap_word.searchString("More than Iron, more than Lead, more than Gold I need Electricity"))
1886
1887            # the sum() builtin can be used to merge results into a single ParseResults object
1888            print(sum(cap_word.searchString("More than Iron, more than Lead, more than Gold I need Electricity")))
1889
1890        prints::
1891
1892            [['More'], ['Iron'], ['Lead'], ['Gold'], ['I'], ['Electricity']]
1893            ['More', 'Iron', 'Lead', 'Gold', 'I', 'Electricity']
1894        """
1895        try:
1896            return ParseResults([ t for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring, maxMatches ) ])
1897        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1898            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1899                raise
1900            else:
1901                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1902                raise exc
1903
1904    def split(self, instring, maxsplit=_MAX_INT, includeSeparators=False):
1905        """
1906        Generator method to split a string using the given expression as a separator.
1907        May be called with optional ``maxsplit`` argument, to limit the number of splits;
1908        and the optional ``includeSeparators`` argument (default= ``False``), if the separating
1909        matching text should be included in the split results.
1910
1911        Example::
1912
1913            punc = oneOf(list(".,;:/-!?"))
1914            print(list(punc.split("This, this?, this sentence, is badly punctuated!")))
1915
1916        prints::
1917
1918            ['This', ' this', '', ' this sentence', ' is badly punctuated', '']
1919        """
1920        splits = 0
1921        last = 0
1922        for t,s,e in self.scanString(instring, maxMatches=maxsplit):
1923            yield instring[last:s]
1924            if includeSeparators:
1925                yield t[0]
1926            last = e
1927        yield instring[last:]
1928
1929    def __add__(self, other ):
1930        """
1931        Implementation of + operator - returns :class:`And`. Adding strings to a ParserElement
1932        converts them to :class:`Literal`s by default.
1933
1934        Example::
1935
1936            greet = Word(alphas) + "," + Word(alphas) + "!"
1937            hello = "Hello, World!"
1938            print (hello, "->", greet.parseString(hello))
1939
1940        prints::
1941
1942            Hello, World! -> ['Hello', ',', 'World', '!']
1943        """
1944        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1945            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1946        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1947            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1948                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1949            return None
1950        return And( [ self, other ] )
1951
1952    def __radd__(self, other ):
1953        """
1954        Implementation of + operator when left operand is not a :class:`ParserElement`
1955        """
1956        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1957            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1958        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1959            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1960                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1961            return None
1962        return other + self
1963
1964    def __sub__(self, other):
1965        """
1966        Implementation of - operator, returns :class:`And` with error stop
1967        """
1968        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1969            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1970        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1971            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1972                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1973            return None
1974        return self + And._ErrorStop() + other
1975
1976    def __rsub__(self, other ):
1977        """
1978        Implementation of - operator when left operand is not a :class:`ParserElement`
1979        """
1980        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1981            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1982        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1983            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1984                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1985            return None
1986        return other - self

1988    def __mul__(self,other):
1989        """
1990        Implementation of * operator, allows use of ``expr * 3`` in place of
1991        ``expr + expr + expr``.  Expressions may also me multiplied by a 2-integer
1992        tuple, similar to ``{min,max}`` multipliers in regular expressions.  Tuples
1993        may also include ``None`` as in:
1994         - ``expr*(n,None)`` or ``expr*(n,)`` is equivalent
1995              to ``expr*n + ZeroOrMore(expr)``
1996              (read as "at least n instances of ``expr``")
1997         - ``expr*(None,n)`` is equivalent to ``expr*(0,n)``
1998              (read as "0 to n instances of ``expr``")
1999         - ``expr*(None,None)`` is equivalent to ``ZeroOrMore(expr)``
2000         - ``expr*(1,None)`` is equivalent to ``OneOrMore(expr)``
2001
2002        Note that ``expr*(None,n)`` does not raise an exception if
2003        more than n exprs exist in the input stream; that is,
2004        ``expr*(None,n)`` does not enforce a maximum number of expr
2005        occurrences.  If this behavior is desired, then write
2006        ``expr*(None,n) + ~expr``
2007        """
2008        if isinstance(other,int):
2009            minElements, optElements = other,0
2010        elif isinstance(other,tuple):
2011            other = (other + (None, None))[:2]
2012            if other[0] is None:
2013                other = (0, other[1])
2014            if isinstance(other[0],int) and other[1] is None:
2015                if other[0] == 0:
2016                    return ZeroOrMore(self)
2017                if other[0] == 1:
2018                    return OneOrMore(self)
2019                else:
2020                    return self*other[0] + ZeroOrMore(self)
2021            elif isinstance(other[0],int) and isinstance(other[1],int):
2022                minElements, optElements = other
2023                optElements -= minElements
2024            else:
2025                raise TypeError("cannot multiply 'ParserElement' and ('%s','%s') objects", type(other[0]),type(other[1]))
2026        else:
2027            raise TypeError("cannot multiply 'ParserElement' and '%s' objects", type(other))
2028
2029        if minElements < 0:
2030            raise ValueError("cannot multiply ParserElement by negative value")
2031        if optElements < 0:
2032            raise ValueError("second tuple value must be greater or equal to first tuple value")
2033        if minElements == optElements == 0:
2034            raise ValueError("cannot multiply ParserElement by 0 or (0,0)")
2035
2036        if (optElements):
2037            def makeOptionalList(n):
2038                if n>1:
2039                    return Optional(self + makeOptionalList(n-1))
2040                else:
2041                    return Optional(self)
2042            if minElements:
2043                if minElements == 1:
2044                    ret = self + makeOptionalList(optElements)
2045                else:
2046                    ret = And([self]*minElements) + makeOptionalList(optElements)
2047            else:
2048                ret = makeOptionalList(optElements)
2049        else:
2050            if minElements == 1:
2051                ret = self
2052            else:
2053                ret = And([self]*minElements)
2054        return ret
2055
2056    def __rmul__(self, other):
2057        return self.__mul__(other)

2137    def __call__(self, name=None):
2138        """
2139        Shortcut for :class:`setResultsName`, with ``listAllMatches=False``.
2140
2141        If ``name`` is given with a trailing ``'*'`` character, then ``listAllMatches`` will be
2142        passed as ``True``.
2143
2144        If ``name` is omitted, same as calling :class:`copy`.
2145
2146        Example::
2147
2148            # these are equivalent
2149            userdata = Word(alphas).setResultsName("name") + Word(nums+"-").setResultsName("socsecno")
2150            userdata = Word(alphas)("name") + Word(nums+"-")("socsecno")
2151        """
2152        if name is not None:
2153            return self.setResultsName(name)
2154        else:
2155            return self.copy()

2157    def suppress( self ):
2158        """
2159        Suppresses the output of this :class:`ParserElement`; useful to keep punctuation from
2160        cluttering up returned output.
2161        """
2162        return Suppress( self )

2164    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
2165        """
2166        Disables the skipping of whitespace before matching the characters in the
2167        :class:`ParserElement`'s defined pattern.  This is normally only used internally by
2168        the pyparsing module, but may be needed in some whitespace-sensitive grammars.
2169        """
2170        self.skipWhitespace = False
2171        return self

2175        Overrides the default whitespace chars
2176        """

2178        self.whiteChars = chars

2182    def parseWithTabs( self ):
2183        """
2184        Overrides default behavior to expand ``<TAB>``s to spaces before parsing the input string.
2185        Must be called before ``parseString`` when the input grammar contains elements that
2186        match ``<TAB>`` characters.
2187        """
2188        self.keepTabs = True
2189        return self

2191    def ignore( self, other ):
2192        """
2193        Define expression to be ignored (e.g., comments) while doing pattern
2194        matching; may be called repeatedly, to define multiple comment or other
2195        ignorable patterns.
2196
2197        Example::
2198
2199            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
2200            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj']
2201
2202            patt.ignore(cStyleComment)
2203            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj', 'lskjd']
2204        """
2205        if isinstance(other, basestring):
2206            other = Suppress(other)
2207
2208        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
2209            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
2210                self.ignoreExprs.append(other)
2211        else:
2212            self.ignoreExprs.append( Suppress( other.copy() ) )
2213        return self

2215    def setDebugActions( self, startAction, successAction, exceptionAction ):
2216        """
2217        Enable display of debugging messages while doing pattern matching.
2218        """
2219        self.debugActions = (startAction or _defaultStartDebugAction,
2220                             successAction or _defaultSuccessDebugAction,
2221                             exceptionAction or _defaultExceptionDebugAction)
2222        self.debug = True
2223        return self
2224
2225    def setDebug( self, flag=True ):
2226        """
2227        Enable display of debugging messages while doing pattern matching.
2228        Set ``flag`` to True to enable, False to disable.
2229
2230        Example::
2231
2232            wd = Word(alphas).setName("alphaword")
2233            integer = Word(nums).setName("numword")
2234            term = wd | integer
2235
2236            # turn on debugging for wd
2237            wd.setDebug()
2238
2239            OneOrMore(term).parseString("abc 123 xyz 890")
2240
2241        prints::
2242
2243            Match alphaword at loc 0(1,1)
2244            Matched alphaword -> ['abc']
2245            Match alphaword at loc 3(1,4)
2246            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 4), (line:1, col:5)
2247            Match alphaword at loc 7(1,8)
2248            Matched alphaword -> ['xyz']
2249            Match alphaword at loc 11(1,12)
2250            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 12), (line:1, col:13)
2251            Match alphaword at loc 15(1,16)
2252            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 15), (line:1, col:16)
2253
2254        The output shown is that produced by the default debug actions - custom debug actions can be
2255        specified using :class:`setDebugActions`. Prior to attempting
2256        to match the ``wd`` expression, the debugging message ``"Match <exprname> at loc <n>(<line>,<col>)"``
2257        is shown. Then if the parse succeeds, a ``"Matched"` message is shown, or an ``"Exception raised"``
2258        message is shown. Also note the use of :class:`setName` to assign a human-readable name to the expression,
2259        which makes debugging and exception messages easier to understand - for instance, the default
2260        name created for the :class:`Word` expression without calling ``setName`` is ``"W:(ABCD...)"``.
2261        """
2262        if flag:
2263            self.setDebugActions( _defaultStartDebugAction, _defaultSuccessDebugAction, _defaultExceptionDebugAction )
2264        else:
2265            self.debug = False
2266        return self
2267

2282    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
2283        """
2284        Check defined expressions for valid structure, check for infinite recursive definitions.
2285        """
2286        self.checkRecursion( [] )
2287
2288    def parseFile( self, file_or_filename, parseAll=False ):
2289        """
2290        Execute the parse expression on the given file or filename.
2291        If a filename is specified (instead of a file object),
2292        the entire file is opened, read, and closed before parsing.
2293        """
2294        try:
2295            file_contents = file_or_filename.read()
2296        except AttributeError:
2297            with open(file_or_filename, "r") as f:
2298                file_contents = f.read()
2299        try:
2300            return self.parseString(file_contents, parseAll)
2301        except ParseBaseException as exc:
2302            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
2303                raise
2304            else:
2305                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
2306                raise exc
2307
2308    def __eq__(self,other):
2309        if isinstance(other, ParserElement):
2310            return self is other or vars(self) == vars(other)
2311        elif isinstance(other, basestring):
2312            return self.matches(other)
2313        else:
2314            return super(ParserElement,self)==other
2315
2316    def __ne__(self,other):
2317        return not (self == other)
2318
2319    def __hash__(self):
2320        return hash(id(self))
2321
2322    def __req__(self,other):
2323        return self == other
2324
2325    def __rne__(self,other):
2326        return not (self == other)
2327
2328    def matches(self, testString, parseAll=True):
2329        """
2330        Method for quick testing of a parser against a test string. Good for simple
2331        inline microtests of sub expressions while building up larger parser.
2332
2333        Parameters:
2334         - testString - to test against this expression for a match
2335         - parseAll - (default= ``True``) - flag to pass to :class:`parseString` when running tests
2336
2337        Example::
2338
2339            expr = Word(nums)
2340            assert expr.matches("100")
2341        """
2342        try:
2343            self.parseString(_ustr(testString), parseAll=parseAll)
2344            return True
2345        except ParseBaseException:
2346            return False
2347
2348    def runTests(self, tests, parseAll=True, comment='#', fullDump=True, printResults=True, failureTests=False):
2349        """
2350        Execute the parse expression on a series of test strings, showing each
2351        test, the parsed results or where the parse failed. Quick and easy way to
2352        run a parse expression against a list of sample strings.
2353
2354        Parameters:
2355         - tests - a list of separate test strings, or a multiline string of test strings
2356         - parseAll - (default= ``True`` ) - flag to pass to :class:`parseString` when running tests
2357         - comment - (default= ``'#'`` ) - expression for indicating embedded comments in the test
2358              string; pass None to disable comment filtering
2359         - fullDump - (default= ``True`` ) - dump results as list followed by results names in nested outline;
2360              if False, only dump nested list
2361         - printResults - (default= ``True`` ) prints test output to stdout
2362         - failureTests - (default= ``False`` ) indicates if these tests are expected to fail parsing
2363
2364        Returns: a (success, results) tuple, where success indicates that all tests succeeded
2365        (or failed if ``failureTests`` is True), and the results contain a list of lines of each
2366        test's output
2367
2368        Example::
2369
2370            number_expr = pyparsing_common.number.copy()
2371
2372            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2373                # unsigned integer
2374                100
2375                # negative integer
2376                -100
2377                # float with scientific notation
2378                6.02e23
2379                # integer with scientific notation
2380                1e-12
2381                ''')
2382            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2383
2384            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2385                # stray character
2386                100Z
2387                # missing leading digit before '.'
2388                -.100
2389                # too many '.'
2390                3.14.159
2391                ''', failureTests=True)
2392            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2393
2394        prints::
2395
2396            # unsigned integer
2397            100
2398            [100]
2399
2400            # negative integer
2401            -100
2402            [-100]
2403
2404            # float with scientific notation
2405            6.02e23
2406            [6.02e+23]
2407
2408            # integer with scientific notation
2409            1e-12
2410            [1e-12]
2411
2412            Success
2413
2414            # stray character
2415            100Z
2416               ^
2417            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 3), (line:1, col:4)
2418
2419            # missing leading digit before '.'
2420            -.100
2421            ^
2422            FAIL: Expected {real number with scientific notation | real number | signed integer} (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
2423
2424            # too many '.'
2425            3.14.159
2426                ^
2427            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 4), (line:1, col:5)
2428
2429            Success
2430
2431        Each test string must be on a single line. If you want to test a string that spans multiple
2432        lines, create a test like this::
2433
2434            expr.runTest(r"this is a test\\n of strings that spans \\n 3 lines")
2435
2436        (Note that this is a raw string literal, you must include the leading 'r'.)
2437        """
2438        if isinstance(tests, basestring):
2439            tests = list(map(str.strip, tests.rstrip().splitlines()))
2440        if isinstance(comment, basestring):
2441            comment = Literal(comment)
2442        allResults = []
2443        comments = []
2444        success = True
2445        for t in tests:
2446            if comment is not None and comment.matches(t, False) or comments and not t:
2447                comments.append(t)
2448                continue
2449            if not t:
2450                continue
2451            out = ['\n'.join(comments), t]
2452            comments = []
2453            try:
2454                t = t.replace(r'\n','\n')
2455                result = self.parseString(t, parseAll=parseAll)
2456                out.append(result.dump(full=fullDump))
2457                success = success and not failureTests
2458            except ParseBaseException as pe:
2459                fatal = "(FATAL)" if isinstance(pe, ParseFatalException) else ""
2460                if '\n' in t:
2461                    out.append(line(pe.loc, t))
2462                    out.append(' '*(col(pe.loc,t)-1) + '^' + fatal)
2463                else:
2464                    out.append(' '*pe.loc + '^' + fatal)
2465                out.append("FAIL: " + str(pe))
2466                success = success and failureTests
2467                result = pe
2468            except Exception as exc:
2469                out.append("FAIL-EXCEPTION: " + str(exc))
2470                success = success and failureTests
2471                result = exc
2472
2473            if printResults:
2474                if fullDump:
2475                    out.append('')
2476                print('\n'.join(out))
2477
2478            allResults.append((t, result))
2479
2480        return success, allResults
2481
2482
2483class Token(ParserElement):
2484    """Abstract :class:`ParserElement` subclass, for defining atomic
2485    matching patterns.
2486    """
2487    def __init__( self ):
2488        super(Token,self).__init__( savelist=False )
2489
2490
2491class Empty(Token):
2492    """An empty token, will always match.
2493    """
2494    def __init__( self ):
2495        super(Empty,self).__init__()
2496        self.name = "Empty"
2497        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
2498        self.mayIndexError = False
2499
2500
2501class NoMatch(Token):
2502    """A token that will never match.
2503    """
2504    def __init__( self ):
2505        super(NoMatch,self).__init__()
2506        self.name = "NoMatch"
2507        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
2508        self.mayIndexError = False
2509        self.errmsg = "Unmatchable token"
2510
2511    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2512        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2513
2514
2515class Literal(Token):
2516    """Token to exactly match a specified string.
2517
2518    Example::
2519
2520        Literal('blah').parseString('blah')  # -> ['blah']
2521        Literal('blah').parseString('blahfooblah')  # -> ['blah']
2522        Literal('blah').parseString('bla')  # -> Exception: Expected "blah"
2523
2524    For case-insensitive matching, use :class:`CaselessLiteral`.
2525
2526    For keyword matching (force word break before and after the matched string),
2527    use :class:`Keyword` or :class:`CaselessKeyword`.
2528    """
2529    def __init__( self, matchString ):
2530        super(Literal,self).__init__()
2531        self.match = matchString
2532        self.matchLen = len(matchString)
2533        try:
2534            self.firstMatchChar = matchString[0]
2535        except IndexError:
2536            warnings.warn("null string passed to Literal; use Empty() instead",
2537                            SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2538            self.__class__ = Empty
2539        self.name = '"%s"' % _ustr(self.match)
2540        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2541        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2542        self.mayIndexError = False
2543
2544    # Performance tuning: this routine gets called a *lot*
2545    # if this is a single character match string  and the first character matches,
2546    # short-circuit as quickly as possible, and avoid calling startswith
2547    #~ @profile
2548    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2549        if (instring[loc] == self.firstMatchChar and
2550            (self.matchLen==1 or instring.startswith(self.match,loc)) ):
2551            return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2552        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2553_L = Literal
2554ParserElement._literalStringClass = Literal
2555
2556class Keyword(Token):
2557    """Token to exactly match a specified string as a keyword, that is,
2558    it must be immediately followed by a non-keyword character.  Compare
2559    with :class:`Literal`:
2560
2561     - ``Literal("if")`` will match the leading ``'if'`` in
2562       ``'ifAndOnlyIf'``.
2563     - ``Keyword("if")`` will not; it will only match the leading
2564       ``'if'`` in ``'if x=1'``, or ``'if(y==2)'``
2565
2566    Accepts two optional constructor arguments in addition to the
2567    keyword string:
2568
2569     - ``identChars`` is a string of characters that would be valid
2570       identifier characters, defaulting to all alphanumerics + "_" and
2571       "$"
2572     - ``caseless`` allows case-insensitive matching, default is ``False``.
2573
2574    Example::
2575
2576        Keyword("start").parseString("start")  # -> ['start']
2577        Keyword("start").parseString("starting")  # -> Exception
2578
2579    For case-insensitive matching, use :class:`CaselessKeyword`.
2580    """
2581    DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS = alphanums+"_$"
2582
2583    def __init__( self, matchString, identChars=None, caseless=False ):
2584        super(Keyword,self).__init__()
2585        if identChars is None:
2586            identChars = Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS
2587        self.match = matchString
2588        self.matchLen = len(matchString)
2589        try:
2590            self.firstMatchChar = matchString[0]
2591        except IndexError:
2592            warnings.warn("null string passed to Keyword; use Empty() instead",
2593                            SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2594        self.name = '"%s"' % self.match
2595        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2596        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2597        self.mayIndexError = False
2598        self.caseless = caseless
2599        if caseless:
2600            self.caselessmatch = matchString.upper()
2601            identChars = identChars.upper()
2602        self.identChars = set(identChars)
2603
2604    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2605        if self.caseless:
2606            if ( (instring[ loc:loc+self.matchLen ].upper() == self.caselessmatch) and
2607                 (loc >= len(instring)-self.matchLen or instring[loc+self.matchLen].upper() not in self.identChars) and
2608                 (loc == 0 or instring[loc-1].upper() not in self.identChars) ):
2609                return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2610        else:
2611            if (instring[loc] == self.firstMatchChar and
2612                (self.matchLen==1 or instring.startswith(self.match,loc)) and
2613                (loc >= len(instring)-self.matchLen or instring[loc+self.matchLen] not in self.identChars) and
2614                (loc == 0 or instring[loc-1] not in self.identChars) ):
2615                return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2616        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2617
2618    def copy(self):
2619        c = super(Keyword,self).copy()
2620        c.identChars = Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS
2621        return c
2622
2623    @staticmethod
2624    def setDefaultKeywordChars( chars ):
2625        """Overrides the default Keyword chars
2626        """
2627        Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS = chars
2628
2629class CaselessLiteral(Literal):
2630    """Token to match a specified string, ignoring case of letters.
2631    Note: the matched results will always be in the case of the given
2632    match string, NOT the case of the input text.
2633
2634    Example::
2635
2636        OneOrMore(CaselessLiteral("CMD")).parseString("cmd CMD Cmd10") # -> ['CMD', 'CMD', 'CMD']
2637
2638    (Contrast with example for :class:`CaselessKeyword`.)
2639    """
2640    def __init__( self, matchString ):
2641        super(CaselessLiteral,self).__init__( matchString.upper() )
2642        # Preserve the defining literal.
2643        self.returnString = matchString
2644        self.name = "'%s'" % self.returnString
2645        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2646
2647    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2648        if instring[ loc:loc+self.matchLen ].upper() == self.match:
2649            return loc+self.matchLen, self.returnString
2650        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2651
2652class CaselessKeyword(Keyword):
2653    """
2654    Caseless version of :class:`Keyword`.
2655
2656    Example::
2657
2658        OneOrMore(CaselessKeyword("CMD")).parseString("cmd CMD Cmd10") # -> ['CMD', 'CMD']
2659
2660    (Contrast with example for :class:`CaselessLiteral`.)
2661    """
2662    def __init__( self, matchString, identChars=None ):
2663        super(CaselessKeyword,self).__init__( matchString, identChars, caseless=True )
2664
2665    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2666        if ( (instring[ loc:loc+self.matchLen ].upper() == self.caselessmatch) and
2667             (loc >= len(instring)-self.matchLen or instring[loc+self.matchLen].upper() not in self.identChars) ):
2668            return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2669        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2670
2671class CloseMatch(Token):
2672    """A variation on :class:`Literal` which matches "close" matches,
2673    that is, strings with at most 'n' mismatching characters.
2674    :class:`CloseMatch` takes parameters:
2675
2676     - ``match_string`` - string to be matched
2677     - ``maxMismatches`` - (``default=1``) maximum number of
2678       mismatches allowed to count as a match
2679
2680    The results from a successful parse will contain the matched text
2681    from the input string and the following named results:
2682
2683     - ``mismatches`` - a list of the positions within the
2684       match_string where mismatches were found
2685     - ``original`` - the original match_string used to compare
2686       against the input string
2687
2688    If ``mismatches`` is an empty list, then the match was an exact
2689    match.
2690
2691    Example::
2692
2693        patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA")
2694        patt.parseString("ATCATCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2695        patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> Exception: Expected 'ATCATCGAATGGA' (with up to 1 mismatches) (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
2696
2697        # exact match
2698        patt.parseString("ATCATCGAATGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAATGGA'], {'mismatches': [[]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2699
2700        # close match allowing up to 2 mismatches
2701        patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA", maxMismatches=2)
2702        patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCAXCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[4, 9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2703    """
2704    def __init__(self, match_string, maxMismatches=1):
2705        super(CloseMatch,self).__init__()
2706        self.name = match_string
2707        self.match_string = match_string
2708        self.maxMismatches = maxMismatches
2709        self.errmsg = "Expected %r (with up to %d mismatches)" % (self.match_string, self.maxMismatches)
2710        self.mayIndexError = False
2711        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2712
2713    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2714        start = loc
2715        instrlen = len(instring)
2716        maxloc = start + len(self.match_string)
2717
2718        if maxloc <= instrlen:
2719            match_string = self.match_string
2720            match_stringloc = 0
2721            mismatches = []
2722            maxMismatches = self.maxMismatches
2723
2724            for match_stringloc,s_m in enumerate(zip(instring[loc:maxloc], self.match_string)):
2725                src,mat = s_m
2726                if src != mat:
2727                    mismatches.append(match_stringloc)
2728                    if len(mismatches) > maxMismatches:
2729                        break
2730            else:
2731                loc = match_stringloc + 1
2732                results = ParseResults([instring[start:loc]])
2733                results['original'] = self.match_string
2734                results['mismatches'] = mismatches
2735                return loc, results
2736
2737        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2738
2739
2740class Word(Token):
2741    """Token for matching words composed of allowed character sets.
2742    Defined with string containing all allowed initial characters, an
2743    optional string containing allowed body characters (if omitted,
2744    defaults to the initial character set), and an optional minimum,
2745    maximum, and/or exact length.  The default value for ``min`` is
2746    1 (a minimum value < 1 is not valid); the default values for
2747    ``max`` and ``exact`` are 0, meaning no maximum or exact
2748    length restriction. An optional ``excludeChars`` parameter can
2749    list characters that might be found in the input ``bodyChars``
2750    string; useful to define a word of all printables except for one or
2751    two characters, for instance.
2752
2753    :class:`srange` is useful for defining custom character set strings
2754    for defining ``Word`` expressions, using range notation from
2755    regular expression character sets.
2756
2757    A common mistake is to use :class:`Word` to match a specific literal
2758    string, as in ``Word("Address")``. Remember that :class:`Word`
2759    uses the string argument to define *sets* of matchable characters.
2760    This expression would match "Add", "AAA", "dAred", or any other word
2761    made up of the characters 'A', 'd', 'r', 'e', and 's'. To match an
2762    exact literal string, use :class:`Literal` or :class:`Keyword`.
2763
2764    pyparsing includes helper strings for building Words:
2765
2766     - :class:`alphas`
2767     - :class:`nums`
2768     - :class:`alphanums`
2769     - :class:`hexnums`
2770     - :class:`alphas8bit` (alphabetic characters in ASCII range 128-255
2771       - accented, tilded, umlauted, etc.)
2772     - :class:`punc8bit` (non-alphabetic characters in ASCII range
2773       128-255 - currency, symbols, superscripts, diacriticals, etc.)
2774     - :class:`printables` (any non-whitespace character)
2775
2776    Example::
2777
2778        # a word composed of digits
2779        integer = Word(nums) # equivalent to Word("0123456789") or Word(srange("0-9"))
2780
2781        # a word with a leading capital, and zero or more lowercase
2782        capital_word = Word(alphas.upper(), alphas.lower())
2783
2784        # hostnames are alphanumeric, with leading alpha, and '-'
2785        hostname = Word(alphas, alphanums+'-')
2786
2787        # roman numeral (not a strict parser, accepts invalid mix of characters)
2788        roman = Word("IVXLCDM")
2789
2790        # any string of non-whitespace characters, except for ','
2791        csv_value = Word(printables, excludeChars=",")
2792    """
2793    def __init__( self, initChars, bodyChars=None, min=1, max=0, exact=0, asKeyword=False, excludeChars=None ):
2794        super(Word,self).__init__()
2795        if excludeChars:
2796            initChars = ''.join(c for c in initChars if c not in excludeChars)
2797            if bodyChars:
2798                bodyChars = ''.join(c for c in bodyChars if c not in excludeChars)
2799        self.initCharsOrig = initChars
2800        self.initChars = set(initChars)
2801        if bodyChars :
2802            self.bodyCharsOrig = bodyChars
2803            self.bodyChars = set(bodyChars)
2804        else:
2805            self.bodyCharsOrig = initChars
2806            self.bodyChars = set(initChars)
2807
2808        self.maxSpecified = max > 0
2809
2810        if min < 1:
2811            raise ValueError("cannot specify a minimum length < 1; use Optional(Word()) if zero-length word is permitted")
2812
2813        self.minLen = min
2814
2815        if max > 0:
2816            self.maxLen = max
2817        else:
2818            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
2819
2820        if exact > 0:
2821            self.maxLen = exact
2822            self.minLen = exact
2823
2824        self.name = _ustr(self)
2825        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2826        self.mayIndexError = False
2827        self.asKeyword = asKeyword
2828
2829        if ' ' not in self.initCharsOrig+self.bodyCharsOrig and (min==1 and max==0 and exact==0):
2830            if self.bodyCharsOrig == self.initCharsOrig:
2831                self.reString = "[%s]+" % _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.initCharsOrig)
2832            elif len(self.initCharsOrig) == 1:
2833                self.reString = "%s[%s]*" % \
2834                                      (re.escape(self.initCharsOrig),
2835                                      _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.bodyCharsOrig),)
2836            else:
2837                self.reString = "[%s][%s]*" % \
2838                                      (_escapeRegexRangeChars(self.initCharsOrig),
2839                                      _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.bodyCharsOrig),)
2840            if self.asKeyword:
2841                self.reString = r"\b"+self.reString+r"\b"
2842            try:
2843                self.re = re.compile( self.reString )
2844            except Exception:
2845                self.re = None
2846
2847    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2848        if self.re:
2849            result = self.re.match(instring,loc)
2850            if not result:
2851                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2852
2853            loc = result.end()
2854            return loc, result.group()
2855
2856        if not(instring[ loc ] in self.initChars):
2857            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2858
2859        start = loc
2860        loc += 1
2861        instrlen = len(instring)
2862        bodychars = self.bodyChars
2863        maxloc = start + self.maxLen
2864        maxloc = min( maxloc, instrlen )
2865        while loc < maxloc and instring[loc] in bodychars:
2866            loc += 1
2867
2868        throwException = False
2869        if loc - start < self.minLen:
2870            throwException = True
2871        if self.maxSpecified and loc < instrlen and instring[loc] in bodychars:
2872            throwException = True
2873        if self.asKeyword:
2874            if (start>0 and instring[start-1] in bodychars) or (loc<instrlen and instring[loc] in bodychars):
2875                throwException = True
2876
2877        if throwException:
2878            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2879
2880        return loc, instring[start:loc]
2881
2882    def __str__( self ):
2883        try:
2884            return super(Word,self).__str__()
2885        except Exception:
2886            pass
2887
2888
2889        if self.strRepr is None:
2890
2891            def charsAsStr(s):
2892                if len(s)>4:
2893                    return s[:4]+"..."
2894                else:
2895                    return s
2896
2897            if ( self.initCharsOrig != self.bodyCharsOrig ):
2898                self.strRepr = "W:(%s,%s)" % ( charsAsStr(self.initCharsOrig), charsAsStr(self.bodyCharsOrig) )
2899            else:
2900                self.strRepr = "W:(%s)" % charsAsStr(self.initCharsOrig)
2901
2902        return self.strRepr

2905class Char(Word):
2906    """A short-cut class for defining ``Word(characters, exact=1)``,
2907    when defining a match of any single character in a string of
2908    characters.
2909    """
2910    def __init__(self, charset):
2911        super(Char, self).__init__(charset, exact=1)
2912        self.reString = "[%s]" % _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.initCharsOrig)
2913        self.re = re.compile( self.reString )

2916class Regex(Token):
2917    r"""Token for matching strings that match a given regular
2918    expression. Defined with string specifying the regular expression in
2919    a form recognized by the stdlib Python  `re module <http://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html>`_.
2920    If the given regex contains named groups (defined using ``(?P<name>...)``),
2921    these will be preserved as named parse results.
2922
2923    Example::
2924
2925        realnum = Regex(r"[+-]?\d+\.\d*")
2926        date = Regex(r'(?P<year>\d{4})-(?P<month>\d\d?)-(?P<day>\d\d?)')
2927        # ref: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/267399/how-do-you-match-only-valid-roman-numerals-with-a-regular-expression
2928        roman = Regex(r"M{0,4}(CM|CD|D?{0,3})(XC|XL|L?X{0,3})(IX|IV|V?I{0,3})")
2929    """
2930    compiledREtype = type(re.compile("[A-Z]"))
2931    def __init__( self, pattern, flags=0, asGroupList=False, asMatch=False):
2932        """The parameters ``pattern`` and ``flags`` are passed
2933        to the ``re.compile()`` function as-is. See the Python
2934        `re module <http://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html>`_ module for an
2935        explanation of the acceptable patterns and flags.
2936        """
2937        super(Regex,self).__init__()
2938
2939        if isinstance(pattern, basestring):
2940            if not pattern:
2941                warnings.warn("null string passed to Regex; use Empty() instead",
2942                        SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2943
2944            self.pattern = pattern
2945            self.flags = flags
2946
2947            try:
2948                self.re = re.compile(self.pattern, self.flags)
2949                self.reString = self.pattern
2950            except sre_constants.error:
2951                warnings.warn("invalid pattern (%s) passed to Regex" % pattern,
2952                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2953                raise
2954
2955        elif isinstance(pattern, Regex.compiledREtype):
2956            self.re = pattern
2957            self.pattern = \
2958            self.reString = str(pattern)
2959            self.flags = flags
2960
2961        else:
2962            raise ValueError("Regex may only be constructed with a string or a compiled RE object")
2963
2964        self.name = _ustr(self)
2965        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2966        self.mayIndexError = False
2967        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
2968        self.asGroupList = asGroupList
2969        self.asMatch = asMatch
2970
2971    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2972        result = self.re.match(instring,loc)
2973        if not result:
2974            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2975
2976        loc = result.end()
2977        d = result.groupdict()
2978        if self.asMatch:
2979            ret = result
2980        elif self.asGroupList:
2981            ret = result.groups()
2982        else:
2983            ret = ParseResults(result.group())
2984            if d:
2985                for k in d:
2986                    ret[k] = d[k]
2987        return loc,ret
2988
2989    def __str__( self ):
2990        try:
2991            return super(Regex,self).__str__()
2992        except Exception:
2993            pass
2994
2995        if self.strRepr is None:
2996            self.strRepr = "Re:(%s)" % repr(self.pattern)
2997
2998        return self.strRepr
2999
3000    def sub(self, repl):
3001        """
3002        Return Regex with an attached parse action to transform the parsed
3003        result as if called using `re.sub(expr, repl, string) <https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html#re.sub>`_.
3004
3005        Example::
3006
3007            make_html = Regex(r"(\w+):(.*?):").sub(r"<\1>\2</\1>")
3008            print(make_html.transformString("h1:main title:"))
3009            # prints "<h1>main title</h1>"
3010        """
3011        if self.asGroupList:
3012            warnings.warn("cannot use sub() with Regex(asGroupList=True)",
3013                           SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3014            raise SyntaxError()
3015
3016        if self.asMatch and callable(repl):
3017            warnings.warn("cannot use sub() with a callable with Regex(asMatch=True)",
3018                           SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3019            raise SyntaxError()
3020
3021        if self.asMatch:
3022            def pa(tokens):
3023                return tokens[0].expand(repl)
3024        else:
3025            def pa(tokens):
3026                return self.re.sub(repl, tokens[0])
3027        return self.addParseAction(pa)

3029class QuotedString(Token):
3030    r"""
3031    Token for matching strings that are delimited by quoting characters.
3032
3033    Defined with the following parameters:
3034
3035        - quoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
3036          quote delimiting string
3037        - escChar - character to escape quotes, typically backslash
3038          (default= ``None`` )
3039        - escQuote - special quote sequence to escape an embedded quote
3040          string (such as SQL's ``""`` to escape an embedded ``"``)
3041          (default= ``None`` )
3042        - multiline - boolean indicating whether quotes can span
3043          multiple lines (default= ``False`` )
3044        - unquoteResults - boolean indicating whether the matched text
3045          should be unquoted (default= ``True`` )
3046        - endQuoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
3047          end of the quote delimited string (default= ``None``  => same as
3048          quoteChar)
3049        - convertWhitespaceEscapes - convert escaped whitespace
3050          (``'\t'``, ``'\n'``, etc.) to actual whitespace
3051          (default= ``True`` )
3052
3053    Example::
3054
3055        qs = QuotedString('"')
3056        print(qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote" sldjf'))
3057        complex_qs = QuotedString('{{', endQuoteChar='}}')
3058        print(complex_qs.searchString('lsjdf {{This is the "quote"}} sldjf'))
3059        sql_qs = QuotedString('"', escQuote='""')
3060        print(sql_qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote with ""embedded"" quotes" sldjf'))
3061
3062    prints::
3063
3064        [['This is the quote']]
3065        [['This is the "quote"']]
3066        [['This is the quote with "embedded" quotes']]
3067    """
3068    def __init__( self, quoteChar, escChar=None, escQuote=None, multiline=False, unquoteResults=True, endQuoteChar=None, convertWhitespaceEscapes=True):
3069        super(QuotedString,self).__init__()
3070
3071        # remove white space from quote chars - wont work anyway
3072        quoteChar = quoteChar.strip()
3073        if not quoteChar:
3074            warnings.warn("quoteChar cannot be the empty string",SyntaxWarning,stacklevel=2)
3075            raise SyntaxError()
3076
3077        if endQuoteChar is None:
3078            endQuoteChar = quoteChar
3079        else:
3080            endQuoteChar = endQuoteChar.strip()
3081            if not endQuoteChar:
3082                warnings.warn("endQuoteChar cannot be the empty string",SyntaxWarning,stacklevel=2)
3083                raise SyntaxError()
3084
3085        self.quoteChar = quoteChar
3086        self.quoteCharLen = len(quoteChar)
3087        self.firstQuoteChar = quoteChar[0]
3088        self.endQuoteChar = endQuoteChar
3089        self.endQuoteCharLen = len(endQuoteChar)
3090        self.escChar = escChar
3091        self.escQuote = escQuote
3092        self.unquoteResults = unquoteResults
3093        self.convertWhitespaceEscapes = convertWhitespaceEscapes
3094
3095        if multiline:
3096            self.flags = re.MULTILINE | re.DOTALL
3097            self.pattern = r'%s(?:[^%s%s]' % \
3098                ( re.escape(self.quoteChar),
3099                  _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[0]),
3100                  (escChar is not None and _escapeRegexRangeChars(escChar) or '') )
3101        else:
3102            self.flags = 0
3103            self.pattern = r'%s(?:[^%s\n\r%s]' % \
3104                ( re.escape(self.quoteChar),
3105                  _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[0]),
3106                  (escChar is not None and _escapeRegexRangeChars(escChar) or '') )
3107        if len(self.endQuoteChar) > 1:
3108            self.pattern += (
3109                '|(?:' + ')|(?:'.join("%s[^%s]" % (re.escape(self.endQuoteChar[:i]),
3110                                               _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[i]))
3111                                    for i in range(len(self.endQuoteChar)-1,0,-1)) + ')'
3112                )
3113        if escQuote:
3114            self.pattern += (r'|(?:%s)' % re.escape(escQuote))
3115        if escChar:
3116            self.pattern += (r'|(?:%s.)' % re.escape(escChar))
3117            self.escCharReplacePattern = re.escape(self.escChar)+"(.)"
3118        self.pattern += (r')*%s' % re.escape(self.endQuoteChar))
3119
3120        try:
3121            self.re = re.compile(self.pattern, self.flags)
3122            self.reString = self.pattern
3123        except sre_constants.error:
3124            warnings.warn("invalid pattern (%s) passed to Regex" % self.pattern,
3125                SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3126            raise
3127
3128        self.name = _ustr(self)
3129        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3130        self.mayIndexError = False
3131        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3132
3133    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3134        result = instring[loc] == self.firstQuoteChar and self.re.match(instring,loc) or None
3135        if not result:
3136            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3137
3138        loc = result.end()
3139        ret = result.group()
3140
3141        if self.unquoteResults:
3142
3143            # strip off quotes
3144            ret = ret[self.quoteCharLen:-self.endQuoteCharLen]
3145
3146            if isinstance(ret,basestring):
3147                # replace escaped whitespace
3148                if '\\' in ret and self.convertWhitespaceEscapes:
3149                    ws_map = {
3150                        r'\t' : '\t',
3151                        r'\n' : '\n',
3152                        r'\f' : '\f',
3153                        r'\r' : '\r',
3154                    }
3155                    for wslit,wschar in ws_map.items():
3156                        ret = ret.replace(wslit, wschar)
3157
3158                # replace escaped characters
3159                if self.escChar:
3160                    ret = re.sub(self.escCharReplacePattern, r"\g<1>", ret)
3161
3162                # replace escaped quotes
3163                if self.escQuote:
3164                    ret = ret.replace(self.escQuote, self.endQuoteChar)
3165
3166        return loc, ret
3167
3168    def __str__( self ):
3169        try:
3170            return super(QuotedString,self).__str__()
3171        except Exception:
3172            pass
3173
3174        if self.strRepr is None:
3175            self.strRepr = "quoted string, starting with %s ending with %s" % (self.quoteChar, self.endQuoteChar)
3176
3177        return self.strRepr

3180class CharsNotIn(Token):
3181    """Token for matching words composed of characters *not* in a given
3182    set (will include whitespace in matched characters if not listed in
3183    the provided exclusion set - see example). Defined with string
3184    containing all disallowed characters, and an optional minimum,
3185    maximum, and/or exact length.  The default value for ``min`` is
3186    1 (a minimum value < 1 is not valid); the default values for
3187    ``max`` and ``exact`` are 0, meaning no maximum or exact
3188    length restriction.
3189
3190    Example::
3191
3192        # define a comma-separated-value as anything that is not a ','
3193        csv_value = CharsNotIn(',')
3194        print(delimitedList(csv_value).parseString("dkls,lsdkjf,s12 34,@!#,213"))
3195
3196    prints::
3197
3198        ['dkls', 'lsdkjf', 's12 34', '@!#', '213']
3199    """
3200    def __init__( self, notChars, min=1, max=0, exact=0 ):
3201        super(CharsNotIn,self).__init__()
3202        self.skipWhitespace = False
3203        self.notChars = notChars
3204
3205        if min < 1:
3206            raise ValueError(
3207                "cannot specify a minimum length < 1; use " +
3208                "Optional(CharsNotIn()) if zero-length char group is permitted")
3209
3210        self.minLen = min
3211
3212        if max > 0:
3213            self.maxLen = max
3214        else:
3215            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
3216
3217        if exact > 0:
3218            self.maxLen = exact
3219            self.minLen = exact
3220
3221        self.name = _ustr(self)
3222        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3223        self.mayReturnEmpty = ( self.minLen == 0 )
3224        self.mayIndexError = False
3225
3226    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3227        if instring[loc] in self.notChars:
3228            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3229
3230        start = loc
3231        loc += 1
3232        notchars = self.notChars
3233        maxlen = min( start+self.maxLen, len(instring) )
3234        while loc < maxlen and \
3235              (instring[loc] not in notchars):
3236            loc += 1
3237
3238        if loc - start < self.minLen:
3239            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3240
3241        return loc, instring[start:loc]
3242
3243    def __str__( self ):
3244        try:
3245            return super(CharsNotIn, self).__str__()
3246        except Exception:
3247            pass
3248
3249        if self.strRepr is None:
3250            if len(self.notChars) > 4:
3251                self.strRepr = "!W:(%s...)" % self.notChars[:4]
3252            else:
3253                self.strRepr = "!W:(%s)" % self.notChars
3254
3255        return self.strRepr

3257class White(Token):
3258    """Special matching class for matching whitespace.  Normally,
3259    whitespace is ignored by pyparsing grammars.  This class is included
3260    when some whitespace structures are significant.  Define with
3261    a string containing the whitespace characters to be matched; default
3262    is ``" \\t\\r\\n"``.  Also takes optional ``min``,
3263    ``max``, and ``exact`` arguments, as defined for the
3264    :class:`Word` class.
3265    """
3266    whiteStrs = {
3267        " " : "<SPC>",
3268        "\t": "<TAB>",
3269        "\n": "<LF>",
3270        "\r": "<CR>",
3271        "\f": "<FF>",
3272        }
3273    def __init__(self, ws=" \t\r\n", min=1, max=0, exact=0):
3274        super(White,self).__init__()
3275        self.matchWhite = ws
3276        self.setWhitespaceChars( "".join(c for c in self.whiteChars if c not in self.matchWhite) )
3277        #~ self.leaveWhitespace()
3278        self.name = ("".join(White.whiteStrs[c] for c in self.matchWhite))
3279        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3280        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3281
3282        self.minLen = min
3283
3284        if max > 0:
3285            self.maxLen = max
3286        else:
3287            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
3288
3289        if exact > 0:
3290            self.maxLen = exact
3291            self.minLen = exact
3292
3293    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3294        if not(instring[ loc ] in self.matchWhite):
3295            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3296        start = loc
3297        loc += 1
3298        maxloc = start + self.maxLen
3299        maxloc = min( maxloc, len(instring) )
3300        while loc < maxloc and instring[loc] in self.matchWhite:
3301            loc += 1
3302
3303        if loc - start < self.minLen:
3304            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3305
3306        return loc, instring[start:loc]

3316class GoToColumn(_PositionToken):
3317    """Token to advance to a specific column of input text; useful for
3318    tabular report scraping.
3319    """
3320    def __init__( self, colno ):
3321        super(GoToColumn,self).__init__()
3322        self.col = colno
3323
3324    def preParse( self, instring, loc ):
3325        if col(loc,instring) != self.col:
3326            instrlen = len(instring)
3327            if self.ignoreExprs:
3328                loc = self._skipIgnorables( instring, loc )
3329            while loc < instrlen and instring[loc].isspace() and col( loc, instring ) != self.col :
3330                loc += 1
3331        return loc
3332
3333    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3334        thiscol = col( loc, instring )
3335        if thiscol > self.col:
3336            raise ParseException( instring, loc, "Text not in expected column", self )
3337        newloc = loc + self.col - thiscol
3338        ret = instring[ loc: newloc ]
3339        return newloc, ret

3342class LineStart(_PositionToken):
3343    """Matches if current position is at the beginning of a line within
3344    the parse string
3345
3346    Example::
3347
3348        test = '''\
3349        AAA this line
3350        AAA and this line
3351          AAA but not this one
3352        B AAA and definitely not this one
3353        '''
3354
3355        for t in (LineStart() + 'AAA' + restOfLine).searchString(test):
3356            print(t)
3357
3358    prints::
3359
3360        ['AAA', ' this line']
3361        ['AAA', ' and this line']
3362
3363    """
3364    def __init__( self ):
3365        super(LineStart,self).__init__()
3366        self.errmsg = "Expected start of line"
3367
3368    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3369        if col(loc, instring) == 1:
3370            return loc, []
3371        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

3373class LineEnd(_PositionToken):
3374    """Matches if current position is at the end of a line within the
3375    parse string
3376    """
3377    def __init__( self ):
3378        super(LineEnd,self).__init__()
3379        self.setWhitespaceChars( ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS.replace("\n","") )
3380        self.errmsg = "Expected end of line"
3381
3382    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3383        if loc<len(instring):
3384            if instring[loc] == "\n":
3385                return loc+1, "\n"
3386            else:
3387                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3388        elif loc == len(instring):
3389            return loc+1, []
3390        else:
3391            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

3393class StringStart(_PositionToken):

3402        if loc != 0:
3403            # see if entire string up to here is just whitespace and ignoreables
3404            if loc != self.preParse( instring, 0 ):
3405                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

3408class StringEnd(_PositionToken):
3409    """Matches if current position is at the end of the parse string

3414

3416        if loc < len(instring):
3417            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3418        elif loc == len(instring):
3419            return loc+1, []
3420        elif loc > len(instring):
3421            return loc, []
3422        else:
3423            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

3425class WordStart(_PositionToken):
3426    """Matches if the current position is at the beginning of a Word,
3427    and is not preceded by any character in a given set of
3428    ``wordChars`` (default= ``printables``). To emulate the
3429    ``\b`` behavior of regular expressions, use
3430    ``WordStart(alphanums)``. ``WordStart`` will also match at
3431    the beginning of the string being parsed, or at the beginning of
3432    a line.
3433    """
3434    def __init__(self, wordChars = printables):
3435        super(WordStart,self).__init__()
3436        self.wordChars = set(wordChars)
3437        self.errmsg = "Not at the start of a word"
3438
3439    def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3440        if loc != 0:
3441            if (instring[loc-1] in self.wordChars or
3442                instring[loc] not in self.wordChars):
3443                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3444        return loc, []

3446class WordEnd(_PositionToken):
3447    """Matches if the current position is at the end of a Word, and is
3448    not followed by any character in a given set of ``wordChars``
3449    (default= ``printables``). To emulate the ``\b`` behavior of
3450    regular expressions, use ``WordEnd(alphanums)``. ``WordEnd``
3451    will also match at the end of the string being parsed, or at the end
3452    of a line.
3453    """
3454    def __init__(self, wordChars = printables):
3455        super(WordEnd,self).__init__()
3456        self.wordChars = set(wordChars)
3457        self.skipWhitespace = False
3458        self.errmsg = "Not at the end of a word"
3459
3460    def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3461        instrlen = len(instring)
3462        if instrlen>0 and loc<instrlen:
3463            if (instring[loc] in self.wordChars or
3464                instring[loc-1] not in self.wordChars):
3465                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3466        return loc, []
