3469class ParseExpression(ParserElement):
3470    """Abstract subclass of ParserElement, for combining and
3471    post-processing parsed tokens.
3472    """
3473    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3474        super(ParseExpression,self).__init__(savelist)
3475        if isinstance( exprs, _generatorType ):
3476            exprs = list(exprs)
3477
3478        if isinstance( exprs, basestring ):
3479            self.exprs = [ ParserElement._literalStringClass( exprs ) ]
3480        elif isinstance( exprs, Iterable ):
3481            exprs = list(exprs)
3482            # if sequence of strings provided, wrap with Literal
3483            if all(isinstance(expr, basestring) for expr in exprs):
3484                exprs = map(ParserElement._literalStringClass, exprs)
3485            self.exprs = list(exprs)
3486        else:
3487            try:
3488                self.exprs = list( exprs )
3489            except TypeError:
3490                self.exprs = [ exprs ]
3491        self.callPreparse = False
3492
3493    def __getitem__( self, i ):
3494        return self.exprs[i]
3495
3496    def append( self, other ):
3497        self.exprs.append( other )
3498        self.strRepr = None
3499        return self
3500
3501    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
3502        """Extends ``leaveWhitespace`` defined in base class, and also invokes ``leaveWhitespace`` on
3503           all contained expressions."""
3504        self.skipWhitespace = False
3505        self.exprs = [ e.copy() for e in self.exprs ]
3506        for e in self.exprs:
3507            e.leaveWhitespace()
3508        return self
3509
3510    def ignore( self, other ):
3511        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
3512            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
3513                super( ParseExpression, self).ignore( other )
3514                for e in self.exprs:
3515                    e.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3516        else:
3517            super( ParseExpression, self).ignore( other )
3518            for e in self.exprs:
3519                e.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3520        return self
3521
3522    def __str__( self ):
3523        try:
3524            return super(ParseExpression,self).__str__()
3525        except Exception:
3526            pass
3527
3528        if self.strRepr is None:
3529            self.strRepr = "%s:(%s)" % ( self.__class__.__name__, _ustr(self.exprs) )
3530        return self.strRepr
3531
3532    def streamline( self ):
3533        super(ParseExpression,self).streamline()
3534
3535        for e in self.exprs:
3536            e.streamline()
3537
3538        # collapse nested And's of the form And( And( And( a,b), c), d) to And( a,b,c,d )
3539        # but only if there are no parse actions or resultsNames on the nested And's
3540        # (likewise for Or's and MatchFirst's)
3541        if ( len(self.exprs) == 2 ):
3542            other = self.exprs[0]
3543            if ( isinstance( other, self.__class__ ) and
3544                  not(other.parseAction) and
3545                  other.resultsName is None and
3546                  not other.debug ):
3547                self.exprs = other.exprs[:] + [ self.exprs[1] ]
3548                self.strRepr = None
3549                self.mayReturnEmpty |= other.mayReturnEmpty
3550                self.mayIndexError  |= other.mayIndexError
3551
3552            other = self.exprs[-1]
3553            if ( isinstance( other, self.__class__ ) and
3554                  not(other.parseAction) and
3555                  other.resultsName is None and
3556                  not other.debug ):
3557                self.exprs = self.exprs[:-1] + other.exprs[:]
3558                self.strRepr = None
3559                self.mayReturnEmpty |= other.mayReturnEmpty
3560                self.mayIndexError  |= other.mayIndexError
3561
3562        self.errmsg = "Expected " + _ustr(self)
3563
3564        return self
3565
3566    def setResultsName( self, name, listAllMatches=False ):
3567        ret = super(ParseExpression,self).setResultsName(name,listAllMatches)
3568        return ret
3569
3570    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
3571        tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
3572        for e in self.exprs:
3573            e.validate(tmp)
3574        self.checkRecursion( [] )
3575
3576    def copy(self):
3577        ret = super(ParseExpression,self).copy()
3578        ret.exprs = [e.copy() for e in self.exprs]
3579        return ret
3580
3581class And(ParseExpression):
3582    """
3583    Requires all given :class:`ParseExpression` s to be found in the given order.
3584    Expressions may be separated by whitespace.
3585    May be constructed using the ``'+'`` operator.
3586    May also be constructed using the ``'-'`` operator, which will
3587    suppress backtracking.
3588
3589    Example::
3590
3591        integer = Word(nums)
3592        name_expr = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
3593
3594        expr = And([integer("id"),name_expr("name"),integer("age")])
3595        # more easily written as:
3596        expr = integer("id") + name_expr("name") + integer("age")
3597    """
3598
3599    class _ErrorStop(Empty):
3600        def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
3601            super(And._ErrorStop,self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
3602            self.name = '-'
3603            self.leaveWhitespace()
3604
3605    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = True ):
3606        super(And,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3607        self.mayReturnEmpty = all(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3608        self.setWhitespaceChars( self.exprs[0].whiteChars )
3609        self.skipWhitespace = self.exprs[0].skipWhitespace
3610        self.callPreparse = True
3611
3612    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3613        # pass False as last arg to _parse for first element, since we already
3614        # pre-parsed the string as part of our And pre-parsing
3615        loc, resultlist = self.exprs[0]._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
3616        errorStop = False
3617        for e in self.exprs[1:]:
3618            if isinstance(e, And._ErrorStop):
3619                errorStop = True
3620                continue
3621            if errorStop:
3622                try:
3623                    loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3624                except ParseSyntaxException:
3625                    raise
3626                except ParseBaseException as pe:
3627                    pe.__traceback__ = None
3628                    raise ParseSyntaxException._from_exception(pe)
3629                except IndexError:
3630                    raise ParseSyntaxException(instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self)
3631            else:
3632                loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3633            if exprtokens or exprtokens.haskeys():
3634                resultlist += exprtokens
3635        return loc, resultlist
3636
3637    def __iadd__(self, other ):
3638        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3639            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3640        return self.append( other ) #And( [ self, other ] )
3641
3642    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3643        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3644        for e in self.exprs:
3645            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3646            if not e.mayReturnEmpty:
3647                break
3648
3649    def __str__( self ):
3650        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3651            return self.name
3652
3653        if self.strRepr is None:
3654            self.strRepr = "{" + " ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3655
3656        return self.strRepr
3657

3659class Or(ParseExpression):
3660    """Requires that at least one :class:`ParseExpression` is found. If
3661    two expressions match, the expression that matches the longest
3662    string will be used. May be constructed using the ``'^'``
3663    operator.
3664
3665    Example::
3666
3667        # construct Or using '^' operator
3668
3669        number = Word(nums) ^ Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
3670        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789"))
3671
3672    prints::
3673
3674        [['123'], ['3.1416'], ['789']]
3675    """
3676    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3677        super(Or,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3678        if self.exprs:
3679            self.mayReturnEmpty = any(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3680        else:
3681            self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3682
3683    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3684        maxExcLoc = -1
3685        maxException = None
3686        matches = []
3687        for e in self.exprs:
3688            try:
3689                loc2 = e.tryParse( instring, loc )
3690            except ParseException as err:
3691                err.__traceback__ = None
3692                if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3693                    maxException = err
3694                    maxExcLoc = err.loc
3695            except IndexError:
3696                if len(instring) > maxExcLoc:
3697                    maxException = ParseException(instring,len(instring),e.errmsg,self)
3698                    maxExcLoc = len(instring)
3699            else:
3700                # save match among all matches, to retry longest to shortest
3701                matches.append((loc2, e))
3702
3703        if matches:
3704            matches.sort(key=lambda x: -x[0])
3705            for _,e in matches:
3706                try:
3707                    return e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3708                except ParseException as err:
3709                    err.__traceback__ = None
3710                    if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3711                        maxException = err
3712                        maxExcLoc = err.loc
3713
3714        if maxException is not None:
3715            maxException.msg = self.errmsg
3716            raise maxException
3717        else:
3718            raise ParseException(instring, loc, "no defined alternatives to match", self)
3719
3720
3721    def __ixor__(self, other ):
3722        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3723            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3724        return self.append( other ) #Or( [ self, other ] )
3725
3726    def __str__( self ):
3727        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3728            return self.name
3729
3730        if self.strRepr is None:
3731            self.strRepr = "{" + " ^ ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3732
3733        return self.strRepr
3734
3735    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3736        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3737        for e in self.exprs:
3738            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3739
3740
3741class MatchFirst(ParseExpression):
3742    """Requires that at least one :class:`ParseExpression` is found. If
3743    two expressions match, the first one listed is the one that will
3744    match. May be constructed using the ``'|'`` operator.
3745
3746    Example::
3747
3748        # construct MatchFirst using '|' operator
3749
3750        # watch the order of expressions to match
3751        number = Word(nums) | Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
3752        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Fail! -> [['123'], ['3'], ['1416'], ['789']]
3753
3754        # put more selective expression first
3755        number = Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums)) | Word(nums)
3756        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Better -> [['123'], ['3.1416'], ['789']]
3757    """
3758    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3759        super(MatchFirst,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3760        if self.exprs:
3761            self.mayReturnEmpty = any(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3762        else:
3763            self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3764
3765    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3766        maxExcLoc = -1
3767        maxException = None
3768        for e in self.exprs:
3769            try:
3770                ret = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3771                return ret
3772            except ParseException as err:
3773                if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3774                    maxException = err
3775                    maxExcLoc = err.loc
3776            except IndexError:
3777                if len(instring) > maxExcLoc:
3778                    maxException = ParseException(instring,len(instring),e.errmsg,self)
3779                    maxExcLoc = len(instring)
3780
3781        # only got here if no expression matched, raise exception for match that made it the furthest
3782        else:
3783            if maxException is not None:
3784                maxException.msg = self.errmsg
3785                raise maxException
3786            else:
3787                raise ParseException(instring, loc, "no defined alternatives to match", self)
3788
3789    def __ior__(self, other ):
3790        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3791            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3792        return self.append( other ) #MatchFirst( [ self, other ] )
3793
3794    def __str__( self ):
3795        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3796            return self.name
3797
3798        if self.strRepr is None:
3799            self.strRepr = "{" + " | ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3800
3801        return self.strRepr
3802
3803    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3804        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3805        for e in self.exprs:
3806            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )

3808
3809class Each(ParseExpression):
3810    """Requires all given :class:`ParseExpression` s to be found, but in
3811    any order. Expressions may be separated by whitespace.
3812
3813    May be constructed using the ``'&'`` operator.
3814
3815    Example::
3816
3817        color = oneOf("RED ORANGE YELLOW GREEN BLUE PURPLE BLACK WHITE BROWN")
3818        shape_type = oneOf("SQUARE CIRCLE TRIANGLE STAR HEXAGON OCTAGON")
3819        integer = Word(nums)
3820        shape_attr = "shape:" + shape_type("shape")
3821        posn_attr = "posn:" + Group(integer("x") + ',' + integer("y"))("posn")
3822        color_attr = "color:" + color("color")
3823        size_attr = "size:" + integer("size")
3824
3825        # use Each (using operator '&') to accept attributes in any order
3826        # (shape and posn are required, color and size are optional)
3827        shape_spec = shape_attr & posn_attr & Optional(color_attr) & Optional(size_attr)
3828
3829        shape_spec.runTests('''
3830            shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: 100, 120
3831            shape: CIRCLE size: 50 color: BLUE posn: 50,80
3832            color:GREEN size:20 shape:TRIANGLE posn:20,40
3833            '''
3834            )
3835
3836    prints::
3837
3838        shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: 100, 120
3839        ['shape:', 'SQUARE', 'color:', 'BLACK', 'posn:', ['100', ',', '120']]
3840        - color: BLACK
3841        - posn: ['100', ',', '120']
3842          - x: 100
3843          - y: 120
3844        - shape: SQUARE
3845
3846
3847        shape: CIRCLE size: 50 color: BLUE posn: 50,80
3848        ['shape:', 'CIRCLE', 'size:', '50', 'color:', 'BLUE', 'posn:', ['50', ',', '80']]
3849        - color: BLUE
3850        - posn: ['50', ',', '80']
3851          - x: 50
3852          - y: 80
3853        - shape: CIRCLE
3854        - size: 50
3855
3856
3857        color: GREEN size: 20 shape: TRIANGLE posn: 20,40
3858        ['color:', 'GREEN', 'size:', '20', 'shape:', 'TRIANGLE', 'posn:', ['20', ',', '40']]
3859        - color: GREEN
3860        - posn: ['20', ',', '40']
3861          - x: 20
3862          - y: 40
3863        - shape: TRIANGLE
3864        - size: 20
3865    """
3866    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = True ):
3867        super(Each,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3868        self.mayReturnEmpty = all(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3869        self.skipWhitespace = True
3870        self.initExprGroups = True
3871
3872    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3873        if self.initExprGroups:
3874            self.opt1map = dict((id(e.expr),e) for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional))
3875            opt1 = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional) ]
3876            opt2 = [ e for e in self.exprs if e.mayReturnEmpty and not isinstance(e,Optional)]
3877            self.optionals = opt1 + opt2
3878            self.multioptionals = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,ZeroOrMore) ]
3879            self.multirequired = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,OneOrMore) ]
3880            self.required = [ e for e in self.exprs if not isinstance(e,(Optional,ZeroOrMore,OneOrMore)) ]
3881            self.required += self.multirequired
3882            self.initExprGroups = False
3883        tmpLoc = loc
3884        tmpReqd = self.required[:]
3885        tmpOpt  = self.optionals[:]
3886        matchOrder = []
3887
3888        keepMatching = True
3889        while keepMatching:
3890            tmpExprs = tmpReqd + tmpOpt + self.multioptionals + self.multirequired
3891            failed = []
3892            for e in tmpExprs:
3893                try:
3894                    tmpLoc = e.tryParse( instring, tmpLoc )
3895                except ParseException:
3896                    failed.append(e)
3897                else:
3898                    matchOrder.append(self.opt1map.get(id(e),e))
3899                    if e in tmpReqd:
3900                        tmpReqd.remove(e)
3901                    elif e in tmpOpt:
3902                        tmpOpt.remove(e)
3903            if len(failed) == len(tmpExprs):
3904                keepMatching = False
3905
3906        if tmpReqd:
3907            missing = ", ".join(_ustr(e) for e in tmpReqd)
3908            raise ParseException(instring,loc,"Missing one or more required elements (%s)" % missing )
3909
3910        # add any unmatched Optionals, in case they have default values defined
3911        matchOrder += [e for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional) and e.expr in tmpOpt]
3912
3913        resultlist = []
3914        for e in matchOrder:
3915            loc,results = e._parse(instring,loc,doActions)
3916            resultlist.append(results)
3917
3918        finalResults = sum(resultlist, ParseResults([]))
3919        return loc, finalResults
3920
3921    def __str__( self ):
3922        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3923            return self.name
3924
3925        if self.strRepr is None:
3926            self.strRepr = "{" + " & ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3927
3928        return self.strRepr
3929
3930    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3931        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3932        for e in self.exprs:
3933            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3934
3935
3936class ParseElementEnhance(ParserElement):
3937    """Abstract subclass of :class:`ParserElement`, for combining and
3938    post-processing parsed tokens.
3939    """
3940    def __init__( self, expr, savelist=False ):
3941        super(ParseElementEnhance,self).__init__(savelist)
3942        if isinstance( expr, basestring ):
3943            if issubclass(ParserElement._literalStringClass, Token):
3944                expr = ParserElement._literalStringClass(expr)
3945            else:
3946                expr = ParserElement._literalStringClass(Literal(expr))
3947        self.expr = expr
3948        self.strRepr = None
3949        if expr is not None:
3950            self.mayIndexError = expr.mayIndexError
3951            self.mayReturnEmpty = expr.mayReturnEmpty
3952            self.setWhitespaceChars( expr.whiteChars )
3953            self.skipWhitespace = expr.skipWhitespace
3954            self.saveAsList = expr.saveAsList
3955            self.callPreparse = expr.callPreparse
3956            self.ignoreExprs.extend(expr.ignoreExprs)
3957
3958    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3959        if self.expr is not None:
3960            return self.expr._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
3961        else:
3962            raise ParseException("",loc,self.errmsg,self)
3963
3964    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
3965        self.skipWhitespace = False
3966        self.expr = self.expr.copy()
3967        if self.expr is not None:
3968            self.expr.leaveWhitespace()
3969        return self
3970
3971    def ignore( self, other ):
3972        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
3973            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
3974                super( ParseElementEnhance, self).ignore( other )
3975                if self.expr is not None:
3976                    self.expr.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3977        else:
3978            super( ParseElementEnhance, self).ignore( other )
3979            if self.expr is not None:
3980                self.expr.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3981        return self
3982
3983    def streamline( self ):
3984        super(ParseElementEnhance,self).streamline()
3985        if self.expr is not None:
3986            self.expr.streamline()
3987        return self
3988
3989    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3990        if self in parseElementList:
3991            raise RecursiveGrammarException( parseElementList+[self] )
3992        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3993        if self.expr is not None:
3994            self.expr.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3995
3996    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
3997        tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
3998        if self.expr is not None:
3999            self.expr.validate(tmp)
4000        self.checkRecursion( [] )
4001
4002    def __str__( self ):
4003        try:
4004            return super(ParseElementEnhance,self).__str__()
4005        except Exception:
4006            pass
4007
4008        if self.strRepr is None and self.expr is not None:
4009            self.strRepr = "%s:(%s)" % ( self.__class__.__name__, _ustr(self.expr) )
4010        return self.strRepr
4011
4012
4013class FollowedBy(ParseElementEnhance):
4014    """Lookahead matching of the given parse expression.
4015    ``FollowedBy`` does *not* advance the parsing position within
4016    the input string, it only verifies that the specified parse
4017    expression matches at the current position.  ``FollowedBy``
4018    always returns a null token list. If any results names are defined
4019    in the lookahead expression, those *will* be returned for access by
4020    name.
4021
4022    Example::
4023
4024        # use FollowedBy to match a label only if it is followed by a ':'
4025        data_word = Word(alphas)
4026        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4027        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4028
4029        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString("shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: upper left").pprint()
4030
4031    prints::
4032
4033        [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['color', 'BLACK'], ['posn', 'upper left']]
4034    """
4035    def __init__( self, expr ):
4036        super(FollowedBy,self).__init__(expr)
4037        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4038
4039    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4040        _, ret = self.expr._parse(instring, loc, doActions=doActions)
4041        del ret[:]
4042        return loc, ret
4043
4044
4045class PrecededBy(ParseElementEnhance):
4046    """Lookbehind matching of the given parse expression.
4047    ``PrecededBy`` does not advance the parsing position within the
4048    input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression
4049    matches prior to the current position.  ``PrecededBy`` always
4050    returns a null token list, but if a results name is defined on the
4051    given expression, it is returned.
4052
4053    Parameters:
4054
4055     - expr - expression that must match prior to the current parse
4056       location
4057     - retreat - (default= ``None``) - (int) maximum number of characters
4058       to lookbehind prior to the current parse location
4059
4060    If the lookbehind expression is a string, Literal, Keyword, or
4061    a Word or CharsNotIn with a specified exact or maximum length, then
4062    the retreat parameter is not required. Otherwise, retreat must be
4063    specified to give a maximum number of characters to look back from
4064    the current parse position for a lookbehind match.
4065
4066    Example::
4067
4068        # VB-style variable names with type prefixes
4069        int_var = PrecededBy("#") + pyparsing_common.identifier
4070        str_var = PrecededBy("$") + pyparsing_common.identifier
4071
4072    """
4073    def __init__(self, expr, retreat=None):
4074        super(PrecededBy, self).__init__(expr)
4075        self.expr = self.expr().leaveWhitespace()
4076        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4077        self.mayIndexError = False
4078        self.exact = False
4079        if isinstance(expr, str):
4080            retreat = len(expr)
4081            self.exact = True
4082        elif isinstance(expr, (Literal, Keyword)):
4083            retreat = expr.matchLen
4084            self.exact = True
4085        elif isinstance(expr, (Word, CharsNotIn)) and expr.maxLen != _MAX_INT:
4086            retreat = expr.maxLen
4087            self.exact = True
4088        elif isinstance(expr, _PositionToken):
4089            retreat = 0
4090            self.exact = True
4091        self.retreat = retreat
4092        self.errmsg = "not preceded by " + str(expr)
4093        self.skipWhitespace = False
4094
4095    def parseImpl(self, instring, loc=0, doActions=True):
4096        if self.exact:
4097            if loc < self.retreat:
4098                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg)
4099            start = loc - self.retreat
4100            _, ret = self.expr._parse(instring, start)
4101        else:
4102            # retreat specified a maximum lookbehind window, iterate
4103            test_expr = self.expr + StringEnd()
4104            instring_slice = instring[:loc]
4105            last_expr = ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg)
4106            for offset in range(1, min(loc, self.retreat+1)):
4107                try:
4108                    _, ret = test_expr._parse(instring_slice, loc-offset)
4109                except ParseBaseException as pbe:
4110                    last_expr = pbe
4111                else:
4112                    break
4113            else:
4114                raise last_expr
4115        # return empty list of tokens, but preserve any defined results names
4116        del ret[:]
4117        return loc, ret
4118
4119
4120class NotAny(ParseElementEnhance):
4121    """Lookahead to disallow matching with the given parse expression.
4122    ``NotAny`` does *not* advance the parsing position within the
4123    input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression
4124    does *not* match at the current position.  Also, ``NotAny`` does
4125    *not* skip over leading whitespace. ``NotAny`` always returns
4126    a null token list.  May be constructed using the '~' operator.
4127
4128    Example::
4129
4130        AND, OR, NOT = map(CaselessKeyword, "AND OR NOT".split())
4131
4132        # take care not to mistake keywords for identifiers
4133        ident = ~(AND | OR | NOT) + Word(alphas)
4134        boolean_term = Optional(NOT) + ident
4135
4136        # very crude boolean expression - to support parenthesis groups and
4137        # operation hierarchy, use infixNotation
4138        boolean_expr = boolean_term + ZeroOrMore((AND | OR) + boolean_term)
4139
4140        # integers that are followed by "." are actually floats
4141        integer = Word(nums) + ~Char(".")
4142    """
4143    def __init__( self, expr ):
4144        super(NotAny,self).__init__(expr)
4145        #~ self.leaveWhitespace()
4146        self.skipWhitespace = False  # do NOT use self.leaveWhitespace(), don't want to propagate to exprs
4147        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4148        self.errmsg = "Found unwanted token, "+_ustr(self.expr)
4149
4150    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4151        if self.expr.canParseNext(instring, loc):
4152            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
4153        return loc, []
4154
4155    def __str__( self ):
4156        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4157            return self.name
4158
4159        if self.strRepr is None:
4160            self.strRepr = "~{" + _ustr(self.expr) + "}"
4161
4162        return self.strRepr
4163
4164class _MultipleMatch(ParseElementEnhance):
4165    def __init__( self, expr, stopOn=None):
4166        super(_MultipleMatch, self).__init__(expr)
4167        self.saveAsList = True
4168        ender = stopOn
4169        if isinstance(ender, basestring):
4170            ender = ParserElement._literalStringClass(ender)
4171        self.not_ender = ~ender if ender is not None else None
4172
4173    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4174        self_expr_parse = self.expr._parse
4175        self_skip_ignorables = self._skipIgnorables
4176        check_ender = self.not_ender is not None
4177        if check_ender:
4178            try_not_ender = self.not_ender.tryParse
4179
4180        # must be at least one (but first see if we are the stopOn sentinel;
4181        # if so, fail)
4182        if check_ender:
4183            try_not_ender(instring, loc)
4184        loc, tokens = self_expr_parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
4185        try:
4186            hasIgnoreExprs = (not not self.ignoreExprs)
4187            while 1:
4188                if check_ender:
4189                    try_not_ender(instring, loc)
4190                if hasIgnoreExprs:
4191                    preloc = self_skip_ignorables( instring, loc )
4192                else:
4193                    preloc = loc
4194                loc, tmptokens = self_expr_parse( instring, preloc, doActions )
4195                if tmptokens or tmptokens.haskeys():
4196                    tokens += tmptokens
4197        except (ParseException,IndexError):
4198            pass
4199
4200        return loc, tokens
4201
4202class OneOrMore(_MultipleMatch):
4203    """Repetition of one or more of the given expression.
4204
4205    Parameters:
4206     - expr - expression that must match one or more times
4207     - stopOn - (default= ``None``) - expression for a terminating sentinel
4208          (only required if the sentinel would ordinarily match the repetition
4209          expression)
4210
4211    Example::
4212
4213        data_word = Word(alphas)
4214        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4215        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word).setParseAction(' '.join))
4216
4217        text = "shape: SQUARE posn: upper left color: BLACK"
4218        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).pprint()  # Fail! read 'color' as data instead of next label -> [['shape', 'SQUARE color']]
4219
4220        # use stopOn attribute for OneOrMore to avoid reading label string as part of the data
4221        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4222        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).pprint() # Better -> [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['posn', 'upper left'], ['color', 'BLACK']]
4223
4224        # could also be written as
4225        (attr_expr * (1,)).parseString(text).pprint()
4226    """
4227
4228    def __str__( self ):
4229        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4230            return self.name
4231
4232        if self.strRepr is None:
4233            self.strRepr = "{" + _ustr(self.expr) + "}..."
4234
4235        return self.strRepr
4236
4237class ZeroOrMore(_MultipleMatch):
4238    """Optional repetition of zero or more of the given expression.
4239
4240    Parameters:
4241     - expr - expression that must match zero or more times
4242     - stopOn - (default= ``None``) - expression for a terminating sentinel
4243          (only required if the sentinel would ordinarily match the repetition
4244          expression)
4245
4246    Example: similar to :class:`OneOrMore`
4247    """
4248    def __init__( self, expr, stopOn=None):
4249        super(ZeroOrMore,self).__init__(expr, stopOn=stopOn)
4250        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4251
4252    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4253        try:
4254            return super(ZeroOrMore, self).parseImpl(instring, loc, doActions)
4255        except (ParseException,IndexError):
4256            return loc, []
4257
4258    def __str__( self ):
4259        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4260            return self.name
4261
4262        if self.strRepr is None:
4263            self.strRepr = "[" + _ustr(self.expr) + "]..."
4264
4265        return self.strRepr
4266
4267class _NullToken(object):
4268    def __bool__(self):
4269        return False
4270    __nonzero__ = __bool__
4271    def __str__(self):
4272        return ""
4273
4274_optionalNotMatched = _NullToken()
4275class Optional(ParseElementEnhance):
4276    """Optional matching of the given expression.
4277
4278    Parameters:
4279     - expr - expression that must match zero or more times
4280     - default (optional) - value to be returned if the optional expression is not found.
4281
4282    Example::
4283
4284        # US postal code can be a 5-digit zip, plus optional 4-digit qualifier
4285        zip = Combine(Word(nums, exact=5) + Optional('-' + Word(nums, exact=4)))
4286        zip.runTests('''
4287            # traditional ZIP code
4288            12345
4289
4290            # ZIP+4 form
4291            12101-0001
4292
4293            # invalid ZIP
4294            98765-
4295            ''')
4296
4297    prints::
4298
4299        # traditional ZIP code
4300        12345
4301        ['12345']
4302
4303        # ZIP+4 form
4304        12101-0001
4305        ['12101-0001']
4306
4307        # invalid ZIP
4308        98765-
4309             ^
4310        FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 5), (line:1, col:6)
4311    """
4312    def __init__( self, expr, default=_optionalNotMatched ):
4313        super(Optional,self).__init__( expr, savelist=False )
4314        self.saveAsList = self.expr.saveAsList
4315        self.defaultValue = default
4316        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4317
4318    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4319        try:
4320            loc, tokens = self.expr._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
4321        except (ParseException,IndexError):
4322            if self.defaultValue is not _optionalNotMatched:
4323                if self.expr.resultsName:
4324                    tokens = ParseResults([ self.defaultValue ])
4325                    tokens[self.expr.resultsName] = self.defaultValue
4326                else:
4327                    tokens = [ self.defaultValue ]
4328            else:
4329                tokens = []
4330        return loc, tokens
4331
4332    def __str__( self ):
4333        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4334            return self.name
4335
4336        if self.strRepr is None:
4337            self.strRepr = "[" + _ustr(self.expr) + "]"
4338
4339        return self.strRepr
4340
4341class SkipTo(ParseElementEnhance):
4342    """Token for skipping over all undefined text until the matched
4343    expression is found.
4344
4345    Parameters:
4346     - expr - target expression marking the end of the data to be skipped
4347     - include - (default= ``False``) if True, the target expression is also parsed
4348          (the skipped text and target expression are returned as a 2-element list).
4349     - ignore - (default= ``None``) used to define grammars (typically quoted strings and
4350          comments) that might contain false matches to the target expression
4351     - failOn - (default= ``None``) define expressions that are not allowed to be
4352          included in the skipped test; if found before the target expression is found,
4353          the SkipTo is not a match
4354
4355    Example::
4356
4357        report = '''
4358            Outstanding Issues Report - 1 Jan 2000
4359
4360               # | Severity | Description                               |  Days Open
4361            -----+----------+-------------------------------------------+-----------
4362             101 | Critical | Intermittent system crash                 |          6
4363              94 | Cosmetic | Spelling error on Login ('log|n')         |         14
4364              79 | Minor    | System slow when running too many reports |         47
4365            '''
4366        integer = Word(nums)
4367        SEP = Suppress('|')
4368        # use SkipTo to simply match everything up until the next SEP
4369        # - ignore quoted strings, so that a '|' character inside a quoted string does not match
4370        # - parse action will call token.strip() for each matched token, i.e., the description body
4371        string_data = SkipTo(SEP, ignore=quotedString)
4372        string_data.setParseAction(tokenMap(str.strip))
4373        ticket_expr = (integer("issue_num") + SEP
4374                      + string_data("sev") + SEP
4375                      + string_data("desc") + SEP
4376                      + integer("days_open"))
4377
4378        for tkt in ticket_expr.searchString(report):
4379            print tkt.dump()
4380
4381    prints::
4382
4383        ['101', 'Critical', 'Intermittent system crash', '6']
4384        - days_open: 6
4385        - desc: Intermittent system crash
4386        - issue_num: 101
4387        - sev: Critical
4388        ['94', 'Cosmetic', "Spelling error on Login ('log|n')", '14']
4389        - days_open: 14
4390        - desc: Spelling error on Login ('log|n')
4391        - issue_num: 94
4392        - sev: Cosmetic
4393        ['79', 'Minor', 'System slow when running too many reports', '47']
4394        - days_open: 47
4395        - desc: System slow when running too many reports
4396        - issue_num: 79
4397        - sev: Minor
4398    """
4399    def __init__( self, other, include=False, ignore=None, failOn=None ):
4400        super( SkipTo, self ).__init__( other )
4401        self.ignoreExpr = ignore
4402        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4403        self.mayIndexError = False
4404        self.includeMatch = include
4405        self.saveAsList = False
4406        if isinstance(failOn, basestring):
4407            self.failOn = ParserElement._literalStringClass(failOn)
4408        else:
4409            self.failOn = failOn
4410        self.errmsg = "No match found for "+_ustr(self.expr)
4411
4412    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4413        startloc = loc
4414        instrlen = len(instring)
4415        expr = self.expr
4416        expr_parse = self.expr._parse
4417        self_failOn_canParseNext = self.failOn.canParseNext if self.failOn is not None else None
4418        self_ignoreExpr_tryParse = self.ignoreExpr.tryParse if self.ignoreExpr is not None else None
4419
4420        tmploc = loc
4421        while tmploc <= instrlen:
4422            if self_failOn_canParseNext is not None:
4423                # break if failOn expression matches
4424                if self_failOn_canParseNext(instring, tmploc):
4425                    break
4426
4427            if self_ignoreExpr_tryParse is not None:
4428                # advance past ignore expressions
4429                while 1:
4430                    try:
4431                        tmploc = self_ignoreExpr_tryParse(instring, tmploc)
4432                    except ParseBaseException:
4433                        break
4434
4435            try:
4436                expr_parse(instring, tmploc, doActions=False, callPreParse=False)
4437            except (ParseException, IndexError):
4438                # no match, advance loc in string
4439                tmploc += 1
4440            else:
4441                # matched skipto expr, done
4442                break
4443
4444        else:
4445            # ran off the end of the input string without matching skipto expr, fail
4446            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
4447
4448        # build up return values
4449        loc = tmploc
4450        skiptext = instring[startloc:loc]
4451        skipresult = ParseResults(skiptext)
4452
4453        if self.includeMatch:
4454            loc, mat = expr_parse(instring,loc,doActions,callPreParse=False)
4455            skipresult += mat
4456
4457        return loc, skipresult
4458
4459class Forward(ParseElementEnhance):
4460    """Forward declaration of an expression to be defined later -
4461    used for recursive grammars, such as algebraic infix notation.
4462    When the expression is known, it is assigned to the ``Forward``
4463    variable using the '<<' operator.
4464
4465    Note: take care when assigning to ``Forward`` not to overlook
4466    precedence of operators.
4467
4468    Specifically, '|' has a lower precedence than '<<', so that::
4469
4470        fwdExpr << a | b | c
4471
4472    will actually be evaluated as::
4473
4474        (fwdExpr << a) | b | c
4475
4476    thereby leaving b and c out as parseable alternatives.  It is recommended that you
4477    explicitly group the values inserted into the ``Forward``::
4478
4479        fwdExpr << (a | b | c)
4480
4481    Converting to use the '<<=' operator instead will avoid this problem.
4482
4483    See :class:`ParseResults.pprint` for an example of a recursive
4484    parser created using ``Forward``.
4485    """
4486    def __init__( self, other=None ):
4487        super(Forward,self).__init__( other, savelist=False )
4488
4489    def __lshift__( self, other ):
4490        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
4491            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass(other)
4492        self.expr = other
4493        self.strRepr = None
4494        self.mayIndexError = self.expr.mayIndexError
4495        self.mayReturnEmpty = self.expr.mayReturnEmpty
4496        self.setWhitespaceChars( self.expr.whiteChars )
4497        self.skipWhitespace = self.expr.skipWhitespace
4498        self.saveAsList = self.expr.saveAsList
4499        self.ignoreExprs.extend(self.expr.ignoreExprs)
4500        return self
4501
4502    def __ilshift__(self, other):
4503        return self << other
4504
4505    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
4506        self.skipWhitespace = False
4507        return self
4508
4509    def streamline( self ):
4510        if not self.streamlined:
4511            self.streamlined = True
4512            if self.expr is not None:
4513                self.expr.streamline()
4514        return self
4515
4516    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
4517        if self not in validateTrace:
4518            tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
4519            if self.expr is not None:
4520                self.expr.validate(tmp)
4521        self.checkRecursion([])
4522
4523    def __str__( self ):
4524        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4525            return self.name
4526        return self.__class__.__name__ + ": ..."
4527
4528        # stubbed out for now - creates awful memory and perf issues
4529        self._revertClass = self.__class__
4530        self.__class__ = _ForwardNoRecurse
4531        try:
4532            if self.expr is not None:
4533                retString = _ustr(self.expr)
4534            else:
4535                retString = "None"
4536        finally:
4537            self.__class__ = self._revertClass
4538        return self.__class__.__name__ + ": " + retString
4539
4540    def copy(self):
4541        if self.expr is not None:
4542            return super(Forward,self).copy()
4543        else:
4544            ret = Forward()
4545            ret <<= self
4546            return ret
4547
4548class _ForwardNoRecurse(Forward):
4549    def __str__( self ):
4550        return "..."
4551
4552class TokenConverter(ParseElementEnhance):
4553    """
4554    Abstract subclass of :class:`ParseExpression`, for converting parsed results.
4555    """
4556    def __init__( self, expr, savelist=False ):
4557        super(TokenConverter,self).__init__( expr )#, savelist )
4558        self.saveAsList = False
4559
4560class Combine(TokenConverter):
4561    """Converter to concatenate all matching tokens to a single string.
4562    By default, the matching patterns must also be contiguous in the
4563    input string; this can be disabled by specifying
4564    ``'adjacent=False'`` in the constructor.
4565
4566    Example::
4567
4568        real = Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums)
4569        print(real.parseString('3.1416')) # -> ['3', '.', '1416']
4570        # will also erroneously match the following
4571        print(real.parseString('3. 1416')) # -> ['3', '.', '1416']
4572
4573        real = Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
4574        print(real.parseString('3.1416')) # -> ['3.1416']
4575        # no match when there are internal spaces
4576        print(real.parseString('3. 1416')) # -> Exception: Expected W:(0123...)
4577    """
4578    def __init__( self, expr, joinString="", adjacent=True ):
4579        super(Combine,self).__init__( expr )
4580        # suppress whitespace-stripping in contained parse expressions, but re-enable it on the Combine itself
4581        if adjacent:
4582            self.leaveWhitespace()
4583        self.adjacent = adjacent
4584        self.skipWhitespace = True
4585        self.joinString = joinString
4586        self.callPreparse = True
4587
4588    def ignore( self, other ):
4589        if self.adjacent:
4590            ParserElement.ignore(self, other)
4591        else:
4592            super( Combine, self).ignore( other )
4593        return self
4594
4595    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4596        retToks = tokenlist.copy()
4597        del retToks[:]
4598        retToks += ParseResults([ "".join(tokenlist._asStringList(self.joinString)) ], modal=self.modalResults)
4599
4600        if self.resultsName and retToks.haskeys():
4601            return [ retToks ]
4602        else:
4603            return retToks
4604
4605class Group(TokenConverter):
4606    """Converter to return the matched tokens as a list - useful for
4607    returning tokens of :class:`ZeroOrMore` and :class:`OneOrMore` expressions.
4608
4609    Example::
4610
4611        ident = Word(alphas)
4612        num = Word(nums)
4613        term = ident | num
4614        func = ident + Optional(delimitedList(term))
4615        print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', 'a', 'b', '100']
4616
4617        func = ident + Group(Optional(delimitedList(term)))
4618        print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', ['a', 'b', '100']]
4619    """
4620    def __init__( self, expr ):
4621        super(Group,self).__init__( expr )
4622        self.saveAsList = True
4623
4624    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4625        return [ tokenlist ]
4626
4627class Dict(TokenConverter):
4628    """Converter to return a repetitive expression as a list, but also
4629    as a dictionary. Each element can also be referenced using the first
4630    token in the expression as its key. Useful for tabular report
4631    scraping when the first column can be used as a item key.
4632
4633    Example::
4634
4635        data_word = Word(alphas)
4636        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4637        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word).setParseAction(' '.join))
4638
4639        text = "shape: SQUARE posn: upper left color: light blue texture: burlap"
4640        attr_expr = (label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4641
4642        # print attributes as plain groups
4643        print(OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).dump())
4644
4645        # instead of OneOrMore(expr), parse using Dict(OneOrMore(Group(expr))) - Dict will auto-assign names
4646        result = Dict(OneOrMore(Group(attr_expr))).parseString(text)
4647        print(result.dump())
4648
4649        # access named fields as dict entries, or output as dict
4650        print(result['shape'])
4651        print(result.asDict())
4652
4653    prints::
4654
4655        ['shape', 'SQUARE', 'posn', 'upper left', 'color', 'light blue', 'texture', 'burlap']
4656        [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['posn', 'upper left'], ['color', 'light blue'], ['texture', 'burlap']]
4657        - color: light blue
4658        - posn: upper left
4659        - shape: SQUARE
4660        - texture: burlap
4661        SQUARE
4662        {'color': 'light blue', 'posn': 'upper left', 'texture': 'burlap', 'shape': 'SQUARE'}
4663
4664    See more examples at :class:`ParseResults` of accessing fields by results name.
4665    """
4666    def __init__( self, expr ):
4667        super(Dict,self).__init__( expr )
4668        self.saveAsList = True
4669
4670    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4671        for i,tok in enumerate(tokenlist):
4672            if len(tok) == 0:
4673                continue
4674            ikey = tok[0]
4675            if isinstance(ikey,int):
4676                ikey = _ustr(tok[0]).strip()
4677            if len(tok)==1:
4678                tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset("",i)
4679            elif len(tok)==2 and not isinstance(tok[1],ParseResults):
4680                tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(tok[1],i)
4681            else:
4682                dictvalue = tok.copy() #ParseResults(i)
4683                del dictvalue[0]
4684                if len(dictvalue)!= 1 or (isinstance(dictvalue,ParseResults) and dictvalue.haskeys()):
4685                    tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(dictvalue,i)
4686                else:
4687                    tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(dictvalue[0],i)
4688
4689        if self.resultsName:
4690            return [ tokenlist ]
4691        else:
4692            return tokenlist
4693
4694
4695class Suppress(TokenConverter):
4696    """Converter for ignoring the results of a parsed expression.
4697
4698    Example::
4699
4700        source = "a, b, c,d"
4701        wd = Word(alphas)
4702        wd_list1 = wd + ZeroOrMore(',' + wd)
4703        print(wd_list1.parseString(source))
4704
4705        # often, delimiters that are useful during parsing are just in the
4706        # way afterward - use Suppress to keep them out of the parsed output
4707        wd_list2 = wd + ZeroOrMore(Suppress(',') + wd)
4708        print(wd_list2.parseString(source))
4709
4710    prints::
4711
4712        ['a', ',', 'b', ',', 'c', ',', 'd']
4713        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']
4714
4715    (See also :class:`delimitedList`.)
4716    """
4717    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4718        return []
4719
4720    def suppress( self ):
4721        return self
4722
4723
4724class OnlyOnce(object):
4725    """Wrapper for parse actions, to ensure they are only called once.
4726    """
4727    def __init__(self, methodCall):
4728        self.callable = _trim_arity(methodCall)
4729        self.called = False
4730    def __call__(self,s,l,t):
4731        if not self.called:
4732            results = self.callable(s,l,t)
4733            self.called = True
4734            return results
4735        raise ParseException(s,l,"")
4736    def reset(self):
4737        self.called = False
4738
4739def traceParseAction(f):
4740    """Decorator for debugging parse actions.
4741
4742    When the parse action is called, this decorator will print
4743    ``">> entering method-name(line:<current_source_line>, <parse_location>, <matched_tokens>)"``.
4744    When the parse action completes, the decorator will print
4745    ``"<<"`` followed by the returned value, or any exception that the parse action raised.
4746
4747    Example::
4748
4749        wd = Word(alphas)
4750
4751        @traceParseAction
4752        def remove_duplicate_chars(tokens):
4753            return ''.join(sorted(set(''.join(tokens))))
4754
4755        wds = OneOrMore(wd).setParseAction(remove_duplicate_chars)
4756        print(wds.parseString("slkdjs sld sldd sdlf sdljf"))
4757
4758    prints::
4759
4760        >>entering remove_duplicate_chars(line: 'slkdjs sld sldd sdlf sdljf', 0, (['slkdjs', 'sld', 'sldd', 'sdlf', 'sdljf'], {}))
4761        <<leaving remove_duplicate_chars (ret: 'dfjkls')
4762        ['dfjkls']
4763    """
4764    f = _trim_arity(f)
4765    def z(*paArgs):
4766        thisFunc = f.__name__
4767        s,l,t = paArgs[-3:]
4768        if len(paArgs)>3:
4769            thisFunc = paArgs[0].__class__.__name__ + '.' + thisFunc
4770        sys.stderr.write( ">>entering %s(line: '%s', %d, %r)\n" % (thisFunc,line(l,s),l,t) )
4771        try:
4772            ret = f(*paArgs)
4773        except Exception as exc:
4774            sys.stderr.write( "<<leaving %s (exception: %s)\n" % (thisFunc,exc) )
4775            raise
4776        sys.stderr.write( "<<leaving %s (ret: %r)\n" % (thisFunc,ret) )
4777        return ret
4778    try:
4779        z.__name__ = f.__name__
4780    except AttributeError:
4781        pass
4782    return z
4783
4784#
4785# global helpers
4786#
4787def delimitedList( expr, delim=",", combine=False ):
4788    """Helper to define a delimited list of expressions - the delimiter
4789    defaults to ','. By default, the list elements and delimiters can
4790    have intervening whitespace, and comments, but this can be
4791    overridden by passing ``combine=True`` in the constructor. If
4792    ``combine`` is set to ``True``, the matching tokens are
4793    returned as a single token string, with the delimiters included;
4794    otherwise, the matching tokens are returned as a list of tokens,
4795    with the delimiters suppressed.
4796
4797    Example::
4798
4799        delimitedList(Word(alphas)).parseString("aa,bb,cc") # -> ['aa', 'bb', 'cc']
4800        delimitedList(Word(hexnums), delim=':', combine=True).parseString("AA:BB:CC:DD:EE") # -> ['AA:BB:CC:DD:EE']
4801    """
4802    dlName = _ustr(expr)+" ["+_ustr(delim)+" "+_ustr(expr)+"]..."
4803    if combine:
4804        return Combine( expr + ZeroOrMore( delim + expr ) ).setName(dlName)
4805    else:
4806        return ( expr + ZeroOrMore( Suppress( delim ) + expr ) ).setName(dlName)
4807
4808def countedArray( expr, intExpr=None ):
4809    """Helper to define a counted list of expressions.
4810
4811    This helper defines a pattern of the form::
4812
4813        integer expr expr expr...
4814
4815    where the leading integer tells how many expr expressions follow.
4816    The matched tokens returns the array of expr tokens as a list - the
4817    leading count token is suppressed.
4818
4819    If ``intExpr`` is specified, it should be a pyparsing expression
4820    that produces an integer value.
4821
4822    Example::
4823
4824        countedArray(Word(alphas)).parseString('2 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']
4825
4826        # in this parser, the leading integer value is given in binary,
4827        # '10' indicating that 2 values are in the array
4828        binaryConstant = Word('01').setParseAction(lambda t: int(t[0], 2))
4829        countedArray(Word(alphas), intExpr=binaryConstant).parseString('10 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']
4830    """
4831    arrayExpr = Forward()
4832    def countFieldParseAction(s,l,t):
4833        n = t[0]
4834        arrayExpr << (n and Group(And([expr]*n)) or Group(empty))
4835        return []
4836    if intExpr is None:
4837        intExpr = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda t:int(t[0]))
4838    else:
4839        intExpr = intExpr.copy()
4840    intExpr.setName("arrayLen")
4841    intExpr.addParseAction(countFieldParseAction, callDuringTry=True)
4842    return ( intExpr + arrayExpr ).setName('(len) ' + _ustr(expr) + '...')
4843
4844def _flatten(L):
4845    ret = []
4846    for i in L:
4847        if isinstance(i,list):
4848            ret.extend(_flatten(i))
4849        else:
4850            ret.append(i)
4851    return ret
4852
4853def matchPreviousLiteral(expr):
4854    """Helper to define an expression that is indirectly defined from
4855    the tokens matched in a previous expression, that is, it looks for
4856    a 'repeat' of a previous expression.  For example::
4857
4858        first = Word(nums)
4859        second = matchPreviousLiteral(first)
4860        matchExpr = first + ":" + second
4861
4862    will match ``"1:1"``, but not ``"1:2"``.  Because this
4863    matches a previous literal, will also match the leading
4864    ``"1:1"`` in ``"1:10"``. If this is not desired, use
4865    :class:`matchPreviousExpr`. Do *not* use with packrat parsing
4866    enabled.
4867    """
4868    rep = Forward()
4869    def copyTokenToRepeater(s,l,t):
4870        if t:
4871            if len(t) == 1:
4872                rep << t[0]
4873            else:
4874                # flatten t tokens
4875                tflat = _flatten(t.asList())
4876                rep << And(Literal(tt) for tt in tflat)
4877        else:
4878            rep << Empty()
4879    expr.addParseAction(copyTokenToRepeater, callDuringTry=True)
4880    rep.setName('(prev) ' + _ustr(expr))
4881    return rep
4882
4883def matchPreviousExpr(expr):
4884    """Helper to define an expression that is indirectly defined from
4885    the tokens matched in a previous expression, that is, it looks for
4886    a 'repeat' of a previous expression.  For example::
4887
4888        first = Word(nums)
4889        second = matchPreviousExpr(first)
4890        matchExpr = first + ":" + second
4891
4892    will match ``"1:1"``, but not ``"1:2"``.  Because this
4893    matches by expressions, will *not* match the leading ``"1:1"``
4894    in ``"1:10"``; the expressions are evaluated first, and then
4895    compared, so ``"1"`` is compared with ``"10"``. Do *not* use
4896    with packrat parsing enabled.
4897    """
4898    rep = Forward()
4899    e2 = expr.copy()
4900    rep <<= e2
4901    def copyTokenToRepeater(s,l,t):
4902        matchTokens = _flatten(t.asList())
4903        def mustMatchTheseTokens(s,l,t):
4904            theseTokens = _flatten(t.asList())
4905            if  theseTokens != matchTokens:
4906                raise ParseException("",0,"")
4907        rep.setParseAction( mustMatchTheseTokens, callDuringTry=True )
4908    expr.addParseAction(copyTokenToRepeater, callDuringTry=True)
4909    rep.setName('(prev) ' + _ustr(expr))
4910    return rep
4911
4912def _escapeRegexRangeChars(s):
4913    #~  escape these chars: ^-]
4914    for c in r"\^-]":
4915        s = s.replace(c,_bslash+c)
4916    s = s.replace("\n",r"\n")
4917    s = s.replace("\t",r"\t")
4918    return _ustr(s)
4919
4920def oneOf( strs, caseless=False, useRegex=True ):
4921    """Helper to quickly define a set of alternative Literals, and makes
4922    sure to do longest-first testing when there is a conflict,
4923    regardless of the input order, but returns
4924    a :class:`MatchFirst` for best performance.
4925
4926    Parameters:
4927
4928     - strs - a string of space-delimited literals, or a collection of
4929       string literals
4930     - caseless - (default= ``False``) - treat all literals as
4931       caseless
4932     - useRegex - (default= ``True``) - as an optimization, will
4933       generate a Regex object; otherwise, will generate
4934       a :class:`MatchFirst` object (if ``caseless=True``, or if
4935       creating a :class:`Regex` raises an exception)
4936
4937    Example::
4938
4939        comp_oper = oneOf("< = > <= >= !=")
4940        var = Word(alphas)
4941        number = Word(nums)
4942        term = var | number
4943        comparison_expr = term + comp_oper + term
4944        print(comparison_expr.searchString("B = 12  AA=23 B<=AA AA>12"))
4945
4946    prints::
4947
4948        [['B', '=', '12'], ['AA', '=', '23'], ['B', '<=', 'AA'], ['AA', '>', '12']]
4949    """
4950    if caseless:
4951        isequal = ( lambda a,b: a.upper() == b.upper() )
4952        masks = ( lambda a,b: b.upper().startswith(a.upper()) )
4953        parseElementClass = CaselessLiteral
4954    else:
4955        isequal = ( lambda a,b: a == b )
4956        masks = ( lambda a,b: b.startswith(a) )
4957        parseElementClass = Literal
4958
4959    symbols = []
4960    if isinstance(strs,basestring):
4961        symbols = strs.split()
4962    elif isinstance(strs, Iterable):
4963        symbols = list(strs)
4964    else:
4965        warnings.warn("Invalid argument to oneOf, expected string or iterable",
4966                SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
4967    if not symbols:
4968        return NoMatch()
4969
4970    i = 0
4971    while i < len(symbols)-1:
4972        cur = symbols[i]
4973        for j,other in enumerate(symbols[i+1:]):
4974            if ( isequal(other, cur) ):
4975                del symbols[i+j+1]
4976                break
4977            elif ( masks(cur, other) ):
4978                del symbols[i+j+1]
4979                symbols.insert(i,other)
4980                cur = other
4981                break
4982        else:
4983            i += 1
4984
4985    if not caseless and useRegex:
4986        #~ print (strs,"->", "|".join( [ _escapeRegexChars(sym) for sym in symbols] ))
4987        try:
4988            if len(symbols)==len("".join(symbols)):
4989                return Regex( "[%s]" % "".join(_escapeRegexRangeChars(sym) for sym in symbols) ).setName(' | '.join(symbols))
4990            else:
4991                return Regex( "|".join(re.escape(sym) for sym in symbols) ).setName(' | '.join(symbols))
4992        except Exception:
4993            warnings.warn("Exception creating Regex for oneOf, building MatchFirst",
4994                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
4995
4996
4997    # last resort, just use MatchFirst
4998    return MatchFirst(parseElementClass(sym) for sym in symbols).setName(' | '.join(symbols))
4999
5000def dictOf( key, value ):
5001    """Helper to easily and clearly define a dictionary by specifying
5002    the respective patterns for the key and value.  Takes care of
5003    defining the :class:`Dict`, :class:`ZeroOrMore`, and
5004    :class:`Group` tokens in the proper order.  The key pattern
5005    can include delimiting markers or punctuation, as long as they are
5006    suppressed, thereby leaving the significant key text.  The value
5007    pattern can include named results, so that the :class:`Dict` results
5008    can include named token fields.
5009
5010    Example::
5011
5012        text = "shape: SQUARE posn: upper left color: light blue texture: burlap"
5013        attr_expr = (label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
5014        print(OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).dump())
5015
5016        attr_label = label
5017        attr_value = Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join)
5018
5019        # similar to Dict, but simpler call format
5020        result = dictOf(attr_label, attr_value).parseString(text)
5021        print(result.dump())
5022        print(result['shape'])
5023        print(result.shape)  # object attribute access works too
5024        print(result.asDict())
5025
5026    prints::
5027
5028        [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['posn', 'upper left'], ['color', 'light blue'], ['texture', 'burlap']]
5029        - color: light blue
5030        - posn: upper left
5031        - shape: SQUARE
5032        - texture: burlap
5033        SQUARE
5034        SQUARE
5035        {'color': 'light blue', 'shape': 'SQUARE', 'posn': 'upper left', 'texture': 'burlap'}
5036    """
5037    return Dict( ZeroOrMore( Group ( key + value ) ) )
5038
5039def originalTextFor(expr, asString=True):
5040    """Helper to return the original, untokenized text for a given
5041    expression.  Useful to restore the parsed fields of an HTML start
5042    tag into the raw tag text itself, or to revert separate tokens with
5043    intervening whitespace back to the original matching input text. By
5044    default, returns astring containing the original parsed text.
5045
5046    If the optional ``asString`` argument is passed as
5047    ``False``, then the return value is
5048    a :class:`ParseResults` containing any results names that
5049    were originally matched, and a single token containing the original
5050    matched text from the input string.  So if the expression passed to
5051    :class:`originalTextFor` contains expressions with defined
5052    results names, you must set ``asString`` to ``False`` if you
5053    want to preserve those results name values.
5054
5055    Example::
5056
5057        src = "this is test <b> bold <i>text</i> </b> normal text "
5058        for tag in ("b","i"):
5059            opener,closer = makeHTMLTags(tag)
5060            patt = originalTextFor(opener + SkipTo(closer) + closer)
5061            print(patt.searchString(src)[0])
5062
5063    prints::
5064
5065        ['<b> bold <i>text</i> </b>']
5066        ['<i>text</i>']
5067    """
5068    locMarker = Empty().setParseAction(lambda s,loc,t: loc)
5069    endlocMarker = locMarker.copy()
5070    endlocMarker.callPreparse = False
5071    matchExpr = locMarker("_original_start") + expr + endlocMarker("_original_end")
5072    if asString:
5073        extractText = lambda s,l,t: s[t._original_start:t._original_end]
5074    else:
5075        def extractText(s,l,t):
5076            t[:] = [s[t.pop('_original_start'):t.pop('_original_end')]]
5077    matchExpr.setParseAction(extractText)
5078    matchExpr.ignoreExprs = expr.ignoreExprs
5079    return matchExpr
5080
5081def ungroup(expr):
5082    """Helper to undo pyparsing's default grouping of And expressions,
5083    even if all but one are non-empty.
5084    """
5085    return TokenConverter(expr).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0])
5086
5087def locatedExpr(expr):
5088    """Helper to decorate a returned token with its starting and ending
5089    locations in the input string.
5090
5091    This helper adds the following results names:
5092
5093     - locn_start = location where matched expression begins
5094     - locn_end = location where matched expression ends
5095     - value = the actual parsed results
5096
5097    Be careful if the input text contains ``<TAB>`` characters, you
5098    may want to call :class:`ParserElement.parseWithTabs`
5099
5100    Example::
5101
5102        wd = Word(alphas)
5103        for match in locatedExpr(wd).searchString("ljsdf123lksdjjf123lkkjj1222"):
5104            print(match)
5105
5106    prints::
5107
5108        [[0, 'ljsdf', 5]]
5109        [[8, 'lksdjjf', 15]]
5110        [[18, 'lkkjj', 23]]
5111    """
5112    locator = Empty().setParseAction(lambda s,l,t: l)
5113    return Group(locator("locn_start") + expr("value") + locator.copy().leaveWhitespace()("locn_end"))

5116# convenience constants for positional expressions
5117empty       = Empty().setName("empty")
5118lineStart   = LineStart().setName("lineStart")
5119lineEnd     = LineEnd().setName("lineEnd")
5120stringStart = StringStart().setName("stringStart")
5121stringEnd   = StringEnd().setName("stringEnd")
5122
5123_escapedPunc = Word( _bslash, r"\[]-*.$+^?()~ ", exact=2 ).setParseAction(lambda s,l,t:t[0][1])
5124_escapedHexChar = Regex(r"\\0?[xX][0-9a-fA-F]+").setParseAction(lambda s,l,t:unichr(int(t[0].lstrip(r'\0x'),16)))
5125_escapedOctChar = Regex(r"\\0[0-7]+").setParseAction(lambda s,l,t:unichr(int(t[0][1:],8)))
5126_singleChar = _escapedPunc | _escapedHexChar | _escapedOctChar | CharsNotIn(r'\]', exact=1)
5127_charRange = Group(_singleChar + Suppress("-") + _singleChar)
5128_reBracketExpr = Literal("[") + Optional("^").setResultsName("negate") + Group( OneOrMore( _charRange | _singleChar ) ).setResultsName("body") + "]"
5129
5130def srange(s):
5131    r"""Helper to easily define string ranges for use in Word
5132    construction. Borrows syntax from regexp '[]' string range
5133    definitions::
5134
5135        srange("[0-9]")   -> "0123456789"
5136        srange("[a-z]")   -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"
5137        srange("[a-z$_]") -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz$_"
5138
5139    The input string must be enclosed in []'s, and the returned string
5140    is the expanded character set joined into a single string. The
5141    values enclosed in the []'s may be:
5142
5143     - a single character
5144     - an escaped character with a leading backslash (such as ``\-``
5145       or ``\]``)
5146     - an escaped hex character with a leading ``'\x'``
5147       (``\x21``, which is a ``'!'`` character) (``\0x##``
5148       is also supported for backwards compatibility)
5149     - an escaped octal character with a leading ``'\0'``
5150       (``\041``, which is a ``'!'`` character)
5151     - a range of any of the above, separated by a dash (``'a-z'``,
5152       etc.)
5153     - any combination of the above (``'aeiouy'``,
5154       ``'a-zA-Z0-9_$'``, etc.)
5155    """
5156    _expanded = lambda p: p if not isinstance(p,ParseResults) else ''.join(unichr(c) for c in range(ord(p[0]),ord(p[1])+1))
5157    try:
5158        return "".join(_expanded(part) for part in _reBracketExpr.parseString(s).body)
5159    except Exception:
5160        return ""
5161
5162def matchOnlyAtCol(n):
5163    """Helper method for defining parse actions that require matching at
5164    a specific column in the input text.
5165    """
5166    def verifyCol(strg,locn,toks):
5167        if col(locn,strg) != n:
5168            raise ParseException(strg,locn,"matched token not at column %d" % n)
5169    return verifyCol

5171def replaceWith(replStr):
5172    """Helper method for common parse actions that simply return
5173    a literal value.  Especially useful when used with
5174    :class:`transformString<ParserElement.transformString>` ().
5175
5176    Example::
5177
5178        num = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
5179        na = oneOf("N/A NA").setParseAction(replaceWith(math.nan))
5180        term = na | num
5181
5182        OneOrMore(term).parseString("324 234 N/A 234") # -> [324, 234, nan, 234]
5183    """
5184    return lambda s,l,t: [replStr]

5186def removeQuotes(s,l,t):
5187    """Helper parse action for removing quotation marks from parsed
5188    quoted strings.
5189
5190    Example::
5191
5192        # by default, quotation marks are included in parsed results
5193        quotedString.parseString("'Now is the Winter of our Discontent'") # -> ["'Now is the Winter of our Discontent'"]
5194
5195        # use removeQuotes to strip quotation marks from parsed results
5196        quotedString.setParseAction(removeQuotes)
5197        quotedString.parseString("'Now is the Winter of our Discontent'") # -> ["Now is the Winter of our Discontent"]
5198    """
5199    return t[0][1:-1]
