5201def tokenMap(func, *args):
5202    """Helper to define a parse action by mapping a function to all
5203    elements of a ParseResults list. If any additional args are passed,
5204    they are forwarded to the given function as additional arguments
5205    after the token, as in
5206    ``hex_integer = Word(hexnums).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16))``,
5207    which will convert the parsed data to an integer using base 16.
5208
5209    Example (compare the last to example in :class:`ParserElement.transformString`::
5210
5211        hex_ints = OneOrMore(Word(hexnums)).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16))
5212        hex_ints.runTests('''
5213            00 11 22 aa FF 0a 0d 1a
5214            ''')
5215
5216        upperword = Word(alphas).setParseAction(tokenMap(str.upper))
5217        OneOrMore(upperword).runTests('''
5218            my kingdom for a horse
5219            ''')
5220
5221        wd = Word(alphas).setParseAction(tokenMap(str.title))
5222        OneOrMore(wd).setParseAction(' '.join).runTests('''
5223            now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york
5224            ''')
5225
5226    prints::
5227
5228        00 11 22 aa FF 0a 0d 1a
5229        [0, 17, 34, 170, 255, 10, 13, 26]
5230
5231        my kingdom for a horse
5232        ['MY', 'KINGDOM', 'FOR', 'A', 'HORSE']
5233
5234        now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york
5235        ['Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York']
5236    """
5237    def pa(s,l,t):
5238        return [func(tokn, *args) for tokn in t]
5239
5240    try:
5241        func_name = getattr(func, '__name__',
5242                            getattr(func, '__class__').__name__)
5243    except Exception:
5244        func_name = str(func)
5245    pa.__name__ = func_name
5246
5247    return pa
5248
5249upcaseTokens = tokenMap(lambda t: _ustr(t).upper())
5250"""(Deprecated) Helper parse action to convert tokens to upper case.
5251Deprecated in favor of :class:`pyparsing_common.upcaseTokens`"""
5252
5253downcaseTokens = tokenMap(lambda t: _ustr(t).lower())
5254"""(Deprecated) Helper parse action to convert tokens to lower case.
5255Deprecated in favor of :class:`pyparsing_common.downcaseTokens`"""
5256
5257def _makeTags(tagStr, xml):
5258    """Internal helper to construct opening and closing tag expressions, given a tag name"""
5259    if isinstance(tagStr,basestring):
5260        resname = tagStr
5261        tagStr = Keyword(tagStr, caseless=not xml)
5262    else:
5263        resname = tagStr.name
5264
5265    tagAttrName = Word(alphas,alphanums+"_-:")
5266    if (xml):
5267        tagAttrValue = dblQuotedString.copy().setParseAction( removeQuotes )
5268        openTag = Suppress("<") + tagStr("tag") + \
5269                Dict(ZeroOrMore(Group( tagAttrName + Suppress("=") + tagAttrValue ))) + \
5270                Optional("/",default=[False]).setResultsName("empty").setParseAction(lambda s,l,t:t[0]=='/') + Suppress(">")
5271    else:
5272        printablesLessRAbrack = "".join(c for c in printables if c not in ">")
5273        tagAttrValue = quotedString.copy().setParseAction( removeQuotes ) | Word(printablesLessRAbrack)
5274        openTag = Suppress("<") + tagStr("tag") + \
5275                Dict(ZeroOrMore(Group( tagAttrName.setParseAction(downcaseTokens) + \
5276                Optional( Suppress("=") + tagAttrValue ) ))) + \
5277                Optional("/",default=[False]).setResultsName("empty").setParseAction(lambda s,l,t:t[0]=='/') + Suppress(">")
5278    closeTag = Combine(_L("</") + tagStr + ">")
5279
5280    openTag = openTag.setResultsName("start"+"".join(resname.replace(":"," ").title().split())).setName("<%s>" % resname)
5281    closeTag = closeTag.setResultsName("end"+"".join(resname.replace(":"," ").title().split())).setName("</%s>" % resname)
5282    openTag.tag = resname
5283    closeTag.tag = resname
5284    return openTag, closeTag
5285
5286def makeHTMLTags(tagStr):
5287    """Helper to construct opening and closing tag expressions for HTML,
5288    given a tag name. Matches tags in either upper or lower case,
5289    attributes with namespaces and with quoted or unquoted values.
5290
5291    Example::
5292
5293        text = '<td>More info at the <a href="https://github.com/pyparsing/pyparsing/wiki">pyparsing</a> wiki page</td>'
5294        # makeHTMLTags returns pyparsing expressions for the opening and
5295        # closing tags as a 2-tuple
5296        a,a_end = makeHTMLTags("A")
5297        link_expr = a + SkipTo(a_end)("link_text") + a_end
5298
5299        for link in link_expr.searchString(text):
5300            # attributes in the <A> tag (like "href" shown here) are
5301            # also accessible as named results
5302            print(link.link_text, '->', link.href)
5303
5304    prints::
5305
5306        pyparsing -> https://github.com/pyparsing/pyparsing/wiki
5307    """
5308    return _makeTags( tagStr, False )
5309
5310def makeXMLTags(tagStr):
5311    """Helper to construct opening and closing tag expressions for XML,
5312    given a tag name. Matches tags only in the given upper/lower case.
5313
5314    Example: similar to :class:`makeHTMLTags`
5315    """
5316    return _makeTags( tagStr, True )
5317
5318def withAttribute(*args,**attrDict):
5319    """Helper to create a validating parse action to be used with start
5320    tags created with :class:`makeXMLTags` or
5321    :class:`makeHTMLTags`. Use ``withAttribute`` to qualify
5322    a starting tag with a required attribute value, to avoid false
5323    matches on common tags such as ``<TD>`` or ``<DIV>``.
5324
5325    Call ``withAttribute`` with a series of attribute names and
5326    values. Specify the list of filter attributes names and values as:
5327
5328     - keyword arguments, as in ``(align="right")``, or
5329     - as an explicit dict with ``**`` operator, when an attribute
5330       name is also a Python reserved word, as in ``**{"class":"Customer", "align":"right"}``
5331     - a list of name-value tuples, as in ``(("ns1:class", "Customer"), ("ns2:align","right"))``
5332
5333    For attribute names with a namespace prefix, you must use the second
5334    form.  Attribute names are matched insensitive to upper/lower case.
5335
5336    If just testing for ``class`` (with or without a namespace), use
5337    :class:`withClass`.
5338
5339    To verify that the attribute exists, but without specifying a value,
5340    pass ``withAttribute.ANY_VALUE`` as the value.
5341
5342    Example::
5343
5344        html = '''
5345            <div>
5346            Some text
5347            <div type="grid">1 4 0 1 0</div>
5348            <div type="graph">1,3 2,3 1,1</div>
5349            <div>this has no type</div>
5350            </div>
5351
5352        '''
5353        div,div_end = makeHTMLTags("div")
5354
5355        # only match div tag having a type attribute with value "grid"
5356        div_grid = div().setParseAction(withAttribute(type="grid"))
5357        grid_expr = div_grid + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5358        for grid_header in grid_expr.searchString(html):
5359            print(grid_header.body)
5360
5361        # construct a match with any div tag having a type attribute, regardless of the value
5362        div_any_type = div().setParseAction(withAttribute(type=withAttribute.ANY_VALUE))
5363        div_expr = div_any_type + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5364        for div_header in div_expr.searchString(html):
5365            print(div_header.body)
5366
5367    prints::
5368
5369        1 4 0 1 0
5370
5371        1 4 0 1 0
5372        1,3 2,3 1,1
5373    """
5374    if args:
5375        attrs = args[:]
5376    else:
5377        attrs = attrDict.items()
5378    attrs = [(k,v) for k,v in attrs]
5379    def pa(s,l,tokens):
5380        for attrName,attrValue in attrs:
5381            if attrName not in tokens:
5382                raise ParseException(s,l,"no matching attribute " + attrName)
5383            if attrValue != withAttribute.ANY_VALUE and tokens[attrName] != attrValue:
5384                raise ParseException(s,l,"attribute '%s' has value '%s', must be '%s'" %
5385                                            (attrName, tokens[attrName], attrValue))
5386    return pa
5387withAttribute.ANY_VALUE = object()
5388
5389def withClass(classname, namespace=''):
5390    """Simplified version of :class:`withAttribute` when
5391    matching on a div class - made difficult because ``class`` is
5392    a reserved word in Python.
5393
5394    Example::
5395
5396        html = '''
5397            <div>
5398            Some text
5399            <div class="grid">1 4 0 1 0</div>
5400            <div class="graph">1,3 2,3 1,1</div>
5401            <div>this &lt;div&gt; has no class</div>
5402            </div>
5403
5404        '''
5405        div,div_end = makeHTMLTags("div")
5406        div_grid = div().setParseAction(withClass("grid"))
5407
5408        grid_expr = div_grid + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5409        for grid_header in grid_expr.searchString(html):
5410            print(grid_header.body)
5411
5412        div_any_type = div().setParseAction(withClass(withAttribute.ANY_VALUE))
5413        div_expr = div_any_type + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5414        for div_header in div_expr.searchString(html):
5415            print(div_header.body)
5416
5417    prints::
5418
5419        1 4 0 1 0
5420
5421        1 4 0 1 0
5422        1,3 2,3 1,1
5423    """
5424    classattr = "%s:class" % namespace if namespace else "class"
5425    return withAttribute(**{classattr : classname})
5426
5427opAssoc = SimpleNamespace()
5428opAssoc.LEFT = object()
5429opAssoc.RIGHT = object()
5430
5431def infixNotation( baseExpr, opList, lpar=Suppress('('), rpar=Suppress(')') ):
5432    """Helper method for constructing grammars of expressions made up of
5433    operators working in a precedence hierarchy.  Operators may be unary
5434    or binary, left- or right-associative.  Parse actions can also be
5435    attached to operator expressions. The generated parser will also
5436    recognize the use of parentheses to override operator precedences
5437    (see example below).
5438
5439    Note: if you define a deep operator list, you may see performance
5440    issues when using infixNotation. See
5441    :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat` for a mechanism to potentially
5442    improve your parser performance.
5443
5444    Parameters:
5445     - baseExpr - expression representing the most basic element for the
5446       nested
5447     - opList - list of tuples, one for each operator precedence level
5448       in the expression grammar; each tuple is of the form ``(opExpr,
5449       numTerms, rightLeftAssoc, parseAction)``, where:
5450
5451       - opExpr is the pyparsing expression for the operator; may also
5452         be a string, which will be converted to a Literal; if numTerms
5453         is 3, opExpr is a tuple of two expressions, for the two
5454         operators separating the 3 terms
5455       - numTerms is the number of terms for this operator (must be 1,
5456         2, or 3)
5457       - rightLeftAssoc is the indicator whether the operator is right
5458         or left associative, using the pyparsing-defined constants
5459         ``opAssoc.RIGHT`` and ``opAssoc.LEFT``.
5460       - parseAction is the parse action to be associated with
5461         expressions matching this operator expression (the parse action
5462         tuple member may be omitted); if the parse action is passed
5463         a tuple or list of functions, this is equivalent to calling
5464         ``setParseAction(*fn)``
5465         (:class:`ParserElement.setParseAction`)
5466     - lpar - expression for matching left-parentheses
5467       (default= ``Suppress('(')``)
5468     - rpar - expression for matching right-parentheses
5469       (default= ``Suppress(')')``)
5470
5471    Example::
5472
5473        # simple example of four-function arithmetic with ints and
5474        # variable names
5475        integer = pyparsing_common.signed_integer
5476        varname = pyparsing_common.identifier
5477
5478        arith_expr = infixNotation(integer | varname,
5479            [
5480            ('-', 1, opAssoc.RIGHT),
5481            (oneOf('* /'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5482            (oneOf('+ -'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5483            ])
5484
5485        arith_expr.runTests('''
5486            5+3*6
5487            (5+3)*6
5488            -2--11
5489            ''', fullDump=False)
5490
5491    prints::
5492
5493        5+3*6
5494        [[5, '+', [3, '*', 6]]]
5495
5496        (5+3)*6
5497        [[[5, '+', 3], '*', 6]]
5498
5499        -2--11
5500        [[['-', 2], '-', ['-', 11]]]
5501    """
5502    # captive version of FollowedBy that does not do parse actions or capture results names
5503    class _FB(FollowedBy):
5504        def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True):
5505            self.expr.tryParse(instring, loc)
5506            return loc, []
5507
5508    ret = Forward()
5509    lastExpr = baseExpr | ( lpar + ret + rpar )
5510    for i,operDef in enumerate(opList):
5511        opExpr,arity,rightLeftAssoc,pa = (operDef + (None,))[:4]
5512        termName = "%s term" % opExpr if arity < 3 else "%s%s term" % opExpr
5513        if arity == 3:
5514            if opExpr is None or len(opExpr) != 2:
5515                raise ValueError(
5516                    "if numterms=3, opExpr must be a tuple or list of two expressions")
5517            opExpr1, opExpr2 = opExpr
5518        thisExpr = Forward().setName(termName)
5519        if rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.LEFT:
5520            if arity == 1:
5521                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr ) )
5522            elif arity == 2:
5523                if opExpr is not None:
5524                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + lastExpr ) )
5525                else:
5526                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr+lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore(lastExpr) )
5527            elif arity == 3:
5528                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr) + \
5529                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr )
5530            else:
5531                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5532        elif rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.RIGHT:
5533            if arity == 1:
5534                # try to avoid LR with this extra test
5535                if not isinstance(opExpr, Optional):
5536                    opExpr = Optional(opExpr)
5537                matchExpr = _FB(opExpr.expr + thisExpr) + Group( opExpr + thisExpr )
5538            elif arity == 2:
5539                if opExpr is not None:
5540                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + thisExpr ) )
5541                else:
5542                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( thisExpr ) )
5543            elif arity == 3:
5544                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr) + \
5545                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr )
5546            else:
5547                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5548        else:
5549            raise ValueError("operator must indicate right or left associativity")
5550        if pa:
5551            if isinstance(pa, (tuple, list)):
5552                matchExpr.setParseAction(*pa)
5553            else:
5554                matchExpr.setParseAction(pa)
5555        thisExpr <<= ( matchExpr.setName(termName) | lastExpr )
5556        lastExpr = thisExpr
5557    ret <<= lastExpr
5558    return ret
5559
5560operatorPrecedence = infixNotation
5561"""(Deprecated) Former name of :class:`infixNotation`, will be
5562dropped in a future release."""

5564dblQuotedString = Combine(Regex(r'"(?:[^"\n\r\\]|(?:"")|(?:\\(?:[^x]|x[0-9a-fA-F]+)))*')+'"').setName("string enclosed in double quotes")
5565sglQuotedString = Combine(Regex(r"'(?:[^'\n\r\\]|(?:'')|(?:\\(?:[^x]|x[0-9a-fA-F]+)))*")+"'").setName("string enclosed in single quotes")
5566quotedString = Combine(Regex(r'"(?:[^"\n\r\\]|(?:"")|(?:\\(?:[^x]|x[0-9a-fA-F]+)))*')+'"'|
5567                       Regex(r"'(?:[^'\n\r\\]|(?:'')|(?:\\(?:[^x]|x[0-9a-fA-F]+)))*")+"'").setName("quotedString using single or double quotes")
5568unicodeString = Combine(_L('u') + quotedString.copy()).setName("unicode string literal")

5570def nestedExpr(opener="(", closer=")", content=None, ignoreExpr=quotedString.copy()):
5571    """Helper method for defining nested lists enclosed in opening and
5572    closing delimiters ("(" and ")" are the default).
5573
5574    Parameters:
5575     - opener - opening character for a nested list
5576       (default= ``"("``); can also be a pyparsing expression
5577     - closer - closing character for a nested list
5578       (default= ``")"``); can also be a pyparsing expression
5579     - content - expression for items within the nested lists
5580       (default= ``None``)
5581     - ignoreExpr - expression for ignoring opening and closing
5582       delimiters (default= :class:`quotedString`)
5583
5584    If an expression is not provided for the content argument, the
5585    nested expression will capture all whitespace-delimited content
5586    between delimiters as a list of separate values.
5587
5588    Use the ``ignoreExpr`` argument to define expressions that may
5589    contain opening or closing characters that should not be treated as
5590    opening or closing characters for nesting, such as quotedString or
5591    a comment expression.  Specify multiple expressions using an
5592    :class:`Or` or :class:`MatchFirst`. The default is
5593    :class:`quotedString`, but if no expressions are to be ignored, then
5594    pass ``None`` for this argument.
5595
5596    Example::
5597
5598        data_type = oneOf("void int short long char float double")
5599        decl_data_type = Combine(data_type + Optional(Word('*')))
5600        ident = Word(alphas+'_', alphanums+'_')
5601        number = pyparsing_common.number
5602        arg = Group(decl_data_type + ident)
5603        LPAR,RPAR = map(Suppress, "()")
5604
5605        code_body = nestedExpr('{', '}', ignoreExpr=(quotedString | cStyleComment))
5606
5607        c_function = (decl_data_type("type")
5608                      + ident("name")
5609                      + LPAR + Optional(delimitedList(arg), [])("args") + RPAR
5610                      + code_body("body"))
5611        c_function.ignore(cStyleComment)
5612
5613        source_code = '''
5614            int is_odd(int x) {
5615                return (x%2);
5616            }
5617
5618            int dec_to_hex(char hchar) {
5619                if (hchar >= '0' && hchar <= '9') {
5620                    return (ord(hchar)-ord('0'));
5621                } else {
5622                    return (10+ord(hchar)-ord('A'));
5623                }
5624            }
5625        '''
5626        for func in c_function.searchString(source_code):
5627            print("%(name)s (%(type)s) args: %(args)s" % func)
5628
5629
5630    prints::
5631
5632        is_odd (int) args: [['int', 'x']]
5633        dec_to_hex (int) args: [['char', 'hchar']]
5634    """
5635    if opener == closer:
5636        raise ValueError("opening and closing strings cannot be the same")
5637    if content is None:
5638        if isinstance(opener,basestring) and isinstance(closer,basestring):
5639            if len(opener) == 1 and len(closer)==1:
5640                if ignoreExpr is not None:
5641                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~ignoreExpr +
5642                                    CharsNotIn(opener+closer+ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5643                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5644                else:
5645                    content = (empty.copy()+CharsNotIn(opener+closer+ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
5646                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5647            else:
5648                if ignoreExpr is not None:
5649                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~ignoreExpr +
5650                                    ~Literal(opener) + ~Literal(closer) +
5651                                    CharsNotIn(ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5652                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5653                else:
5654                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~Literal(opener) + ~Literal(closer) +
5655                                    CharsNotIn(ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5656                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5657        else:
5658            raise ValueError("opening and closing arguments must be strings if no content expression is given")
5659    ret = Forward()
5660    if ignoreExpr is not None:
5661        ret <<= Group( Suppress(opener) + ZeroOrMore( ignoreExpr | ret | content ) + Suppress(closer) )
5662    else:
5663        ret <<= Group( Suppress(opener) + ZeroOrMore( ret | content )  + Suppress(closer) )
5664    ret.setName('nested %s%s expression' % (opener,closer))
5665    return ret
5666
5667def indentedBlock(blockStatementExpr, indentStack, indent=True):
5668    """Helper method for defining space-delimited indentation blocks,
5669    such as those used to define block statements in Python source code.
5670
5671    Parameters:
5672
5673     - blockStatementExpr - expression defining syntax of statement that
5674       is repeated within the indented block
5675     - indentStack - list created by caller to manage indentation stack
5676       (multiple statementWithIndentedBlock expressions within a single
5677       grammar should share a common indentStack)
5678     - indent - boolean indicating whether block must be indented beyond
5679       the the current level; set to False for block of left-most
5680       statements (default= ``True``)
5681
5682    A valid block must contain at least one ``blockStatement``.
5683
5684    Example::
5685
5686        data = '''
5687        def A(z):
5688          A1
5689          B = 100
5690          G = A2
5691          A2
5692          A3
5693        B
5694        def BB(a,b,c):
5695          BB1
5696          def BBA():
5697            bba1
5698            bba2
5699            bba3
5700        C
5701        D
5702        def spam(x,y):
5703             def eggs(z):
5704                 pass
5705        '''
5706
5707
5708        indentStack = [1]
5709        stmt = Forward()
5710
5711        identifier = Word(alphas, alphanums)
5712        funcDecl = ("def" + identifier + Group( "(" + Optional( delimitedList(identifier) ) + ")" ) + ":")
5713        func_body = indentedBlock(stmt, indentStack)
5714        funcDef = Group( funcDecl + func_body )
5715
5716        rvalue = Forward()
5717        funcCall = Group(identifier + "(" + Optional(delimitedList(rvalue)) + ")")
5718        rvalue << (funcCall | identifier | Word(nums))
5719        assignment = Group(identifier + "=" + rvalue)
5720        stmt << ( funcDef | assignment | identifier )
5721
5722        module_body = OneOrMore(stmt)
5723
5724        parseTree = module_body.parseString(data)
5725        parseTree.pprint()
5726
5727    prints::
5728
5729        [['def',
5730          'A',
5731          ['(', 'z', ')'],
5732          ':',
5733          [['A1'], [['B', '=', '100']], [['G', '=', 'A2']], ['A2'], ['A3']]],
5734         'B',
5735         ['def',
5736          'BB',
5737          ['(', 'a', 'b', 'c', ')'],
5738          ':',
5739          [['BB1'], [['def', 'BBA', ['(', ')'], ':', [['bba1'], ['bba2'], ['bba3']]]]]],
5740         'C',
5741         'D',
5742         ['def',
5743          'spam',
5744          ['(', 'x', 'y', ')'],
5745          ':',
5746          [[['def', 'eggs', ['(', 'z', ')'], ':', [['pass']]]]]]]
5747    """
5748    def checkPeerIndent(s,l,t):
5749        if l >= len(s): return
5750        curCol = col(l,s)
5751        if curCol != indentStack[-1]:
5752            if curCol > indentStack[-1]:
5753                raise ParseFatalException(s,l,"illegal nesting")
5754            raise ParseException(s,l,"not a peer entry")
5755
5756    def checkSubIndent(s,l,t):
5757        curCol = col(l,s)
5758        if curCol > indentStack[-1]:
5759            indentStack.append( curCol )
5760        else:
5761            raise ParseException(s,l,"not a subentry")
5762
5763    def checkUnindent(s,l,t):
5764        if l >= len(s): return
5765        curCol = col(l,s)
5766        if not(indentStack and curCol < indentStack[-1] and curCol <= indentStack[-2]):
5767            raise ParseException(s,l,"not an unindent")
5768        indentStack.pop()
5769
5770    NL = OneOrMore(LineEnd().setWhitespaceChars("\t ").suppress())
5771    INDENT = (Empty() + Empty().setParseAction(checkSubIndent)).setName('INDENT')
5772    PEER   = Empty().setParseAction(checkPeerIndent).setName('')
5773    UNDENT = Empty().setParseAction(checkUnindent).setName('UNINDENT')
5774    if indent:
5775        smExpr = Group( Optional(NL) +
5776            #~ FollowedBy(blockStatementExpr) +
5777            INDENT + (OneOrMore( PEER + Group(blockStatementExpr) + Optional(NL) )) + UNDENT)
5778    else:
5779        smExpr = Group( Optional(NL) +
5780            (OneOrMore( PEER + Group(blockStatementExpr) + Optional(NL) )) )
5781    blockStatementExpr.ignore(_bslash + LineEnd())
5782    return smExpr.setName('indented block')
5783
5784alphas8bit = srange(r"[\0xc0-\0xd6\0xd8-\0xf6\0xf8-\0xff]")
5785punc8bit = srange(r"[\0xa1-\0xbf\0xd7\0xf7]")

5787anyOpenTag,anyCloseTag = makeHTMLTags(Word(alphas,alphanums+"_:").setName('any tag'))
5788_htmlEntityMap = dict(zip("gt lt amp nbsp quot apos".split(),'><& "\''))
5789commonHTMLEntity = Regex('&(?P<entity>' + '|'.join(_htmlEntityMap.keys()) +");").setName("common HTML entity")

5792    return _htmlEntityMap.get(t.entity)

5816                                            ~Literal(",") + ~LineEnd() ) ) ).streamline().setName("commaItem")
5817commaSeparatedList = delimitedList( Optional( quotedString.copy() | _commasepitem, default="") ).setName("commaSeparatedList")

5824# some other useful expressions - using lower-case class name since we are really using this as a namespace
5825class pyparsing_common:
5826    """Here are some common low-level expressions that may be useful in
5827    jump-starting parser development:
5828
5829     - numeric forms (:class:`integers<integer>`, :class:`reals<real>`,
5830       :class:`scientific notation<sci_real>`)
5831     - common :class:`programming identifiers<identifier>`
5832     - network addresses (:class:`MAC<mac_address>`,
5833       :class:`IPv4<ipv4_address>`, :class:`IPv6<ipv6_address>`)
5834     - ISO8601 :class:`dates<iso8601_date>` and
5835       :class:`datetime<iso8601_datetime>`
5836     - :class:`UUID<uuid>`
5837     - :class:`comma-separated list<comma_separated_list>`
5838
5839    Parse actions:
5840
5841     - :class:`convertToInteger`
5842     - :class:`convertToFloat`
5843     - :class:`convertToDate`
5844     - :class:`convertToDatetime`
5845     - :class:`stripHTMLTags`
5846     - :class:`upcaseTokens`
5847     - :class:`downcaseTokens`
5848
5849    Example::
5850

5972    Parse action for converting parsed integers to Python int
5973    """

5981    """expression that parses an unsigned integer, returns an int"""
5982

5984    """expression that parses a hexadecimal integer, returns an int"""

5987    """expression that parses an integer with optional leading sign, returns an int"""
5988
5989    fraction = (signed_integer().setParseAction(convertToFloat) + '/' + signed_integer().setParseAction(convertToFloat)).setName("fraction")
5990    """fractional expression of an integer divided by an integer, returns a float"""
5991    fraction.addParseAction(lambda t: t[0]/t[-1])
5992
5993    mixed_integer = (fraction | signed_integer + Optional(Optional('-').suppress() + fraction)).setName("fraction or mixed integer-fraction")
5994    """mixed integer of the form 'integer - fraction', with optional leading integer, returns float"""
5995    mixed_integer.addParseAction(sum)
5996

6015    "IPv4 address (``0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255``)"

6028    @staticmethod
6029    def convertToDate(fmt="%Y-%m-%d"):
6030        """
6031        Helper to create a parse action for converting parsed date string to Python datetime.date
6032
6033        Params -
6034         - fmt - format to be passed to datetime.strptime (default= ``"%Y-%m-%d"``)
6035
6036        Example::
6037
6038            date_expr = pyparsing_common.iso8601_date.copy()
6039            date_expr.setParseAction(pyparsing_common.convertToDate())
6040            print(date_expr.parseString("1999-12-31"))
6041
6042        prints::
6043
6044            [datetime.date(1999, 12, 31)]
6045        """
6046        def cvt_fn(s,l,t):
6047            try:
6048                return datetime.strptime(t[0], fmt).date()
6049            except ValueError as ve:
6050                raise ParseException(s, l, str(ve))
6051        return cvt_fn
6052
6053    @staticmethod
6054    def convertToDatetime(fmt="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f"):
6055        """Helper to create a parse action for converting parsed
6056        datetime string to Python datetime.datetime
6057
6058        Params -
6059         - fmt - format to be passed to datetime.strptime (default= ``"%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f"``)
6060
6061        Example::
6062
6063            dt_expr = pyparsing_common.iso8601_datetime.copy()
6064            dt_expr.setParseAction(pyparsing_common.convertToDatetime())
6065            print(dt_expr.parseString("1999-12-31T23:59:59.999"))
6066
6067        prints::
6068
6069            [datetime.datetime(1999, 12, 31, 23, 59, 59, 999000)]
6070        """
6071        def cvt_fn(s,l,t):
6072            try:
6073                return datetime.strptime(t[0], fmt)
6074            except ValueError as ve:
6075                raise ParseException(s, l, str(ve))
6076        return cvt_fn

6118class _lazyclassproperty(object):
6119    def __init__(self, fn):
6120        self.fn = fn
6121
6122    def __get__(self, obj, cls):
6123        if cls is None:
6124            cls = type(obj)
6125        if not hasattr(cls, '_intern') or any(cls._intern is getattr(superclass, '_intern', []) for superclass in cls.__mro__[1:]):
6126            cls._intern = {}
6127        attrname = self.fn.__name__
6128        if attrname not in cls._intern:
6129            cls._intern[attrname] = self.fn(cls)
6130        return cls._intern[attrname]

6132
6133class unicode_set(object):
6134    """
6135    A set of Unicode characters, for language-specific strings for
6136    ``alphas``, ``nums``, ``alphanums``, and ``printables``.
6137    A unicode_set is defined by a list of ranges in the Unicode character
6138    set, in a class attribute ``_ranges``, such as::
6139
6140        _ranges = [(0x0020, 0x007e), (0x00a0, 0x00ff),]
6141
6142    A unicode set can also be defined using multiple inheritance of other unicode sets::
6143
6144        class CJK(Chinese, Japanese, Korean):
6145            pass
6146    """
6147    _ranges = []
6148
6149    @classmethod
6150    def _get_chars_for_ranges(cls):
6151        ret = []
6152        for cc in cls.__mro__:
6153            if cc is unicode_set:
6154                break
6155            for rr in cc._ranges:
6156                ret.extend(range(rr[0], rr[-1]+1))
6157        return [unichr(c) for c in sorted(set(ret))]
6158
6159    @_lazyclassproperty
6160    def printables(cls):
6161        "all non-whitespace characters in this range"
6162        return u''.join(filterfalse(unicode.isspace, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6163
6164    @_lazyclassproperty
6165    def alphas(cls):
6166        "all alphabetic characters in this range"
6167        return u''.join(filter(unicode.isalpha, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6168
6169    @_lazyclassproperty
6170    def nums(cls):
6171        "all numeric digit characters in this range"
6172        return u''.join(filter(unicode.isdigit, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6173
6174    @_lazyclassproperty
6175    def alphanums(cls):
6176        "all alphanumeric characters in this range"
6177        return cls.alphas + cls.nums
6178
6179

3582class And(ParseExpression):
3583    """
3584    Requires all given :class:`ParseExpression` s to be found in the given order.
3585    Expressions may be separated by whitespace.
3586    May be constructed using the ``'+'`` operator.
3587    May also be constructed using the ``'-'`` operator, which will
3588    suppress backtracking.
3589
3590    Example::
3591
3592        integer = Word(nums)
3593        name_expr = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
3594
3595        expr = And([integer("id"),name_expr("name"),integer("age")])
3596        # more easily written as:
3597        expr = integer("id") + name_expr("name") + integer("age")
3598    """
3599
3600    class _ErrorStop(Empty):
3601        def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
3602            super(And._ErrorStop,self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
3603            self.name = '-'
3604            self.leaveWhitespace()
3605
3606    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = True ):
3607        super(And,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3608        self.mayReturnEmpty = all(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3609        self.setWhitespaceChars( self.exprs[0].whiteChars )
3610        self.skipWhitespace = self.exprs[0].skipWhitespace
3611        self.callPreparse = True
3612
3613    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3614        # pass False as last arg to _parse for first element, since we already
3615        # pre-parsed the string as part of our And pre-parsing
3616        loc, resultlist = self.exprs[0]._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
3617        errorStop = False
3618        for e in self.exprs[1:]:
3619            if isinstance(e, And._ErrorStop):
3620                errorStop = True
3621                continue
3622            if errorStop:
3623                try:
3624                    loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3625                except ParseSyntaxException:
3626                    raise
3627                except ParseBaseException as pe:
3628                    pe.__traceback__ = None
3629                    raise ParseSyntaxException._from_exception(pe)
3630                except IndexError:
3631                    raise ParseSyntaxException(instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self)
3632            else:
3633                loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3634            if exprtokens or exprtokens.haskeys():
3635                resultlist += exprtokens
3636        return loc, resultlist
3637
3638    def __iadd__(self, other ):
3639        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3640            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3641        return self.append( other ) #And( [ self, other ] )
3642
3643    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3644        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3645        for e in self.exprs:
3646            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3647            if not e.mayReturnEmpty:
3648                break
3649
3650    def __str__( self ):
3651        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3652            return self.name
3653
3654        if self.strRepr is None:
3655            self.strRepr = "{" + " ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3656
3657        return self.strRepr

3608        self.mayReturnEmpty = all(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)

3610        self.skipWhitespace = self.exprs[0].skipWhitespace
3611        self.callPreparse = True
#   def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True):
View Source 
3613    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3614        # pass False as last arg to _parse for first element, since we already
3615        # pre-parsed the string as part of our And pre-parsing
3616        loc, resultlist = self.exprs[0]._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
3617        errorStop = False
3618        for e in self.exprs[1:]:
3619            if isinstance(e, And._ErrorStop):
3620                errorStop = True
3621                continue
3622            if errorStop:
3623                try:
3624                    loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3625                except ParseSyntaxException:
3626                    raise
3627                except ParseBaseException as pe:
3628                    pe.__traceback__ = None
3629                    raise ParseSyntaxException._from_exception(pe)
3630                except IndexError:
3631                    raise ParseSyntaxException(instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self)
3632            else:
3633                loc, exprtokens = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3634            if exprtokens or exprtokens.haskeys():
3635                resultlist += exprtokens
3636        return loc, resultlist

2630class CaselessLiteral(Literal):
2631    """Token to match a specified string, ignoring case of letters.

3181class CharsNotIn(Token):
3182    """Token for matching words composed of characters *not* in a given
3183    set (will include whitespace in matched characters if not listed in
3184    the provided exclusion set - see example). Defined with string
3185    containing all disallowed characters, and an optional minimum,
3186    maximum, and/or exact length.  The default value for ``min`` is
3187    1 (a minimum value < 1 is not valid); the default values for
3188    ``max`` and ``exact`` are 0, meaning no maximum or exact
3189    length restriction.
3190
3191    Example::
3192
3193        # define a comma-separated-value as anything that is not a ','
3194        csv_value = CharsNotIn(',')
3195        print(delimitedList(csv_value).parseString("dkls,lsdkjf,s12 34,@!#,213"))
3196
3197    prints::
3198
3199        ['dkls', 'lsdkjf', 's12 34', '@!#', '213']
3200    """
3201    def __init__( self, notChars, min=1, max=0, exact=0 ):
3202        super(CharsNotIn,self).__init__()
3203        self.skipWhitespace = False
3204        self.notChars = notChars
3205
3206        if min < 1:
3207            raise ValueError(
3208                "cannot specify a minimum length < 1; use " +
3209                "Optional(CharsNotIn()) if zero-length char group is permitted")
3210
3211        self.minLen = min
3212
3213        if max > 0:
3214            self.maxLen = max
3215        else:
3216            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
3217
3218        if exact > 0:
3219            self.maxLen = exact
3220            self.minLen = exact
3221
3222        self.name = _ustr(self)
3223        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3224        self.mayReturnEmpty = ( self.minLen == 0 )
3225        self.mayIndexError = False
3226
3227    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3228        if instring[loc] in self.notChars:
3229            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3230
3231        start = loc
3232        loc += 1
3233        notchars = self.notChars
3234        maxlen = min( start+self.maxLen, len(instring) )
3235        while loc < maxlen and \
3236              (instring[loc] not in notchars):
3237            loc += 1
3238
3239        if loc - start < self.minLen:
3240            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3241
3242        return loc, instring[start:loc]
3243
3244    def __str__( self ):
3245        try:
3246            return super(CharsNotIn, self).__str__()
3247        except Exception:
3248            pass
3249
3250        if self.strRepr is None:
3251            if len(self.notChars) > 4:
3252                self.strRepr = "!W:(%s...)" % self.notChars[:4]
3253            else:
3254                self.strRepr = "!W:(%s)" % self.notChars
3255
3256        return self.strRepr

4561class Combine(TokenConverter):
4562    """Converter to concatenate all matching tokens to a single string.
4563    By default, the matching patterns must also be contiguous in the
4564    input string; this can be disabled by specifying
4565    ``'adjacent=False'`` in the constructor.
4566
4567    Example::
4568
4569        real = Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums)
4570        print(real.parseString('3.1416')) # -> ['3', '.', '1416']
4571        # will also erroneously match the following
4572        print(real.parseString('3. 1416')) # -> ['3', '.', '1416']
4573
4574        real = Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
4575        print(real.parseString('3.1416')) # -> ['3.1416']
4576        # no match when there are internal spaces
4577        print(real.parseString('3. 1416')) # -> Exception: Expected W:(0123...)
4578    """
4579    def __init__( self, expr, joinString="", adjacent=True ):
4580        super(Combine,self).__init__( expr )
4581        # suppress whitespace-stripping in contained parse expressions, but re-enable it on the Combine itself
4582        if adjacent:
4583            self.leaveWhitespace()
4584        self.adjacent = adjacent
4585        self.skipWhitespace = True
4586        self.joinString = joinString
4587        self.callPreparse = True
4588
4589    def ignore( self, other ):
4590        if self.adjacent:
4591            ParserElement.ignore(self, other)
4592        else:
4593            super( Combine, self).ignore( other )
4594        return self
4595
4596    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4597        retToks = tokenlist.copy()
4598        del retToks[:]
4599        retToks += ParseResults([ "".join(tokenlist._asStringList(self.joinString)) ], modal=self.modalResults)
4600
4601        if self.resultsName and retToks.haskeys():
4602            return [ retToks ]
4603        else:
4604            return retToks

4628class Dict(TokenConverter):
4629    """Converter to return a repetitive expression as a list, but also
4630    as a dictionary. Each element can also be referenced using the first
4631    token in the expression as its key. Useful for tabular report
4632    scraping when the first column can be used as a item key.
4633
4634    Example::
4635
4636        data_word = Word(alphas)
4637        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4638        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word).setParseAction(' '.join))
4639
4640        text = "shape: SQUARE posn: upper left color: light blue texture: burlap"
4641        attr_expr = (label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4642
4643        # print attributes as plain groups
4644        print(OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).dump())
4645
4646        # instead of OneOrMore(expr), parse using Dict(OneOrMore(Group(expr))) - Dict will auto-assign names
4647        result = Dict(OneOrMore(Group(attr_expr))).parseString(text)
4648        print(result.dump())
4649
4650        # access named fields as dict entries, or output as dict
4651        print(result['shape'])
4652        print(result.asDict())
4653
4654    prints::
4655
4656        ['shape', 'SQUARE', 'posn', 'upper left', 'color', 'light blue', 'texture', 'burlap']
4657        [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['posn', 'upper left'], ['color', 'light blue'], ['texture', 'burlap']]
4658        - color: light blue
4659        - posn: upper left
4660        - shape: SQUARE
4661        - texture: burlap
4662        SQUARE
4663        {'color': 'light blue', 'posn': 'upper left', 'texture': 'burlap', 'shape': 'SQUARE'}
4664
4665    See more examples at :class:`ParseResults` of accessing fields by results name.
4666    """
4667    def __init__( self, expr ):
4668        super(Dict,self).__init__( expr )
4669        self.saveAsList = True
4670
4671    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4672        for i,tok in enumerate(tokenlist):
4673            if len(tok) == 0:
4674                continue
4675            ikey = tok[0]
4676            if isinstance(ikey,int):
4677                ikey = _ustr(tok[0]).strip()
4678            if len(tok)==1:
4679                tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset("",i)
4680            elif len(tok)==2 and not isinstance(tok[1],ParseResults):
4681                tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(tok[1],i)
4682            else:
4683                dictvalue = tok.copy() #ParseResults(i)
4684                del dictvalue[0]
4685                if len(dictvalue)!= 1 or (isinstance(dictvalue,ParseResults) and dictvalue.haskeys()):
4686                    tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(dictvalue,i)
4687                else:
4688                    tokenlist[ikey] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(dictvalue[0],i)
4689
4690        if self.resultsName:
4691            return [ tokenlist ]
4692        else:
4693            return tokenlist

Converter to return a repetitive expression as a list, but also as a dictionary. Each element can also be referenced using the first token in the expression as its key. Useful for tabular report scraping when the first column can be used as a item key.

Example::

print(result.asDict())

- color: light blue
- posn: upper left
- shape: SQUARE
- texture: burlap
SQUARE
{'color': 'light blue', 'posn': 'upper left', 'texture': 'burlap', 'shape': 'SQUARE'}

See more examples at ParseResults of accessing fields by results name.

#   class Each(ParseExpression):

3810class Each(ParseExpression):
3811    """Requires all given :class:`ParseExpression` s to be found, but in
3812    any order. Expressions may be separated by whitespace.
3813
3814    May be constructed using the ``'&'`` operator.
3815
3816    Example::
3817
3818        color = oneOf("RED ORANGE YELLOW GREEN BLUE PURPLE BLACK WHITE BROWN")
3819        shape_type = oneOf("SQUARE CIRCLE TRIANGLE STAR HEXAGON OCTAGON")
3820        integer = Word(nums)
3821        shape_attr = "shape:" + shape_type("shape")
3822        posn_attr = "posn:" + Group(integer("x") + ',' + integer("y"))("posn")
3823        color_attr = "color:" + color("color")
3824        size_attr = "size:" + integer("size")
3825
3826        # use Each (using operator '&') to accept attributes in any order
3827        # (shape and posn are required, color and size are optional)
3828        shape_spec = shape_attr & posn_attr & Optional(color_attr) & Optional(size_attr)
3829
3830        shape_spec.runTests('''
3831            shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: 100, 120
3832            shape: CIRCLE size: 50 color: BLUE posn: 50,80
3833            color:GREEN size:20 shape:TRIANGLE posn:20,40
3834            '''
3835            )
3836
3837    prints::
3838
3839        shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: 100, 120
3840        ['shape:', 'SQUARE', 'color:', 'BLACK', 'posn:', ['100', ',', '120']]
3841        - color: BLACK
3842        - posn: ['100', ',', '120']
3843          - x: 100
3844          - y: 120
3845        - shape: SQUARE
3846
3847
3848        shape: CIRCLE size: 50 color: BLUE posn: 50,80
3849        ['shape:', 'CIRCLE', 'size:', '50', 'color:', 'BLUE', 'posn:', ['50', ',', '80']]
3850        - color: BLUE
3851        - posn: ['50', ',', '80']
3852          - x: 50
3853          - y: 80
3854        - shape: CIRCLE
3855        - size: 50
3856
3857
3858        color: GREEN size: 20 shape: TRIANGLE posn: 20,40
3859        ['color:', 'GREEN', 'size:', '20', 'shape:', 'TRIANGLE', 'posn:', ['20', ',', '40']]
3860        - color: GREEN
3861        - posn: ['20', ',', '40']
3862          - x: 20
3863          - y: 40
3864        - shape: TRIANGLE
3865        - size: 20
3866    """
3867    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = True ):
3868        super(Each,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3869        self.mayReturnEmpty = all(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3870        self.skipWhitespace = True
3871        self.initExprGroups = True
3872
3873    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3874        if self.initExprGroups:
3875            self.opt1map = dict((id(e.expr),e) for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional))
3876            opt1 = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional) ]
3877            opt2 = [ e for e in self.exprs if e.mayReturnEmpty and not isinstance(e,Optional)]
3878            self.optionals = opt1 + opt2
3879            self.multioptionals = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,ZeroOrMore) ]
3880            self.multirequired = [ e.expr for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,OneOrMore) ]
3881            self.required = [ e for e in self.exprs if not isinstance(e,(Optional,ZeroOrMore,OneOrMore)) ]
3882            self.required += self.multirequired
3883            self.initExprGroups = False
3884        tmpLoc = loc
3885        tmpReqd = self.required[:]
3886        tmpOpt  = self.optionals[:]
3887        matchOrder = []
3888
3889        keepMatching = True
3890        while keepMatching:
3891            tmpExprs = tmpReqd + tmpOpt + self.multioptionals + self.multirequired
3892            failed = []
3893            for e in tmpExprs:
3894                try:
3895                    tmpLoc = e.tryParse( instring, tmpLoc )
3896                except ParseException:
3897                    failed.append(e)
3898                else:
3899                    matchOrder.append(self.opt1map.get(id(e),e))
3900                    if e in tmpReqd:
3901                        tmpReqd.remove(e)
3902                    elif e in tmpOpt:
3903                        tmpOpt.remove(e)
3904            if len(failed) == len(tmpExprs):
3905                keepMatching = False
3906
3907        if tmpReqd:
3908            missing = ", ".join(_ustr(e) for e in tmpReqd)
3909            raise ParseException(instring,loc,"Missing one or more required elements (%s)" % missing )
3910
3911        # add any unmatched Optionals, in case they have default values defined
3912        matchOrder += [e for e in self.exprs if isinstance(e,Optional) and e.expr in tmpOpt]
3913
3914        resultlist = []
3915        for e in matchOrder:
3916            loc,results = e._parse(instring,loc,doActions)
3917            resultlist.append(results)
3918
3919        finalResults = sum(resultlist, ParseResults([]))
3920        return loc, finalResults
3921
3922    def __str__( self ):
3923        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3924            return self.name
3925
3926        if self.strRepr is None:
3927            self.strRepr = "{" + " & ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3928
3929        return self.strRepr
3930
3931    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3932        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3933        for e in self.exprs:
3934            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )

Requires all given ParseExpression s to be found, but in any order. Expressions may be separated by whitespace.

May be constructed using the '&' operator.

Example::

4014class FollowedBy(ParseElementEnhance):
4015    """Lookahead matching of the given parse expression.
4016    ``FollowedBy`` does *not* advance the parsing position within
4017    the input string, it only verifies that the specified parse
4018    expression matches at the current position.  ``FollowedBy``
4019    always returns a null token list. If any results names are defined
4020    in the lookahead expression, those *will* be returned for access by
4021    name.
4022
4023    Example::
4024
4025        # use FollowedBy to match a label only if it is followed by a ':'
4026        data_word = Word(alphas)
4027        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4028        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4029
4030        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString("shape: SQUARE color: BLACK posn: upper left").pprint()
4031
4032    prints::
4033
4034        [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['color', 'BLACK'], ['posn', 'upper left']]
4035    """
4036    def __init__( self, expr ):
4037        super(FollowedBy,self).__init__(expr)
4038        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4039
4040    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4041        _, ret = self.expr._parse(instring, loc, doActions=doActions)
4042        del ret[:]
4043        return loc, ret

4460class Forward(ParseElementEnhance):
4461    """Forward declaration of an expression to be defined later -
4462    used for recursive grammars, such as algebraic infix notation.
4463    When the expression is known, it is assigned to the ``Forward``
4464    variable using the '<<' operator.
4465
4466    Note: take care when assigning to ``Forward`` not to overlook
4467    precedence of operators.
4468
4469    Specifically, '|' has a lower precedence than '<<', so that::
4470
4471        fwdExpr << a | b | c
4472
4473    will actually be evaluated as::
4474
4475        (fwdExpr << a) | b | c
4476
4477    thereby leaving b and c out as parseable alternatives.  It is recommended that you
4478    explicitly group the values inserted into the ``Forward``::
4479
4480        fwdExpr << (a | b | c)
4481
4482    Converting to use the '<<=' operator instead will avoid this problem.
4483
4484    See :class:`ParseResults.pprint` for an example of a recursive
4485    parser created using ``Forward``.
4486    """
4487    def __init__( self, other=None ):
4488        super(Forward,self).__init__( other, savelist=False )
4489
4490    def __lshift__( self, other ):
4491        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
4492            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass(other)
4493        self.expr = other
4494        self.strRepr = None
4495        self.mayIndexError = self.expr.mayIndexError
4496        self.mayReturnEmpty = self.expr.mayReturnEmpty
4497        self.setWhitespaceChars( self.expr.whiteChars )
4498        self.skipWhitespace = self.expr.skipWhitespace
4499        self.saveAsList = self.expr.saveAsList
4500        self.ignoreExprs.extend(self.expr.ignoreExprs)
4501        return self
4502
4503    def __ilshift__(self, other):
4504        return self << other
4505
4506    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
4507        self.skipWhitespace = False
4508        return self
4509
4510    def streamline( self ):
4511        if not self.streamlined:
4512            self.streamlined = True
4513            if self.expr is not None:
4514                self.expr.streamline()
4515        return self
4516
4517    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
4518        if self not in validateTrace:
4519            tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
4520            if self.expr is not None:
4521                self.expr.validate(tmp)
4522        self.checkRecursion([])
4523
4524    def __str__( self ):
4525        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4526            return self.name
4527        return self.__class__.__name__ + ": ..."
4528
4529        # stubbed out for now - creates awful memory and perf issues
4530        self._revertClass = self.__class__
4531        self.__class__ = _ForwardNoRecurse
4532        try:
4533            if self.expr is not None:
4534                retString = _ustr(self.expr)
4535            else:
4536                retString = "None"
4537        finally:
4538            self.__class__ = self._revertClass
4539        return self.__class__.__name__ + ": " + retString
4540
4541    def copy(self):
4542        if self.expr is not None:
4543            return super(Forward,self).copy()
4544        else:
4545            ret = Forward()
4546            ret <<= self
4547            return ret

Forward declaration of an expression to be defined later - used for recursive grammars, such as algebraic infix notation. When the expression is known, it is assigned to the Forward variable using the '<<' operator.

Note: take care when assigning to Forward not to overlook precedence of operators.

Specifically, '|' has a lower precedence than '<<', so that::

fwdExpr << a | b | c

will actually be evaluated as::

(fwdExpr << a) | b | c

thereby leaving b and c out as parseable alternatives. It is recommended that you explicitly group the values inserted into the Forward::

fwdExpr << (a | b | c)

Converting to use the '<<=' operator instead will avoid this problem.

See ParseResults.pprint for an example of a recursive parser created using Forward.

Make a copy of this ParserElement. Useful for defining different parse actions for the same parsing pattern, using copies of the original parse element.

Example::

integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
integerK = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024) + Suppress("K")
integerM = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

print(OneOrMore(integerK | integerM | integer).parseString("5K 100 640K 256M"))

prints::

[5120, 100, 655360, 268435456]

Equivalent form of expr.copy() is just expr()::

integerM = integer().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

3317class GoToColumn(_PositionToken):
3318    """Token to advance to a specific column of input text; useful for
3319    tabular report scraping.
3320    """
3321    def __init__( self, colno ):
3322        super(GoToColumn,self).__init__()
3323        self.col = colno
3324
3325    def preParse( self, instring, loc ):
3326        if col(loc,instring) != self.col:
3327            instrlen = len(instring)
3328            if self.ignoreExprs:
3329                loc = self._skipIgnorables( instring, loc )
3330            while loc < instrlen and instring[loc].isspace() and col( loc, instring ) != self.col :
3331                loc += 1
3332        return loc
3333
3334    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3335        thiscol = col( loc, instring )
3336        if thiscol > self.col:
3337            raise ParseException( instring, loc, "Text not in expected column", self )
3338        newloc = loc + self.col - thiscol
3339        ret = instring[ loc: newloc ]
3340        return newloc, ret

4606class Group(TokenConverter):
4607    """Converter to return the matched tokens as a list - useful for
4608    returning tokens of :class:`ZeroOrMore` and :class:`OneOrMore` expressions.
4609
4610    Example::
4611
4612        ident = Word(alphas)
4613        num = Word(nums)
4614        term = ident | num
4615        func = ident + Optional(delimitedList(term))
4616        print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', 'a', 'b', '100']
4617
4618        func = ident + Group(Optional(delimitedList(term)))
4619        print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', ['a', 'b', '100']]
4620    """
4621    def __init__( self, expr ):
4622        super(Group,self).__init__( expr )
4623        self.saveAsList = True
4624
4625    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4626        return [ tokenlist ]

Converter to return the matched tokens as a list - useful for returning tokens of ZeroOrMore and OneOrMore expressions.

Example::

ident = Word(alphas)
num = Word(nums)
term = ident | num
func = ident + Optional(delimitedList(term))
print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', 'a', 'b', '100']

func = ident + Group(Optional(delimitedList(term)))
print(func.parseString("fn a,b,100"))  # -> ['fn', ['a', 'b', '100']]

2557class Keyword(Token):
2558    """Token to exactly match a specified string as a keyword, that is,
2559    it must be immediately followed by a non-keyword character.  Compare
2560    with :class:`Literal`:
2561
2562     - ``Literal("if")`` will match the leading ``'if'`` in
2563       ``'ifAndOnlyIf'``.
2564     - ``Keyword("if")`` will not; it will only match the leading
2565       ``'if'`` in ``'if x=1'``, or ``'if(y==2)'``
2566
2567    Accepts two optional constructor arguments in addition to the
2568    keyword string:
2569
2570     - ``identChars`` is a string of characters that would be valid
2571       identifier characters, defaulting to all alphanumerics + "_" and
2572       "$"
2573     - ``caseless`` allows case-insensitive matching, default is ``False``.
2574
2575    Example::
2576
2577        Keyword("start").parseString("start")  # -> ['start']
2578        Keyword("start").parseString("starting")  # -> Exception
2579
2580    For case-insensitive matching, use :class:`CaselessKeyword`.
2581    """
2582    DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS = alphanums+"_$"
2583
2584    def __init__( self, matchString, identChars=None, caseless=False ):
2585        super(Keyword,self).__init__()
2586        if identChars is None:
2587            identChars = Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS
2588        self.match = matchString
2589        self.matchLen = len(matchString)
2590        try:
2591            self.firstMatchChar = matchString[0]
2592        except IndexError:
2593            warnings.warn("null string passed to Keyword; use Empty() instead",
2594                            SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2595        self.name = '"%s"' % self.match
2596        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2597        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2598        self.mayIndexError = False
2599        self.caseless = caseless
2600        if caseless:
2601            self.caselessmatch = matchString.upper()
2602            identChars = identChars.upper()
2603        self.identChars = set(identChars)
2604
2605    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2606        if self.caseless:
2607            if ( (instring[ loc:loc+self.matchLen ].upper() == self.caselessmatch) and
2608                 (loc >= len(instring)-self.matchLen or instring[loc+self.matchLen].upper() not in self.identChars) and
2609                 (loc == 0 or instring[loc-1].upper() not in self.identChars) ):
2610                return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2611        else:
2612            if (instring[loc] == self.firstMatchChar and
2613                (self.matchLen==1 or instring.startswith(self.match,loc)) and
2614                (loc >= len(instring)-self.matchLen or instring[loc+self.matchLen] not in self.identChars) and
2615                (loc == 0 or instring[loc-1] not in self.identChars) ):
2616                return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2617        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2618
2619    def copy(self):
2620        c = super(Keyword,self).copy()
2621        c.identChars = Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS
2622        return c
2623
2624    @staticmethod
2625    def setDefaultKeywordChars( chars ):
2626        """Overrides the default Keyword chars
2627        """
2628        Keyword.DEFAULT_KEYWORD_CHARS = chars

Token to exactly match a specified string as a keyword, that is, it must be immediately followed by a non-keyword character. Compare with Literal:

  • Literal("if") will match the leading 'if' in 'ifAndOnlyIf'.
  • Keyword("if") will not; it will only match the leading 'if' in 'if x=1', or 'if(y==2)'

Accepts two optional constructor arguments in addition to the keyword string:

  • identChars is a string of characters that would be valid identifier characters, defaulting to all alphanumerics + "_" and "$"
  • caseless allows case-insensitive matching, default is False.

Example::

Keyword("start").parseString("starting")  # -> Exception

For case-insensitive matching, use CaselessKeyword.

Make a copy of this ParserElement. Useful for defining different parse actions for the same parsing pattern, using copies of the original parse element.

Example::

integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
integerK = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024) + Suppress("K")
integerM = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

print(OneOrMore(integerK | integerM | integer).parseString("5K 100 640K 256M"))

prints::

[5120, 100, 655360, 268435456]

Equivalent form of expr.copy() is just expr()::

integerM = integer().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

3374class LineEnd(_PositionToken):
3375    """Matches if current position is at the end of a line within the
3376    parse string
3377    """
3378    def __init__( self ):
3379        super(LineEnd,self).__init__()
3380        self.setWhitespaceChars( ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS.replace("\n","") )
3381        self.errmsg = "Expected end of line"
3382
3383    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3384        if loc<len(instring):
3385            if instring[loc] == "\n":
3386                return loc+1, "\n"
3387            else:
3388                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3389        elif loc == len(instring):
3390            return loc+1, []
3391        else:
3392            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

2516class Literal(Token):
2517    """Token to exactly match a specified string.
2518
2519    Example::
2520
2521        Literal('blah').parseString('blah')  # -> ['blah']
2522        Literal('blah').parseString('blahfooblah')  # -> ['blah']
2523        Literal('blah').parseString('bla')  # -> Exception: Expected "blah"
2524
2525    For case-insensitive matching, use :class:`CaselessLiteral`.
2526
2527    For keyword matching (force word break before and after the matched string),
2528    use :class:`Keyword` or :class:`CaselessKeyword`.
2529    """
2530    def __init__( self, matchString ):
2531        super(Literal,self).__init__()
2532        self.match = matchString
2533        self.matchLen = len(matchString)
2534        try:
2535            self.firstMatchChar = matchString[0]
2536        except IndexError:
2537            warnings.warn("null string passed to Literal; use Empty() instead",
2538                            SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2539            self.__class__ = Empty
2540        self.name = '"%s"' % _ustr(self.match)
2541        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2542        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2543        self.mayIndexError = False
2544
2545    # Performance tuning: this routine gets called a *lot*
2546    # if this is a single character match string  and the first character matches,
2547    # short-circuit as quickly as possible, and avoid calling startswith
2548    #~ @profile
2549    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2550        if (instring[loc] == self.firstMatchChar and
2551            (self.matchLen==1 or instring.startswith(self.match,loc)) ):
2552            return loc+self.matchLen, self.match
2553        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

Literal('blah').parseString('blahfooblah')  # -> ['blah']
Literal('blah').parseString('bla')  # -> Exception: Expected "blah"

For case-insensitive matching, use CaselessLiteral.

For keyword matching (force word break before and after the matched string), use Keyword or CaselessKeyword.

#   class PrecededBy(ParseElementEnhance):
View Source 
4046class PrecededBy(ParseElementEnhance):
4047    """Lookbehind matching of the given parse expression.
4048    ``PrecededBy`` does not advance the parsing position within the
4049    input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression
4050    matches prior to the current position.  ``PrecededBy`` always
4051    returns a null token list, but if a results name is defined on the
4052    given expression, it is returned.
4053
4054    Parameters:
4055
4056     - expr - expression that must match prior to the current parse
4057       location
4058     - retreat - (default= ``None``) - (int) maximum number of characters
4059       to lookbehind prior to the current parse location
4060
4061    If the lookbehind expression is a string, Literal, Keyword, or
4062    a Word or CharsNotIn with a specified exact or maximum length, then
4063    the retreat parameter is not required. Otherwise, retreat must be
4064    specified to give a maximum number of characters to look back from
4065    the current parse position for a lookbehind match.
4066
4067    Example::
4068
4069        # VB-style variable names with type prefixes
4070        int_var = PrecededBy("#") + pyparsing_common.identifier
4071        str_var = PrecededBy("$") + pyparsing_common.identifier
4072
4073    """
4074    def __init__(self, expr, retreat=None):
4075        super(PrecededBy, self).__init__(expr)
4076        self.expr = self.expr().leaveWhitespace()
4077        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4078        self.mayIndexError = False
4079        self.exact = False
4080        if isinstance(expr, str):
4081            retreat = len(expr)
4082            self.exact = True
4083        elif isinstance(expr, (Literal, Keyword)):
4084            retreat = expr.matchLen
4085            self.exact = True
4086        elif isinstance(expr, (Word, CharsNotIn)) and expr.maxLen != _MAX_INT:
4087            retreat = expr.maxLen
4088            self.exact = True
4089        elif isinstance(expr, _PositionToken):
4090            retreat = 0
4091            self.exact = True
4092        self.retreat = retreat
4093        self.errmsg = "not preceded by " + str(expr)
4094        self.skipWhitespace = False
4095
4096    def parseImpl(self, instring, loc=0, doActions=True):
4097        if self.exact:
4098            if loc < self.retreat:
4099                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg)
4100            start = loc - self.retreat
4101            _, ret = self.expr._parse(instring, start)
4102        else:
4103            # retreat specified a maximum lookbehind window, iterate
4104            test_expr = self.expr + StringEnd()
4105            instring_slice = instring[:loc]
4106            last_expr = ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg)
4107            for offset in range(1, min(loc, self.retreat+1)):
4108                try:
4109                    _, ret = test_expr._parse(instring_slice, loc-offset)
4110                except ParseBaseException as pbe:
4111                    last_expr = pbe
4112                else:
4113                    break
4114            else:
4115                raise last_expr
4116        # return empty list of tokens, but preserve any defined results names
4117        del ret[:]
4118        return loc, ret

Lookbehind matching of the given parse expression. PrecededBy does not advance the parsing position within the input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression matches prior to the current position. PrecededBy always returns a null token list, but if a results name is defined on the given expression, it is returned.

Parameters:

  • expr - expression that must match prior to the current parse location
  • retreat - (default= None) - (int) maximum number of characters to lookbehind prior to the current parse location

If the lookbehind expression is a string, Literal, Keyword, or a Word or CharsNotIn with a specified exact or maximum length, then the retreat parameter is not required. Otherwise, retreat must be specified to give a maximum number of characters to look back from the current parse position for a lookbehind match.

Example::

# VB-style variable names with type prefixes
int_var = PrecededBy("#") + pyparsing_common.identifier
str_var = PrecededBy("$") + pyparsing_common.identifier

#   class MatchFirst(ParseExpression):

3742class MatchFirst(ParseExpression):
3743    """Requires that at least one :class:`ParseExpression` is found. If
3744    two expressions match, the first one listed is the one that will
3745    match. May be constructed using the ``'|'`` operator.
3746
3747    Example::
3748
3749        # construct MatchFirst using '|' operator
3750
3751        # watch the order of expressions to match
3752        number = Word(nums) | Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
3753        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Fail! -> [['123'], ['3'], ['1416'], ['789']]
3754
3755        # put more selective expression first
3756        number = Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums)) | Word(nums)
3757        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Better -> [['123'], ['3.1416'], ['789']]
3758    """
3759    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3760        super(MatchFirst,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3761        if self.exprs:
3762            self.mayReturnEmpty = any(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3763        else:
3764            self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3765
3766    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3767        maxExcLoc = -1
3768        maxException = None
3769        for e in self.exprs:
3770            try:
3771                ret = e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3772                return ret
3773            except ParseException as err:
3774                if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3775                    maxException = err
3776                    maxExcLoc = err.loc
3777            except IndexError:
3778                if len(instring) > maxExcLoc:
3779                    maxException = ParseException(instring,len(instring),e.errmsg,self)
3780                    maxExcLoc = len(instring)
3781
3782        # only got here if no expression matched, raise exception for match that made it the furthest
3783        else:
3784            if maxException is not None:
3785                maxException.msg = self.errmsg
3786                raise maxException
3787            else:
3788                raise ParseException(instring, loc, "no defined alternatives to match", self)
3789
3790    def __ior__(self, other ):
3791        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3792            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3793        return self.append( other ) #MatchFirst( [ self, other ] )
3794
3795    def __str__( self ):
3796        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3797            return self.name
3798
3799        if self.strRepr is None:
3800            self.strRepr = "{" + " | ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3801
3802        return self.strRepr
3803
3804    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3805        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3806        for e in self.exprs:
3807            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )

Requires that at least one ParseExpression is found. If two expressions match, the first one listed is the one that will match. May be constructed using the '|' operator.

Example::

# construct MatchFirst using '|' operator

# watch the order of expressions to match
number = Word(nums) | Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Fail! -> [['123'], ['3'], ['1416'], ['789']]

# put more selective expression first
number = Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums)) | Word(nums)
print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789")) #  Better -> [['123'], ['3.1416'], ['789']]

4121class NotAny(ParseElementEnhance):
4122    """Lookahead to disallow matching with the given parse expression.
4123    ``NotAny`` does *not* advance the parsing position within the
4124    input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression
4125    does *not* match at the current position.  Also, ``NotAny`` does
4126    *not* skip over leading whitespace. ``NotAny`` always returns
4127    a null token list.  May be constructed using the '~' operator.
4128
4129    Example::
4130
4131        AND, OR, NOT = map(CaselessKeyword, "AND OR NOT".split())
4132
4133        # take care not to mistake keywords for identifiers
4134        ident = ~(AND | OR | NOT) + Word(alphas)
4135        boolean_term = Optional(NOT) + ident
4136
4137        # very crude boolean expression - to support parenthesis groups and
4138        # operation hierarchy, use infixNotation
4139        boolean_expr = boolean_term + ZeroOrMore((AND | OR) + boolean_term)
4140
4141        # integers that are followed by "." are actually floats
4142        integer = Word(nums) + ~Char(".")
4143    """
4144    def __init__( self, expr ):
4145        super(NotAny,self).__init__(expr)
4146        #~ self.leaveWhitespace()
4147        self.skipWhitespace = False  # do NOT use self.leaveWhitespace(), don't want to propagate to exprs
4148        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4149        self.errmsg = "Found unwanted token, "+_ustr(self.expr)
4150
4151    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4152        if self.expr.canParseNext(instring, loc):
4153            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
4154        return loc, []
4155
4156    def __str__( self ):
4157        if hasattr(self,"name"):
4158            return self.name
4159
4160        if self.strRepr is None:
4161            self.strRepr = "~{" + _ustr(self.expr) + "}"
4162
4163        return self.strRepr

NotAny does not advance the parsing position within the input string, it only verifies that the specified parse expression does not match at the current position. Also, NotAny does not skip over leading whitespace. NotAny always returns a null token list. May be constructed using the '~' operator.

4203class OneOrMore(_MultipleMatch):
4204    """Repetition of one or more of the given expression.
4205
4206    Parameters:
4207     - expr - expression that must match one or more times
4208     - stopOn - (default= ``None``) - expression for a terminating sentinel
4209          (only required if the sentinel would ordinarily match the repetition
4210          expression)
4211
4212    Example::
4213
4214        data_word = Word(alphas)
4215        label = data_word + FollowedBy(':')
4216        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word).setParseAction(' '.join))
4217
4218        text = "shape: SQUARE posn: upper left color: BLACK"
4219        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).pprint()  # Fail! read 'color' as data instead of next label -> [['shape', 'SQUARE color']]
4220
4221        # use stopOn attribute for OneOrMore to avoid reading label string as part of the data
4222        attr_expr = Group(label + Suppress(':') + OneOrMore(data_word, stopOn=label).setParseAction(' '.join))
4223        OneOrMore(attr_expr).parseString(text).pprint() # Better -> [['shape', 'SQUARE'], ['posn', 'upper left'], ['color', 'BLACK']]

4225        # could also be written as
4226        (attr_expr * (1,)).parseString(text).pprint()

4232

4234            self.strRepr = "{" + _ustr(self.expr) + "}..."
4235
4236        return self.strRepr

Repetition of one or more of the given expression.

Parameters:

  • expr - expression that must match one or more times
  • stopOn - (default= None) - expression for a terminating sentinel (only required if the sentinel would ordinarily match the repetition expression)

Example::

4725class OnlyOnce(object):

4734            self.called = True
4735            return results

4276class Optional(ParseElementEnhance):
4277    """Optional matching of the given expression.
