3660class Or(ParseExpression):
3661    """Requires that at least one :class:`ParseExpression` is found. If
3662    two expressions match, the expression that matches the longest
3663    string will be used. May be constructed using the ``'^'``
3664    operator.
3665
3666    Example::
3667
3668        # construct Or using '^' operator
3669
3670        number = Word(nums) ^ Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
3671        print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789"))
3672
3673    prints::
3674
3675        [['123'], ['3.1416'], ['789']]
3676    """
3677    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3678        super(Or,self).__init__(exprs, savelist)
3679        if self.exprs:
3680            self.mayReturnEmpty = any(e.mayReturnEmpty for e in self.exprs)
3681        else:
3682            self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3683
3684    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3685        maxExcLoc = -1
3686        maxException = None
3687        matches = []
3688        for e in self.exprs:
3689            try:
3690                loc2 = e.tryParse( instring, loc )
3691            except ParseException as err:
3692                err.__traceback__ = None
3693                if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3694                    maxException = err
3695                    maxExcLoc = err.loc
3696            except IndexError:
3697                if len(instring) > maxExcLoc:
3698                    maxException = ParseException(instring,len(instring),e.errmsg,self)
3699                    maxExcLoc = len(instring)
3700            else:
3701                # save match among all matches, to retry longest to shortest
3702                matches.append((loc2, e))
3703
3704        if matches:
3705            matches.sort(key=lambda x: -x[0])
3706            for _,e in matches:
3707                try:
3708                    return e._parse( instring, loc, doActions )
3709                except ParseException as err:
3710                    err.__traceback__ = None
3711                    if err.loc > maxExcLoc:
3712                        maxException = err
3713                        maxExcLoc = err.loc
3714
3715        if maxException is not None:
3716            maxException.msg = self.errmsg
3717            raise maxException
3718        else:
3719            raise ParseException(instring, loc, "no defined alternatives to match", self)
3720
3721
3722    def __ixor__(self, other ):
3723        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
3724            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
3725        return self.append( other ) #Or( [ self, other ] )
3726
3727    def __str__( self ):
3728        if hasattr(self,"name"):
3729            return self.name
3730
3731        if self.strRepr is None:
3732            self.strRepr = "{" + " ^ ".join(_ustr(e) for e in self.exprs) + "}"
3733
3734        return self.strRepr
3735
3736    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3737        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3738        for e in self.exprs:
3739            e.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )

Requires that at least one ParseExpression is found. If two expressions match, the expression that matches the longest string will be used. May be constructed using the '^' operator.

Example::

# construct Or using '^' operator

number = Word(nums) ^ Combine(Word(nums) + '.' + Word(nums))
print(number.searchString("123 3.1416 789"))

prints::

#   class ParseBaseException(builtins.Exception):
View Source 
243class ParseBaseException(Exception):
244    """base exception class for all parsing runtime exceptions"""
245    # Performance tuning: we construct a *lot* of these, so keep this
246    # constructor as small and fast as possible
247    def __init__( self, pstr, loc=0, msg=None, elem=None ):
248        self.loc = loc
249        if msg is None:
250            self.msg = pstr
251            self.pstr = ""
252        else:
253            self.msg = msg
254            self.pstr = pstr
255        self.parserElement = elem
256        self.args = (pstr, loc, msg)
257
258    @classmethod
259    def _from_exception(cls, pe):
260        """
261        internal factory method to simplify creating one type of ParseException
262        from another - avoids having __init__ signature conflicts among subclasses
263        """
264        return cls(pe.pstr, pe.loc, pe.msg, pe.parserElement)
265
266    def __getattr__( self, aname ):
267        """supported attributes by name are:
268           - lineno - returns the line number of the exception text
269           - col - returns the column number of the exception text
270           - line - returns the line containing the exception text
271        """
272        if( aname == "lineno" ):
273            return lineno( self.loc, self.pstr )
274        elif( aname in ("col", "column") ):
275            return col( self.loc, self.pstr )
276        elif( aname == "line" ):
277            return line( self.loc, self.pstr )
278        else:
279            raise AttributeError(aname)
280
281    def __str__( self ):
282        return "%s (at char %d), (line:%d, col:%d)" % \
283                ( self.msg, self.loc, self.lineno, self.column )
284    def __repr__( self ):
285        return _ustr(self)
286    def markInputline( self, markerString = ">!<" ):
287        """Extracts the exception line from the input string, and marks
288           the location of the exception with a special symbol.
289        """
290        line_str = self.line
291        line_column = self.column - 1
292        if markerString:
293            line_str = "".join((line_str[:line_column],
294                                markerString, line_str[line_column:]))
295        return line_str.strip()
296    def __dir__(self):
297        return "lineno col line".split() + dir(type(self))

3937class ParseElementEnhance(ParserElement):
3938    """Abstract subclass of :class:`ParserElement`, for combining and
3939    post-processing parsed tokens.
3940    """
3941    def __init__( self, expr, savelist=False ):
3942        super(ParseElementEnhance,self).__init__(savelist)
3943        if isinstance( expr, basestring ):
3944            if issubclass(ParserElement._literalStringClass, Token):
3945                expr = ParserElement._literalStringClass(expr)
3946            else:
3947                expr = ParserElement._literalStringClass(Literal(expr))
3948        self.expr = expr
3949        self.strRepr = None
3950        if expr is not None:
3951            self.mayIndexError = expr.mayIndexError
3952            self.mayReturnEmpty = expr.mayReturnEmpty
3953            self.setWhitespaceChars( expr.whiteChars )
3954            self.skipWhitespace = expr.skipWhitespace
3955            self.saveAsList = expr.saveAsList
3956            self.callPreparse = expr.callPreparse
3957            self.ignoreExprs.extend(expr.ignoreExprs)
3958
3959    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3960        if self.expr is not None:
3961            return self.expr._parse( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse=False )
3962        else:
3963            raise ParseException("",loc,self.errmsg,self)
3964
3965    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
3966        self.skipWhitespace = False
3967        self.expr = self.expr.copy()
3968        if self.expr is not None:
3969            self.expr.leaveWhitespace()
3970        return self
3971
3972    def ignore( self, other ):
3973        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
3974            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
3975                super( ParseElementEnhance, self).ignore( other )
3976                if self.expr is not None:
3977                    self.expr.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3978        else:
3979            super( ParseElementEnhance, self).ignore( other )
3980            if self.expr is not None:
3981                self.expr.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3982        return self
3983
3984    def streamline( self ):
3985        super(ParseElementEnhance,self).streamline()
3986        if self.expr is not None:
3987            self.expr.streamline()
3988        return self
3989
3990    def checkRecursion( self, parseElementList ):
3991        if self in parseElementList:
3992            raise RecursiveGrammarException( parseElementList+[self] )
3993        subRecCheckList = parseElementList[:] + [ self ]
3994        if self.expr is not None:
3995            self.expr.checkRecursion( subRecCheckList )
3996
3997    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
3998        tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
3999        if self.expr is not None:
4000            self.expr.validate(tmp)
4001        self.checkRecursion( [] )
4002
4003    def __str__( self ):
4004        try:
4005            return super(ParseElementEnhance,self).__str__()
4006        except Exception:
4007            pass
4008
4009        if self.strRepr is None and self.expr is not None:
4010            self.strRepr = "%s:(%s)" % ( self.__class__.__name__, _ustr(self.expr) )
4011        return self.strRepr

299class ParseException(ParseBaseException):
300    """
301    Exception thrown when parse expressions don't match class;
302    supported attributes by name are:
303    - lineno - returns the line number of the exception text
304    - col - returns the column number of the exception text
305    - line - returns the line containing the exception text
306
307    Example::
308

310            Word(nums).setName("integer").parseString("ABC")
311        except ParseException as pe:
312            print(pe)
313            print("column: {}".format(pe.col))
314

316
317       Expected integer (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
318        column: 1
319

321    pass

Exception thrown when parse expressions don't match class; supported attributes by name are:

  • lineno - returns the line number of the exception text
  • col - returns the column number of the exception text
  • line - returns the line containing the exception text

Example::

try:
    Word(nums).setName("integer").parseString("ABC")
except ParseException as pe:
    print(pe)
    print("column: {}".format(pe.col))

prints::

Expected integer (at char 0), (line:1, col:1) column: 1

3470class ParseExpression(ParserElement):
3471    """Abstract subclass of ParserElement, for combining and
3472    post-processing parsed tokens.
3473    """
3474    def __init__( self, exprs, savelist = False ):
3475        super(ParseExpression,self).__init__(savelist)
3476        if isinstance( exprs, _generatorType ):
3477            exprs = list(exprs)
3478
3479        if isinstance( exprs, basestring ):
3480            self.exprs = [ ParserElement._literalStringClass( exprs ) ]
3481        elif isinstance( exprs, Iterable ):
3482            exprs = list(exprs)
3483            # if sequence of strings provided, wrap with Literal
3484            if all(isinstance(expr, basestring) for expr in exprs):
3485                exprs = map(ParserElement._literalStringClass, exprs)
3486            self.exprs = list(exprs)
3487        else:
3488            try:
3489                self.exprs = list( exprs )
3490            except TypeError:
3491                self.exprs = [ exprs ]
3492        self.callPreparse = False
3493
3494    def __getitem__( self, i ):
3495        return self.exprs[i]
3496
3497    def append( self, other ):
3498        self.exprs.append( other )
3499        self.strRepr = None
3500        return self
3501
3502    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
3503        """Extends ``leaveWhitespace`` defined in base class, and also invokes ``leaveWhitespace`` on
3504           all contained expressions."""
3505        self.skipWhitespace = False
3506        self.exprs = [ e.copy() for e in self.exprs ]
3507        for e in self.exprs:
3508            e.leaveWhitespace()
3509        return self
3510
3511    def ignore( self, other ):
3512        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
3513            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
3514                super( ParseExpression, self).ignore( other )
3515                for e in self.exprs:
3516                    e.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3517        else:
3518            super( ParseExpression, self).ignore( other )
3519            for e in self.exprs:
3520                e.ignore( self.ignoreExprs[-1] )
3521        return self
3522
3523    def __str__( self ):
3524        try:
3525            return super(ParseExpression,self).__str__()
3526        except Exception:
3527            pass
3528
3529        if self.strRepr is None:
3530            self.strRepr = "%s:(%s)" % ( self.__class__.__name__, _ustr(self.exprs) )
3531        return self.strRepr
3532
3533    def streamline( self ):
3534        super(ParseExpression,self).streamline()
3535
3536        for e in self.exprs:
3537            e.streamline()
3538
3539        # collapse nested And's of the form And( And( And( a,b), c), d) to And( a,b,c,d )
3540        # but only if there are no parse actions or resultsNames on the nested And's
3541        # (likewise for Or's and MatchFirst's)
3542        if ( len(self.exprs) == 2 ):
3543            other = self.exprs[0]
3544            if ( isinstance( other, self.__class__ ) and
3545                  not(other.parseAction) and
3546                  other.resultsName is None and
3547                  not other.debug ):
3548                self.exprs = other.exprs[:] + [ self.exprs[1] ]
3549                self.strRepr = None
3550                self.mayReturnEmpty |= other.mayReturnEmpty
3551                self.mayIndexError  |= other.mayIndexError
3552
3553            other = self.exprs[-1]
3554            if ( isinstance( other, self.__class__ ) and
3555                  not(other.parseAction) and
3556                  other.resultsName is None and
3557                  not other.debug ):
3558                self.exprs = self.exprs[:-1] + other.exprs[:]
3559                self.strRepr = None
3560                self.mayReturnEmpty |= other.mayReturnEmpty
3561                self.mayIndexError  |= other.mayIndexError
3562
3563        self.errmsg = "Expected " + _ustr(self)
3564
3565        return self
3566
3567    def setResultsName( self, name, listAllMatches=False ):
3568        ret = super(ParseExpression,self).setResultsName(name,listAllMatches)
3569        return ret
3570
3571    def validate( self, validateTrace=[] ):
3572        tmp = validateTrace[:]+[self]
3573        for e in self.exprs:
3574            e.validate(tmp)
3575        self.checkRecursion( [] )
3576
3577    def copy(self):
3578        ret = super(ParseExpression,self).copy()
3579        ret.exprs = [e.copy() for e in self.exprs]
3580        return ret

Define name for referencing matching tokens as a nested attribute of the returned parse results. NOTE: this returns a copy of the original ParserElement object; this is so that the client can define a basic element, such as an integer, and reference it in multiple places with different names.

You can also set results names using the abbreviated syntax, expr("name") in place of expr.setResultsName("name")

  • see __call__.

Example::

date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
            + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
            + integer.setResultsName("day"))

# equivalent form:
date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")

#   def copy(self):
View Source 
3577    def copy(self):
3578        ret = super(ParseExpression,self).copy()

Make a copy of this ParserElement. Useful for defining different parse actions for the same parsing pattern, using copies of the original parse element.

Example::

integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
integerK = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024) + Suppress("K")
integerM = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

print(OneOrMore(integerK | integerM | integer).parseString("5K 100 640K 256M"))

prints::

[5120, 100, 655360, 268435456]

Equivalent form of expr.copy() is just expr()::

integerM = integer().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")

#   class ParseResults:
View Source 
 369class ParseResults(object):
 370    """Structured parse results, to provide multiple means of access to
 371    the parsed data:
 372
 373       - as a list (``len(results)``)
 374       - by list index (``results[0], results[1]``, etc.)
 375       - by attribute (``results.<resultsName>`` - see :class:`ParserElement.setResultsName`)
 376
 377    Example::
 378
 379        integer = Word(nums)
 380        date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
 381                        + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
 382                        + integer.setResultsName("day"))
 383        # equivalent form:
 384        # date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 385
 386        # parseString returns a ParseResults object
 387        result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")
 388
 389        def test(s, fn=repr):
 390            print("%s -> %s" % (s, fn(eval(s))))
 391        test("list(result)")
 392        test("result[0]")
 393        test("result['month']")
 394        test("result.day")
 395        test("'month' in result")
 396        test("'minutes' in result")
 397        test("result.dump()", str)
 398
 399    prints::
 400
 401        list(result) -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
 402        result[0] -> '1999'
 403        result['month'] -> '12'
 404        result.day -> '31'
 405        'month' in result -> True
 406        'minutes' in result -> False
 407        result.dump() -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
 408        - day: 31
 409        - month: 12
 410        - year: 1999
 411    """
 412    def __new__(cls, toklist=None, name=None, asList=True, modal=True ):
 413        if isinstance(toklist, cls):
 414            return toklist
 415        retobj = object.__new__(cls)
 416        retobj.__doinit = True
 417        return retobj
 418
 419    # Performance tuning: we construct a *lot* of these, so keep this
 420    # constructor as small and fast as possible
 421    def __init__( self, toklist=None, name=None, asList=True, modal=True, isinstance=isinstance ):
 422        if self.__doinit:
 423            self.__doinit = False
 424            self.__name = None
 425            self.__parent = None
 426            self.__accumNames = {}
 427            self.__asList = asList
 428            self.__modal = modal
 429            if toklist is None:
 430                toklist = []
 431            if isinstance(toklist, list):
 432                self.__toklist = toklist[:]
 433            elif isinstance(toklist, _generatorType):
 434                self.__toklist = list(toklist)
 435            else:
 436                self.__toklist = [toklist]
 437            self.__tokdict = dict()
 438
 439        if name is not None and name:
 440            if not modal:
 441                self.__accumNames[name] = 0
 442            if isinstance(name,int):
 443                name = _ustr(name) # will always return a str, but use _ustr for consistency
 444            self.__name = name
 445            if not (isinstance(toklist, (type(None), basestring, list)) and toklist in (None,'',[])):
 446                if isinstance(toklist,basestring):
 447                    toklist = [ toklist ]
 448                if asList:
 449                    if isinstance(toklist,ParseResults):
 450                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist.__toklist), 0)
 451                    else:
 452                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist[0]),0)
 453                    self[name].__name = name
 454                else:
 455                    try:
 456                        self[name] = toklist[0]
 457                    except (KeyError,TypeError,IndexError):
 458                        self[name] = toklist
 459
 460    def __getitem__( self, i ):
 461        if isinstance( i, (int,slice) ):
 462            return self.__toklist[i]
 463        else:
 464            if i not in self.__accumNames:
 465                return self.__tokdict[i][-1][0]
 466            else:
 467                return ParseResults([ v[0] for v in self.__tokdict[i] ])
 468
 469    def __setitem__( self, k, v, isinstance=isinstance ):
 470        if isinstance(v,_ParseResultsWithOffset):
 471            self.__tokdict[k] = self.__tokdict.get(k,list()) + [v]
 472            sub = v[0]
 473        elif isinstance(k,(int,slice)):
 474            self.__toklist[k] = v
 475            sub = v
 476        else:
 477            self.__tokdict[k] = self.__tokdict.get(k,list()) + [_ParseResultsWithOffset(v,0)]
 478            sub = v
 479        if isinstance(sub,ParseResults):
 480            sub.__parent = wkref(self)
 481
 482    def __delitem__( self, i ):
 483        if isinstance(i,(int,slice)):
 484            mylen = len( self.__toklist )
 485            del self.__toklist[i]
 486
 487            # convert int to slice
 488            if isinstance(i, int):
 489                if i < 0:
 490                    i += mylen
 491                i = slice(i, i+1)
 492            # get removed indices
 493            removed = list(range(*i.indices(mylen)))
 494            removed.reverse()
 495            # fixup indices in token dictionary
 496            for name,occurrences in self.__tokdict.items():
 497                for j in removed:
 498                    for k, (value, position) in enumerate(occurrences):
 499                        occurrences[k] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(value, position - (position > j))
 500        else:
 501            del self.__tokdict[i]
 502
 503    def __contains__( self, k ):
 504        return k in self.__tokdict
 505
 506    def __len__( self ): return len( self.__toklist )
 507    def __bool__(self): return ( not not self.__toklist )
 508    __nonzero__ = __bool__
 509    def __iter__( self ): return iter( self.__toklist )
 510    def __reversed__( self ): return iter( self.__toklist[::-1] )
 511    def _iterkeys( self ):
 512        if hasattr(self.__tokdict, "iterkeys"):
 513            return self.__tokdict.iterkeys()
 514        else:
 515            return iter(self.__tokdict)
 516
 517    def _itervalues( self ):
 518        return (self[k] for k in self._iterkeys())
 519
 520    def _iteritems( self ):
 521        return ((k, self[k]) for k in self._iterkeys())
 522
 523    if PY_3:
 524        keys = _iterkeys
 525        """Returns an iterator of all named result keys (Python 3.x only)."""
 526
 527        values = _itervalues
 528        """Returns an iterator of all named result values (Python 3.x only)."""
 529
 530        items = _iteritems
 531        """Returns an iterator of all named result key-value tuples (Python 3.x only)."""
 532
 533    else:
 534        iterkeys = _iterkeys
 535        """Returns an iterator of all named result keys (Python 2.x only)."""
 536
 537        itervalues = _itervalues
 538        """Returns an iterator of all named result values (Python 2.x only)."""
 539
 540        iteritems = _iteritems
 541        """Returns an iterator of all named result key-value tuples (Python 2.x only)."""
 542
 543        def keys( self ):
 544            """Returns all named result keys (as a list in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 545            return list(self.iterkeys())
 546
 547        def values( self ):
 548            """Returns all named result values (as a list in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 549            return list(self.itervalues())
 550
 551        def items( self ):
 552            """Returns all named result key-values (as a list of tuples in Python 2.x, as an iterator in Python 3.x)."""
 553            return list(self.iteritems())
 554
 555    def haskeys( self ):
 556        """Since keys() returns an iterator, this method is helpful in bypassing
 557           code that looks for the existence of any defined results names."""
 558        return bool(self.__tokdict)
 559
 560    def pop( self, *args, **kwargs):
 561        """
 562        Removes and returns item at specified index (default= ``last``).
 563        Supports both ``list`` and ``dict`` semantics for ``pop()``. If
 564        passed no argument or an integer argument, it will use ``list``
 565        semantics and pop tokens from the list of parsed tokens. If passed
 566        a non-integer argument (most likely a string), it will use ``dict``
 567        semantics and pop the corresponding value from any defined results
 568        names. A second default return value argument is supported, just as in
 569        ``dict.pop()``.
 570
 571        Example::
 572
 573            def remove_first(tokens):
 574                tokens.pop(0)
 575            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 576            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(remove_first).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['123', '321']
 577
 578            label = Word(alphas)
 579            patt = label("LABEL") + OneOrMore(Word(nums))
 580            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
 581
 582            # Use pop() in a parse action to remove named result (note that corresponding value is not
 583            # removed from list form of results)
 584            def remove_LABEL(tokens):
 585                tokens.pop("LABEL")
 586                return tokens
 587            patt.addParseAction(remove_LABEL)
 588            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
 589
 590        prints::
 591
 592            ['AAB', '123', '321']
 593            - LABEL: AAB
 594
 595            ['AAB', '123', '321']
 596        """
 597        if not args:
 598            args = [-1]
 599        for k,v in kwargs.items():
 600            if k == 'default':
 601                args = (args[0], v)
 602            else:
 603                raise TypeError("pop() got an unexpected keyword argument '%s'" % k)
 604        if (isinstance(args[0], int) or
 605                        len(args) == 1 or
 606                        args[0] in self):
 607            index = args[0]
 608            ret = self[index]
 609            del self[index]
 610            return ret
 611        else:
 612            defaultvalue = args[1]
 613            return defaultvalue
 614
 615    def get(self, key, defaultValue=None):
 616        """
 617        Returns named result matching the given key, or if there is no
 618        such name, then returns the given ``defaultValue`` or ``None`` if no
 619        ``defaultValue`` is specified.
 620
 621        Similar to ``dict.get()``.
 622
 623        Example::
 624
 625            integer = Word(nums)
 626            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 627
 628            result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")
 629            print(result.get("year")) # -> '1999'
 630            print(result.get("hour", "not specified")) # -> 'not specified'
 631            print(result.get("hour")) # -> None
 632        """
 633        if key in self:
 634            return self[key]
 635        else:
 636            return defaultValue
 637
 638    def insert( self, index, insStr ):
 639        """
 640        Inserts new element at location index in the list of parsed tokens.
 641
 642        Similar to ``list.insert()``.
 643
 644        Example::
 645
 646            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 647
 648            # use a parse action to insert the parse location in the front of the parsed results
 649            def insert_locn(locn, tokens):
 650                tokens.insert(0, locn)
 651            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(insert_locn).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> [0, '0', '123', '321']
 652        """
 653        self.__toklist.insert(index, insStr)
 654        # fixup indices in token dictionary
 655        for name,occurrences in self.__tokdict.items():
 656            for k, (value, position) in enumerate(occurrences):
 657                occurrences[k] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(value, position + (position > index))
 658
 659    def append( self, item ):
 660        """
 661        Add single element to end of ParseResults list of elements.
 662
 663        Example::
 664
 665            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
 666
 667            # use a parse action to compute the sum of the parsed integers, and add it to the end
 668            def append_sum(tokens):
 669                tokens.append(sum(map(int, tokens)))
 670            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(append_sum).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321', 444]
 671        """
 672        self.__toklist.append(item)
 673
 674    def extend( self, itemseq ):
 675        """
 676        Add sequence of elements to end of ParseResults list of elements.
 677
 678        Example::
 679
 680            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
 681
 682            # use a parse action to append the reverse of the matched strings, to make a palindrome
 683            def make_palindrome(tokens):
 684                tokens.extend(reversed([t[::-1] for t in tokens]))
 685                return ''.join(tokens)
 686            print(patt.addParseAction(make_palindrome).parseString("lskdj sdlkjf lksd")) # -> 'lskdjsdlkjflksddsklfjkldsjdksl'
 687        """
 688        if isinstance(itemseq, ParseResults):
 689            self += itemseq
 690        else:
 691            self.__toklist.extend(itemseq)
 692
 693    def clear( self ):
 694        """
 695        Clear all elements and results names.
 696        """
 697        del self.__toklist[:]
 698        self.__tokdict.clear()
 699
 700    def __getattr__( self, name ):
 701        try:
 702            return self[name]
 703        except KeyError:
 704            return ""
 705
 706        if name in self.__tokdict:
 707            if name not in self.__accumNames:
 708                return self.__tokdict[name][-1][0]
 709            else:
 710                return ParseResults([ v[0] for v in self.__tokdict[name] ])
 711        else:
 712            return ""
 713
 714    def __add__( self, other ):
 715        ret = self.copy()
 716        ret += other
 717        return ret
 718
 719    def __iadd__( self, other ):
 720        if other.__tokdict:
 721            offset = len(self.__toklist)
 722            addoffset = lambda a: offset if a<0 else a+offset
 723            otheritems = other.__tokdict.items()
 724            otherdictitems = [(k, _ParseResultsWithOffset(v[0],addoffset(v[1])) )
 725                                for (k,vlist) in otheritems for v in vlist]
 726            for k,v in otherdictitems:
 727                self[k] = v
 728                if isinstance(v[0],ParseResults):
 729                    v[0].__parent = wkref(self)
 730
 731        self.__toklist += other.__toklist
 732        self.__accumNames.update( other.__accumNames )
 733        return self
 734
 735    def __radd__(self, other):
 736        if isinstance(other,int) and other == 0:
 737            # useful for merging many ParseResults using sum() builtin
 738            return self.copy()
 739        else:
 740            # this may raise a TypeError - so be it
 741            return other + self
 742
 743    def __repr__( self ):
 744        return "(%s, %s)" % ( repr( self.__toklist ), repr( self.__tokdict ) )
 745
 746    def __str__( self ):
 747        return '[' + ', '.join(_ustr(i) if isinstance(i, ParseResults) else repr(i) for i in self.__toklist) + ']'
 748
 749    def _asStringList( self, sep='' ):
 750        out = []
 751        for item in self.__toklist:
 752            if out and sep:
 753                out.append(sep)
 754            if isinstance( item, ParseResults ):
 755                out += item._asStringList()
 756            else:
 757                out.append( _ustr(item) )
 758        return out
 759
 760    def asList( self ):
 761        """
 762        Returns the parse results as a nested list of matching tokens, all converted to strings.
 763
 764        Example::
 765
 766            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
 767            result = patt.parseString("sldkj lsdkj sldkj")
 768            # even though the result prints in string-like form, it is actually a pyparsing ParseResults
 769            print(type(result), result) # -> <class 'pyparsing.ParseResults'> ['sldkj', 'lsdkj', 'sldkj']
 770
 771            # Use asList() to create an actual list
 772            result_list = result.asList()
 773            print(type(result_list), result_list) # -> <class 'list'> ['sldkj', 'lsdkj', 'sldkj']
 774        """
 775        return [res.asList() if isinstance(res,ParseResults) else res for res in self.__toklist]
 776
 777    def asDict( self ):
 778        """
 779        Returns the named parse results as a nested dictionary.
 780
 781        Example::
 782
 783            integer = Word(nums)
 784            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 785
 786            result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
 787            print(type(result), repr(result)) # -> <class 'pyparsing.ParseResults'> (['12', '/', '31', '/', '1999'], {'day': [('1999', 4)], 'year': [('12', 0)], 'month': [('31', 2)]})
 788
 789            result_dict = result.asDict()
 790            print(type(result_dict), repr(result_dict)) # -> <class 'dict'> {'day': '1999', 'year': '12', 'month': '31'}
 791
 792            # even though a ParseResults supports dict-like access, sometime you just need to have a dict
 793            import json
 794            print(json.dumps(result)) # -> Exception: TypeError: ... is not JSON serializable
 795            print(json.dumps(result.asDict())) # -> {"month": "31", "day": "1999", "year": "12"}
 796        """
 797        if PY_3:
 798            item_fn = self.items
 799        else:
 800            item_fn = self.iteritems
 801
 802        def toItem(obj):
 803            if isinstance(obj, ParseResults):
 804                if obj.haskeys():
 805                    return obj.asDict()
 806                else:
 807                    return [toItem(v) for v in obj]
 808            else:
 809                return obj
 810
 811        return dict((k,toItem(v)) for k,v in item_fn())
 812
 813    def copy( self ):
 814        """
 815        Returns a new copy of a :class:`ParseResults` object.
 816        """
 817        ret = ParseResults( self.__toklist )
 818        ret.__tokdict = dict(self.__tokdict.items())
 819        ret.__parent = self.__parent
 820        ret.__accumNames.update( self.__accumNames )
 821        ret.__name = self.__name
 822        return ret
 823
 824    def asXML( self, doctag=None, namedItemsOnly=False, indent="", formatted=True ):
 825        """
 826        (Deprecated) Returns the parse results as XML. Tags are created for tokens and lists that have defined results names.
 827        """
 828        nl = "\n"
 829        out = []
 830        namedItems = dict((v[1],k) for (k,vlist) in self.__tokdict.items()
 831                                                            for v in vlist)
 832        nextLevelIndent = indent + "  "
 833
 834        # collapse out indents if formatting is not desired
 835        if not formatted:
 836            indent = ""
 837            nextLevelIndent = ""
 838            nl = ""
 839
 840        selfTag = None
 841        if doctag is not None:
 842            selfTag = doctag
 843        else:
 844            if self.__name:
 845                selfTag = self.__name
 846
 847        if not selfTag:
 848            if namedItemsOnly:
 849                return ""
 850            else:
 851                selfTag = "ITEM"
 852
 853        out += [ nl, indent, "<", selfTag, ">" ]
 854
 855        for i,res in enumerate(self.__toklist):
 856            if isinstance(res,ParseResults):
 857                if i in namedItems:
 858                    out += [ res.asXML(namedItems[i],
 859                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
 860                                        nextLevelIndent,
 861                                        formatted)]
 862                else:
 863                    out += [ res.asXML(None,
 864                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
 865                                        nextLevelIndent,
 866                                        formatted)]
 867            else:
 868                # individual token, see if there is a name for it
 869                resTag = None
 870                if i in namedItems:
 871                    resTag = namedItems[i]
 872                if not resTag:
 873                    if namedItemsOnly:
 874                        continue
 875                    else:
 876                        resTag = "ITEM"
 877                xmlBodyText = _xml_escape(_ustr(res))
 878                out += [ nl, nextLevelIndent, "<", resTag, ">",
 879                                                xmlBodyText,
 880                                                "</", resTag, ">" ]
 881
 882        out += [ nl, indent, "</", selfTag, ">" ]
 883        return "".join(out)
 884
 885    def __lookup(self,sub):
 886        for k,vlist in self.__tokdict.items():
 887            for v,loc in vlist:
 888                if sub is v:
 889                    return k
 890        return None
 891
 892    def getName(self):
 893        r"""
 894        Returns the results name for this token expression. Useful when several
 895        different expressions might match at a particular location.
 896
 897        Example::
 898
 899            integer = Word(nums)
 900            ssn_expr = Regex(r"\d\d\d-\d\d-\d\d\d\d")
 901            house_number_expr = Suppress('#') + Word(nums, alphanums)
 902            user_data = (Group(house_number_expr)("house_number")
 903                        | Group(ssn_expr)("ssn")
 904                        | Group(integer)("age"))
 905            user_info = OneOrMore(user_data)
 906
 907            result = user_info.parseString("22 111-22-3333 #221B")
 908            for item in result:
 909                print(item.getName(), ':', item[0])
 910
 911        prints::
 912
 913            age : 22
 914            ssn : 111-22-3333
 915            house_number : 221B
 916        """
 917        if self.__name:
 918            return self.__name
 919        elif self.__parent:
 920            par = self.__parent()
 921            if par:
 922                return par.__lookup(self)
 923            else:
 924                return None
 925        elif (len(self) == 1 and
 926               len(self.__tokdict) == 1 and
 927               next(iter(self.__tokdict.values()))[0][1] in (0,-1)):
 928            return next(iter(self.__tokdict.keys()))
 929        else:
 930            return None
 931
 932    def dump(self, indent='', depth=0, full=True):
 933        """
 934        Diagnostic method for listing out the contents of
 935        a :class:`ParseResults`. Accepts an optional ``indent`` argument so
 936        that this string can be embedded in a nested display of other data.
 937
 938        Example::
 939
 940            integer = Word(nums)
 941            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
 942
 943            result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
 944            print(result.dump())
 945
 946        prints::
 947
 948            ['12', '/', '31', '/', '1999']
 949            - day: 1999
 950            - month: 31
 951            - year: 12
 952        """
 953        out = []
 954        NL = '\n'
 955        out.append( indent+_ustr(self.asList()) )
 956        if full:
 957            if self.haskeys():
 958                items = sorted((str(k), v) for k,v in self.items())
 959                for k,v in items:
 960                    if out:
 961                        out.append(NL)
 962                    out.append( "%s%s- %s: " % (indent,('  '*depth), k) )
 963                    if isinstance(v,ParseResults):
 964                        if v:
 965                            out.append( v.dump(indent,depth+1) )
 966                        else:
 967                            out.append(_ustr(v))
 968                    else:
 969                        out.append(repr(v))
 970            elif any(isinstance(vv,ParseResults) for vv in self):
 971                v = self
 972                for i,vv in enumerate(v):
 973                    if isinstance(vv,ParseResults):
 974                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),vv.dump(indent,depth+1) ))
 975                    else:
 976                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),_ustr(vv)))
 977
 978        return "".join(out)
 979
 980    def pprint(self, *args, **kwargs):
 981        """
 982        Pretty-printer for parsed results as a list, using the
 983        `pprint <http://docs.python.org/3/library/pprint.html>`_ module.
 984        Accepts additional positional or keyword args as defined for
 985        `pprint.pprint <http://docs.python.org/3/library/pprint.html#pprint.pprint>`_ .
 986
 987        Example::
 988
 989            ident = Word(alphas, alphanums)
 990            num = Word(nums)
 991            func = Forward()
 992            term = ident | num | Group('(' + func + ')')
 993            func <<= ident + Group(Optional(delimitedList(term)))
 994            result = func.parseString("fna a,b,(fnb c,d,200),100")
 995            result.pprint(width=40)
 996
 997        prints::
 998
 999            ['fna',
1000             ['a',
1001              'b',
1002              ['(', 'fnb', ['c', 'd', '200'], ')'],
1003              '100']]
1004        """
1005        pprint.pprint(self.asList(), *args, **kwargs)

1007    # add support for pickle protocol
1008    def __getstate__(self):
1009        return ( self.__toklist,
1010                 ( self.__tokdict.copy(),
1011                   self.__parent is not None and self.__parent() or None,
1012                   self.__accumNames,
1013                   self.__name ) )
1014
1015    def __setstate__(self,state):
1016        self.__toklist = state[0]
1017        (self.__tokdict,
1018         par,
1019         inAccumNames,
1020         self.__name) = state[1]
1021        self.__accumNames = {}
1022        self.__accumNames.update(inAccumNames)
1023        if par is not None:
1024            self.__parent = wkref(par)
1025        else:
1026            self.__parent = None
1027
1028    def __getnewargs__(self):
1029        return self.__toklist, self.__name, self.__asList, self.__modal

1031    def __dir__(self):
1032        return (dir(type(self)) + list(self.keys()))

Structured parse results, to provide multiple means of access to the parsed data:

  • as a list (len(results))
  • by list index (results[0], results[1], etc.)
  • by attribute (results.<resultsName> - see ParserElement.setResultsName)

Example::

integer = Word(nums)
date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
                + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
                + integer.setResultsName("day"))
# equivalent form:
# date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")

# parseString returns a ParseResults object
result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")

def test(s, fn=repr):
    print("%s -> %s" % (s, fn(eval(s))))
test("list(result)")
test("result[0]")
test("result['month']")
test("result.day")
test("'month' in result")
test("'minutes' in result")
test("result.dump()", str)

prints::

list(result) -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
result[0] -> '1999'
result['month'] -> '12'
result.day -> '31'
'month' in result -> True
'minutes' in result -> False
result.dump() -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
- day: 31
- month: 12
- year: 1999

421    def __init__( self, toklist=None, name=None, asList=True, modal=True, isinstance=isinstance ):
422        if self.__doinit:
423            self.__doinit = False
424            self.__name = None
425            self.__parent = None
426            self.__accumNames = {}
427            self.__asList = asList
428            self.__modal = modal
429            if toklist is None:
430                toklist = []
431            if isinstance(toklist, list):
432                self.__toklist = toklist[:]
433            elif isinstance(toklist, _generatorType):
434                self.__toklist = list(toklist)
435            else:
436                self.__toklist = [toklist]
437            self.__tokdict = dict()
438
439        if name is not None and name:
440            if not modal:
441                self.__accumNames[name] = 0
442            if isinstance(name,int):
443                name = _ustr(name) # will always return a str, but use _ustr for consistency
444            self.__name = name
445            if not (isinstance(toklist, (type(None), basestring, list)) and toklist in (None,'',[])):
446                if isinstance(toklist,basestring):
447                    toklist = [ toklist ]
448                if asList:
449                    if isinstance(toklist,ParseResults):
450                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist.__toklist), 0)
451                    else:
452                        self[name] = _ParseResultsWithOffset(ParseResults(toklist[0]),0)
453                    self[name].__name = name
454                else:
455                    try:
456                        self[name] = toklist[0]
457                    except (KeyError,TypeError,IndexError):
458                        self[name] = toklist

560    def pop( self, *args, **kwargs):
561        """
562        Removes and returns item at specified index (default= ``last``).
563        Supports both ``list`` and ``dict`` semantics for ``pop()``. If
564        passed no argument or an integer argument, it will use ``list``
565        semantics and pop tokens from the list of parsed tokens. If passed
566        a non-integer argument (most likely a string), it will use ``dict``
567        semantics and pop the corresponding value from any defined results
568        names. A second default return value argument is supported, just as in
569        ``dict.pop()``.
570
571        Example::
572
573            def remove_first(tokens):
574                tokens.pop(0)
575            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
576            print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(remove_first).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['123', '321']
577
578            label = Word(alphas)
579            patt = label("LABEL") + OneOrMore(Word(nums))
580            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
581
582            # Use pop() in a parse action to remove named result (note that corresponding value is not
583            # removed from list form of results)
584            def remove_LABEL(tokens):
585                tokens.pop("LABEL")
586                return tokens
587            patt.addParseAction(remove_LABEL)
588            print(patt.parseString("AAB 123 321").dump())
589
590        prints::
591
592            ['AAB', '123', '321']
593            - LABEL: AAB
594
595            ['AAB', '123', '321']
596        """
597        if not args:
598            args = [-1]
599        for k,v in kwargs.items():
600            if k == 'default':
601                args = (args[0], v)
602            else:
603                raise TypeError("pop() got an unexpected keyword argument '%s'" % k)
604        if (isinstance(args[0], int) or
605                        len(args) == 1 or
606                        args[0] in self):
607            index = args[0]
608            ret = self[index]
609            del self[index]
610            return ret
611        else:
612            defaultvalue = args[1]
613            return defaultvalue

Removes and returns item at specified index (default= last). Supports both list and dict semantics for pop(). If passed no argument or an integer argument, it will use list semantics and pop tokens from the list of parsed tokens. If passed a non-integer argument (most likely a string), it will use dict semantics and pop the corresponding value from any defined results names. A second default return value argument is supported, just as in dict.pop().

Example::

    tokens.pop(0)
print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['0', '123', '321']
print(OneOrMore(Word(nums)).addParseAction(remove_first).parseString("0 123 321")) # -> ['123', '321']

615    def get(self, key, defaultValue=None):
616        """
617        Returns named result matching the given key, or if there is no

619        ``defaultValue`` is specified.

622

629            print(result.get("year")) # -> '1999'
630            print(result.get("hour", "not specified")) # -> 'not specified'
631            print(result.get("hour")) # -> None
632        """
633        if key in self:
634            return self[key]
635        else:
636            return defaultValue

777    def asDict( self ):
778        """
779        Returns the named parse results as a nested dictionary.
780
781        Example::
782
783            integer = Word(nums)
784            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")

788
789            result_dict = result.asDict()
790            print(type(result_dict), repr(result_dict)) # -> <class 'dict'> {'day': '1999', 'year': '12', 'month': '31'}
791
792            # even though a ParseResults supports dict-like access, sometime you just need to have a dict
793            import json
794            print(json.dumps(result)) # -> Exception: TypeError: ... is not JSON serializable
795            print(json.dumps(result.asDict())) # -> {"month": "31", "day": "1999", "year": "12"}
796        """
797        if PY_3:
798            item_fn = self.items
799        else:
800            item_fn = self.iteritems
801
802        def toItem(obj):
803            if isinstance(obj, ParseResults):
804                if obj.haskeys():
805                    return obj.asDict()
806                else:
807                    return [toItem(v) for v in obj]
808            else:
809                return obj
810
811        return dict((k,toItem(v)) for k,v in item_fn())

#   def asXML(self, doctag=None, namedItemsOnly=False, indent='', formatted=True):

824    def asXML( self, doctag=None, namedItemsOnly=False, indent="", formatted=True ):
825        """
826        (Deprecated) Returns the parse results as XML. Tags are created for tokens and lists that have defined results names.
827        """
828        nl = "\n"
829        out = []
830        namedItems = dict((v[1],k) for (k,vlist) in self.__tokdict.items()
831                                                            for v in vlist)
832        nextLevelIndent = indent + "  "
833
834        # collapse out indents if formatting is not desired
835        if not formatted:
836            indent = ""
837            nextLevelIndent = ""
838            nl = ""
839
840        selfTag = None
841        if doctag is not None:
842            selfTag = doctag
843        else:
844            if self.__name:
845                selfTag = self.__name
846
847        if not selfTag:
848            if namedItemsOnly:
849                return ""
850            else:
851                selfTag = "ITEM"
852
853        out += [ nl, indent, "<", selfTag, ">" ]
854
855        for i,res in enumerate(self.__toklist):
856            if isinstance(res,ParseResults):
857                if i in namedItems:
858                    out += [ res.asXML(namedItems[i],
859                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
860                                        nextLevelIndent,
861                                        formatted)]
862                else:
863                    out += [ res.asXML(None,
864                                        namedItemsOnly and doctag is None,
865                                        nextLevelIndent,
866                                        formatted)]
867            else:
868                # individual token, see if there is a name for it
869                resTag = None
870                if i in namedItems:
871                    resTag = namedItems[i]
872                if not resTag:
873                    if namedItemsOnly:
874                        continue
875                    else:
876                        resTag = "ITEM"
877                xmlBodyText = _xml_escape(_ustr(res))
878                out += [ nl, nextLevelIndent, "<", resTag, ">",
879                                                xmlBodyText,
880                                                "</", resTag, ">" ]
881
882        out += [ nl, indent, "</", selfTag, ">" ]
883        return "".join(out)

(Deprecated) Returns the parse results as XML. Tags are created for tokens and lists that have defined results names.

892    def getName(self):
893        r"""
894        Returns the results name for this token expression. Useful when several
895        different expressions might match at a particular location.
896
897        Example::
898
899            integer = Word(nums)
900            ssn_expr = Regex(r"\d\d\d-\d\d-\d\d\d\d")
901            house_number_expr = Suppress('#') + Word(nums, alphanums)
902            user_data = (Group(house_number_expr)("house_number")
903                        | Group(ssn_expr)("ssn")
904                        | Group(integer)("age"))
905            user_info = OneOrMore(user_data)
906
907            result = user_info.parseString("22 111-22-3333 #221B")
908            for item in result:
909                print(item.getName(), ':', item[0])
910
911        prints::
912
913            age : 22
914            ssn : 111-22-3333
915            house_number : 221B
916        """
917        if self.__name:
918            return self.__name
919        elif self.__parent:
920            par = self.__parent()
921            if par:
922                return par.__lookup(self)
923            else:
924                return None
925        elif (len(self) == 1 and
926               len(self.__tokdict) == 1 and
927               next(iter(self.__tokdict.values()))[0][1] in (0,-1)):
928            return next(iter(self.__tokdict.keys()))
929        else:
930            return None

#   def dump(self, indent='', depth=0, full=True):
View Source 
932    def dump(self, indent='', depth=0, full=True):
933        """
934        Diagnostic method for listing out the contents of
935        a :class:`ParseResults`. Accepts an optional ``indent`` argument so
936        that this string can be embedded in a nested display of other data.
937
938        Example::
939
940            integer = Word(nums)
941            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
942
943            result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
944            print(result.dump())
945
946        prints::
947
948            ['12', '/', '31', '/', '1999']
949            - day: 1999
950            - month: 31
951            - year: 12
952        """
953        out = []
954        NL = '\n'
955        out.append( indent+_ustr(self.asList()) )
956        if full:
957            if self.haskeys():
958                items = sorted((str(k), v) for k,v in self.items())
959                for k,v in items:
960                    if out:
961                        out.append(NL)
962                    out.append( "%s%s- %s: " % (indent,('  '*depth), k) )
963                    if isinstance(v,ParseResults):
964                        if v:
965                            out.append( v.dump(indent,depth+1) )
966                        else:
967                            out.append(_ustr(v))
968                    else:
969                        out.append(repr(v))
970            elif any(isinstance(vv,ParseResults) for vv in self):
971                v = self
972                for i,vv in enumerate(v):
973                    if isinstance(vv,ParseResults):
974                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),vv.dump(indent,depth+1) ))
975                    else:
976                        out.append("\n%s%s[%d]:\n%s%s%s" % (indent,('  '*(depth)),i,indent,('  '*(depth+1)),_ustr(vv)))
977
978        return "".join(out)

Diagnostic method for listing out the contents of a ParseResults. Accepts an optional indent argument so that this string can be embedded in a nested display of other data.

Example::

integer = Word(nums)
date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")

result = date_str.parseString('12/31/1999')
print(result.dump())

- year: 12

1183
1184            # default whitespace chars are space, <TAB> and newline
1185            OneOrMore(Word(alphas)).parseString("abc def\nghi jkl")  # -> ['abc', 'def', 'ghi', 'jkl']
1186
1187            # change to just treat newline as significant
1188            ParserElement.setDefaultWhitespaceChars(" \t")
1189            OneOrMore(Word(alphas)).parseString("abc def\nghi jkl")  # -> ['abc', 'def']
1190        """
1191        ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS = chars
1192
1193    @staticmethod
1194    def inlineLiteralsUsing(cls):
1195        """
1196        Set class to be used for inclusion of string literals into a parser.
1197
1198        Example::
1199
1200            # default literal class used is Literal
1201            integer = Word(nums)
1202            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1203
1204            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
1205
1206
1207            # change to Suppress
1208            ParserElement.inlineLiteralsUsing(Suppress)
1209            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1210
1211            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '12', '31']
1212        """
1213        ParserElement._literalStringClass = cls
1214
1215    def __init__( self, savelist=False ):
1216        self.parseAction = list()
1217        self.failAction = None
1218        #~ self.name = "<unknown>"  # don't define self.name, let subclasses try/except upcall
1219        self.strRepr = None
1220        self.resultsName = None
1221        self.saveAsList = savelist
1222        self.skipWhitespace = True
1223        self.whiteChars = ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
1224        self.copyDefaultWhiteChars = True
1225        self.mayReturnEmpty = False # used when checking for left-recursion
1226        self.keepTabs = False
1227        self.ignoreExprs = list()
1228        self.debug = False
1229        self.streamlined = False
1230        self.mayIndexError = True # used to optimize exception handling for subclasses that don't advance parse index
1231        self.errmsg = ""
1232        self.modalResults = True # used to mark results names as modal (report only last) or cumulative (list all)
1233        self.debugActions = ( None, None, None ) #custom debug actions
1234        self.re = None
1235        self.callPreparse = True # used to avoid redundant calls to preParse
1236        self.callDuringTry = False
1237
1238    def copy( self ):
1239        """
1240        Make a copy of this :class:`ParserElement`.  Useful for defining
1241        different parse actions for the same parsing pattern, using copies of
1242        the original parse element.
1243
1244        Example::
1245
1246            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1247            integerK = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024) + Suppress("K")
1248            integerM = integer.copy().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")
1249
1250            print(OneOrMore(integerK | integerM | integer).parseString("5K 100 640K 256M"))
1251
1252        prints::
1253
1254            [5120, 100, 655360, 268435456]
1255
1256        Equivalent form of ``expr.copy()`` is just ``expr()``::
1257
1258            integerM = integer().addParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0]*1024*1024) + Suppress("M")
1259        """
1260        cpy = copy.copy( self )
1261        cpy.parseAction = self.parseAction[:]
1262        cpy.ignoreExprs = self.ignoreExprs[:]
1263        if self.copyDefaultWhiteChars:
1264            cpy.whiteChars = ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
1265        return cpy
1266
1267    def setName( self, name ):
1268        """
1269        Define name for this expression, makes debugging and exception messages clearer.
1270
1271        Example::
1272
1273            Word(nums).parseString("ABC")  # -> Exception: Expected W:(0123...) (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1274            Word(nums).setName("integer").parseString("ABC")  # -> Exception: Expected integer (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1275        """
1276        self.name = name
1277        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
1278        if hasattr(self,"exception"):
1279            self.exception.msg = self.errmsg
1280        return self
1281
1282    def setResultsName( self, name, listAllMatches=False ):
1283        """
1284        Define name for referencing matching tokens as a nested attribute
1285        of the returned parse results.
1286        NOTE: this returns a *copy* of the original :class:`ParserElement` object;
1287        this is so that the client can define a basic element, such as an
1288        integer, and reference it in multiple places with different names.
1289
1290        You can also set results names using the abbreviated syntax,
1291        ``expr("name")`` in place of ``expr.setResultsName("name")``
1292        - see :class:`__call__`.
1293
1294        Example::
1295
1296            date_str = (integer.setResultsName("year") + '/'
1297                        + integer.setResultsName("month") + '/'
1298                        + integer.setResultsName("day"))
1299
1300            # equivalent form:
1301            date_str = integer("year") + '/' + integer("month") + '/' + integer("day")
1302        """
1303        newself = self.copy()
1304        if name.endswith("*"):
1305            name = name[:-1]
1306            listAllMatches=True
1307        newself.resultsName = name
1308        newself.modalResults = not listAllMatches
1309        return newself
1310
1311    def setBreak(self,breakFlag = True):
1312        """Method to invoke the Python pdb debugger when this element is
1313           about to be parsed. Set ``breakFlag`` to True to enable, False to
1314           disable.
1315        """
1316        if breakFlag:
1317            _parseMethod = self._parse
1318            def breaker(instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True):
1319                import pdb
1320                pdb.set_trace()
1321                return _parseMethod( instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse )
1322            breaker._originalParseMethod = _parseMethod
1323            self._parse = breaker
1324        else:
1325            if hasattr(self._parse,"_originalParseMethod"):
1326                self._parse = self._parse._originalParseMethod
1327        return self
1328
1329    def setParseAction( self, *fns, **kwargs ):
1330        """
1331        Define one or more actions to perform when successfully matching parse element definition.
1332        Parse action fn is a callable method with 0-3 arguments, called as ``fn(s,loc,toks)`` ,
1333        ``fn(loc,toks)`` , ``fn(toks)`` , or just ``fn()`` , where:
1334
1335        - s   = the original string being parsed (see note below)
1336        - loc = the location of the matching substring
1337        - toks = a list of the matched tokens, packaged as a :class:`ParseResults` object
1338
1339        If the functions in fns modify the tokens, they can return them as the return
1340        value from fn, and the modified list of tokens will replace the original.
1341        Otherwise, fn does not need to return any value.
1342
1343        Optional keyword arguments:
1344        - callDuringTry = (default= ``False`` ) indicate if parse action should be run during lookaheads and alternate testing
1345
1346        Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1347        before starting the parsing process.  See :class:`parseString for more
1348        information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and suggested
1349        methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse
1350        location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1351
1352        Example::
1353
1354            integer = Word(nums)
1355            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1356
1357            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
1358
1359            # use parse action to convert to ints at parse time
1360            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1361            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1362
1363            # note that integer fields are now ints, not strings
1364            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> [1999, '/', 12, '/', 31]
1365        """
1366        self.parseAction = list(map(_trim_arity, list(fns)))
1367        self.callDuringTry = kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1368        return self
1369
1370    def addParseAction( self, *fns, **kwargs ):
1371        """
1372        Add one or more parse actions to expression's list of parse actions. See :class:`setParseAction`.
1373
1374        See examples in :class:`copy`.
1375        """
1376        self.parseAction += list(map(_trim_arity, list(fns)))
1377        self.callDuringTry = self.callDuringTry or kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1378        return self
1379
1380    def addCondition(self, *fns, **kwargs):
1381        """Add a boolean predicate function to expression's list of parse actions. See
1382        :class:`setParseAction` for function call signatures. Unlike ``setParseAction``,
1383        functions passed to ``addCondition`` need to return boolean success/fail of the condition.
1384
1385        Optional keyword arguments:
1386        - message = define a custom message to be used in the raised exception
1387        - fatal   = if True, will raise ParseFatalException to stop parsing immediately; otherwise will raise ParseException
1388
1389        Example::
1390
1391            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1392            year_int = integer.copy()
1393            year_int.addCondition(lambda toks: toks[0] >= 2000, message="Only support years 2000 and later")
1394            date_str = year_int + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1395
1396            result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> Exception: Only support years 2000 and later (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1397        """
1398        msg = kwargs.get("message", "failed user-defined condition")
1399        exc_type = ParseFatalException if kwargs.get("fatal", False) else ParseException
1400        for fn in fns:
1401            def pa(s,l,t):
1402                if not bool(_trim_arity(fn)(s,l,t)):
1403                    raise exc_type(s,l,msg)
1404            self.parseAction.append(pa)
1405        self.callDuringTry = self.callDuringTry or kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1406        return self
1407
1408    def setFailAction( self, fn ):
1409        """Define action to perform if parsing fails at this expression.
1410           Fail acton fn is a callable function that takes the arguments
1411           ``fn(s,loc,expr,err)`` where:
1412           - s = string being parsed
1413           - loc = location where expression match was attempted and failed
1414           - expr = the parse expression that failed
1415           - err = the exception thrown
1416           The function returns no value.  It may throw :class:`ParseFatalException`
1417           if it is desired to stop parsing immediately."""
1418        self.failAction = fn
1419        return self
1420
1421    def _skipIgnorables( self, instring, loc ):
1422        exprsFound = True
1423        while exprsFound:
1424            exprsFound = False
1425            for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1426                try:
1427                    while 1:
1428                        loc,dummy = e._parse( instring, loc )
1429                        exprsFound = True
1430                except ParseException:
1431                    pass
1432        return loc
1433
1434    def preParse( self, instring, loc ):
1435        if self.ignoreExprs:
1436            loc = self._skipIgnorables( instring, loc )
1437
1438        if self.skipWhitespace:
1439            wt = self.whiteChars
1440            instrlen = len(instring)
1441            while loc < instrlen and instring[loc] in wt:
1442                loc += 1
1443
1444        return loc
1445
1446    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
1447        return loc, []
1448
1449    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
1450        return tokenlist
1451
1452    #~ @profile
1453    def _parseNoCache( self, instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True ):
1454        debugging = ( self.debug ) #and doActions )
1455
1456        if debugging or self.failAction:
1457            #~ print ("Match",self,"at loc",loc,"(%d,%d)" % ( lineno(loc,instring), col(loc,instring) ))
1458            if (self.debugActions[0] ):
1459                self.debugActions[0]( instring, loc, self )
1460            if callPreParse and self.callPreparse:
1461                preloc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1462            else:
1463                preloc = loc
1464            tokensStart = preloc
1465            try:
1466                try:
1467                    loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1468                except IndexError:
1469                    raise ParseException( instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self )
1470            except ParseBaseException as err:
1471                #~ print ("Exception raised:", err)
1472                if self.debugActions[2]:
1473                    self.debugActions[2]( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1474                if self.failAction:
1475                    self.failAction( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1476                raise
1477        else:
1478            if callPreParse and self.callPreparse:
1479                preloc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1480            else:
1481                preloc = loc
1482            tokensStart = preloc
1483            if self.mayIndexError or preloc >= len(instring):
1484                try:
1485                    loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1486                except IndexError:
1487                    raise ParseException( instring, len(instring), self.errmsg, self )
1488            else:
1489                loc,tokens = self.parseImpl( instring, preloc, doActions )
1490
1491        tokens = self.postParse( instring, loc, tokens )
1492
1493        retTokens = ParseResults( tokens, self.resultsName, asList=self.saveAsList, modal=self.modalResults )
1494        if self.parseAction and (doActions or self.callDuringTry):
1495            if debugging:
1496                try:
1497                    for fn in self.parseAction:
1498                        try:
1499                            tokens = fn( instring, tokensStart, retTokens )
1500                        except IndexError as parse_action_exc:
1501                            exc = ParseException("exception raised in parse action")
1502                            exc.__cause__ = parse_action_exc
1503                            raise exc
1504
1505                        if tokens is not None and tokens is not retTokens:
1506                            retTokens = ParseResults( tokens,
1507                                                      self.resultsName,
1508                                                      asList=self.saveAsList and isinstance(tokens,(ParseResults,list)),
1509                                                      modal=self.modalResults )
1510                except ParseBaseException as err:
1511                    #~ print "Exception raised in user parse action:", err
1512                    if (self.debugActions[2] ):
1513                        self.debugActions[2]( instring, tokensStart, self, err )
1514                    raise
1515            else:
1516                for fn in self.parseAction:
1517                    try:
1518                        tokens = fn( instring, tokensStart, retTokens )
1519                    except IndexError as parse_action_exc:
1520                        exc = ParseException("exception raised in parse action")
1521                        exc.__cause__ = parse_action_exc
1522                        raise exc
1523
1524                    if tokens is not None and tokens is not retTokens:
1525                        retTokens = ParseResults( tokens,
1526                                                  self.resultsName,
1527                                                  asList=self.saveAsList and isinstance(tokens,(ParseResults,list)),
1528                                                  modal=self.modalResults )
1529        if debugging:
1530            #~ print ("Matched",self,"->",retTokens.asList())
1531            if (self.debugActions[1] ):
1532                self.debugActions[1]( instring, tokensStart, loc, self, retTokens )
1533
1534        return loc, retTokens
1535
1536    def tryParse( self, instring, loc ):
1537        try:
1538            return self._parse( instring, loc, doActions=False )[0]
1539        except ParseFatalException:
1540            raise ParseException( instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
1541
1542    def canParseNext(self, instring, loc):
1543        try:
1544            self.tryParse(instring, loc)
1545        except (ParseException, IndexError):
1546            return False
1547        else:
1548            return True
