1550    class _UnboundedCache(object):
1551        def __init__(self):
1552            cache = {}
1553            self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1554
1555            def get(self, key):
1556                return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1557
1558            def set(self, key, value):
1559                cache[key] = value
1560
1561            def clear(self):
1562                cache.clear()
1563
1564            def cache_len(self):
1565                return len(cache)
1566
1567            self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1568            self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1569            self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1570            self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1571
1572    if _OrderedDict is not None:
1573        class _FifoCache(object):
1574            def __init__(self, size):
1575                self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1576
1577                cache = _OrderedDict()
1578
1579                def get(self, key):
1580                    return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1581
1582                def set(self, key, value):
1583                    cache[key] = value
1584                    while len(cache) > size:
1585                        try:
1586                            cache.popitem(False)
1587                        except KeyError:
1588                            pass
1589
1590                def clear(self):
1591                    cache.clear()
1592
1593                def cache_len(self):
1594                    return len(cache)
1595
1596                self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1597                self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1598                self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1599                self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1600
1601    else:
1602        class _FifoCache(object):
1603            def __init__(self, size):
1604                self.not_in_cache = not_in_cache = object()
1605
1606                cache = {}
1607                key_fifo = collections.deque([], size)
1608
1609                def get(self, key):
1610                    return cache.get(key, not_in_cache)
1611
1612                def set(self, key, value):
1613                    cache[key] = value
1614                    while len(key_fifo) > size:
1615                        cache.pop(key_fifo.popleft(), None)
1616                    key_fifo.append(key)
1617
1618                def clear(self):
1619                    cache.clear()
1620                    key_fifo.clear()
1621
1622                def cache_len(self):
1623                    return len(cache)
1624
1625                self.get = types.MethodType(get, self)
1626                self.set = types.MethodType(set, self)
1627                self.clear = types.MethodType(clear, self)
1628                self.__len__ = types.MethodType(cache_len, self)
1629
1630    # argument cache for optimizing repeated calls when backtracking through recursive expressions
1631    packrat_cache = {} # this is set later by enabledPackrat(); this is here so that resetCache() doesn't fail
1632    packrat_cache_lock = RLock()
1633    packrat_cache_stats = [0, 0]
1634
1635    # this method gets repeatedly called during backtracking with the same arguments -
1636    # we can cache these arguments and save ourselves the trouble of re-parsing the contained expression
1637    def _parseCache( self, instring, loc, doActions=True, callPreParse=True ):
1638        HIT, MISS = 0, 1
1639        lookup = (self, instring, loc, callPreParse, doActions)
1640        with ParserElement.packrat_cache_lock:
1641            cache = ParserElement.packrat_cache
1642            value = cache.get(lookup)
1643            if value is cache.not_in_cache:
1644                ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[MISS] += 1
1645                try:
1646                    value = self._parseNoCache(instring, loc, doActions, callPreParse)
1647                except ParseBaseException as pe:
1648                    # cache a copy of the exception, without the traceback
1649                    cache.set(lookup, pe.__class__(*pe.args))
1650                    raise
1651                else:
1652                    cache.set(lookup, (value[0], value[1].copy()))
1653                    return value
1654            else:
1655                ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[HIT] += 1
1656                if isinstance(value, Exception):
1657                    raise value
1658                return (value[0], value[1].copy())
1659
1660    _parse = _parseNoCache
1661
1662    @staticmethod
1663    def resetCache():
1664        ParserElement.packrat_cache.clear()
1665        ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats[:] = [0] * len(ParserElement.packrat_cache_stats)
1666
1667    _packratEnabled = False
1668    @staticmethod
1669    def enablePackrat(cache_size_limit=128):
1670        """Enables "packrat" parsing, which adds memoizing to the parsing logic.
1671           Repeated parse attempts at the same string location (which happens
1672           often in many complex grammars) can immediately return a cached value,
1673           instead of re-executing parsing/validating code.  Memoizing is done of
1674           both valid results and parsing exceptions.
1675
1676           Parameters:
1677
1678           - cache_size_limit - (default= ``128``) - if an integer value is provided
1679             will limit the size of the packrat cache; if None is passed, then
1680             the cache size will be unbounded; if 0 is passed, the cache will
1681             be effectively disabled.
1682
1683           This speedup may break existing programs that use parse actions that
1684           have side-effects.  For this reason, packrat parsing is disabled when
1685           you first import pyparsing.  To activate the packrat feature, your
1686           program must call the class method :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat`.  If
1687           your program uses ``psyco`` to "compile as you go", you must call
1688           ``enablePackrat`` before calling ``psyco.full()``.  If you do not do this,
1689           Python will crash.  For best results, call ``enablePackrat()`` immediately
1690           after importing pyparsing.
1691
1692           Example::
1693
1694               import pyparsing
1695               pyparsing.ParserElement.enablePackrat()
1696        """
1697        if not ParserElement._packratEnabled:
1698            ParserElement._packratEnabled = True
1699            if cache_size_limit is None:
1700                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._UnboundedCache()
1701            else:
1702                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._FifoCache(cache_size_limit)
1703            ParserElement._parse = ParserElement._parseCache
1704
1705    def parseString( self, instring, parseAll=False ):
1706        """
1707        Execute the parse expression with the given string.
1708        This is the main interface to the client code, once the complete
1709        expression has been built.
1710
1711        If you want the grammar to require that the entire input string be
1712        successfully parsed, then set ``parseAll`` to True (equivalent to ending
1713        the grammar with ``StringEnd()``).
1714
1715        Note: ``parseString`` implicitly calls ``expandtabs()`` on the input string,
1716        in order to report proper column numbers in parse actions.
1717        If the input string contains tabs and
1718        the grammar uses parse actions that use the ``loc`` argument to index into the
1719        string being parsed, you can ensure you have a consistent view of the input
1720        string by:
1721
1722        - calling ``parseWithTabs`` on your grammar before calling ``parseString``
1723          (see :class:`parseWithTabs`)
1724        - define your parse action using the full ``(s,loc,toks)`` signature, and
1725          reference the input string using the parse action's ``s`` argument
1726        - explictly expand the tabs in your input string before calling
1727          ``parseString``
1728
1729        Example::
1730
1731            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa')  # -> ['aaaaa']
1732            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa', parseAll=True)  # -> Exception: Expected end of text
1733        """
1734        ParserElement.resetCache()
1735        if not self.streamlined:
1736            self.streamline()
1737            #~ self.saveAsList = True
1738        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1739            e.streamline()
1740        if not self.keepTabs:
1741            instring = instring.expandtabs()
1742        try:
1743            loc, tokens = self._parse( instring, 0 )
1744            if parseAll:
1745                loc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1746                se = Empty() + StringEnd()
1747                se._parse( instring, loc )
1748        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1749            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1750                raise
1751            else:
1752                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1753                raise exc
1754        else:
1755            return tokens
1756
1757    def scanString( self, instring, maxMatches=_MAX_INT, overlap=False ):
1758        """
1759        Scan the input string for expression matches.  Each match will return the
1760        matching tokens, start location, and end location.  May be called with optional
1761        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip scanning after 'n' matches are found.  If
1762        ``overlap`` is specified, then overlapping matches will be reported.
1763
1764        Note that the start and end locations are reported relative to the string
1765        being parsed.  See :class:`parseString` for more information on parsing
1766        strings with embedded tabs.
1767
1768        Example::
1769
1770            source = "sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987"
1771            print(source)
1772            for tokens,start,end in Word(alphas).scanString(source):
1773                print(' '*start + '^'*(end-start))
1774                print(' '*start + tokens[0])
1775
1776        prints::
1777
1778            sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987
1779            ^^^^^
1780            sldjf
1781                    ^^^^^^^
1782                    lsdjjkf
1783                              ^^^^^^
1784                              sldkjf
1785                                       ^^^^^^
1786                                       lkjsfd
1787        """
1788        if not self.streamlined:
1789            self.streamline()
1790        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1791            e.streamline()
1792
1793        if not self.keepTabs:
1794            instring = _ustr(instring).expandtabs()
1795        instrlen = len(instring)
1796        loc = 0
1797        preparseFn = self.preParse
1798        parseFn = self._parse
1799        ParserElement.resetCache()
1800        matches = 0
1801        try:
1802            while loc <= instrlen and matches < maxMatches:
1803                try:
1804                    preloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1805                    nextLoc,tokens = parseFn( instring, preloc, callPreParse=False )
1806                except ParseException:
1807                    loc = preloc+1
1808                else:
1809                    if nextLoc > loc:
1810                        matches += 1
1811                        yield tokens, preloc, nextLoc
1812                        if overlap:
1813                            nextloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1814                            if nextloc > loc:
1815                                loc = nextLoc
1816                            else:
1817                                loc += 1
1818                        else:
1819                            loc = nextLoc
1820                    else:
1821                        loc = preloc+1
1822        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1823            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1824                raise
1825            else:
1826                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1827                raise exc
1828
1829    def transformString( self, instring ):
1830        """
1831        Extension to :class:`scanString`, to modify matching text with modified tokens that may
1832        be returned from a parse action.  To use ``transformString``, define a grammar and
1833        attach a parse action to it that modifies the returned token list.
1834        Invoking ``transformString()`` on a target string will then scan for matches,
1835        and replace the matched text patterns according to the logic in the parse
1836        action.  ``transformString()`` returns the resulting transformed string.
1837
1838        Example::
1839
1840            wd = Word(alphas)
1841            wd.setParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0].title())
1842
1843            print(wd.transformString("now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york."))
1844
1845        prints::
1846
1847            Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York.
1848        """
1849        out = []
1850        lastE = 0
1851        # force preservation of <TAB>s, to minimize unwanted transformation of string, and to
1852        # keep string locs straight between transformString and scanString
1853        self.keepTabs = True
1854        try:
1855            for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring ):
1856                out.append( instring[lastE:s] )
1857                if t:
1858                    if isinstance(t,ParseResults):
1859                        out += t.asList()
1860                    elif isinstance(t,list):
1861                        out += t
1862                    else:
1863                        out.append(t)
1864                lastE = e
1865            out.append(instring[lastE:])
1866            out = [o for o in out if o]
1867            return "".join(map(_ustr,_flatten(out)))
1868        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1869            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1870                raise
1871            else:
1872                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1873                raise exc
1874
1875    def searchString( self, instring, maxMatches=_MAX_INT ):
1876        """
1877        Another extension to :class:`scanString`, simplifying the access to the tokens found
1878        to match the given parse expression.  May be called with optional
1879        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip searching after 'n' matches are found.
1880
1881        Example::
1882
1883            # a capitalized word starts with an uppercase letter, followed by zero or more lowercase letters
1884            cap_word = Word(alphas.upper(), alphas.lower())
1885
1886            print(cap_word.searchString("More than Iron, more than Lead, more than Gold I need Electricity"))
1887
1888            # the sum() builtin can be used to merge results into a single ParseResults object
1889            print(sum(cap_word.searchString("More than Iron, more than Lead, more than Gold I need Electricity")))
1890
1891        prints::
1892
1893            [['More'], ['Iron'], ['Lead'], ['Gold'], ['I'], ['Electricity']]
1894            ['More', 'Iron', 'Lead', 'Gold', 'I', 'Electricity']
1895        """
1896        try:
1897            return ParseResults([ t for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring, maxMatches ) ])
1898        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1899            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1900                raise
1901            else:
1902                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1903                raise exc
1904
1905    def split(self, instring, maxsplit=_MAX_INT, includeSeparators=False):
1906        """
1907        Generator method to split a string using the given expression as a separator.
1908        May be called with optional ``maxsplit`` argument, to limit the number of splits;
1909        and the optional ``includeSeparators`` argument (default= ``False``), if the separating
1910        matching text should be included in the split results.
1911
1912        Example::
1913
1914            punc = oneOf(list(".,;:/-!?"))
1915            print(list(punc.split("This, this?, this sentence, is badly punctuated!")))
1916
1917        prints::
1918
1919            ['This', ' this', '', ' this sentence', ' is badly punctuated', '']
1920        """
1921        splits = 0
1922        last = 0
1923        for t,s,e in self.scanString(instring, maxMatches=maxsplit):
1924            yield instring[last:s]
1925            if includeSeparators:
1926                yield t[0]
1927            last = e
1928        yield instring[last:]
1929
1930    def __add__(self, other ):
1931        """
1932        Implementation of + operator - returns :class:`And`. Adding strings to a ParserElement
1933        converts them to :class:`Literal`s by default.
1934
1935        Example::
1936
1937            greet = Word(alphas) + "," + Word(alphas) + "!"
1938            hello = "Hello, World!"
1939            print (hello, "->", greet.parseString(hello))
1940
1941        prints::
1942
1943            Hello, World! -> ['Hello', ',', 'World', '!']
1944        """
1945        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1946            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1947        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1948            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1949                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1950            return None
1951        return And( [ self, other ] )
1952
1953    def __radd__(self, other ):
1954        """
1955        Implementation of + operator when left operand is not a :class:`ParserElement`
1956        """
1957        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1958            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1959        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1960            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1961                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1962            return None
1963        return other + self
1964
1965    def __sub__(self, other):
1966        """
1967        Implementation of - operator, returns :class:`And` with error stop
1968        """
1969        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1970            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1971        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1972            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1973                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1974            return None
1975        return self + And._ErrorStop() + other
1976
1977    def __rsub__(self, other ):
1978        """
1979        Implementation of - operator when left operand is not a :class:`ParserElement`
1980        """
1981        if isinstance( other, basestring ):
1982            other = ParserElement._literalStringClass( other )
1983        if not isinstance( other, ParserElement ):
1984            warnings.warn("Cannot combine element of type %s with ParserElement" % type(other),
1985                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
1986            return None
1987        return other - self
1988
1989    def __mul__(self,other):
1990        """
1991        Implementation of * operator, allows use of ``expr * 3`` in place of
1992        ``expr + expr + expr``.  Expressions may also me multiplied by a 2-integer
1993        tuple, similar to ``{min,max}`` multipliers in regular expressions.  Tuples
1994        may also include ``None`` as in:
1995         - ``expr*(n,None)`` or ``expr*(n,)`` is equivalent
1996              to ``expr*n + ZeroOrMore(expr)``
1997              (read as "at least n instances of ``expr``")
1998         - ``expr*(None,n)`` is equivalent to ``expr*(0,n)``
1999              (read as "0 to n instances of ``expr``")
2000         - ``expr*(None,None)`` is equivalent to ``ZeroOrMore(expr)``
2001         - ``expr*(1,None)`` is equivalent to ``OneOrMore(expr)``
2002
2003        Note that ``expr*(None,n)`` does not raise an exception if
2004        more than n exprs exist in the input stream; that is,
2005        ``expr*(None,n)`` does not enforce a maximum number of expr
2006        occurrences.  If this behavior is desired, then write
2007        ``expr*(None,n) + ~expr``
2008        """
2009        if isinstance(other,int):
2010            minElements, optElements = other,0
2011        elif isinstance(other,tuple):
2012            other = (other + (None, None))[:2]
2013            if other[0] is None:
2014                other = (0, other[1])
2015            if isinstance(other[0],int) and other[1] is None:
2016                if other[0] == 0:
2017                    return ZeroOrMore(self)
2018                if other[0] == 1:
2019                    return OneOrMore(self)
2020                else:
2021                    return self*other[0] + ZeroOrMore(self)
2022            elif isinstance(other[0],int) and isinstance(other[1],int):
2023                minElements, optElements = other
2024                optElements -= minElements
2025            else:
2026                raise TypeError("cannot multiply 'ParserElement' and ('%s','%s') objects", type(other[0]),type(other[1]))
2027        else:
2028            raise TypeError("cannot multiply 'ParserElement' and '%s' objects", type(other))
2029
2030        if minElements < 0:
2031            raise ValueError("cannot multiply ParserElement by negative value")
2032        if optElements < 0:
2033            raise ValueError("second tuple value must be greater or equal to first tuple value")
2034        if minElements == optElements == 0:
2035            raise ValueError("cannot multiply ParserElement by 0 or (0,0)")
2036
2037        if (optElements):
2038            def makeOptionalList(n):
2039                if n>1:
2040                    return Optional(self + makeOptionalList(n-1))
2041                else:
2042                    return Optional(self)
2043            if minElements:
2044                if minElements == 1:
2045                    ret = self + makeOptionalList(optElements)
2046                else:
2047                    ret = And([self]*minElements) + makeOptionalList(optElements)
2048            else:
2049                ret = makeOptionalList(optElements)
2050        else:
2051            if minElements == 1:
2052                ret = self
2053            else:
2054                ret = And([self]*minElements)
2055        return ret
2056
2057    def __rmul__(self, other):
2058        return self.__mul__(other)

2138    def __call__(self, name=None):
2139        """
2140        Shortcut for :class:`setResultsName`, with ``listAllMatches=False``.
2141
2142        If ``name`` is given with a trailing ``'*'`` character, then ``listAllMatches`` will be
2143        passed as ``True``.
2144
2145        If ``name` is omitted, same as calling :class:`copy`.
2146
2147        Example::
2148
2149            # these are equivalent
2150            userdata = Word(alphas).setResultsName("name") + Word(nums+"-").setResultsName("socsecno")
2151            userdata = Word(alphas)("name") + Word(nums+"-")("socsecno")
2152        """
2153        if name is not None:
2154            return self.setResultsName(name)
2155        else:
2156            return self.copy()

2159        """
2160        Suppresses the output of this :class:`ParserElement`; useful to keep punctuation from
2161        cluttering up returned output.
2162        """
2163        return Suppress( self )

2165    def leaveWhitespace( self ):
2166        """
2167        Disables the skipping of whitespace before matching the characters in the
2168        :class:`ParserElement`'s defined pattern.  This is normally only used internally by
2169        the pyparsing module, but may be needed in some whitespace-sensitive grammars.
2170        """
2171        self.skipWhitespace = False
2172        return self

2184        """

2186        Must be called before ``parseString`` when the input grammar contains elements that
2187        match ``<TAB>`` characters.
2188        """
2189        self.keepTabs = True

2192    def ignore( self, other ):
2193        """
2194        Define expression to be ignored (e.g., comments) while doing pattern
2195        matching; may be called repeatedly, to define multiple comment or other
2196        ignorable patterns.
2197
2198        Example::
2199
2200            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
2201            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj']
2202
2203            patt.ignore(cStyleComment)
2204            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj', 'lskjd']
2205        """
2206        if isinstance(other, basestring):
2207            other = Suppress(other)
2208
2209        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
2210            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
2211                self.ignoreExprs.append(other)
2212        else:
2213            self.ignoreExprs.append( Suppress( other.copy() ) )
2214        return self

2216    def setDebugActions( self, startAction, successAction, exceptionAction ):
2217        """
2218        Enable display of debugging messages while doing pattern matching.
2219        """
2220        self.debugActions = (startAction or _defaultStartDebugAction,
2221                             successAction or _defaultSuccessDebugAction,
2222                             exceptionAction or _defaultExceptionDebugAction)
2223        self.debug = True
2224        return self
2225
2226    def setDebug( self, flag=True ):
2227        """
2228        Enable display of debugging messages while doing pattern matching.
2229        Set ``flag`` to True to enable, False to disable.
2230
2231        Example::
2232
2233            wd = Word(alphas).setName("alphaword")
2234            integer = Word(nums).setName("numword")
2235            term = wd | integer
2236
2237            # turn on debugging for wd
2238            wd.setDebug()
2239
2240            OneOrMore(term).parseString("abc 123 xyz 890")
2241
2242        prints::
2243
2244            Match alphaword at loc 0(1,1)
2245            Matched alphaword -> ['abc']
2246            Match alphaword at loc 3(1,4)
2247            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 4), (line:1, col:5)
2248            Match alphaword at loc 7(1,8)
2249            Matched alphaword -> ['xyz']
2250            Match alphaword at loc 11(1,12)
2251            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 12), (line:1, col:13)
2252            Match alphaword at loc 15(1,16)
2253            Exception raised:Expected alphaword (at char 15), (line:1, col:16)
2254
2255        The output shown is that produced by the default debug actions - custom debug actions can be
2256        specified using :class:`setDebugActions`. Prior to attempting
2257        to match the ``wd`` expression, the debugging message ``"Match <exprname> at loc <n>(<line>,<col>)"``
2258        is shown. Then if the parse succeeds, a ``"Matched"` message is shown, or an ``"Exception raised"``
2259        message is shown. Also note the use of :class:`setName` to assign a human-readable name to the expression,
2260        which makes debugging and exception messages easier to understand - for instance, the default
2261        name created for the :class:`Word` expression without calling ``setName`` is ``"W:(ABCD...)"``.
2262        """
2263        if flag:
2264            self.setDebugActions( _defaultStartDebugAction, _defaultSuccessDebugAction, _defaultExceptionDebugAction )
2265        else:
2266            self.debug = False
2267        return self

2289    def parseFile( self, file_or_filename, parseAll=False ):
2290        """
2291        Execute the parse expression on the given file or filename.
2292        If a filename is specified (instead of a file object),
2293        the entire file is opened, read, and closed before parsing.
2294        """
2295        try:
2296            file_contents = file_or_filename.read()
2297        except AttributeError:
2298            with open(file_or_filename, "r") as f:
2299                file_contents = f.read()
2300        try:
2301            return self.parseString(file_contents, parseAll)
2302        except ParseBaseException as exc:
2303            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
2304                raise
2305            else:
2306                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
2307                raise exc

2309    def __eq__(self,other):
2310        if isinstance(other, ParserElement):
2311            return self is other or vars(self) == vars(other)
2312        elif isinstance(other, basestring):
2313            return self.matches(other)
2314        else:
2315            return super(ParserElement,self)==other
2316
2317    def __ne__(self,other):
2318        return not (self == other)

2321        return hash(id(self))

2324        return self == other

2329    def matches(self, testString, parseAll=True):
2330        """
2331        Method for quick testing of a parser against a test string. Good for simple
2332        inline microtests of sub expressions while building up larger parser.
2333
2334        Parameters:
2335         - testString - to test against this expression for a match
2336         - parseAll - (default= ``True``) - flag to pass to :class:`parseString` when running tests
2337
2338        Example::
2339
2340            expr = Word(nums)
2341            assert expr.matches("100")
2342        """
2343        try:
2344            self.parseString(_ustr(testString), parseAll=parseAll)
2345            return True
2346        except ParseBaseException:
2347            return False
2348
2349    def runTests(self, tests, parseAll=True, comment='#', fullDump=True, printResults=True, failureTests=False):
2350        """
2351        Execute the parse expression on a series of test strings, showing each
2352        test, the parsed results or where the parse failed. Quick and easy way to
2353        run a parse expression against a list of sample strings.
2354
2355        Parameters:
2356         - tests - a list of separate test strings, or a multiline string of test strings
2357         - parseAll - (default= ``True`` ) - flag to pass to :class:`parseString` when running tests
2358         - comment - (default= ``'#'`` ) - expression for indicating embedded comments in the test
2359              string; pass None to disable comment filtering
2360         - fullDump - (default= ``True`` ) - dump results as list followed by results names in nested outline;
2361              if False, only dump nested list
2362         - printResults - (default= ``True`` ) prints test output to stdout
2363         - failureTests - (default= ``False`` ) indicates if these tests are expected to fail parsing
2364
2365        Returns: a (success, results) tuple, where success indicates that all tests succeeded
2366        (or failed if ``failureTests`` is True), and the results contain a list of lines of each
2367        test's output
2368
2369        Example::
2370
2371            number_expr = pyparsing_common.number.copy()
2372
2373            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2374                # unsigned integer
2375                100
2376                # negative integer
2377                -100
2378                # float with scientific notation
2379                6.02e23
2380                # integer with scientific notation
2381                1e-12
2382                ''')
2383            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2384
2385            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2386                # stray character
2387                100Z
2388                # missing leading digit before '.'
2389                -.100
2390                # too many '.'
2391                3.14.159
2392                ''', failureTests=True)
2393            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2394
2395        prints::
2396
2397            # unsigned integer
2398            100
2399            [100]
2400
2401            # negative integer
2402            -100
2403            [-100]
2404
2405            # float with scientific notation
2406            6.02e23
2407            [6.02e+23]
2408
2409            # integer with scientific notation
2410            1e-12
2411            [1e-12]
2412
2413            Success
2414
2415            # stray character
2416            100Z
2417               ^
2418            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 3), (line:1, col:4)
2419
2420            # missing leading digit before '.'
2421            -.100
2422            ^
2423            FAIL: Expected {real number with scientific notation | real number | signed integer} (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
2424
2425            # too many '.'
2426            3.14.159
2427                ^
2428            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 4), (line:1, col:5)
2429
2430            Success
2431
2432        Each test string must be on a single line. If you want to test a string that spans multiple
2433        lines, create a test like this::
2434
2435            expr.runTest(r"this is a test\\n of strings that spans \\n 3 lines")
2436
2437        (Note that this is a raw string literal, you must include the leading 'r'.)
2438        """
2439        if isinstance(tests, basestring):
2440            tests = list(map(str.strip, tests.rstrip().splitlines()))
2441        if isinstance(comment, basestring):
2442            comment = Literal(comment)
2443        allResults = []
2444        comments = []
2445        success = True
2446        for t in tests:
2447            if comment is not None and comment.matches(t, False) or comments and not t:
2448                comments.append(t)
2449                continue
2450            if not t:
2451                continue
2452            out = ['\n'.join(comments), t]
2453            comments = []
2454            try:
2455                t = t.replace(r'\n','\n')
2456                result = self.parseString(t, parseAll=parseAll)
2457                out.append(result.dump(full=fullDump))
2458                success = success and not failureTests
2459            except ParseBaseException as pe:
2460                fatal = "(FATAL)" if isinstance(pe, ParseFatalException) else ""
2461                if '\n' in t:
2462                    out.append(line(pe.loc, t))
2463                    out.append(' '*(col(pe.loc,t)-1) + '^' + fatal)
2464                else:
2465                    out.append(' '*pe.loc + '^' + fatal)
2466                out.append("FAIL: " + str(pe))
2467                success = success and failureTests
2468                result = pe
2469            except Exception as exc:
2470                out.append("FAIL-EXCEPTION: " + str(exc))
2471                success = success and failureTests
2472                result = exc
2473
2474            if printResults:
2475                if fullDump:
2476                    out.append('')
2477                print('\n'.join(out))
2478
2479            allResults.append((t, result))
2480
2481        return success, allResults

Abstract base level parser element class.

1264            cpy.whiteChars = ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
1265        return cpy

1329    def setParseAction( self, *fns, **kwargs ):
1330        """
1331        Define one or more actions to perform when successfully matching parse element definition.
1332        Parse action fn is a callable method with 0-3 arguments, called as ``fn(s,loc,toks)`` ,
1333        ``fn(loc,toks)`` , ``fn(toks)`` , or just ``fn()`` , where:
1334
1335        - s   = the original string being parsed (see note below)
1336        - loc = the location of the matching substring
1337        - toks = a list of the matched tokens, packaged as a :class:`ParseResults` object
1338
1339        If the functions in fns modify the tokens, they can return them as the return
1340        value from fn, and the modified list of tokens will replace the original.
1341        Otherwise, fn does not need to return any value.
1342
1343        Optional keyword arguments:
1344        - callDuringTry = (default= ``False`` ) indicate if parse action should be run during lookaheads and alternate testing
1345
1346        Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1347        before starting the parsing process.  See :class:`parseString for more
1348        information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and suggested
1349        methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse
1350        location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1351
1352        Example::
1353
1354            integer = Word(nums)
1355            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1356
1357            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']
1358
1359            # use parse action to convert to ints at parse time
1360            integer = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda toks: int(toks[0]))
1361            date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1362
1363            # note that integer fields are now ints, not strings
1364            date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> [1999, '/', 12, '/', 31]
1365        """
1366        self.parseAction = list(map(_trim_arity, list(fns)))
1367        self.callDuringTry = kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1368        return self

Define one or more actions to perform when successfully matching parse element definition. Parse action fn is a callable method with 0-3 arguments, called as fn(s,loc,toks) , fn(loc,toks) , fn(toks) , or just fn() , where:

  • s = the original string being parsed (see note below)
  • loc = the location of the matching substring
  • toks = a list of the matched tokens, packaged as a ParseResults object

If the functions in fns modify the tokens, they can return them as the return value from fn, and the modified list of tokens will replace the original. Otherwise, fn does not need to return any value.

Optional keyword arguments:

  • callDuringTry = (default= False ) indicate if parse action should be run during lookaheads and alternate testing

Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string before starting the parsing process. See `parseString for more information on parsing strings containing <TAB> s, and suggested methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.

Example::

integer = Word(nums)
date_str = integer + '/' + integer + '/' + integer

date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> ['1999', '/', '12', '/', '31']

# note that integer fields are now ints, not strings

1380    def addCondition(self, *fns, **kwargs):
1381        """Add a boolean predicate function to expression's list of parse actions. See
1382        :class:`setParseAction` for function call signatures. Unlike ``setParseAction``,
1383        functions passed to ``addCondition`` need to return boolean success/fail of the condition.
1384

1387        - fatal   = if True, will raise ParseFatalException to stop parsing immediately; otherwise will raise ParseException
1388

1392            year_int = integer.copy()

1394            date_str = year_int + '/' + integer + '/' + integer
1395
1396            result = date_str.parseString("1999/12/31")  # -> Exception: Only support years 2000 and later (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
1397        """
1398        msg = kwargs.get("message", "failed user-defined condition")
1399        exc_type = ParseFatalException if kwargs.get("fatal", False) else ParseException
1400        for fn in fns:
1401            def pa(s,l,t):
1402                if not bool(_trim_arity(fn)(s,l,t)):
1403                    raise exc_type(s,l,msg)
1404            self.parseAction.append(pa)
1405        self.callDuringTry = self.callDuringTry or kwargs.get("callDuringTry", False)
1406        return self

  • fatal = if True, will raise ParseFatalException to stop parsing immediately; otherwise will raise ParseException

#  
@staticmethod
def enablePackrat(cache_size_limit=128):
View Source 
1668    @staticmethod
1669    def enablePackrat(cache_size_limit=128):
1670        """Enables "packrat" parsing, which adds memoizing to the parsing logic.
1671           Repeated parse attempts at the same string location (which happens
1672           often in many complex grammars) can immediately return a cached value,
1673           instead of re-executing parsing/validating code.  Memoizing is done of
1674           both valid results and parsing exceptions.
1675
1676           Parameters:
1677
1678           - cache_size_limit - (default= ``128``) - if an integer value is provided
1679             will limit the size of the packrat cache; if None is passed, then
1680             the cache size will be unbounded; if 0 is passed, the cache will
1681             be effectively disabled.
1682
1683           This speedup may break existing programs that use parse actions that
1684           have side-effects.  For this reason, packrat parsing is disabled when
1685           you first import pyparsing.  To activate the packrat feature, your
1686           program must call the class method :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat`.  If
1687           your program uses ``psyco`` to "compile as you go", you must call
1688           ``enablePackrat`` before calling ``psyco.full()``.  If you do not do this,
1689           Python will crash.  For best results, call ``enablePackrat()`` immediately
1690           after importing pyparsing.
1691
1692           Example::
1693
1694               import pyparsing
1695               pyparsing.ParserElement.enablePackrat()
1696        """
1697        if not ParserElement._packratEnabled:
1698            ParserElement._packratEnabled = True
1699            if cache_size_limit is None:
1700                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._UnboundedCache()
1701            else:
1702                ParserElement.packrat_cache = ParserElement._FifoCache(cache_size_limit)
1703            ParserElement._parse = ParserElement._parseCache

Enables "packrat" parsing, which adds memoizing to the parsing logic. Repeated parse attempts at the same string location (which happens often in many complex grammars) can immediately return a cached value, instead of re-executing parsing/validating code. Memoizing is done of both valid results and parsing exceptions.

Parameters:

  • cache_size_limit - (default= 128) - if an integer value is provided will limit the size of the packrat cache; if None is passed, then the cache size will be unbounded; if 0 is passed, the cache will be effectively disabled.

This speedup may break existing programs that use parse actions that have side-effects. For this reason, packrat parsing is disabled when you first import pyparsing. To activate the packrat feature, your program must call the class method ParserElement.enablePackrat. If your program uses psyco to "compile as you go", you must call enablePackrat before calling psyco.full(). If you do not do this, Python will crash. For best results, call enablePackrat() immediately after importing pyparsing.

Example::

import pyparsing
pyparsing.ParserElement.enablePackrat()
#   def parseString(self, instring, parseAll=False):
View Source 
1705    def parseString( self, instring, parseAll=False ):
1706        """
1707        Execute the parse expression with the given string.
1708        This is the main interface to the client code, once the complete
1709        expression has been built.
1710
1711        If you want the grammar to require that the entire input string be
1712        successfully parsed, then set ``parseAll`` to True (equivalent to ending
1713        the grammar with ``StringEnd()``).
1714
1715        Note: ``parseString`` implicitly calls ``expandtabs()`` on the input string,
1716        in order to report proper column numbers in parse actions.
1717        If the input string contains tabs and
1718        the grammar uses parse actions that use the ``loc`` argument to index into the
1719        string being parsed, you can ensure you have a consistent view of the input
1720        string by:
1721
1722        - calling ``parseWithTabs`` on your grammar before calling ``parseString``
1723          (see :class:`parseWithTabs`)
1724        - define your parse action using the full ``(s,loc,toks)`` signature, and
1725          reference the input string using the parse action's ``s`` argument
1726        - explictly expand the tabs in your input string before calling
1727          ``parseString``
1728
1729        Example::
1730
1731            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa')  # -> ['aaaaa']
1732            Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa', parseAll=True)  # -> Exception: Expected end of text
1733        """
1734        ParserElement.resetCache()
1735        if not self.streamlined:
1736            self.streamline()
1737            #~ self.saveAsList = True
1738        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1739            e.streamline()
1740        if not self.keepTabs:
1741            instring = instring.expandtabs()
1742        try:
1743            loc, tokens = self._parse( instring, 0 )
1744            if parseAll:
1745                loc = self.preParse( instring, loc )
1746                se = Empty() + StringEnd()
1747                se._parse( instring, loc )
1748        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1749            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1750                raise
1751            else:
1752                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1753                raise exc
1754        else:
1755            return tokens

Execute the parse expression with the given string. This is the main interface to the client code, once the complete expression has been built.

If you want the grammar to require that the entire input string be successfully parsed, then set parseAll to True (equivalent to ending the grammar with StringEnd()).

Note: parseString implicitly calls expandtabs() on the input string, in order to report proper column numbers in parse actions. If the input string contains tabs and the grammar uses parse actions that use the loc argument to index into the string being parsed, you can ensure you have a consistent view of the input string by:

  • calling parseWithTabs on your grammar before calling parseString (see parseWithTabs)
  • define your parse action using the full (s,loc,toks) signature, and reference the input string using the parse action's s argument
  • explictly expand the tabs in your input string before calling parseString

Example::

Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa')  # -> ['aaaaa']
Word('a').parseString('aaaaabaaa', parseAll=True)  # -> Exception: Expected end of text
#   def scanString(self, instring, maxMatches=9223372036854775807, overlap=False):
View Source 
1757    def scanString( self, instring, maxMatches=_MAX_INT, overlap=False ):
1758        """
1759        Scan the input string for expression matches.  Each match will return the
1760        matching tokens, start location, and end location.  May be called with optional
1761        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip scanning after 'n' matches are found.  If
1762        ``overlap`` is specified, then overlapping matches will be reported.
1763
1764        Note that the start and end locations are reported relative to the string
1765        being parsed.  See :class:`parseString` for more information on parsing
1766        strings with embedded tabs.
1767
1768        Example::
1769
1770            source = "sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987"
1771            print(source)
1772            for tokens,start,end in Word(alphas).scanString(source):
1773                print(' '*start + '^'*(end-start))
1774                print(' '*start + tokens[0])
1775
1776        prints::
1777
1778            sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987
1779            ^^^^^
1780            sldjf
1781                    ^^^^^^^
1782                    lsdjjkf
1783                              ^^^^^^
1784                              sldkjf
1785                                       ^^^^^^
1786                                       lkjsfd
1787        """
1788        if not self.streamlined:
1789            self.streamline()
1790        for e in self.ignoreExprs:
1791            e.streamline()
1792
1793        if not self.keepTabs:
1794            instring = _ustr(instring).expandtabs()
1795        instrlen = len(instring)
1796        loc = 0
1797        preparseFn = self.preParse
1798        parseFn = self._parse
1799        ParserElement.resetCache()
1800        matches = 0
1801        try:
1802            while loc <= instrlen and matches < maxMatches:
1803                try:
1804                    preloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1805                    nextLoc,tokens = parseFn( instring, preloc, callPreParse=False )
1806                except ParseException:
1807                    loc = preloc+1
1808                else:
1809                    if nextLoc > loc:
1810                        matches += 1
1811                        yield tokens, preloc, nextLoc
1812                        if overlap:
1813                            nextloc = preparseFn( instring, loc )
1814                            if nextloc > loc:
1815                                loc = nextLoc
1816                            else:
1817                                loc += 1
1818                        else:
1819                            loc = nextLoc
1820                    else:
1821                        loc = preloc+1
1822        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1823            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1824                raise
1825            else:
1826                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1827                raise exc

Scan the input string for expression matches. Each match will return the matching tokens, start location, and end location. May be called with optional maxMatches argument, to clip scanning after 'n' matches are found. If overlap is specified, then overlapping matches will be reported.

Note that the start and end locations are reported relative to the string being parsed. See parseString for more information on parsing strings with embedded tabs.

Example::

source = "sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987"
print(source)
for tokens,start,end in Word(alphas).scanString(source):
    print(' '*start + '^'*(end-start))
    print(' '*start + tokens[0])

prints::

sldjf123lsdjjkf345sldkjf879lkjsfd987
^^^^^
sldjf
        ^^^^^^^
        lsdjjkf
                  ^^^^^^
                  sldkjf
                           ^^^^^^
                           lkjsfd

1829    def transformString( self, instring ):
1830        """
1831        Extension to :class:`scanString`, to modify matching text with modified tokens that may
1832        be returned from a parse action.  To use ``transformString``, define a grammar and
1833        attach a parse action to it that modifies the returned token list.
1834        Invoking ``transformString()`` on a target string will then scan for matches,
1835        and replace the matched text patterns according to the logic in the parse
1836        action.  ``transformString()`` returns the resulting transformed string.
1837
1838        Example::
1839
1840            wd = Word(alphas)
1841            wd.setParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0].title())
1842
1843            print(wd.transformString("now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york."))
1844
1845        prints::
1846
1847            Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York.
1848        """
1849        out = []
1850        lastE = 0
1851        # force preservation of <TAB>s, to minimize unwanted transformation of string, and to
1852        # keep string locs straight between transformString and scanString
1853        self.keepTabs = True
1854        try:
1855            for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring ):
1856                out.append( instring[lastE:s] )
1857                if t:
1858                    if isinstance(t,ParseResults):
1859                        out += t.asList()
1860                    elif isinstance(t,list):
1861                        out += t
1862                    else:
1863                        out.append(t)
1864                lastE = e
1865            out.append(instring[lastE:])
1866            out = [o for o in out if o]
1867            return "".join(map(_ustr,_flatten(out)))
1868        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1869            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1870                raise
1871            else:
1872                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1873                raise exc

Extension to scanString, to modify matching text with modified tokens that may be returned from a parse action. To use transformString, define a grammar and attach a parse action to it that modifies the returned token list. Invoking transformString() on a target string will then scan for matches, and replace the matched text patterns according to the logic in the parse action. transformString() returns the resulting transformed string.

Example::

wd = Word(alphas)
wd.setParseAction(lambda toks: toks[0].title())

print(wd.transformString("now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york."))

prints::

Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York.

1879        ``maxMatches`` argument, to clip searching after 'n' matches are found.

1889            print(sum(cap_word.searchString("More than Iron, more than Lead, more than Gold I need Electricity")))
1890
1891        prints::
1892
1893            [['More'], ['Iron'], ['Lead'], ['Gold'], ['I'], ['Electricity']]
1894            ['More', 'Iron', 'Lead', 'Gold', 'I', 'Electricity']
1895        """
1896        try:
1897            return ParseResults([ t for t,s,e in self.scanString( instring, maxMatches ) ])
1898        except ParseBaseException as exc:
1899            if ParserElement.verbose_stacktrace:
1900                raise
1901            else:
1902                # catch and re-raise exception from here, clears out pyparsing internal stack trace
1903                raise exc

1905    def split(self, instring, maxsplit=_MAX_INT, includeSeparators=False):
1906        """
1907        Generator method to split a string using the given expression as a separator.
1908        May be called with optional ``maxsplit`` argument, to limit the number of splits;
1909        and the optional ``includeSeparators`` argument (default= ``False``), if the separating
1910        matching text should be included in the split results.
1911
1912        Example::
1913
1914            punc = oneOf(list(".,;:/-!?"))
1915            print(list(punc.split("This, this?, this sentence, is badly punctuated!")))
1916
1917        prints::
1918
1919            ['This', ' this', '', ' this sentence', ' is badly punctuated', '']
1920        """
1921        splits = 0
1922        last = 0
1923        for t,s,e in self.scanString(instring, maxMatches=maxsplit):
1924            yield instring[last:s]
1925            if includeSeparators:
1926                yield t[0]
1927            last = e
1928        yield instring[last:]

2192    def ignore( self, other ):
2193        """
2194        Define expression to be ignored (e.g., comments) while doing pattern
2195        matching; may be called repeatedly, to define multiple comment or other
2196        ignorable patterns.
2197
2198        Example::
2199
2200            patt = OneOrMore(Word(alphas))
2201            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj']
2202
2203            patt.ignore(cStyleComment)
2204            patt.parseString('ablaj /* comment */ lskjd') # -> ['ablaj', 'lskjd']
2205        """
2206        if isinstance(other, basestring):
2207            other = Suppress(other)
2208
2209        if isinstance( other, Suppress ):
2210            if other not in self.ignoreExprs:
2211                self.ignoreExprs.append(other)
2212        else:
2213            self.ignoreExprs.append( Suppress( other.copy() ) )
2214        return self

#   def runTests( self, tests, parseAll=True, comment='#', fullDump=True, printResults=True, failureTests=False ):

2349    def runTests(self, tests, parseAll=True, comment='#', fullDump=True, printResults=True, failureTests=False):
2350        """
2351        Execute the parse expression on a series of test strings, showing each
2352        test, the parsed results or where the parse failed. Quick and easy way to
2353        run a parse expression against a list of sample strings.
2354
2355        Parameters:
2356         - tests - a list of separate test strings, or a multiline string of test strings
2357         - parseAll - (default= ``True`` ) - flag to pass to :class:`parseString` when running tests
2358         - comment - (default= ``'#'`` ) - expression for indicating embedded comments in the test
2359              string; pass None to disable comment filtering
2360         - fullDump - (default= ``True`` ) - dump results as list followed by results names in nested outline;
2361              if False, only dump nested list
2362         - printResults - (default= ``True`` ) prints test output to stdout
2363         - failureTests - (default= ``False`` ) indicates if these tests are expected to fail parsing
2364
2365        Returns: a (success, results) tuple, where success indicates that all tests succeeded
2366        (or failed if ``failureTests`` is True), and the results contain a list of lines of each
2367        test's output
2368
2369        Example::
2370
2371            number_expr = pyparsing_common.number.copy()
2372
2373            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2374                # unsigned integer
2375                100
2376                # negative integer
2377                -100
2378                # float with scientific notation
2379                6.02e23
2380                # integer with scientific notation
2381                1e-12
2382                ''')
2383            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2384
2385            result = number_expr.runTests('''
2386                # stray character
2387                100Z
2388                # missing leading digit before '.'
2389                -.100
2390                # too many '.'
2391                3.14.159
2392                ''', failureTests=True)
2393            print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")
2394
2395        prints::
2396
2397            # unsigned integer
2398            100
2399            [100]
2400
2401            # negative integer
2402            -100
2403            [-100]
2404
2405            # float with scientific notation
2406            6.02e23
2407            [6.02e+23]
2408
2409            # integer with scientific notation
2410            1e-12
2411            [1e-12]
2412
2413            Success
2414
2415            # stray character
2416            100Z
2417               ^
2418            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 3), (line:1, col:4)
2419
2420            # missing leading digit before '.'
2421            -.100
2422            ^
2423            FAIL: Expected {real number with scientific notation | real number | signed integer} (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
2424
2425            # too many '.'
2426            3.14.159
2427                ^
2428            FAIL: Expected end of text (at char 4), (line:1, col:5)
2429
2430            Success
2431
2432        Each test string must be on a single line. If you want to test a string that spans multiple
2433        lines, create a test like this::
2434
2435            expr.runTest(r"this is a test\\n of strings that spans \\n 3 lines")
2436
2437        (Note that this is a raw string literal, you must include the leading 'r'.)
2438        """
2439        if isinstance(tests, basestring):
2440            tests = list(map(str.strip, tests.rstrip().splitlines()))
2441        if isinstance(comment, basestring):
2442            comment = Literal(comment)
2443        allResults = []
2444        comments = []
2445        success = True
2446        for t in tests:
2447            if comment is not None and comment.matches(t, False) or comments and not t:
2448                comments.append(t)
2449                continue
2450            if not t:
2451                continue
2452            out = ['\n'.join(comments), t]
2453            comments = []
2454            try:
2455                t = t.replace(r'\n','\n')
2456                result = self.parseString(t, parseAll=parseAll)
2457                out.append(result.dump(full=fullDump))
2458                success = success and not failureTests
2459            except ParseBaseException as pe:
2460                fatal = "(FATAL)" if isinstance(pe, ParseFatalException) else ""
2461                if '\n' in t:
2462                    out.append(line(pe.loc, t))
2463                    out.append(' '*(col(pe.loc,t)-1) + '^' + fatal)
2464                else:
2465                    out.append(' '*pe.loc + '^' + fatal)
2466                out.append("FAIL: " + str(pe))
2467                success = success and failureTests
2468                result = pe
2469            except Exception as exc:
2470                out.append("FAIL-EXCEPTION: " + str(exc))
2471                success = success and failureTests
2472                result = exc
2473
2474            if printResults:
2475                if fullDump:
2476                    out.append('')
2477                print('\n'.join(out))
2478
2479            allResults.append((t, result))
2480
2481        return success, allResults

Execute the parse expression on a series of test strings, showing each test, the parsed results or where the parse failed. Quick and easy way to run a parse expression against a list of sample strings.

Parameters:

  • tests - a list of separate test strings, or a multiline string of test strings
  • parseAll - (default= True ) - flag to pass to parseString when running tests
  • comment - (default= '#' ) - expression for indicating embedded comments in the test string; pass None to disable comment filtering
  • fullDump - (default= True ) - dump results as list followed by results names in nested outline; if False, only dump nested list
  • printResults - (default= True ) prints test output to stdout
  • failureTests - (default= False ) indicates if these tests are expected to fail parsing

Returns: a (success, results) tuple, where success indicates that all tests succeeded (or failed if failureTests is True), and the results contain a list of lines of each test's output

Example::

number_expr = pyparsing_common.number.copy()

result = number_expr.runTests('''
    # unsigned integer
    100
    # negative integer
    -100
    # float with scientific notation
    6.02e23
    # integer with scientific notation
    1e-12
    ''')
print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")

result = number_expr.runTests('''
    # stray character
    100Z
    # missing leading digit before '.'
    -.100
    # too many '.'
    3.14.159
    ''', failureTests=True)
print("Success" if result[0] else "Failed!")

prints::

# unsigned integer
100
[100]

# negative integer
-100
[-100]

# float with scientific notation
6.02e23
[6.02e+23]

3030class QuotedString(Token):
3031    r"""
3032    Token for matching strings that are delimited by quoting characters.
3033
3034    Defined with the following parameters:
3035
3036        - quoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
3037          quote delimiting string
3038        - escChar - character to escape quotes, typically backslash
3039          (default= ``None`` )
3040        - escQuote - special quote sequence to escape an embedded quote
3041          string (such as SQL's ``""`` to escape an embedded ``"``)
3042          (default= ``None`` )
3043        - multiline - boolean indicating whether quotes can span
3044          multiple lines (default= ``False`` )
3045        - unquoteResults - boolean indicating whether the matched text
3046          should be unquoted (default= ``True`` )
3047        - endQuoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
3048          end of the quote delimited string (default= ``None``  => same as
3049          quoteChar)
3050        - convertWhitespaceEscapes - convert escaped whitespace
3051          (``'\t'``, ``'\n'``, etc.) to actual whitespace
3052          (default= ``True`` )
3053
3054    Example::
3055
3056        qs = QuotedString('"')
3057        print(qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote" sldjf'))
3058        complex_qs = QuotedString('{{', endQuoteChar='}}')
3059        print(complex_qs.searchString('lsjdf {{This is the "quote"}} sldjf'))
3060        sql_qs = QuotedString('"', escQuote='""')
3061        print(sql_qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote with ""embedded"" quotes" sldjf'))
3062
3063    prints::
3064
3065        [['This is the quote']]
3066        [['This is the "quote"']]
3067        [['This is the quote with "embedded" quotes']]
3068    """
3069    def __init__( self, quoteChar, escChar=None, escQuote=None, multiline=False, unquoteResults=True, endQuoteChar=None, convertWhitespaceEscapes=True):
3070        super(QuotedString,self).__init__()
3071
3072        # remove white space from quote chars - wont work anyway
3073        quoteChar = quoteChar.strip()
3074        if not quoteChar:
3075            warnings.warn("quoteChar cannot be the empty string",SyntaxWarning,stacklevel=2)
3076            raise SyntaxError()
3077
3078        if endQuoteChar is None:
3079            endQuoteChar = quoteChar
3080        else:
3081            endQuoteChar = endQuoteChar.strip()
3082            if not endQuoteChar:
3083                warnings.warn("endQuoteChar cannot be the empty string",SyntaxWarning,stacklevel=2)
3084                raise SyntaxError()
3085
3086        self.quoteChar = quoteChar
3087        self.quoteCharLen = len(quoteChar)
3088        self.firstQuoteChar = quoteChar[0]
3089        self.endQuoteChar = endQuoteChar
3090        self.endQuoteCharLen = len(endQuoteChar)
3091        self.escChar = escChar
3092        self.escQuote = escQuote
3093        self.unquoteResults = unquoteResults
3094        self.convertWhitespaceEscapes = convertWhitespaceEscapes
3095
3096        if multiline:
3097            self.flags = re.MULTILINE | re.DOTALL
3098            self.pattern = r'%s(?:[^%s%s]' % \
3099                ( re.escape(self.quoteChar),
3100                  _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[0]),
3101                  (escChar is not None and _escapeRegexRangeChars(escChar) or '') )
3102        else:
3103            self.flags = 0
3104            self.pattern = r'%s(?:[^%s\n\r%s]' % \
3105                ( re.escape(self.quoteChar),
3106                  _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[0]),
3107                  (escChar is not None and _escapeRegexRangeChars(escChar) or '') )
3108        if len(self.endQuoteChar) > 1:
3109            self.pattern += (
3110                '|(?:' + ')|(?:'.join("%s[^%s]" % (re.escape(self.endQuoteChar[:i]),
3111                                               _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.endQuoteChar[i]))
3112                                    for i in range(len(self.endQuoteChar)-1,0,-1)) + ')'
3113                )
3114        if escQuote:
3115            self.pattern += (r'|(?:%s)' % re.escape(escQuote))
3116        if escChar:
3117            self.pattern += (r'|(?:%s.)' % re.escape(escChar))
3118            self.escCharReplacePattern = re.escape(self.escChar)+"(.)"
3119        self.pattern += (r')*%s' % re.escape(self.endQuoteChar))
3120
3121        try:
3122            self.re = re.compile(self.pattern, self.flags)
3123            self.reString = self.pattern
3124        except sre_constants.error:
3125            warnings.warn("invalid pattern (%s) passed to Regex" % self.pattern,
3126                SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3127            raise
3128
3129        self.name = _ustr(self)
3130        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3131        self.mayIndexError = False
3132        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3133
3134    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3135        result = instring[loc] == self.firstQuoteChar and self.re.match(instring,loc) or None
3136        if not result:
3137            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3138
3139        loc = result.end()
3140        ret = result.group()
3141
3142        if self.unquoteResults:
3143
3144            # strip off quotes
3145            ret = ret[self.quoteCharLen:-self.endQuoteCharLen]
3146
3147            if isinstance(ret,basestring):
3148                # replace escaped whitespace
3149                if '\\' in ret and self.convertWhitespaceEscapes:
3150                    ws_map = {
3151                        r'\t' : '\t',
3152                        r'\n' : '\n',
3153                        r'\f' : '\f',
3154                        r'\r' : '\r',
3155                    }
3156                    for wslit,wschar in ws_map.items():
3157                        ret = ret.replace(wslit, wschar)
3158
3159                # replace escaped characters
3160                if self.escChar:
3161                    ret = re.sub(self.escCharReplacePattern, r"\g<1>", ret)
3162
3163                # replace escaped quotes
3164                if self.escQuote:
3165                    ret = ret.replace(self.escQuote, self.endQuoteChar)
3166
3167        return loc, ret

3169    def __str__( self ):
3170        try:
3171            return super(QuotedString,self).__str__()
3172        except Exception:
3173            pass
3174
3175        if self.strRepr is None:
3176            self.strRepr = "quoted string, starting with %s ending with %s" % (self.quoteChar, self.endQuoteChar)
3177
3178        return self.strRepr

Token for matching strings that are delimited by quoting characters.

Defined with the following parameters:

- quoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
  quote delimiting string
- escChar - character to escape quotes, typically backslash
  (default= ``None`` )
- escQuote - special quote sequence to escape an embedded quote
  string (such as SQL's ``""`` to escape an embedded ``"``)
  (default= ``None`` )
- multiline - boolean indicating whether quotes can span
  multiple lines (default= ``False`` )
- unquoteResults - boolean indicating whether the matched text
  should be unquoted (default= ``True`` )
- endQuoteChar - string of one or more characters defining the
  end of the quote delimited string (default= ``None``  => same as
  quoteChar)
- convertWhitespaceEscapes - convert escaped whitespace
  (``'\t'``, ``'\n'``, etc.) to actual whitespace
  (default= ``True`` )

Example::

qs = QuotedString('"')
print(qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote" sldjf'))
complex_qs = QuotedString('{{', endQuoteChar='}}')
print(complex_qs.searchString('lsjdf {{This is the "quote"}} sldjf'))
sql_qs = QuotedString('"', escQuote='""')
print(sql_qs.searchString('lsjdf "This is the quote with ""embedded"" quotes" sldjf'))

prints::

[['This is the quote']]
[['This is the "quote"']]
[['This is the quote with "embedded" quotes']]

2917class Regex(Token):
2918    r"""Token for matching strings that match a given regular
2919    expression. Defined with string specifying the regular expression in
2920    a form recognized by the stdlib Python  `re module <http://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html>`_.
2921    If the given regex contains named groups (defined using ``(?P<name>...)``),
2922    these will be preserved as named parse results.
2923
2924    Example::
2925
2926        realnum = Regex(r"[+-]?\d+\.\d*")
2927        date = Regex(r'(?P<year>\d{4})-(?P<month>\d\d?)-(?P<day>\d\d?)')
2928        # ref: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/267399/how-do-you-match-only-valid-roman-numerals-with-a-regular-expression
2929        roman = Regex(r"M{0,4}(CM|CD|D?{0,3})(XC|XL|L?X{0,3})(IX|IV|V?I{0,3})")
2930    """
2931    compiledREtype = type(re.compile("[A-Z]"))
2932    def __init__( self, pattern, flags=0, asGroupList=False, asMatch=False):
2933        """The parameters ``pattern`` and ``flags`` are passed
2934        to the ``re.compile()`` function as-is. See the Python
2935        `re module <http://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html>`_ module for an
2936        explanation of the acceptable patterns and flags.
2937        """
2938        super(Regex,self).__init__()
2939
2940        if isinstance(pattern, basestring):
2941            if not pattern:
2942                warnings.warn("null string passed to Regex; use Empty() instead",
2943                        SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2944
2945            self.pattern = pattern
2946            self.flags = flags
2947
2948            try:
2949                self.re = re.compile(self.pattern, self.flags)
2950                self.reString = self.pattern
2951            except sre_constants.error:
2952                warnings.warn("invalid pattern (%s) passed to Regex" % pattern,
2953                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
2954                raise
2955
2956        elif isinstance(pattern, Regex.compiledREtype):
2957            self.re = pattern
2958            self.pattern = \
2959            self.reString = str(pattern)
2960            self.flags = flags
2961
2962        else:
2963            raise ValueError("Regex may only be constructed with a string or a compiled RE object")
2964
2965        self.name = _ustr(self)
2966        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2967        self.mayIndexError = False
2968        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
2969        self.asGroupList = asGroupList
2970        self.asMatch = asMatch
2971
2972    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2973        result = self.re.match(instring,loc)
2974        if not result:
2975            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2976
2977        loc = result.end()
2978        d = result.groupdict()
2979        if self.asMatch:
2980            ret = result
2981        elif self.asGroupList:
2982            ret = result.groups()
2983        else:
2984            ret = ParseResults(result.group())
2985            if d:
2986                for k in d:
2987                    ret[k] = d[k]
2988        return loc,ret
2989
2990    def __str__( self ):
2991        try:
2992            return super(Regex,self).__str__()
2993        except Exception:
2994            pass
2995
2996        if self.strRepr is None:
2997            self.strRepr = "Re:(%s)" % repr(self.pattern)
2998
2999        return self.strRepr

3001    def sub(self, repl):
3002        """
3003        Return Regex with an attached parse action to transform the parsed
3004        result as if called using `re.sub(expr, repl, string) <https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html#re.sub>`_.
3005
3006        Example::
3007
3008            make_html = Regex(r"(\w+):(.*?):").sub(r"<\1>\2</\1>")
3009            print(make_html.transformString("h1:main title:"))
3010            # prints "<h1>main title</h1>"
3011        """
3012        if self.asGroupList:
3013            warnings.warn("cannot use sub() with Regex(asGroupList=True)",
3014                           SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3015            raise SyntaxError()
3016
3017        if self.asMatch and callable(repl):
3018            warnings.warn("cannot use sub() with a callable with Regex(asMatch=True)",
3019                           SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
3020            raise SyntaxError()
3021
3022        if self.asMatch:
3023            def pa(tokens):
3024                return tokens[0].expand(repl)
3025        else:
3026            def pa(tokens):
3027                return self.re.sub(repl, tokens[0])
3028        return self.addParseAction(pa)

Token for matching strings that match a given regular expression. Defined with string specifying the regular expression in a form recognized by the stdlib Python re module . If the given regex contains named groups (defined using (?P<name>...)), these will be preserved as named parse results.

Example::
