4342class SkipTo(ParseElementEnhance):
4343    """Token for skipping over all undefined text until the matched
4344    expression is found.
4345
4346    Parameters:
4347     - expr - target expression marking the end of the data to be skipped
4348     - include - (default= ``False``) if True, the target expression is also parsed
4349          (the skipped text and target expression are returned as a 2-element list).
4350     - ignore - (default= ``None``) used to define grammars (typically quoted strings and
4351          comments) that might contain false matches to the target expression
4352     - failOn - (default= ``None``) define expressions that are not allowed to be
4353          included in the skipped test; if found before the target expression is found,
4354          the SkipTo is not a match
4355
4356    Example::
4357
4358        report = '''
4359            Outstanding Issues Report - 1 Jan 2000
4360
4361               # | Severity | Description                               |  Days Open
4362            -----+----------+-------------------------------------------+-----------
4363             101 | Critical | Intermittent system crash                 |          6
4364              94 | Cosmetic | Spelling error on Login ('log|n')         |         14
4365              79 | Minor    | System slow when running too many reports |         47
4366            '''
4367        integer = Word(nums)
4368        SEP = Suppress('|')
4369        # use SkipTo to simply match everything up until the next SEP
4370        # - ignore quoted strings, so that a '|' character inside a quoted string does not match
4371        # - parse action will call token.strip() for each matched token, i.e., the description body
4372        string_data = SkipTo(SEP, ignore=quotedString)
4373        string_data.setParseAction(tokenMap(str.strip))
4374        ticket_expr = (integer("issue_num") + SEP
4375                      + string_data("sev") + SEP
4376                      + string_data("desc") + SEP
4377                      + integer("days_open"))
4378
4379        for tkt in ticket_expr.searchString(report):
4380            print tkt.dump()
4381
4382    prints::
4383
4384        ['101', 'Critical', 'Intermittent system crash', '6']
4385        - days_open: 6
4386        - desc: Intermittent system crash
4387        - issue_num: 101
4388        - sev: Critical
4389        ['94', 'Cosmetic', "Spelling error on Login ('log|n')", '14']
4390        - days_open: 14
4391        - desc: Spelling error on Login ('log|n')
4392        - issue_num: 94
4393        - sev: Cosmetic
4394        ['79', 'Minor', 'System slow when running too many reports', '47']
4395        - days_open: 47
4396        - desc: System slow when running too many reports
4397        - issue_num: 79
4398        - sev: Minor
4399    """
4400    def __init__( self, other, include=False, ignore=None, failOn=None ):
4401        super( SkipTo, self ).__init__( other )
4402        self.ignoreExpr = ignore
4403        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
4404        self.mayIndexError = False
4405        self.includeMatch = include
4406        self.saveAsList = False
4407        if isinstance(failOn, basestring):
4408            self.failOn = ParserElement._literalStringClass(failOn)
4409        else:
4410            self.failOn = failOn
4411        self.errmsg = "No match found for "+_ustr(self.expr)
4412
4413    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
4414        startloc = loc
4415        instrlen = len(instring)
4416        expr = self.expr
4417        expr_parse = self.expr._parse
4418        self_failOn_canParseNext = self.failOn.canParseNext if self.failOn is not None else None
4419        self_ignoreExpr_tryParse = self.ignoreExpr.tryParse if self.ignoreExpr is not None else None
4420
4421        tmploc = loc
4422        while tmploc <= instrlen:
4423            if self_failOn_canParseNext is not None:
4424                # break if failOn expression matches
4425                if self_failOn_canParseNext(instring, tmploc):
4426                    break
4427
4428            if self_ignoreExpr_tryParse is not None:
4429                # advance past ignore expressions
4430                while 1:
4431                    try:
4432                        tmploc = self_ignoreExpr_tryParse(instring, tmploc)
4433                    except ParseBaseException:
4434                        break
4435
4436            try:
4437                expr_parse(instring, tmploc, doActions=False, callPreParse=False)
4438            except (ParseException, IndexError):
4439                # no match, advance loc in string
4440                tmploc += 1
4441            else:
4442                # matched skipto expr, done
4443                break
4444
4445        else:
4446            # ran off the end of the input string without matching skipto expr, fail
4447            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
4448
4449        # build up return values
4450        loc = tmploc
4451        skiptext = instring[startloc:loc]
4452        skipresult = ParseResults(skiptext)
4453
4454        if self.includeMatch:
4455            loc, mat = expr_parse(instring,loc,doActions,callPreParse=False)
4456            skipresult += mat
4457
4458        return loc, skipresult

Token for skipping over all undefined text until the matched expression is found.

Parameters:

  • expr - target expression marking the end of the data to be skipped
  • include - (default= False) if True, the target expression is also parsed (the skipped text and target expression are returned as a 2-element list).
  • ignore - (default= None) used to define grammars (typically quoted strings and comments) that might contain false matches to the target expression
  • failOn - (default= None) define expressions that are not allowed to be included in the skipped test; if found before the target expression is found, the SkipTo is not a match

Example::

report = '''
    Outstanding Issues Report - 1 Jan 2000

       # | Severity | Description                               |  Days Open
    -----+----------+-------------------------------------------+-----------
     101 | Critical | Intermittent system crash                 |          6
      94 | Cosmetic | Spelling error on Login ('log|n')         |         14
      79 | Minor    | System slow when running too many reports |         47
    '''
integer = Word(nums)
SEP = Suppress('|')
# use SkipTo to simply match everything up until the next SEP
# - ignore quoted strings, so that a '|' character inside a quoted string does not match
# - parse action will call token.strip() for each matched token, i.e., the description body
string_data = SkipTo(SEP, ignore=quotedString)
string_data.setParseAction(tokenMap(str.strip))
ticket_expr = (integer("issue_num") + SEP
              + string_data("sev") + SEP
              + string_data("desc") + SEP
              + integer("days_open"))

for tkt in ticket_expr.searchString(report):
    print tkt.dump()

prints::

['101', 'Critical', 'Intermittent system crash', '6']
- days_open: 6
- desc: Intermittent system crash
- issue_num: 101
- sev: Critical
['94', 'Cosmetic', "Spelling error on Login ('log|n')", '14']
- days_open: 14
- desc: Spelling error on Login ('log|n')
- issue_num: 94
- sev: Cosmetic
['79', 'Minor', 'System slow when running too many reports', '47']
- days_open: 47
- desc: System slow when running too many reports
- issue_num: 79
- sev: Minor

3409class StringEnd(_PositionToken):
3410    """Matches if current position is at the end of the parse string
3411    """
3412    def __init__( self ):
3413        super(StringEnd,self).__init__()
3414        self.errmsg = "Expected end of text"
3415
3416    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3417        if loc < len(instring):
3418            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3419        elif loc == len(instring):
3420            return loc+1, []
3421        elif loc > len(instring):
3422            return loc, []
3423        else:
3424            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

4696class Suppress(TokenConverter):
4697    """Converter for ignoring the results of a parsed expression.
4698
4699    Example::
4700
4701        source = "a, b, c,d"
4702        wd = Word(alphas)
4703        wd_list1 = wd + ZeroOrMore(',' + wd)
4704        print(wd_list1.parseString(source))
4705
4706        # often, delimiters that are useful during parsing are just in the
4707        # way afterward - use Suppress to keep them out of the parsed output
4708        wd_list2 = wd + ZeroOrMore(Suppress(',') + wd)
4709        print(wd_list2.parseString(source))
4710

4712
4713        ['a', ',', 'b', ',', 'c', ',', 'd']
4714        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']
4715
4716    (See also :class:`delimitedList`.)
4717    """
4718    def postParse( self, instring, loc, tokenlist ):
4719        return []
4720
4721    def suppress( self ):
4722        return self

#   class White(Token):

3258class White(Token):
3259    """Special matching class for matching whitespace.  Normally,
3260    whitespace is ignored by pyparsing grammars.  This class is included
3261    when some whitespace structures are significant.  Define with
3262    a string containing the whitespace characters to be matched; default
3263    is ``" \\t\\r\\n"``.  Also takes optional ``min``,
3264    ``max``, and ``exact`` arguments, as defined for the
3265    :class:`Word` class.
3266    """
3267    whiteStrs = {
3268        " " : "<SPC>",
3269        "\t": "<TAB>",
3270        "\n": "<LF>",
3271        "\r": "<CR>",
3272        "\f": "<FF>",
3273        }
3274    def __init__(self, ws=" \t\r\n", min=1, max=0, exact=0):
3275        super(White,self).__init__()
3276        self.matchWhite = ws
3277        self.setWhitespaceChars( "".join(c for c in self.whiteChars if c not in self.matchWhite) )
3278        #~ self.leaveWhitespace()
3279        self.name = ("".join(White.whiteStrs[c] for c in self.matchWhite))
3280        self.mayReturnEmpty = True
3281        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
3282
3283        self.minLen = min
3284
3285        if max > 0:
3286            self.maxLen = max
3287        else:
3288            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
3289
3290        if exact > 0:
3291            self.maxLen = exact
3292            self.minLen = exact
3293
3294    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3295        if not(instring[ loc ] in self.matchWhite):
3296            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3297        start = loc
3298        loc += 1
3299        maxloc = start + self.maxLen
3300        maxloc = min( maxloc, len(instring) )
3301        while loc < maxloc and instring[loc] in self.matchWhite:
3302            loc += 1
3303
3304        if loc - start < self.minLen:
3305            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3306
3307        return loc, instring[start:loc]

Define with a string containing the whitespace characters to be matched; default is " \t\r\n". Also takes optional min, max, and exact arguments, as defined for the Word class.

#   class Word(Token):
View Source 
2741class Word(Token):
2742    """Token for matching words composed of allowed character sets.
2743    Defined with string containing all allowed initial characters, an
2744    optional string containing allowed body characters (if omitted,
2745    defaults to the initial character set), and an optional minimum,
2746    maximum, and/or exact length.  The default value for ``min`` is
2747    1 (a minimum value < 1 is not valid); the default values for
2748    ``max`` and ``exact`` are 0, meaning no maximum or exact
2749    length restriction. An optional ``excludeChars`` parameter can
2750    list characters that might be found in the input ``bodyChars``
2751    string; useful to define a word of all printables except for one or
2752    two characters, for instance.
2753
2754    :class:`srange` is useful for defining custom character set strings
2755    for defining ``Word`` expressions, using range notation from
2756    regular expression character sets.
2757
2758    A common mistake is to use :class:`Word` to match a specific literal
2759    string, as in ``Word("Address")``. Remember that :class:`Word`
2760    uses the string argument to define *sets* of matchable characters.
2761    This expression would match "Add", "AAA", "dAred", or any other word
2762    made up of the characters 'A', 'd', 'r', 'e', and 's'. To match an
2763    exact literal string, use :class:`Literal` or :class:`Keyword`.
2764
2765    pyparsing includes helper strings for building Words:
2766
2767     - :class:`alphas`
2768     - :class:`nums`
2769     - :class:`alphanums`
2770     - :class:`hexnums`
2771     - :class:`alphas8bit` (alphabetic characters in ASCII range 128-255
2772       - accented, tilded, umlauted, etc.)
2773     - :class:`punc8bit` (non-alphabetic characters in ASCII range
2774       128-255 - currency, symbols, superscripts, diacriticals, etc.)
2775     - :class:`printables` (any non-whitespace character)
2776
2777    Example::
2778
2779        # a word composed of digits
2780        integer = Word(nums) # equivalent to Word("0123456789") or Word(srange("0-9"))
2781
2782        # a word with a leading capital, and zero or more lowercase
2783        capital_word = Word(alphas.upper(), alphas.lower())
2784
2785        # hostnames are alphanumeric, with leading alpha, and '-'
2786        hostname = Word(alphas, alphanums+'-')
2787
2788        # roman numeral (not a strict parser, accepts invalid mix of characters)
2789        roman = Word("IVXLCDM")
2790
2791        # any string of non-whitespace characters, except for ','
2792        csv_value = Word(printables, excludeChars=",")
2793    """
2794    def __init__( self, initChars, bodyChars=None, min=1, max=0, exact=0, asKeyword=False, excludeChars=None ):
2795        super(Word,self).__init__()
2796        if excludeChars:
2797            initChars = ''.join(c for c in initChars if c not in excludeChars)
2798            if bodyChars:
2799                bodyChars = ''.join(c for c in bodyChars if c not in excludeChars)
2800        self.initCharsOrig = initChars
2801        self.initChars = set(initChars)
2802        if bodyChars :
2803            self.bodyCharsOrig = bodyChars
2804            self.bodyChars = set(bodyChars)
2805        else:
2806            self.bodyCharsOrig = initChars
2807            self.bodyChars = set(initChars)
2808
2809        self.maxSpecified = max > 0
2810
2811        if min < 1:
2812            raise ValueError("cannot specify a minimum length < 1; use Optional(Word()) if zero-length word is permitted")
2813
2814        self.minLen = min
2815
2816        if max > 0:
2817            self.maxLen = max
2818        else:
2819            self.maxLen = _MAX_INT
2820
2821        if exact > 0:
2822            self.maxLen = exact
2823            self.minLen = exact
2824
2825        self.name = _ustr(self)
2826        self.errmsg = "Expected " + self.name
2827        self.mayIndexError = False
2828        self.asKeyword = asKeyword
2829
2830        if ' ' not in self.initCharsOrig+self.bodyCharsOrig and (min==1 and max==0 and exact==0):
2831            if self.bodyCharsOrig == self.initCharsOrig:
2832                self.reString = "[%s]+" % _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.initCharsOrig)
2833            elif len(self.initCharsOrig) == 1:
2834                self.reString = "%s[%s]*" % \
2835                                      (re.escape(self.initCharsOrig),
2836                                      _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.bodyCharsOrig),)
2837            else:
2838                self.reString = "[%s][%s]*" % \
2839                                      (_escapeRegexRangeChars(self.initCharsOrig),
2840                                      _escapeRegexRangeChars(self.bodyCharsOrig),)
2841            if self.asKeyword:
2842                self.reString = r"\b"+self.reString+r"\b"
2843            try:
2844                self.re = re.compile( self.reString )
2845            except Exception:
2846                self.re = None
2847
2848    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2849        if self.re:
2850            result = self.re.match(instring,loc)
2851            if not result:
2852                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2853
2854            loc = result.end()
2855            return loc, result.group()
2856
2857        if not(instring[ loc ] in self.initChars):
2858            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2859
2860        start = loc
2861        loc += 1
2862        instrlen = len(instring)
2863        bodychars = self.bodyChars
2864        maxloc = start + self.maxLen
2865        maxloc = min( maxloc, instrlen )
2866        while loc < maxloc and instring[loc] in bodychars:
2867            loc += 1
2868
2869        throwException = False
2870        if loc - start < self.minLen:
2871            throwException = True
2872        if self.maxSpecified and loc < instrlen and instring[loc] in bodychars:
2873            throwException = True
2874        if self.asKeyword:
2875            if (start>0 and instring[start-1] in bodychars) or (loc<instrlen and instring[loc] in bodychars):
2876                throwException = True
2877
2878        if throwException:
2879            raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
2880
2881        return loc, instring[start:loc]
2882
2883    def __str__( self ):
2884        try:
2885            return super(Word,self).__str__()
2886        except Exception:
2887            pass
2888
2889
2890        if self.strRepr is None:
2891
2892            def charsAsStr(s):
2893                if len(s)>4:
2894                    return s[:4]+"..."
2895                else:
2896                    return s
2897
2898            if ( self.initCharsOrig != self.bodyCharsOrig ):
2899                self.strRepr = "W:(%s,%s)" % ( charsAsStr(self.initCharsOrig), charsAsStr(self.bodyCharsOrig) )
2900            else:
2901                self.strRepr = "W:(%s)" % charsAsStr(self.initCharsOrig)
2902
2903        return self.strRepr

Token for matching words composed of allowed character sets. Defined with string containing all allowed initial characters, an optional string containing allowed body characters (if omitted, defaults to the initial character set), and an optional minimum, maximum, and/or exact length. The default value for min is 1 (a minimum value < 1 is not valid); the default values for max and exact are 0, meaning no maximum or exact length restriction. An optional excludeChars parameter can list characters that might be found in the input bodyChars string; useful to define a word of all printables except for one or two characters, for instance.

srange is useful for defining custom character set strings for defining Word expressions, using range notation from regular expression character sets.

A common mistake is to use Word to match a specific literal string, as in Word("Address"). Remember that Word uses the string argument to define sets of matchable characters. This expression would match "Add", "AAA", "dAred", or any other word made up of the characters 'A', 'd', 'r', 'e', and 's'. To match an exact literal string, use Literal or Keyword.

pyparsing includes helper strings for building Words:

  • alphas
  • nums
  • alphanums
  • hexnums
  • alphas8bit (alphabetic characters in ASCII range 128-255
    • accented, tilded, umlauted, etc.)
  • punc8bit (non-alphabetic characters in ASCII range 128-255 - currency, symbols, superscripts, diacriticals, etc.)
  • printables (any non-whitespace character)

Example::

# a word composed of digits
integer = Word(nums) # equivalent to Word("0123456789") or Word(srange("0-9"))

# a word with a leading capital, and zero or more lowercase
capital_word = Word(alphas.upper(), alphas.lower())

# hostnames are alphanumeric, with leading alpha, and '-'
hostname = Word(alphas, alphanums+'-')

# roman numeral (not a strict parser, accepts invalid mix of characters)
roman = Word("IVXLCDM")

# any string of non-whitespace characters, except for ','
csv_value = Word(printables, excludeChars=",")

3447class WordEnd(_PositionToken):
3448    """Matches if the current position is at the end of a Word, and is
3449    not followed by any character in a given set of ``wordChars``
3450    (default= ``printables``). To emulate the ``\b`` behavior of
3451    regular expressions, use ``WordEnd(alphanums)``. ``WordEnd``
3452    will also match at the end of the string being parsed, or at the end
3453    of a line.
3454    """
3455    def __init__(self, wordChars = printables):
3456        super(WordEnd,self).__init__()
3457        self.wordChars = set(wordChars)
3458        self.skipWhitespace = False
3459        self.errmsg = "Not at the end of a word"
3460
3461    def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
3462        instrlen = len(instring)
3463        if instrlen>0 and loc<instrlen:
3464            if (instring[loc] in self.wordChars or
3465                instring[loc-1] not in self.wordChars):
3466                raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)
3467        return loc, []

1036def col (loc,strg):
1037    """Returns current column within a string, counting newlines as line separators.
1038   The first column is number 1.
1039
1040   Note: the default parsing behavior is to expand tabs in the input string
1041   before starting the parsing process.  See
1042   :class:`ParserElement.parseString` for more
1043   information on parsing strings containing ``<TAB>`` s, and suggested
1044   methods to maintain a consistent view of the parsed string, the parse
1045   location, and line and column positions within the parsed string.
1046   """
1047    s = strg
1048    return 1 if 0<loc<len(s) and s[loc-1] == '\n' else loc - s.rfind("\n", 0, loc)

4809def countedArray( expr, intExpr=None ):
4810    """Helper to define a counted list of expressions.
4811
4812    This helper defines a pattern of the form::
4813
4814        integer expr expr expr...
4815
4816    where the leading integer tells how many expr expressions follow.
4817    The matched tokens returns the array of expr tokens as a list - the
4818    leading count token is suppressed.
4819
4820    If ``intExpr`` is specified, it should be a pyparsing expression
4821    that produces an integer value.
4822
4823    Example::
4824
4825        countedArray(Word(alphas)).parseString('2 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']
4826
4827        # in this parser, the leading integer value is given in binary,
4828        # '10' indicating that 2 values are in the array
4829        binaryConstant = Word('01').setParseAction(lambda t: int(t[0], 2))
4830        countedArray(Word(alphas), intExpr=binaryConstant).parseString('10 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']
4831    """
4832    arrayExpr = Forward()
4833    def countFieldParseAction(s,l,t):
4834        n = t[0]
4835        arrayExpr << (n and Group(And([expr]*n)) or Group(empty))
4836        return []
4837    if intExpr is None:
4838        intExpr = Word(nums).setParseAction(lambda t:int(t[0]))
4839    else:
4840        intExpr = intExpr.copy()
4841    intExpr.setName("arrayLen")
4842    intExpr.addParseAction(countFieldParseAction, callDuringTry=True)
4843    return ( intExpr + arrayExpr ).setName('(len) ' + _ustr(expr) + '...')

Helper to define a counted list of expressions.

This helper defines a pattern of the form::

integer expr expr expr...

where the leading integer tells how many expr expressions follow. The matched tokens returns the array of expr tokens as a list - the leading count token is suppressed.

If intExpr is specified, it should be a pyparsing expression that produces an integer value.

Example::

countedArray(Word(alphas)).parseString('2 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']

# in this parser, the leading integer value is given in binary,
# '10' indicating that 2 values are in the array
binaryConstant = Word('01').setParseAction(lambda t: int(t[0], 2))
countedArray(Word(alphas), intExpr=binaryConstant).parseString('10 ab cd ef')  # -> ['ab', 'cd']

4788def delimitedList( expr, delim=",", combine=False ):
4789    """Helper to define a delimited list of expressions - the delimiter
4790    defaults to ','. By default, the list elements and delimiters can
4791    have intervening whitespace, and comments, but this can be
4792    overridden by passing ``combine=True`` in the constructor. If
4793    ``combine`` is set to ``True``, the matching tokens are
4794    returned as a single token string, with the delimiters included;
4795    otherwise, the matching tokens are returned as a list of tokens,
4796    with the delimiters suppressed.
4797
4798    Example::
4799
4800        delimitedList(Word(alphas)).parseString("aa,bb,cc") # -> ['aa', 'bb', 'cc']
4801        delimitedList(Word(hexnums), delim=':', combine=True).parseString("AA:BB:CC:DD:EE") # -> ['AA:BB:CC:DD:EE']
4802    """
4803    dlName = _ustr(expr)+" ["+_ustr(delim)+" "+_ustr(expr)+"]..."
4804    if combine:
4805        return Combine( expr + ZeroOrMore( delim + expr ) ).setName(dlName)
4806    else:
4807        return ( expr + ZeroOrMore( Suppress( delim ) + expr ) ).setName(dlName)

Helper to define a delimited list of expressions - the delimiter defaults to ','. By default, the list elements and delimiters can have intervening whitespace, and comments, but this can be overridden by passing combine=True in the constructor. If combine is set to True, the matching tokens are returned as a single token string, with the delimiters included; otherwise, the matching tokens are returned as a list of tokens, with the delimiters suppressed.

Example::

delimitedList(Word(alphas)).parseString("aa,bb,cc") # -> ['aa', 'bb', 'cc']
delimitedList(Word(hexnums), delim=':', combine=True).parseString("AA:BB:CC:DD:EE") # -> ['AA:BB:CC:DD:EE']

1062def line( loc, strg ):
1063    """Returns the line of text containing loc within a string, counting newlines as line separators.
1064       """
1065    lastCR = strg.rfind("\n", 0, loc)
1066    nextCR = strg.find("\n", loc)
1067    if nextCR >= 0:
1068        return strg[lastCR+1:nextCR]
1069    else:
1070        return strg[lastCR+1:]

4884def matchPreviousExpr(expr):
4885    """Helper to define an expression that is indirectly defined from
4886    the tokens matched in a previous expression, that is, it looks for
4887    a 'repeat' of a previous expression.  For example::
4888
4889        first = Word(nums)
4890        second = matchPreviousExpr(first)
4891        matchExpr = first + ":" + second
4892
4893    will match ``"1:1"``, but not ``"1:2"``.  Because this
4894    matches by expressions, will *not* match the leading ``"1:1"``
4895    in ``"1:10"``; the expressions are evaluated first, and then
4896    compared, so ``"1"`` is compared with ``"10"``. Do *not* use
4897    with packrat parsing enabled.
4898    """
4899    rep = Forward()
4900    e2 = expr.copy()
4901    rep <<= e2
4902    def copyTokenToRepeater(s,l,t):
4903        matchTokens = _flatten(t.asList())
4904        def mustMatchTheseTokens(s,l,t):
4905            theseTokens = _flatten(t.asList())
4906            if  theseTokens != matchTokens:
4907                raise ParseException("",0,"")
4908        rep.setParseAction( mustMatchTheseTokens, callDuringTry=True )
4909    expr.addParseAction(copyTokenToRepeater, callDuringTry=True)
4910    rep.setName('(prev) ' + _ustr(expr))
4911    return rep

Helper to define an expression that is indirectly defined from the tokens matched in a previous expression, that is, it looks for a 'repeat' of a previous expression. For example::

first = Word(nums)
second = matchPreviousExpr(first)
matchExpr = first + ":" + second

will match "1:1", but not "1:2". Because this matches by expressions, will not match the leading "1:1" in "1:10"; the expressions are evaluated first, and then compared, so "1" is compared with "10". Do not use with packrat parsing enabled.

4854def matchPreviousLiteral(expr):
4855    """Helper to define an expression that is indirectly defined from
4856    the tokens matched in a previous expression, that is, it looks for
4857    a 'repeat' of a previous expression.  For example::
4858
4859        first = Word(nums)
4860        second = matchPreviousLiteral(first)
4861        matchExpr = first + ":" + second
4862
4863    will match ``"1:1"``, but not ``"1:2"``.  Because this
4864    matches a previous literal, will also match the leading
4865    ``"1:1"`` in ``"1:10"``. If this is not desired, use
4866    :class:`matchPreviousExpr`. Do *not* use with packrat parsing
4867    enabled.
4868    """
4869    rep = Forward()
4870    def copyTokenToRepeater(s,l,t):
4871        if t:
4872            if len(t) == 1:
4873                rep << t[0]
4874            else:
4875                # flatten t tokens
4876                tflat = _flatten(t.asList())
4877                rep << And(Literal(tt) for tt in tflat)
4878        else:
4879            rep << Empty()
4880    expr.addParseAction(copyTokenToRepeater, callDuringTry=True)
4881    rep.setName('(prev) ' + _ustr(expr))
4882    return rep

will match "1:1", but not "1:2". Because this matches a previous literal, will also match the leading "1:1" in "1:10". If this is not desired, use matchPreviousExpr. Do not use with packrat parsing enabled.

5571def nestedExpr(opener="(", closer=")", content=None, ignoreExpr=quotedString.copy()):
5572    """Helper method for defining nested lists enclosed in opening and
5573    closing delimiters ("(" and ")" are the default).
5574
5575    Parameters:
5576     - opener - opening character for a nested list
5577       (default= ``"("``); can also be a pyparsing expression
5578     - closer - closing character for a nested list
5579       (default= ``")"``); can also be a pyparsing expression
5580     - content - expression for items within the nested lists
5581       (default= ``None``)
5582     - ignoreExpr - expression for ignoring opening and closing
5583       delimiters (default= :class:`quotedString`)
5584
5585    If an expression is not provided for the content argument, the
5586    nested expression will capture all whitespace-delimited content
5587    between delimiters as a list of separate values.
5588
5589    Use the ``ignoreExpr`` argument to define expressions that may
5590    contain opening or closing characters that should not be treated as
5591    opening or closing characters for nesting, such as quotedString or
5592    a comment expression.  Specify multiple expressions using an
5593    :class:`Or` or :class:`MatchFirst`. The default is
5594    :class:`quotedString`, but if no expressions are to be ignored, then
5595    pass ``None`` for this argument.
5596
5597    Example::
5598
5599        data_type = oneOf("void int short long char float double")
5600        decl_data_type = Combine(data_type + Optional(Word('*')))
5601        ident = Word(alphas+'_', alphanums+'_')
5602        number = pyparsing_common.number
5603        arg = Group(decl_data_type + ident)
5604        LPAR,RPAR = map(Suppress, "()")
5605
5606        code_body = nestedExpr('{', '}', ignoreExpr=(quotedString | cStyleComment))
5607
5608        c_function = (decl_data_type("type")
5609                      + ident("name")
5610                      + LPAR + Optional(delimitedList(arg), [])("args") + RPAR
5611                      + code_body("body"))
5612        c_function.ignore(cStyleComment)
5613
5614        source_code = '''
5615            int is_odd(int x) {
5616                return (x%2);
5617            }
5618
5619            int dec_to_hex(char hchar) {
5620                if (hchar >= '0' && hchar <= '9') {
5621                    return (ord(hchar)-ord('0'));
5622                } else {
5623                    return (10+ord(hchar)-ord('A'));
5624                }
5625            }
5626        '''
5627        for func in c_function.searchString(source_code):
5628            print("%(name)s (%(type)s) args: %(args)s" % func)
5629
5630
5631    prints::
5632
5633        is_odd (int) args: [['int', 'x']]
5634        dec_to_hex (int) args: [['char', 'hchar']]
5635    """
5636    if opener == closer:
5637        raise ValueError("opening and closing strings cannot be the same")
5638    if content is None:
5639        if isinstance(opener,basestring) and isinstance(closer,basestring):
5640            if len(opener) == 1 and len(closer)==1:
5641                if ignoreExpr is not None:
5642                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~ignoreExpr +
5643                                    CharsNotIn(opener+closer+ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5644                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5645                else:
5646                    content = (empty.copy()+CharsNotIn(opener+closer+ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS
5647                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5648            else:
5649                if ignoreExpr is not None:
5650                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~ignoreExpr +
5651                                    ~Literal(opener) + ~Literal(closer) +
5652                                    CharsNotIn(ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5653                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5654                else:
5655                    content = (Combine(OneOrMore(~Literal(opener) + ~Literal(closer) +
5656                                    CharsNotIn(ParserElement.DEFAULT_WHITE_CHARS,exact=1))
5657                                ).setParseAction(lambda t:t[0].strip()))
5658        else:
5659            raise ValueError("opening and closing arguments must be strings if no content expression is given")
5660    ret = Forward()
5661    if ignoreExpr is not None:
5662        ret <<= Group( Suppress(opener) + ZeroOrMore( ignoreExpr | ret | content ) + Suppress(closer) )
5663    else:
5664        ret <<= Group( Suppress(opener) + ZeroOrMore( ret | content )  + Suppress(closer) )
5665    ret.setName('nested %s%s expression' % (opener,closer))
5666    return ret

Helper method for defining nested lists enclosed in opening and closing delimiters ("(" and ")" are the default).

Parameters:

  • opener - opening character for a nested list (default= "("); can also be a pyparsing expression
  • closer - closing character for a nested list (default= ")"); can also be a pyparsing expression
  • content - expression for items within the nested lists (default= None)
  • ignoreExpr - expression for ignoring opening and closing delimiters (default= quotedString)

If an expression is not provided for the content argument, the nested expression will capture all whitespace-delimited content between delimiters as a list of separate values.

Use the ignoreExpr argument to define expressions that may contain opening or closing characters that should not be treated as opening or closing characters for nesting, such as quotedString or a comment expression. 4921def oneOf( strs, caseless=False, useRegex=True ):
4922    """Helper to quickly define a set of alternative Literals, and makes
4923    sure to do longest-first testing when there is a conflict,
4924    regardless of the input order, but returns
4925    a :class:`MatchFirst` for best performance.
4926
4927    Parameters:
4928
4929     - strs - a string of space-delimited literals, or a collection of
4930       string literals
4931     - caseless - (default= ``False``) - treat all literals as
4932       caseless
4933     - useRegex - (default= ``True``) - as an optimization, will
4934       generate a Regex object; otherwise, will generate
4935       a :class:`MatchFirst` object (if ``caseless=True``, or if
4936       creating a :class:`Regex` raises an exception)
4937
4938    Example::
4939
4940        comp_oper = oneOf("< = > <= >= !=")
4941        var = Word(alphas)
4942        number = Word(nums)
4943        term = var | number
4944        comparison_expr = term + comp_oper + term
4945        print(comparison_expr.searchString("B = 12  AA=23 B<=AA AA>12"))
4946
4947    prints::
4948
4949        [['B', '=', '12'], ['AA', '=', '23'], ['B', '<=', 'AA'], ['AA', '>', '12']]
4950    """
4951    if caseless:
4952        isequal = ( lambda a,b: a.upper() == b.upper() )
4953        masks = ( lambda a,b: b.upper().startswith(a.upper()) )
4954        parseElementClass = CaselessLiteral
4955    else:
4956        isequal = ( lambda a,b: a == b )
4957        masks = ( lambda a,b: b.startswith(a) )
4958        parseElementClass = Literal
4959
4960    symbols = []
4961    if isinstance(strs,basestring):
4962        symbols = strs.split()
4963    elif isinstance(strs, Iterable):
4964        symbols = list(strs)
4965    else:
4966        warnings.warn("Invalid argument to oneOf, expected string or iterable",
4967                SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
4968    if not symbols:
4969        return NoMatch()
4970
4971    i = 0
4972    while i < len(symbols)-1:
4973        cur = symbols[i]
4974        for j,other in enumerate(symbols[i+1:]):
4975            if ( isequal(other, cur) ):
4976                del symbols[i+j+1]
4977                break
4978            elif ( masks(cur, other) ):
4979                del symbols[i+j+1]
4980                symbols.insert(i,other)
4981                cur = other
4982                break
4983        else:
4984            i += 1
4985
4986    if not caseless and useRegex:
4987        #~ print (strs,"->", "|".join( [ _escapeRegexChars(sym) for sym in symbols] ))
4988        try:
4989            if len(symbols)==len("".join(symbols)):
4990                return Regex( "[%s]" % "".join(_escapeRegexRangeChars(sym) for sym in symbols) ).setName(' | '.join(symbols))
4991            else:
4992                return Regex( "|".join(re.escape(sym) for sym in symbols) ).setName(' | '.join(symbols))
4993        except Exception:
4994            warnings.warn("Exception creating Regex for oneOf, building MatchFirst",
4995                    SyntaxWarning, stacklevel=2)
4996
4997
4998    # last resort, just use MatchFirst
4999    return MatchFirst(parseElementClass(sym) for sym in symbols).setName(' | '.join(symbols))

Helper to quickly define a set of alternative Literals, and makes sure to do longest-first testing when there is a conflict, regardless of the input order, but returns a MatchFirst for best performance.

Parameters:

  • strs - a string of space-delimited literals, or a collection of string literals
  • caseless - (default= False) - treat all literals as caseless
  • useRegex - (default= True) - as an optimization, will generate a Regex object; otherwise, will generate a MatchFirst object (if caseless=True, or if creating a Regex raises an exception)

Example::

var = Word(alphas)
number = Word(nums)
term = var | number
comparison_expr = term + comp_oper + term
print(comparison_expr.searchString("B = 12  AA=23 B<=AA AA>12"))

[['B', '=', '12'], ['AA', '=', '23'], ['B', '<=', 'AA'], ['AA', '>', '12']]

#   def operatorPrecedence(baseExpr, opList, lpar=Suppress:("("), rpar=Suppress:(")")):

5432def infixNotation( baseExpr, opList, lpar=Suppress('('), rpar=Suppress(')') ):
5433    """Helper method for constructing grammars of expressions made up of
5434    operators working in a precedence hierarchy.  Operators may be unary
5435    or binary, left- or right-associative.  Parse actions can also be
5436    attached to operator expressions. The generated parser will also
5437    recognize the use of parentheses to override operator precedences
5438    (see example below).
5439
5440    Note: if you define a deep operator list, you may see performance
5441    issues when using infixNotation. See
5442    :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat` for a mechanism to potentially
5443    improve your parser performance.
5444
5445    Parameters:
5446     - baseExpr - expression representing the most basic element for the
5447       nested
5448     - opList - list of tuples, one for each operator precedence level
5449       in the expression grammar; each tuple is of the form ``(opExpr,
5450       numTerms, rightLeftAssoc, parseAction)``, where:
5451
5452       - opExpr is the pyparsing expression for the operator; may also
5453         be a string, which will be converted to a Literal; if numTerms
5454         is 3, opExpr is a tuple of two expressions, for the two
5455         operators separating the 3 terms
5456       - numTerms is the number of terms for this operator (must be 1,
5457         2, or 3)
5458       - rightLeftAssoc is the indicator whether the operator is right
5459         or left associative, using the pyparsing-defined constants
5460         ``opAssoc.RIGHT`` and ``opAssoc.LEFT``.
5461       - parseAction is the parse action to be associated with
5462         expressions matching this operator expression (the parse action
5463         tuple member may be omitted); if the parse action is passed
5464         a tuple or list of functions, this is equivalent to calling
5465         ``setParseAction(*fn)``
5466         (:class:`ParserElement.setParseAction`)
5467     - lpar - expression for matching left-parentheses
5468       (default= ``Suppress('(')``)
5469     - rpar - expression for matching right-parentheses
5470       (default= ``Suppress(')')``)
5471
5472    Example::
5473
5474        # simple example of four-function arithmetic with ints and
5475        # variable names
5476        integer = pyparsing_common.signed_integer
5477        varname = pyparsing_common.identifier
5478
5479        arith_expr = infixNotation(integer | varname,
5480            [
5481            ('-', 1, opAssoc.RIGHT),
5482            (oneOf('* /'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5483            (oneOf('+ -'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5484            ])
5485
5486        arith_expr.runTests('''
5487            5+3*6
5488            (5+3)*6
5489            -2--11
5490            ''', fullDump=False)
5491
5492    prints::
5493
5494        5+3*6
5495        [[5, '+', [3, '*', 6]]]
5496
5497        (5+3)*6
5498        [[[5, '+', 3], '*', 6]]
5499
5500        -2--11
5501        [[['-', 2], '-', ['-', 11]]]
5502    """
5503    # captive version of FollowedBy that does not do parse actions or capture results names
5504    class _FB(FollowedBy):
5505        def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True):
5506            self.expr.tryParse(instring, loc)
5507            return loc, []
5508
5509    ret = Forward()
5510    lastExpr = baseExpr | ( lpar + ret + rpar )
5511    for i,operDef in enumerate(opList):
5512        opExpr,arity,rightLeftAssoc,pa = (operDef + (None,))[:4]
5513        termName = "%s term" % opExpr if arity < 3 else "%s%s term" % opExpr
5514        if arity == 3:
5515            if opExpr is None or len(opExpr) != 2:
5516                raise ValueError(
5517                    "if numterms=3, opExpr must be a tuple or list of two expressions")
5518            opExpr1, opExpr2 = opExpr
5519        thisExpr = Forward().setName(termName)
5520        if rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.LEFT:
5521            if arity == 1:
5522                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr ) )
5523            elif arity == 2:
5524                if opExpr is not None:
5525                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + lastExpr ) )
5526                else:
5527                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr+lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore(lastExpr) )
5528            elif arity == 3:
5529                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr) + \
5530                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr )
5531            else:
5532                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5533        elif rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.RIGHT:
5534            if arity == 1:
5535                # try to avoid LR with this extra test
5536                if not isinstance(opExpr, Optional):
5537                    opExpr = Optional(opExpr)
5538                matchExpr = _FB(opExpr.expr + thisExpr) + Group( opExpr + thisExpr )
5539            elif arity == 2:
5540                if opExpr is not None:
5541                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + thisExpr ) )
5542                else:
5543                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( thisExpr ) )
5544            elif arity == 3:
5545                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr) + \
5546                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr )
5547            else:
5548                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5549        else:
5550            raise ValueError("operator must indicate right or left associativity")
5551        if pa:
5552            if isinstance(pa, (tuple, list)):
5553                matchExpr.setParseAction(*pa)
5554            else:
5555                matchExpr.setParseAction(pa)
5556        thisExpr <<= ( matchExpr.setName(termName) | lastExpr )
5557        lastExpr = thisExpr
5558    ret <<= lastExpr
5559    return ret

(Deprecated) Former name of infixNotation, will be dropped in a future release.

5131def srange(s):
5132    r"""Helper to easily define string ranges for use in Word
5133    construction. Borrows syntax from regexp '[]' string range
5134    definitions::
5135
5136        srange("[0-9]")   -> "0123456789"
5137        srange("[a-z]")   -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"
5138        srange("[a-z$_]") -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz$_"
5139
5140    The input string must be enclosed in []'s, and the returned string
5141    is the expanded character set joined into a single string. The
5142    values enclosed in the []'s may be:
5143
5144     - a single character
5145     - an escaped character with a leading backslash (such as ``\-``
5146       or ``\]``)
5147     - an escaped hex character with a leading ``'\x'``
5148       (``\x21``, which is a ``'!'`` character) (``\0x##``
5149       is also supported for backwards compatibility)
5150     - an escaped octal character with a leading ``'\0'``
5151       (``\041``, which is a ``'!'`` character)
5152     - a range of any of the above, separated by a dash (``'a-z'``,
5153       etc.)
5154     - any combination of the above (``'aeiouy'``,
5155       ``'a-zA-Z0-9_$'``, etc.)
5156    """
5157    _expanded = lambda p: p if not isinstance(p,ParseResults) else ''.join(unichr(c) for c in range(ord(p[0]),ord(p[1])+1))
5158    try:
5159        return "".join(_expanded(part) for part in _reBracketExpr.parseString(s).body)
5160    except Exception:
5161        return ""

Helper to easily define string ranges for use in Word construction. Borrows syntax from regexp '[]' string range definitions::

srange("[0-9]")   -> "0123456789"
srange("[a-z]")   -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"
srange("[a-z$_]") -> "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz$_"

The input string must be enclosed in []'s, and the returned string is the expanded character set joined into a single string. The values enclosed in the []'s may be:

  • a single character
  • an escaped character with a leading backslash (such as \- or \])
  • an escaped hex character with a leading '\x' (\x21, which is a '!' character) (\0x## is also supported for backwards compatibility)
  • an escaped octal character with a leading '\0' (\041, which is a '!' character)
  • a range of any of the above, separated by a dash ('a-z', etc.)
  • any combination of the above ('aeiouy', 'a-zA-Z0-9_$', etc.)

4740def traceParseAction(f):
4741    """Decorator for debugging parse actions.
4742
4743    When the parse action is called, this decorator will print
4744    ``">> entering method-name(line:<current_source_line>, <parse_location>, <matched_tokens>)"``.
4745    When the parse action completes, the decorator will print
4746    ``"<<"`` followed by the returned value, or any exception that the parse action raised.
4747
4748    Example::
4749
4750        wd = Word(alphas)
4751
4752        @traceParseAction
4753        def remove_duplicate_chars(tokens):
4754            return ''.join(sorted(set(''.join(tokens))))
4755
4756        wds = OneOrMore(wd).setParseAction(remove_duplicate_chars)
4757        print(wds.parseString("slkdjs sld sldd sdlf sdljf"))
4758
4759    prints::
4760
4761        >>entering remove_duplicate_chars(line: 'slkdjs sld sldd sdlf sdljf', 0, (['slkdjs', 'sld', 'sldd', 'sdlf', 'sdljf'], {}))
4762        <<leaving remove_duplicate_chars (ret: 'dfjkls')
4763        ['dfjkls']
4764    """
4765    f = _trim_arity(f)
4766    def z(*paArgs):
4767        thisFunc = f.__name__
4768        s,l,t = paArgs[-3:]
4769        if len(paArgs)>3:
4770            thisFunc = paArgs[0].__class__.__name__ + '.' + thisFunc
4771        sys.stderr.write( ">>entering %s(line: '%s', %d, %r)\n" % (thisFunc,line(l,s),l,t) )
4772        try:
4773            ret = f(*paArgs)
4774        except Exception as exc:
4775            sys.stderr.write( "<<leaving %s (exception: %s)\n" % (thisFunc,exc) )
4776            raise
4777        sys.stderr.write( "<<leaving %s (ret: %r)\n" % (thisFunc,ret) )
4778        return ret
4779    try:
4780        z.__name__ = f.__name__
4781    except AttributeError:
4782        pass
4783    return z

When the parse action is called, this decorator will print ">> entering method-name(line:<current_source_line>, <parse_location>, <matched_tokens>)". When the parse action completes, the decorator will print "<<" followed by the returned value, or any exception that the parse action raised.

#   def withAttribute(*args, **attrDict):

5319def withAttribute(*args,**attrDict):
5320    """Helper to create a validating parse action to be used with start
5321    tags created with :class:`makeXMLTags` or
5322    :class:`makeHTMLTags`. Use ``withAttribute`` to qualify
5323    a starting tag with a required attribute value, to avoid false
5324    matches on common tags such as ``<TD>`` or ``<DIV>``.
5325
5326    Call ``withAttribute`` with a series of attribute names and
5327    values. Specify the list of filter attributes names and values as:
5328
5329     - keyword arguments, as in ``(align="right")``, or
5330     - as an explicit dict with ``**`` operator, when an attribute
5331       name is also a Python reserved word, as in ``**{"class":"Customer", "align":"right"}``
5332     - a list of name-value tuples, as in ``(("ns1:class", "Customer"), ("ns2:align","right"))``
5333
5334    For attribute names with a namespace prefix, you must use the second
5335    form.  Attribute names are matched insensitive to upper/lower case.
5336
5337    If just testing for ``class`` (with or without a namespace), use
5338    :class:`withClass`.
5339
5340    To verify that the attribute exists, but without specifying a value,
5341    pass ``withAttribute.ANY_VALUE`` as the value.
5342
5343    Example::
5344
5345        html = '''
5346            <div>
5347            Some text
5348            <div type="grid">1 4 0 1 0</div>
5349            <div type="graph">1,3 2,3 1,1</div>
5350            <div>this has no type</div>
5351            </div>
5352
5353        '''
5354        div,div_end = makeHTMLTags("div")
5355
5356        # only match div tag having a type attribute with value "grid"
5357        div_grid = div().setParseAction(withAttribute(type="grid"))
5358        grid_expr = div_grid + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5359        for grid_header in grid_expr.searchString(html):
5360            print(grid_header.body)
5361
5362        # construct a match with any div tag having a type attribute, regardless of the value
5363        div_any_type = div().setParseAction(withAttribute(type=withAttribute.ANY_VALUE))
5364        div_expr = div_any_type + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5365        for div_header in div_expr.searchString(html):
5366            print(div_header.body)
5367
5368    prints::
5369
5370        1 4 0 1 0
5371
5372        1 4 0 1 0
5373        1,3 2,3 1,1
5374    """
5375    if args:
5376        attrs = args[:]
5377    else:
5378        attrs = attrDict.items()
5379    attrs = [(k,v) for k,v in attrs]
5380    def pa(s,l,tokens):
5381        for attrName,attrValue in attrs:
5382            if attrName not in tokens:
5383                raise ParseException(s,l,"no matching attribute " + attrName)
5384            if attrValue != withAttribute.ANY_VALUE and tokens[attrName] != attrValue:
5385                raise ParseException(s,l,"attribute '%s' has value '%s', must be '%s'" %
5386                                            (attrName, tokens[attrName], attrValue))
5387    return pa

Helper to create a validating parse action to be used with start tags created with makeXMLTags or makeHTMLTags. Use withAttribute to qualify a starting tag with a required attribute value, to avoid false matches on common tags such as <TD> or <DIV>.

Call withAttribute with a series of attribute names and values. Specify the list of filter attributes names and values as:

  • keyword arguments, as in (align="right"), or
  • as an explicit dict with ** operator, when an attribute name is also a Python reserved word, as in **{"class":"Customer", "align":"right"}
  • a list of name-value tuples, as in (("ns1:class", "Customer"), ("ns2:align","right"))

For attribute names with a namespace prefix, you must use the second form. Attribute names are matched insensitive to upper/lower case.

If just testing for class (with or without a namespace), use withClass.

To verify that the attribute exists, but without specifying a value, pass withAttribute.ANY_VALUE as the value.

Example::

html = '''
    <div>
    Some text
    <div type="grid">1 4 0 1 0</div>
    <div type="graph">1,3 2,3 1,1</div>
    <div>this has no type</div>
    </div>

'''

grid_expr = div_grid + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
for grid_header in grid_expr.searchString(html):
    print(grid_header.body)

# construct a match with any div tag having a type attribute, regardless of the value
div_any_type = div().setParseAction(withAttribute(type=withAttribute.ANY_VALUE))
div_expr = div_any_type + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")

    print(div_header.body)

5668def indentedBlock(blockStatementExpr, indentStack, indent=True):
5669    """Helper method for defining space-delimited indentation blocks,
5670    such as those used to define block statements in Python source code.
5671
5672    Parameters:
5673
5674     - blockStatementExpr - expression defining syntax of statement that
5675       is repeated within the indented block
5676     - indentStack - list created by caller to manage indentation stack
5677       (multiple statementWithIndentedBlock expressions within a single
5678       grammar should share a common indentStack)
5679     - indent - boolean indicating whether block must be indented beyond
5680       the the current level; set to False for block of left-most
5681       statements (default= ``True``)
5682
5683    A valid block must contain at least one ``blockStatement``.
5684
5685    Example::
5686
5687        data = '''
5688        def A(z):
5689          A1
5690          B = 100
5691          G = A2
5692          A2
5693          A3
5694        B
5695        def BB(a,b,c):
5696          BB1
5697          def BBA():
5698            bba1
5699            bba2
5700            bba3
5701        C
5702        D
5703        def spam(x,y):
5704             def eggs(z):
5705                 pass
5706        '''
5707
5708
5709        indentStack = [1]
5710        stmt = Forward()
5711
5712        identifier = Word(alphas, alphanums)
5713        funcDecl = ("def" + identifier + Group( "(" + Optional( delimitedList(identifier) ) + ")" ) + ":")
5714        func_body = indentedBlock(stmt, indentStack)
5715        funcDef = Group( funcDecl + func_body )
5716
5717        rvalue = Forward()
5718        funcCall = Group(identifier + "(" + Optional(delimitedList(rvalue)) + ")")
5719        rvalue << (funcCall | identifier | Word(nums))
5720        assignment = Group(identifier + "=" + rvalue)
5721        stmt << ( funcDef | assignment | identifier )
5722
5723        module_body = OneOrMore(stmt)
5724
5725        parseTree = module_body.parseString(data)
5726        parseTree.pprint()
5727
5728    prints::
5729
5730        [['def',
5731          'A',
5732          ['(', 'z', ')'],
5733          ':',
5734          [['A1'], [['B', '=', '100']], [['G', '=', 'A2']], ['A2'], ['A3']]],
5735         'B',
5736         ['def',
5737          'BB',
5738          ['(', 'a', 'b', 'c', ')'],
5739          ':',
5740          [['BB1'], [['def', 'BBA', ['(', ')'], ':', [['bba1'], ['bba2'], ['bba3']]]]]],
5741         'C',
5742         'D',
5743         ['def',
5744          'spam',
5745          ['(', 'x', 'y', ')'],
5746          ':',
5747          [[['def', 'eggs', ['(', 'z', ')'], ':', [['pass']]]]]]]
5748    """
5749    def checkPeerIndent(s,l,t):
5750        if l >= len(s): return
5751        curCol = col(l,s)
5752        if curCol != indentStack[-1]:
5753            if curCol > indentStack[-1]:
5754                raise ParseFatalException(s,l,"illegal nesting")
5755            raise ParseException(s,l,"not a peer entry")
5756
5757    def checkSubIndent(s,l,t):
5758        curCol = col(l,s)
5759        if curCol > indentStack[-1]:
5760            indentStack.append( curCol )
5761        else:
5762            raise ParseException(s,l,"not a subentry")
5763
5764    def checkUnindent(s,l,t):
5765        if l >= len(s): return
5766        curCol = col(l,s)
5767        if not(indentStack and curCol < indentStack[-1] and curCol <= indentStack[-2]):
5768            raise ParseException(s,l,"not an unindent")
5769        indentStack.pop()
5770
5771    NL = OneOrMore(LineEnd().setWhitespaceChars("\t ").suppress())
5772    INDENT = (Empty() + Empty().setParseAction(checkSubIndent)).setName('INDENT')
5773    PEER   = Empty().setParseAction(checkPeerIndent).setName('')
5774    UNDENT = Empty().setParseAction(checkUnindent).setName('UNINDENT')
5775    if indent:
5776        smExpr = Group( Optional(NL) +
5777            #~ FollowedBy(blockStatementExpr) +
5778            INDENT + (OneOrMore( PEER + Group(blockStatementExpr) + Optional(NL) )) + UNDENT)
5779    else:
5780        smExpr = Group( Optional(NL) +
5781            (OneOrMore( PEER + Group(blockStatementExpr) + Optional(NL) )) )
5782    blockStatementExpr.ignore(_bslash + LineEnd())
5783    return smExpr.setName('indented block')

Helper method for defining space-delimited indentation blocks, such as those used to define block statements in Python source code.

Parameters:

  • blockStatementExpr - expression defining syntax of statement that is repeated within the indented block
  • indentStack - list created by caller to manage indentation stack (multiple statementWithIndentedBlock expressions within a single grammar should share a common indentStack)
  • indent - boolean indicating whether block must be indented beyond the the current level; set to False for block of left-most statements (default= True)

A valid block must contain at least one blockStatement.

Example::

  A1
  B = 100
  G = A2
  A2
  A3
B
def BB(a,b,c):
  BB1
  def BBA():
    bba1
    bba2
    bba3
C
D
def spam(x,y):
     def eggs(z):
         pass
'''

stmt = Forward()

func_body = indentedBlock(stmt, indentStack)
funcDef = Group( funcDecl + func_body )

rvalue = Forward()
funcCall = Group(identifier + "(" + Optional(delimitedList(rvalue)) + ")")
rvalue << (funcCall | identifier | Word(nums))
assignment = Group(identifier + "=" + rvalue)
stmt << ( funcDef | assignment | identifier )

module_body = OneOrMore(stmt)

parseTree = module_body.parseString(data)
parseTree.pprint()

  'BB',

#   def originalTextFor(expr, asString=True):

5040def originalTextFor(expr, asString=True):
5041    """Helper to return the original, untokenized text for a given
5042    expression.  Useful to restore the parsed fields of an HTML start
5043    tag into the raw tag text itself, or to revert separate tokens with
5044    intervening whitespace back to the original matching input text. By
5045    default, returns astring containing the original parsed text.
5046
5047    If the optional ``asString`` argument is passed as
5048    ``False``, then the return value is
5049    a :class:`ParseResults` containing any results names that
5050    were originally matched, and a single token containing the original
5051    matched text from the input string.  So if the expression passed to
5052    :class:`originalTextFor` contains expressions with defined
5053    results names, you must set ``asString`` to ``False`` if you
5054    want to preserve those results name values.
5055
5056    Example::
5057
5058        src = "this is test <b> bold <i>text</i> </b> normal text "
5059        for tag in ("b","i"):
5060            opener,closer = makeHTMLTags(tag)
5061            patt = originalTextFor(opener + SkipTo(closer) + closer)
5062            print(patt.searchString(src)[0])
5063
5064    prints::
5065
5066        ['<b> bold <i>text</i> </b>']
5067        ['<i>text</i>']
5068    """
5069    locMarker = Empty().setParseAction(lambda s,loc,t: loc)
5070    endlocMarker = locMarker.copy()
5071    endlocMarker.callPreparse = False
5072    matchExpr = locMarker("_original_start") + expr + endlocMarker("_original_end")
5073    if asString:
5074        extractText = lambda s,l,t: s[t._original_start:t._original_end]
5075    else:
5076        def extractText(s,l,t):
5077            t[:] = [s[t.pop('_original_start'):t.pop('_original_end')]]
5078    matchExpr.setParseAction(extractText)
5079    matchExpr.ignoreExprs = expr.ignoreExprs
5080    return matchExpr

Helper to return the original, untokenized text for a given expression. Useful to restore the parsed fields of an HTML start tag into the raw tag text itself, or to revert separate tokens with intervening whitespace back to the original matching input text. By default, returns astring containing the original parsed text.

If the optional asString argument is passed as False, then the return value is a ParseResults containing any results names that were originally matched, and a single token containing the original matched text from the input string. So if the expression passed to originalTextFor contains expressions with defined results names, you must set asString to False if you want to preserve those results name values.

Example::

src = "this is test <b> bold <i>text</i> </b> normal text "
for tag in ("b","i"):
    opener,closer = makeHTMLTags(tag)
    patt = originalTextFor(opener + SkipTo(closer) + closer)
    print(patt.searchString(src)[0])

prints::

['<b> bold <i>text</i> </b>']
['<i>text</i>']

#   def infixNotation(baseExpr, opList, lpar=Suppress:("("), rpar=Suppress:(")")):
View Source 
5432def infixNotation( baseExpr, opList, lpar=Suppress('('), rpar=Suppress(')') ):
5433    """Helper method for constructing grammars of expressions made up of
5434    operators working in a precedence hierarchy.  Operators may be unary
5435    or binary, left- or right-associative.  Parse actions can also be
5436    attached to operator expressions. The generated parser will also
5437    recognize the use of parentheses to override operator precedences
5438    (see example below).
5439
5440    Note: if you define a deep operator list, you may see performance
5441    issues when using infixNotation. See
5442    :class:`ParserElement.enablePackrat` for a mechanism to potentially
5443    improve your parser performance.
5444
5445    Parameters:
5446     - baseExpr - expression representing the most basic element for the
5447       nested
5448     - opList - list of tuples, one for each operator precedence level
5449       in the expression grammar; each tuple is of the form ``(opExpr,
5450       numTerms, rightLeftAssoc, parseAction)``, where:
5451
5452       - opExpr is the pyparsing expression for the operator; may also
5453         be a string, which will be converted to a Literal; if numTerms
5454         is 3, opExpr is a tuple of two expressions, for the two
5455         operators separating the 3 terms
5456       - numTerms is the number of terms for this operator (must be 1,
5457         2, or 3)
5458       - rightLeftAssoc is the indicator whether the operator is right
5459         or left associative, using the pyparsing-defined constants
5460         ``opAssoc.RIGHT`` and ``opAssoc.LEFT``.
5461       - parseAction is the parse action to be associated with
5462         expressions matching this operator expression (the parse action
5463         tuple member may be omitted); if the parse action is passed
5464         a tuple or list of functions, this is equivalent to calling
5465         ``setParseAction(*fn)``
5466         (:class:`ParserElement.setParseAction`)
5467     - lpar - expression for matching left-parentheses
5468       (default= ``Suppress('(')``)
5469     - rpar - expression for matching right-parentheses
5470       (default= ``Suppress(')')``)
5471
5472    Example::
5473
5474        # simple example of four-function arithmetic with ints and
5475        # variable names
5476        integer = pyparsing_common.signed_integer
5477        varname = pyparsing_common.identifier
5478
5479        arith_expr = infixNotation(integer | varname,
5480            [
5481            ('-', 1, opAssoc.RIGHT),
5482            (oneOf('* /'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5483            (oneOf('+ -'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
5484            ])
5485
5486        arith_expr.runTests('''
5487            5+3*6
5488            (5+3)*6
5489            -2--11
5490            ''', fullDump=False)
5491
5492    prints::
5493
5494        5+3*6
5495        [[5, '+', [3, '*', 6]]]
5496
5497        (5+3)*6
5498        [[[5, '+', 3], '*', 6]]
5499
5500        -2--11
5501        [[['-', 2], '-', ['-', 11]]]
5502    """
5503    # captive version of FollowedBy that does not do parse actions or capture results names
5504    class _FB(FollowedBy):
5505        def parseImpl(self, instring, loc, doActions=True):
5506            self.expr.tryParse(instring, loc)
5507            return loc, []
5508
5509    ret = Forward()
5510    lastExpr = baseExpr | ( lpar + ret + rpar )
5511    for i,operDef in enumerate(opList):
5512        opExpr,arity,rightLeftAssoc,pa = (operDef + (None,))[:4]
5513        termName = "%s term" % opExpr if arity < 3 else "%s%s term" % opExpr
5514        if arity == 3:
5515            if opExpr is None or len(opExpr) != 2:
5516                raise ValueError(
5517                    "if numterms=3, opExpr must be a tuple or list of two expressions")
5518            opExpr1, opExpr2 = opExpr
5519        thisExpr = Forward().setName(termName)
5520        if rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.LEFT:
5521            if arity == 1:
5522                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr ) )
5523            elif arity == 2:
5524                if opExpr is not None:
5525                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + lastExpr ) )
5526                else:
5527                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr+lastExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore(lastExpr) )
5528            elif arity == 3:
5529                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr) + \
5530                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + lastExpr + opExpr2 + lastExpr )
5531            else:
5532                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5533        elif rightLeftAssoc == opAssoc.RIGHT:
5534            if arity == 1:
5535                # try to avoid LR with this extra test
5536                if not isinstance(opExpr, Optional):
5537                    opExpr = Optional(opExpr)
5538                matchExpr = _FB(opExpr.expr + thisExpr) + Group( opExpr + thisExpr )
5539            elif arity == 2:
5540                if opExpr is not None:
5541                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( opExpr + thisExpr ) )
5542                else:
5543                    matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + thisExpr) + Group( lastExpr + OneOrMore( thisExpr ) )
5544            elif arity == 3:
5545                matchExpr = _FB(lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr) + \
5546                            Group( lastExpr + opExpr1 + thisExpr + opExpr2 + thisExpr )
5547            else:
5548                raise ValueError("operator must be unary (1), binary (2), or ternary (3)")
5549        else:
5550            raise ValueError("operator must indicate right or left associativity")
5551        if pa:
5552            if isinstance(pa, (tuple, list)):
5553                matchExpr.setParseAction(*pa)
5554            else:
5555                matchExpr.setParseAction(pa)
5556        thisExpr <<= ( matchExpr.setName(termName) | lastExpr )
5557        lastExpr = thisExpr
5558    ret <<= lastExpr
5559    return ret

Helper method for constructing grammars of expressions made up of operators working in a precedence hierarchy. Operators may be unary or binary, left- or right-associative. Parse actions can also be attached to operator expressions. The generated parser will also recognize the use of parentheses to override operator precedences (see example below).

Note: if you define a deep operator list, you may see performance issues when using infixNotation. See ParserElement.enablePackrat for a mechanism to potentially improve your parser performance.

Parameters:

  • baseExpr - expression representing the most basic element for the nested
  • opList - list of tuples, one for each operator precedence level in the expression grammar; each tuple is of the form (opExpr, numTerms, rightLeftAssoc, parseAction), where:
  • opExpr is the pyparsing expression for the operator; may also be a string, which will be converted to a Literal; if numTerms is 3, opExpr is a tuple of two expressions, for the two operators separating the 3 terms
  • numTerms is the number of terms for this operator (must be 1, 2, or 3)
  • rightLeftAssoc is the indicator whether the operator is right or left associative, using the pyparsing-defined constants opAssoc.RIGHT and opAssoc.LEFT.
  • parseAction is the parse action to be associated with expressions matching this operator expression (the parse action tuple member may be omitted); if the parse action is passed a tuple or list of functions, this is equivalent to calling setParseAction(*fn) (ParserElement.setParseAction)
    • lpar - expression for matching left-parentheses (default= Suppress('('))
    • rpar - expression for matching right-parentheses (default= Suppress(')'))

Example::

# simple example of four-function arithmetic with ints and
# variable names
integer = pyparsing_common.signed_integer
varname = pyparsing_common.identifier

arith_expr = infixNotation(integer | varname,
    [
    ('-', 1, opAssoc.RIGHT),
    (oneOf('* /'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
    (oneOf('+ -'), 2, opAssoc.LEFT),
    ])

arith_expr.runTests('''
    5+3*6
    (5+3)*6
    -2--11
    ''', fullDump=False)

prints::

5+3*6
[[5, '+', [3, '*', 6]]]

(5+3)*6
[[[5, '+', 3], '*', 6]]

-2--11
[[['-', 2], '-', ['-', 11]]]

5088def locatedExpr(expr):
5089    """Helper to decorate a returned token with its starting and ending
5090    locations in the input string.
5091
5092    This helper adds the following results names:
5093
5094     - locn_start = location where matched expression begins
5095     - locn_end = location where matched expression ends
5096     - value = the actual parsed results
5097
5098    Be careful if the input text contains ``<TAB>`` characters, you
5099    may want to call :class:`ParserElement.parseWithTabs`
5100
5101    Example::
5102
5103        wd = Word(alphas)
5104        for match in locatedExpr(wd).searchString("ljsdf123lksdjjf123lkkjj1222"):
5105            print(match)
5106
5107    prints::
5108
5109        [[0, 'ljsdf', 5]]
5110        [[8, 'lksdjjf', 15]]
5111        [[18, 'lkkjj', 23]]
5112    """
5113    locator = Empty().setParseAction(lambda s,l,t: l)
5114    return Group(locator("locn_start") + expr("value") + locator.copy().leaveWhitespace()("locn_end"))

5390def withClass(classname, namespace=''):
5391    """Simplified version of :class:`withAttribute` when
5392    matching on a div class - made difficult because ``class`` is
5393    a reserved word in Python.
5394
5395    Example::
5396
5397        html = '''
5398            <div>
5399            Some text
5400            <div class="grid">1 4 0 1 0</div>
5401            <div class="graph">1,3 2,3 1,1</div>
5402            <div>this &lt;div&gt; has no class</div>
5403            </div>
5404
5405        '''
5406        div,div_end = makeHTMLTags("div")
5407        div_grid = div().setParseAction(withClass("grid"))
5408
5409        grid_expr = div_grid + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5410        for grid_header in grid_expr.searchString(html):
5411            print(grid_header.body)
5412
5413        div_any_type = div().setParseAction(withClass(withAttribute.ANY_VALUE))
5414        div_expr = div_any_type + SkipTo(div | div_end)("body")
5415        for div_header in div_expr.searchString(html):
5416            print(div_header.body)
5417
5418    prints::
5419
5420        1 4 0 1 0
5421
5422        1 4 0 1 0
5423        1,3 2,3 1,1
5424    """
5425    classattr = "%s:class" % namespace if namespace else "class"
5426    return withAttribute(**{classattr : classname})

Simplified version of withAttribute when matching on a div class - made difficult because class is a reserved word in Python.

2672class CloseMatch(Token):
2673    """A variation on :class:`Literal` which matches "close" matches,
2674    that is, strings with at most 'n' mismatching characters.
2675    :class:`CloseMatch` takes parameters:
2676
2677     - ``match_string`` - string to be matched
2678     - ``maxMismatches`` - (``default=1``) maximum number of
2679       mismatches allowed to count as a match
2680
2681    The results from a successful parse will contain the matched text
2682    from the input string and the following named results:
2683
2684     - ``mismatches`` - a list of the positions within the
2685       match_string where mismatches were found
2686     - ``original`` - the original match_string used to compare
2687       against the input string
2688
2689    If ``mismatches`` is an empty list, then the match was an exact
2690    match.
2691
2692    Example::
2693
2694        patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA")
2695        patt.parseString("ATCATCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2696        patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> Exception: Expected 'ATCATCGAATGGA' (with up to 1 mismatches) (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)
2697
2698        # exact match
2699        patt.parseString("ATCATCGAATGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAATGGA'], {'mismatches': [[]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2700
2701        # close match allowing up to 2 mismatches
2702        patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA", maxMismatches=2)
2703        patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCAXCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[4, 9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
2704    """
2705    def __init__(self, match_string, maxMismatches=1):
2706        super(CloseMatch,self).__init__()
2707        self.name = match_string
2708        self.match_string = match_string
2709        self.maxMismatches = maxMismatches
2710        self.errmsg = "Expected %r (with up to %d mismatches)" % (self.match_string, self.maxMismatches)
2711        self.mayIndexError = False
2712        self.mayReturnEmpty = False
2713
2714    def parseImpl( self, instring, loc, doActions=True ):
2715        start = loc
2716        instrlen = len(instring)
2717        maxloc = start + len(self.match_string)
2718
2719        if maxloc <= instrlen:
2720            match_string = self.match_string
2721            match_stringloc = 0
2722            mismatches = []
2723            maxMismatches = self.maxMismatches
2724
2725            for match_stringloc,s_m in enumerate(zip(instring[loc:maxloc], self.match_string)):
2726                src,mat = s_m
2727                if src != mat:
2728                    mismatches.append(match_stringloc)
2729                    if len(mismatches) > maxMismatches:
2730                        break
2731            else:
2732                loc = match_stringloc + 1
2733                results = ParseResults([instring[start:loc]])
2734                results['original'] = self.match_string
2735                results['mismatches'] = mismatches
2736                return loc, results
2737
2738        raise ParseException(instring, loc, self.errmsg, self)

A variation on Literal which matches "close" matches, that is, strings with at most 'n' mismatching characters. CloseMatch takes parameters:

  • match_string - string to be matched
  • maxMismatches - (default=1) maximum number of mismatches allowed to count as a match

The results from a successful parse will contain the matched text from the input string and the following named results:

  • mismatches - a list of the positions within the match_string where mismatches were found
  • original - the original match_string used to compare against the input string

If mismatches is an empty list, then the match was an exact match.

Example::

patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA")
patt.parseString("ATCATCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> Exception: Expected 'ATCATCGAATGGA' (with up to 1 mismatches) (at char 0), (line:1, col:1)

# exact match
patt.parseString("ATCATCGAATGGA") # -> (['ATCATCGAATGGA'], {'mismatches': [[]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})

# close match allowing up to 2 mismatches
patt = CloseMatch("ATCATCGAATGGA", maxMismatches=2)
patt.parseString("ATCAXCGAAXGGA") # -> (['ATCAXCGAAXGGA'], {'mismatches': [[4, 9]], 'original': ['ATCATCGAATGGA']})
