5202def tokenMap(func, *args):
5203    """Helper to define a parse action by mapping a function to all
5204    elements of a ParseResults list. If any additional args are passed,
5205    they are forwarded to the given function as additional arguments
5206    after the token, as in
5207    ``hex_integer = Word(hexnums).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16))``,
5208    which will convert the parsed data to an integer using base 16.
5209
5210    Example (compare the last to example in :class:`ParserElement.transformString`::
5211
5212        hex_ints = OneOrMore(Word(hexnums)).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16))
5213        hex_ints.runTests('''
5214            00 11 22 aa FF 0a 0d 1a
5215            ''')
5216
5217        upperword = Word(alphas).setParseAction(tokenMap(str.upper))
5218        OneOrMore(upperword).runTests('''
5219            my kingdom for a horse
5220            ''')
5221
5222        wd = Word(alphas).setParseAction(tokenMap(str.title))
5223        OneOrMore(wd).setParseAction(' '.join).runTests('''
5224            now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york
5225            ''')
5226
5227    prints::
5228
5229        00 11 22 aa FF 0a 0d 1a
5230        [0, 17, 34, 170, 255, 10, 13, 26]
5231
5232        my kingdom for a horse
5233        ['MY', 'KINGDOM', 'FOR', 'A', 'HORSE']
5234
5235        now is the winter of our discontent made glorious summer by this sun of york
5236        ['Now Is The Winter Of Our Discontent Made Glorious Summer By This Sun Of York']
5237    """
5238    def pa(s,l,t):
5239        return [func(tokn, *args) for tokn in t]
5240
5241    try:
5242        func_name = getattr(func, '__name__',
5243                            getattr(func, '__class__').__name__)
5244    except Exception:
5245        func_name = str(func)
5246    pa.__name__ = func_name
5247
5248    return pa

Helper to define a parse action by mapping a function to all elements of a ParseResults list. If any additional args are passed, they are forwarded to the given function as additional arguments after the token, as in hex_integer = Word(hexnums).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16)), which will convert the parsed data to an integer using base 16.

Example (compare the last to example in ParserElement.transformString::

hex_ints = OneOrMore(Word(hexnums)).setParseAction(tokenMap(int, 16))
hex_ints.runTests('''
    00 11 22 aa FF 0a 0d 1a
    ''')

OneOrMore(upperword).runTests('''
    my kingdom for a horse
    ''')

5978    Parse action for converting parsed numbers to Python float

5981    integer = Word(nums).setName("integer").setParseAction(convertToInteger)
5982    """expression that parses an unsigned integer, returns an int"""
5983
5984    hex_integer = Word(hexnums).setName("hex integer").setParseAction(tokenMap(int,16))
5985    """expression that parses a hexadecimal integer, returns an int"""
5986
5987    signed_integer = Regex(r'[+-]?\d+').setName("signed integer").setParseAction(convertToInteger)
5988    """expression that parses an integer with optional leading sign, returns an int"""
5989
5990    fraction = (signed_integer().setParseAction(convertToFloat) + '/' + signed_integer().setParseAction(convertToFloat)).setName("fraction")
5991    """fractional expression of an integer divided by an integer, returns a float"""
5992    fraction.addParseAction(lambda t: t[0]/t[-1])
5993
5994    mixed_integer = (fraction | signed_integer + Optional(Optional('-').suppress() + fraction)).setName("fraction or mixed integer-fraction")
5995    """mixed integer of the form 'integer - fraction', with optional leading integer, returns float"""
5996    mixed_integer.addParseAction(sum)
5997
5998    real = Regex(r'[+-]?\d+\.\d*').setName("real number").setParseAction(convertToFloat)
5999    """expression that parses a floating point number and returns a float"""
6000
6001    sci_real = Regex(r'[+-]?\d+([eE][+-]?\d+|\.\d*([eE][+-]?\d+)?)').setName("real number with scientific notation").setParseAction(convertToFloat)
6002    """expression that parses a floating point number with optional
6003    scientific notation and returns a float"""
6004
6005    # streamlining this expression makes the docs nicer-looking
6006    number = (sci_real | real | signed_integer).streamline()
6007    """any numeric expression, returns the corresponding Python type"""
6008
6009    fnumber = Regex(r'[+-]?\d+\.?\d*([eE][+-]?\d+)?').setName("fnumber").setParseAction(convertToFloat)
6010    """any int or real number, returned as float"""
6011
6012    identifier = Word(alphas+'_', alphanums+'_').setName("identifier")
6013    """typical code identifier (leading alpha or '_', followed by 0 or more alphas, nums, or '_')"""
6014
6015    ipv4_address = Regex(r'(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|1?[0-9]{1,2})(\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|1?[0-9]{1,2})){3}').setName("IPv4 address")
6016    "IPv4 address (``0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255``)"
6017
6018    _ipv6_part = Regex(r'[0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}').setName("hex_integer")
6019    _full_ipv6_address = (_ipv6_part + (':' + _ipv6_part)*7).setName("full IPv6 address")
6020    _short_ipv6_address = (Optional(_ipv6_part + (':' + _ipv6_part)*(0,6)) + "::" + Optional(_ipv6_part + (':' + _ipv6_part)*(0,6))).setName("short IPv6 address")
6021    _short_ipv6_address.addCondition(lambda t: sum(1 for tt in t if pyparsing_common._ipv6_part.matches(tt)) < 8)
6022    _mixed_ipv6_address = ("::ffff:" + ipv4_address).setName("mixed IPv6 address")
6023    ipv6_address = Combine((_full_ipv6_address | _mixed_ipv6_address | _short_ipv6_address).setName("IPv6 address")).setName("IPv6 address")
6024    "IPv6 address (long, short, or mixed form)"
6025
6026    mac_address = Regex(r'[0-9a-fA-F]{2}([:.-])[0-9a-fA-F]{2}(?:\1[0-9a-fA-F]{2}){4}').setName("MAC address")
6027    "MAC address xx:xx:xx:xx:xx (may also have '-' or '.' delimiters)"
6028
6029    @staticmethod
6030    def convertToDate(fmt="%Y-%m-%d"):
6031        """
6032        Helper to create a parse action for converting parsed date string to Python datetime.date
6033
6034        Params -
6035         - fmt - format to be passed to datetime.strptime (default= ``"%Y-%m-%d"``)
6036
6037        Example::
6038
6039            date_expr = pyparsing_common.iso8601_date.copy()
6040            date_expr.setParseAction(pyparsing_common.convertToDate())
6041            print(date_expr.parseString("1999-12-31"))
6042
6043        prints::
6044
6045            [datetime.date(1999, 12, 31)]
6046        """
6047        def cvt_fn(s,l,t):
6048            try:
6049                return datetime.strptime(t[0], fmt).date()
6050            except ValueError as ve:
6051                raise ParseException(s, l, str(ve))
6052        return cvt_fn
6053
6054    @staticmethod
6055    def convertToDatetime(fmt="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f"):

6057        datetime string to Python datetime.datetime
6058

6060         - fmt - format to be passed to datetime.strptime (default= ``"%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f"``)

6062        Example::

6066            print(dt_expr.parseString("1999-12-31T23:59:59.999"))

6068        prints::
6069
6070            [datetime.datetime(1999, 12, 31, 23, 59, 59, 999000)]
6071        """
6072        def cvt_fn(s,l,t):
6073            try:
6074                return datetime.strptime(t[0], fmt)
6075            except ValueError as ve:
6076                raise ParseException(s, l, str(ve))
6077        return cvt_fn
6078
6079    iso8601_date = Regex(r'(?P<year>\d{4})(?:-(?P<month>\d\d)(?:-(?P<day>\d\d))?)?').setName("ISO8601 date")
6080    "ISO8601 date (``yyyy-mm-dd``)"

6082    iso8601_datetime = Regex(r'(?P<year>\d{4})-(?P<month>\d\d)-(?P<day>\d\d)[T ](?P<hour>\d\d):(?P<minute>\d\d)(:(?P<second>\d\d(\.\d*)?)?)?(?P<tz>Z|[+-]\d\d:?\d\d)?').setName("ISO8601 datetime")

Here are some common low-level expressions that may be useful in jump-starting parser development:

  • numeric forms (integers<integer>, reals<real>, scientific notation<sci_real>)
  • common programming identifiers<identifier>
  • network addresses (MAC<mac_address>, IPv4<ipv4_address>, IPv6<ipv6_address>)
  • ISO8601 dates<iso8601_date> and datetime<iso8601_datetime>
  • UUID<uuid>
  • comma-separated list<comma_separated_list>

Parse actions:

  • convertToInteger
  • convertToFloat
  • convertToDate
  • convertToDatetime
  • stripHTMLTags
  • upcaseTokens
  • downcaseTokens

Example::

pyparsing_common.number.runTests('''
    # any int or real number, returned as the appropriate type
    100
    -100
    +100
    3.14159
    6.02e23
    1e-12
    ''')

pyparsing_common.fnumber.runTests('''
    # any int or real number, returned as float
    100
    -100
    +100
    3.14159
    6.02e23
    1e-12
    ''')

pyparsing_common.hex_integer.runTests('''
    # hex numbers
    100
    FF
    ''')

pyparsing_common.fraction.runTests('''
    # fractions
    1/2
    -3/4
    ''')

pyparsing_common.mixed_integer.runTests('''
    # mixed fractions
    1
    1/2
    -3/4
    1-3/4
    ''')

import uuid
pyparsing_common.uuid.setParseAction(tokenMap(uuid.UUID))
pyparsing_common.uuid.runTests('''
    # uuid
    12345678-1234-5678-1234-567812345678
    ''')

A set of Unicode characters, for language-specific strings for alphas, nums, alphanums, and printables. A unicode_set is defined by a list of ranges in the Unicode character set, in a class attribute _ranges, such as::

_ranges = [(0x0020, 0x007e), (0x00a0, 0x00ff),]

A unicode set can also be defined using multiple inheritance of other unicode sets::

class CJK(Chinese, Japanese, Korean):
    pass

#   class unicode_set:
View Source 
6134class unicode_set(object):
6135    """
6136    A set of Unicode characters, for language-specific strings for
6137    ``alphas``, ``nums``, ``alphanums``, and ``printables``.
6138    A unicode_set is defined by a list of ranges in the Unicode character
6139    set, in a class attribute ``_ranges``, such as::
6140
6141        _ranges = [(0x0020, 0x007e), (0x00a0, 0x00ff),]
6142
6143    A unicode set can also be defined using multiple inheritance of other unicode sets::
6144
6145        class CJK(Chinese, Japanese, Korean):
6146            pass
6147    """
6148    _ranges = []
6149
6150    @classmethod
6151    def _get_chars_for_ranges(cls):
6152        ret = []
6153        for cc in cls.__mro__:
6154            if cc is unicode_set:
6155                break
6156            for rr in cc._ranges:
6157                ret.extend(range(rr[0], rr[-1]+1))
6158        return [unichr(c) for c in sorted(set(ret))]
6159
6160    @_lazyclassproperty
6161    def printables(cls):
6162        "all non-whitespace characters in this range"
6163        return u''.join(filterfalse(unicode.isspace, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6164
6165    @_lazyclassproperty
6166    def alphas(cls):
6167        "all alphabetic characters in this range"
6168        return u''.join(filter(unicode.isalpha, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6169
6170    @_lazyclassproperty
6171    def nums(cls):
6172        "all numeric digit characters in this range"
6173        return u''.join(filter(unicode.isdigit, cls._get_chars_for_ranges()))
6174
6175    @_lazyclassproperty
6176    def alphanums(cls):
6177        "all alphanumeric characters in this range"
6178        return cls.alphas + cls.nums

A set of Unicode characters, for language-specific strings for alphas, nums, alphanums, and printables. A unicode_set is defined by a list of ranges in the Unicode character set, in a class attribute _ranges, such as::

_ranges = [(0x0020, 0x007e), (0x00a0, 0x00ff),]

A unicode set can also be defined using multiple inheritance of other unicode sets::

class CJK(Chinese, Japanese, Korean):
    pass

str(object='') -> str str(bytes_or_buffer[, encoding[, errors]]) -> str

Create a new string object from the given object. If encoding or errors is specified, then the object must expose a data buffer that will be decoded using the given encoding and error handler. Otherwise, returns the result of object.__str__() (if defined) or repr(object). encoding defaults to sys.getdefaultencoding(). errors defaults to 'strict'.
